INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (505, 'Offshore Wind Farms Face Turbulence: Fishers and Tourists Say \'Not in My Ocean\'', 'Plans for offshore wind farms near Port Stephens hit choppy waters as local fishers and tourism operators push back. Renewable energy meets the NIMBY (Not In My Back Yard) brigade.', 'Turns out, Australias plan to save the planet might come with a side of seagull-flavoured outrage. Coastal communities from Gippsland to the Illawarra are throwing metaphorical sand at the governments offshore wind rollout, with fishers, tour operators, and beach purists screaming a collective Not in my backyardor my ocean.\n\nWhile Chris Bowen is waxing lyrical about renewable zones and energy independence, locals are hosting town hall dramas that make Married At First Sight look civilised. Fishers argue the turbines will mess with marine life, tourists fear the pristine views will turn into Blade Runner: Sea Edition, and some just want Canberra to stop doing things near their beach.\n\nBut heres the plot twist: these are the same regions that politicians point to when they say we need to \"transition jobs\" and \"rebuild economies.\" Its climate policy meets coastal real estate snobbery. And with the Coalition now positioning themselves as defenders of the visual amenity, you know weve entered a bizarre alternate timeline.\n\nThis week, the Albanese government paused community consultation in the Hunter after locals crashed the session with handmade signs, heated rants, and possibly a conch shell of protest. Offshore wind? More like onshore drama.\n\nSources: ABC News, The Guardian, Sydney Morning Herald, Renew Economy', 0, 'factabot', 'offshore-wind-farms-face-turbulence-fishers-and-tourists-say-not-in-my-ocean', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-04-18 00:53:39', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (506, 'Medicare Misinformation: Right-Wing Ad Accidentally Promotes Satirical Labor Video', 'A right-wing campaign ad intended to criticize Labor ends up promoting a satirical video warning about Medicare privatization. Oopstalk about shooting yourself in the foot.', 'A right-wing Facebook ad campaign aimed at roasting Labors Medicare reforms just accidentally did the oppositeby linking directly to a parody Labor video praising universal healthcare. Yes, someone spent actual money to send angry voters straight into a love letter to bulk billing.\n\nThe group behind the adAustralians for Medicare Accountability, which sounds totally grassroots and definitely not a front for conservative donorspushed out a clip with the warning Labor\'s plan will ruin Medicare. But the link they used? It redirected to Labor\'s own satirical skit starring a fake doctor and a very enthusiastic patient. Oops.\n\nThis is political advertisings version of slipping on a banana peel while yelling watch your step. And while Meta scrambles to review the campaign, Labors digital team is probably cracking open some celebratory kombucha.\n\nIts a cautionary tale about the digital wild west of political ads. When half the electorate is already skeptical, and the other half is on TikTok, maybe dont base your $20,000 ad buy on a dodgy hyperlink.\n\nLatest twist? The videos views have now tripled, and Labor MP Mark Butler cheekily thanked his unexpected collaborators during a press interview. Irony level: Shakespearean.\n\nSources: Crikey, ABC News, Meta Ad Library, The Saturday Paper\n', 0, 'factabot', 'medicare-misinformation-right-wing-ad-accidentally-promotes-satirical-labor-video', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-04-18 00:53:39', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (507, 'Clive Palmer\'s Digital Blitz: $1.4 Million Spent to Trumpet Coal and Campaigns', 'Clive Palmer\'s Trumpet of Patriots party goes all-in online, spending over a million dollars on ads promoting coal and, presumably, himself. Because nothing says grassroots like a millionaire\'s ad spree.', 'Like a political NPC with unlimited gold coins, Clive Palmer is backsplashing $1.4 million in just three months on digital ads, mostly to tell us that coal is good, net zero is evil, and the only party worth trusting has his name all over it. Democracy? More like a browser-based billboard war.\n\nAccording to new AEC disclosures, Palmers United Australia Party is by far the top spender on online political ads, with most of that cash going into Facebook and YouTube. The ads range from fire-and-brimstone climate denial to AI-generated videos of Clive looking vaguely disappointed at wind turbines.\n\nPalmers strategy is blunt: flood the internet, skip the policy, and outshout everyone else with volume and cash. Its not subtle. Its not nuanced. But in a digital space where attention spans last six seconds, maybe subtletys overrated.\n\nZooming out, this is part of a worrying trend: ultra-rich candidates bypassing journalism and public debate to beam propaganda straight into your eyeballs. It\'s the political version of autoplaying YouTube ads, except you cant skipand the sound is always on.\n\nThis week, fact-checkers flagged multiple UAP ads for misleading claims, but the Electoral Commission confirmed that unless it breaks the law, they cant touch it. So basically: facts optional, money talks, and Clive yells.\n\nSources: AEC Disclosures, ABC News, Guardian Australia, Meta Ad Library\n', 0, 'factabot', 'clive-palmers-digital-blitz-14-million-spent-to-trumpet-coal-and-campaigns', 'draft', 'images/news/c2fac369-034f-40f4-bbd4-f24c2a6a15fb.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-05-02 15:47:43', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (508, '\'Big Boys\' Return: Jack and Danny Navigate Adulting in New Season', 'The beloved series \'Big Boys\' is back, with Jack and Danny facing dissertations and the daunting world of adulthood. Spoiler: adulting is hard.', 'Everyones favourite emotionally constipated flatmates are back, and yesBig Boys Season 2 has finally dropped in Australia. Jack (played by Jack Rooke, the shows creator) and Danny (Dylan Llewellyn, of Derry Girls fame) are still fumbling through life, grief, and hookup apps, except now they have student loans, unresolved trauma, and adulting to worry about. So basically: same chaos, just with higher stakes and lower bank balances.\n\nThe BAFTA-winning series charmed viewers last year with its mix of laddish banter and sudden emotional ambushes. Think of it as The Inbetweeners if someone gave them therapy and a pastel colour palette. Season 2 sees Jack working at a uni radio station while Danny tries his hand at theatre and datingtwo activities he\'s equally unqualified for.\n\nBut behind the LOLs, the shows still sneakily clever. It handles mental health, masculinity, and sexuality with a light touch and heavy relatability. Its like being smacked with a feather duster full of feelings.\n\nThis week, SBS On Demand quietly dropped the full season, leading to a mini Twitter stampede from viewers ready to cry, laugh, and spiral. And honestly? The timing couldnt be better. With Aussie streaming currently awash in bleak dramas and reboots, Big Boys is a warm, awkward hug we didnt know we needed.\n\nSources: SBS On Demand, Guardian Australia, Pedestrian.TV, The Independent', 0, 'factabot', 'big-boys-return-jack-and-danny-navigate-adulting-in-new-season', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-04-18 00:53:39', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (509, 'Boarded-Up Home Sparks Bidding War: Buyers Fight Over Fixer-Upper', 'A dilapidated, boarded-up property manages to trigger a bidding frenzy, proving once again that the Australian housing market is more chaotic than a reality show reunion.', 'Nothing screams Australian housing crisis quite like people fighting over a boarded-up dump with no kitchen, no bathroom, and no dignity. This week, a derelict Brisbane homecomplete with crumbling walls and a garden best described as feralsparked a bidding war and sold for nearly $1 million. Because who needs comfort when you have potential?\n\nThe three-bedroom carcass, located in a supposedly \"up-and-coming\" suburb, had been abandoned for years and needed so much work it shouldve come with a hard hat and a tetanus shot. But that didnt stop investors and young couples from crawling over each other for a shot at the Aussie Dream: owning land, even if it looks like a horror movie set.\n\nReal estate agents spun it like gold: A renovators delight, prime for development, and our favouriteunique character. Translation: haunted but zoned for a granny flat.\n\nIts the latest sign that the market has completely unhinged from reality. Supplys tight, rates are high, and millennials are now calculating whether they can live inside a skip bin and call it equity. Housing affordability? Please. Were in the Hunger Games now.\n\nThe kicker? The house sold for $200k over reserve. Which is great newsfor the termites.\n\nSources: Domain, 9News, The Courier-Mail, RealEstate.com.au', 0, 'factabot', 'boarded-up-home-sparks-bidding-war-buyers-fight-over-fixer-upper', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-04-18 00:53:39', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (510, 'Bored of Bread? Aussie Bakeries Go Viral with Croissant Cheeseburgers', 'Move over cronutsAustralias latest carb craze is the croissant cheeseburger. Its flaky, beefy, and bound to make your arteries scream.', 'If your arteries werent already on notice, Aussie bakeries are now slapping beef patties between buttery croissantsand somehow the internet cant get enough. Welcome to the unholy union of French pastry and Maccas energy: the croissant cheeseburger.\n\nThis Frankenstein of food was first spotted in Melbourne, where a hipster bakery decided that carbs alone werent chaotic enough. The croissant acts as the bun, the beef patty oozes over the edge, and the whole thing is typically crowned with pickles, melted cheese, and existential guilt.\n\nTikToks having a field day, of course. Videos of people biting into these flaky monstrosities are clocking millions of views, triggering both hunger and heated debates over cultural crimes against pastry. The French are reportedly traumatised.\n\nBut like all viral food trends, this ones more about vibe than flavour. Its not clear if anyone actually enjoys eating them, or if were all just pretending because its more photogenic than a regular burger and 200% more likely to get a like.\n\nAs of this week, bakeries in Sydney and Brisbane are joining the trend, with one shop selling out by 10am daily. So yes, weve officially hit peak foodie chaos. Gluten-free girlies, avert your eyes.\n\nSources: Broadsheet, Good Food, News.com.au, TikTok\n', 0, 'factabot', 'bored-of-bread-aussie-bakeries-go-viral-with-croissant-cheeseburgers', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-04-18 00:53:39', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (511, 'Pilot\'s Fatal Plot: Lawn Mower Death Scene \'Manipulated\' in Murder Case', 'An air force pilot is accused of turning a tragic lawn mower accident into a murder scene. CSI: Backyard Edition.', 'Buckle up for the most unhinged true-crime plot this side of Midsomer Murders. Queensland pilot Gregory Lynn is now standing trial for allegedly murdering two elderly campers, Russell Hill and Carol Clay, and trying to cover it up with a scene so clumsy it couldve been a deleted scene from CSI: Outback. The prosecution says Lynn staged a lawn mower accident to make the deaths look like a bushland mishap. Spoiler: it didnt fool anyone.\n\nLynn, 57, was camping near the remote Wonnangatta Valley in 2020 when Hill and Clay vanished. The lovers had been secretly rendezvousing for years (because why should teenagers have all the sneaky romance fun?) and were last heard from via a crackly radio call. Their charred campsite was later discoveredalong with Lynns explanation that they died in a tragic lawn mower blaze gone wrong. Yes, really.\n\nFast forward to this week: prosecutors allege Lynn not only killed the pair, but also tried to torch their remains, burn their belongings, and stage the whole scene to look like an unfortunate machinery accident. His defence? That there was a struggle and things just spiralled into accidental arson. As you do.\n\nZooming out, this isnt just a bushland murder mysteryits now one of the most bizarre and high-profile trials in Victoria. A retired Jetstar captain accused of double murder, a love affair turned tragedy, and a crime scene more suspicious than a politicians tax return.\n\nLatest update: forensic experts testified the scene had been manipulated, calling out inconsistencies between burn patterns, object placement, and Lynns story. The trial continues, but one things clearthis plot has more twists than a garden hose in summer.\n\nSources: ABC News, The Age, 9News, Guardian Australia', 0, 'factabot', 'pilots-fatal-plot-lawn-mower-death-scene-manipulated-in-murder-case', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-04-21 11:03:11', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (512, 'Albanese\'s $1K Tax Tease: Election Bribe or Generous Gesture?', 'PM promises a $1,000 tax deduction for every Aussie worker. Because who doesn\'t love a pre-election sugar hit?', 'Anthony Albanese is playing Oprah with taxpayer money againexcept this time, instead of handing out cars, hes dangling a $1,000 tax cut in front of voters like a shiny pre-election chew toy. The cash sweetener was unveiled ahead of the May budget, but lets be honest: it smells less like fiscal policy and more like campaign cologne.\n\nThe PM says its cost-of-living relief for middle-income earners. Critics say its vote-buying in a discount suit. Meanwhile, Peter Dutton has resorted to economic fan fiction, accusing Labor of being simultaneously too generous and not generous enough.\n\nThis isnt Labors first flirtation with tax theatrics. The government scrapped the Morrison-era Stage 3 cuts earlier this year, then rebranded them with slightly more progressive opticsbut not enough to scare the mortgage belt. Now, this $1K handout is being sold as targeted relief, not a bribe. Just like politicians always listen during community consultation sessions.\n\nZooming out, it\'s a masterclass in political theatre. Dangle cash. Blame inflation on everyone else. Smile for Sunrise. Rinse, repeat.\n\nLatest? The Coalition hasnt ruled out matching the tax cut, which means we might be entering a delightful bidding war where the only winner is whichever party can most effectively weaponise Treasury spreadsheets.\n\nSources: ABC News, The Australian, Guardian Australia, 7News\n', 0, 'factabot', 'albaneses-1k-tax-tease-election-bribe-or-generous-gesture', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-04-23 12:46:47', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (513, 'Katy Perry\'s Space Odyssey: Pop Star Joins All-Women Rocket Launch', 'Katy Perry blasts off on an all-female spaceflight. From pop charts to star charts.', 'Because nothing says girl power like launching a pop star into low Earth orbit, Katy Perry is now strapped inmetaphoricallyfor an upcoming all-female space mission organised by Blue Origin. Yes, that Blue Origin. Yes, Jeff Bezos\' Blue Origin. Because obviously, Firework was a foreshadowing.\n\nPerry joins a star-studded astronaut roster including aviator Gopi Thotakura and entrepreneur Ed Dwight (the first Black astronaut candidate). While Perry isnt technically flying the rocket (yet), shes been vocal in her support for the historic launch and has been jokingly prepping zero-gravity eyeliner and space-themed setlists on socials.\n\nThis is Blue Origins seventh crewed mission, and its first to feature only women. Bezos, who previously shot Captain Kirk into space, seems hell-bent on turning the cosmos into a billionaire-sponsored Comic-Con.\n\nCulturally, its a win for visibility. Scientifically? Eh, its a suborbital selfie at best. But its hard to hate on a space trip that blends STEM, spectacle, and sequins. After all, if tech bros get to cosplay astronauts, why cant pop stars?\n\nLaunch is scheduled for early May, pending safety checks and influencer schedules. Whether Perry\'s headed to the stratosphere or just stealing the photo op, one thing\'s certain: NASA is definitely side-eyeing this.\n\nSources: ABC News, News.com.au, Reuters, Variety', 0, 'factabot', 'katy-perrys-space-odyssey-pop-star-joins-all-women-rocket-launch', 'draft', 'images/news/385f9145-2551-43c6-85b3-1fa606f8f152.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-03 07:51:25', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (514, 'Willie Rioli Takes Leave Amid Online Abuse After Instagram Post', 'Port Adelaide star steps back from the game following a storm of racist comments. Social media strikes again.', 'Port Adelaide star Willie Rioli has stepped away from the game after a barrage of online abuse that followed a controversial Instagram postbecause apparently, scoring goals comes with a side of racial vilification now. Again.\n\nRiolis since-deleted post referenced the death of Indigenous teen Fred Amos during a police pursuit in Perth, accompanied by the hashtag #justice. Cue a storm of outrage, racist vitriol, and the kind of toxic online commentary that proves Australia still hasnt learned how to talk about race without imploding.\n\nThe AFL says its supporting Rioli. Translation: releasing generic statements while hoping it all blows over before the next round. Meanwhile, fans are divided, and Indigenous players across the league are once again left carrying the emotional burden of calling out injustice and performing under stadium lights.\n\nIts not the first time Riolis name has trended for reasons unrelated to footy. The 28-year-old has faced everything from suspension to spotlight, and through it all, the media has been quicker to dissect his tone than address the racism aimed at him.\n\nThis week, Rioli requested time away from the club, with Ports leadership backing his decision. One silver lining? The scandal has sparked fresh calls for stronger AFL protocols on social media abuse. Again. For the fifth time in five years.\n\nSources: ABC Sport, AFL.com.au, The Age, 7News\n', 0, 'factabot', 'willie-rioli-takes-leave-amid-online-abuse-after-instagram-post', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-02 20:15:53', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (515, 'Outback Town Drenched: Levee Breaks, Floodwaters Rise', 'Thargomindah faces devastation as a levee failure leads to widespread flooding. Nature\'s not playing fair.', 'Its raining, its pouringand the outback is absolutely drowning. The tiny Queensland town of Winton, better known for dinosaurs and dusty pubs, is now flooded after the local levee gave up the ghost. Locals woke up to find streets turned into streams and pub beer gardens doubling as wading pools.\n\nThe levee, designed to protect the town from the sort of rain youd expect once every few decades, was overwhelmed by a one-in-50-year downpour that decided to show up uninvited and angry. Authorities say over 100mm fell overnight, with emergency crews scrambling to help stranded residents and livestock alike.\n\nThis isnt Wintons first soggy rodeo, but with roads cut off and power patchy, the situation is turning biblical. Locals are using tinny boats to move essentials, while the council pleads with gawkers to stop popping by to see the chaos. Yes, someone did try to launch a kayak down the main drag. No, they werent wearing a life vest.\n\nThe bigger story? Climate-fuelled weather events are becoming routine, and infrastructure built for last century isnt keeping up. Insurance costs are skyrocketing, federal response times are glacial, and small towns like Winton are left swimmingliterallyin neglect.\n\nSources: ABC News, Courier-Mail, BOM, The Guardian', 0, 'factabot', 'outback-town-drenched-levee-breaks-floodwaters-rise', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-04-20 08:08:37', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (516, 'Paraplegic Stands Again with Robotic Help: Sci-Fi Meets Reality', 'A paraplegic man takes steps with the aid of a robotic device. The future is now, and it\'s walking.', 'Call off the next Iron Man rebootscience just gave us something better. A Perth paraplegic has stood and taken steps for the first time in over a decade, thanks to a robotic exoskeleton that looks straight out of The Matrix and moves like a dream on steel stilts.\n\nThe man, injured in a motorcycle crash 14 years ago, was trialling a Japanese-designed exosuit as part of a new rehab program at Fiona Stanley Hospital. Once strapped in, the suit senses muscle signals and translates them into movementbasically like borrowing a set of robot legs from a sci-fi future.\n\nCue tears, applause, and a ton of people asking if its covered by Medicare (spoiler: its not). The machine costs upwards of $150,000, but for patients and researchers alike, its a glimpse at what modern medicine can actually do when its not arguing over bulk billing caps.\n\nWhile it wont replace wheelchairs overnight, the tech is a massive leapliterallyfor mobility therapy. Its not about walking marathons. Its about dignity, independence, and telling gravity to get stuffed.\n\nLatest update? The hospitals seeking funding for a full pilot program, with hopes the tech could be rolled out in more Aussie clinics. Until then, the dream walks one robotic step at a time.\n\nSources: ABC Perth, WA Health, The West Australian, 7News\n', 0, 'factabot', 'paraplegic-stands-again-with-robotic-help-sci-fi-meets-reality', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-02 20:51:54', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (517, 'Craft Beer Flooded by Supermarket Giants: Indie Brewers Cry Foul', 'Independent brewers accuse big supermarkets of saturating the market. It\'s a hoppy mess.', 'Crack open a cold oneunless its from your local indie brewer, because theyre getting squeezed harder than a lime in a Corona. Australias independent beer scene is under siege as Coles and Woolies ramp up their craft-style private label beers, pushing tiny brewers to the edge of extinction.\n\nBig chains are now stocking their shelves with fake craftlocally inspired beers that sound artisanal but are brewed en masse in factories bigger than the actual towns they claim to represent. The prices? Dirt cheap. The marketing? Suspiciously hip. The impact? Brutal.\n\nIndie brewers say they cant compete with supermarket scale and shelf space dominance. Even popular names like Young Henrys and Balter (which, yes, is now owned by CUB) are feeling the pinch. And dont even mention tap contractsthose are locked up tighter than Dan Murphys on Good Friday.\n\nBehind the fizzy facade, its another David vs Goliath moment. Except Goliath has a marketing team and unlimited hops. And while consumers think theyre drinking small-batch, handcrafted bliss, theyre mostly chugging down corporate cosplay in a brown bottle.\n\nIndustry leaders are now calling for mandatory labelling that separates real independents from the conglomerate cosplay crowd. Until then, its buyer bewareand brewers screaming into their fermenters.\n\nSources: Brews News, ABC Rural, Sydney Morning Herald, Financial Review\n', 0, 'factabot', 'craft-beer-flooded-by-supermarket-giants-indie-brewers-cry-foul', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-02 05:13:54', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (518, 'Lady Gaga\'s Aussie Tour Tickets Cause Fan Frenzy Over Pricing', 'Fans are reeling over ticket prices for Lady Gaga\'s upcoming Australian tour. Poker face? More like broke-er face.', 'Mother Monster is coming down under, but judging by the ticket prices, she might be flying first class on a private unicorn. Lady Gagas upcoming Australian tour dates triggered a full-blown meltdown this week as presale seats launched with prices that ranged from \"meh\" to \"do I have to sell a kidney?\"\n\nBasic seats? Around $250. Decent view? Over $400. VIP experience with a blurry Polaroid and half a handshake? Pushing $900. Fans rushed Ticketek like it was a Black Friday stampede, only to be met with queue crashes, page reloads, and soul-crushing sold out messages.\n\nNaturally, Little Monsters took to Twitter/X to air their grievances. Some blamed bots, some blamed capitalism, and some just posted crying memes wearing meat dresses.\n\nThis isnt the first time a megastars Aussie tour turned into a financial Hunger Games. Taylor, Beyonc, now Gagait\'s clear that concert tickets are the new crypto. Price surges, mystery fees, and dynamic pricing that somehow always feels like punishment for having taste.\n\nLatest twist? Resale sites are now listing seats at double the original price, with fans begging Live Nation to intervene while simultaneously begging their banks for a loan.\n\nSources: The Music, Pedestrian.TV, ABC News, Ticketek', 0, 'factabot', 'lady-gagas-aussie-tour-tickets-cause-fan-frenzy-over-pricing', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-05 12:05:21', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (519, 'Tiny Slice of Sydney Up for Sale at $60K: The Catch? It\'s Minuscule', 'A postage-stamp-sized plot in Sydney hits the market for $60,000. Location, location, lack of space.', 'Real estate in Sydney has officially jumped the sharkand landed on a patch of dirt smaller than a doormat. This week, a 1.6 square metre slice of land in Chippendale hit the market for $60,000. Thats $37,500 per square metrefor a plot you couldnt even pitch a tent on without breaking council bylaws.\n\nThe listing proudly describes the site as rare and unique, which is just real estate code for completely useless, but we dare you. Technically, the land could be used for storage or a caf table, but realistically its the size of a pizza box and about as practical as buying a driveway in Monaco.\n\nOf course, the internet ran wild with ideas. Pop-up espresso stand? Tiny gallery for one ant? An NFT museum with zero shade and negative equity?\n\nBut underneath the viral chaos is a reminder of just how bonkers Sydney\'s property market has become. First homebuyers cant afford actual homes, but someones paying sixty grand for an awkward crack in the pavement with postcode clout.\n\nThe auction is still open, and realtors are betting on hype over function. Which, to be fair, is basically the entire Sydney housing model anyway.\n\nSources: Domain, News.com.au, The Guardian', 0, 'factabot', 'tiny-slice-of-sydney-up-for-sale-at-60k-the-catch-its-minuscule', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-04-18 12:44:19', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (520, 'Fish and Chip Shop Owner Serves Up Sass to Salty Customers', 'A fish and chip shop owner claps back at rude patrons online. Serving seafood and shade.', 'Over in Victoria, one fish and chip shop owner is fighting the cost-of-living crisisand rude customerswith deep-fried sass and a side of sarcasm. When complaints over prices and long waits flooded her Facebook page, owner Lynnie clapped back with responses so spicy they belong in the tartare sauce.\n\nOne post read: Were not McDonalds. We dont flash fry frozen cardboard. We make food. It takes time. Calm down. Another? If you want fish for $2, go buy bait.\n\nLynnies pub-level roasts have now gone viral, with her no-nonsense attitude earning praise from customers who are tired of keyboard warriors and entitlement masquerading as feedback.\n\nBehind the banter is a real struggle: ingredient prices are up, staff costs are rising, and small businesses are barely scraping by. But while some shop owners grovel for good reviews, Lynnies approach is simpledont like it? Dont come back. Or do. Shes not fussed.\n\nThis week, the shop saw a surge in orders thanks to the viral sassstorm, with regulars posting selfies next to a chalkboard that now reads: We dont argue with clowns.\n\nSources: 9News, ABC Regional, The Age, Facebook\n', 0, 'factabot', 'fish-and-chip-shop-owner-serves-up-sass-to-salty-customers', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-02 22:22:00', 12);
