INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (657, 'Dutton\'s Nuclear Plan Faces Radioactive Backlash in Gippsland', 'Nationals MP Darren Chester calls for a \'calm conversation\' on nuclear energy but seems to have misplaced his RSVP to community meetings. Constituents feel ghosted, and the only thing glowing is their frustration.', 'Peter Duttons nuclear energy crusade is getting some serious static in Gippsland, and its not just from old AM radios. Nationals MP Darren Chester, usually the regions political mascot, is now playing hide-and-seek with his own voters while calling for a calm conversation on nuclear power. Calm wouldve been greatif hed shown up to any of the actual community meetings. Locals say they feel ghosted, and honestly, Darrens RSVP game is weaker than a dodgy power grid in a blackout. This from the man who once declared wind turbines visual pollution, but apparently radioactive waste is just rustic charm?\n\nHeres the tea: Dutton and his Coalition comrades are dusting off the nuclear debate like its a vintage recordexcept nobody asked for a remix. Their shiny new plan wants to plonk small modular reactors into regions like Gippsland, home to the now-defunct Hazelwood coal plant. The idea? Replace one environmental headache with another, but this time make it glow. Locals, however, arent lining up for radioactive roulette. Instead, theyre demanding consultation, transparency, and some actual detailpreferably before the uranium hits the fan.\n\nZooming out, the whole thing smells a lot like political cosplay. Duttons nuclear pitch is being marketed as clean energy, even as his party trashes renewables at every other opportunity. Lets not forget this is the same Coalition that gutted climate policy for years, and now suddenly wants to play Captain Planet. Theres also a global cost curve to reckon with: nuclear is slow, expensive, and notoriously allergic to budget deadlinesperfect for a party obsessed with economic discipline.\n\nThe latest scene? Chester is dodging town halls like theyre TikTok challenges, leaving community groups to fill the vacuum with signs, sass, and serious concern. Gippslanders arent anti-energytheyre anti-BS. And if Dutton thinks theyll glow along quietly, he might want to rethink that reactor placement preferably from a safe distance.', 0, 'factabot', 'duttons-nuclear-plan-faces-radioactive-backlash-in-gippsland', 'published', 'images/news/cdda78e7-b95c-44bf-9ba4-2db69904eace.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-06 22:39:59', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (658, 'Leaders\' Debate Turns into \'Liar, Liar\' Match; Truth Still Missing', 'The third leaders\' debate devolved into a playground spat with both sides hurling \'liar\' accusations. Meanwhile, voters search for policies amidst the name-calling.', 'Australia tuned in for the third leaders\' debate hoping for substance and maybejust maybea policy. Instead, we got a live-action reboot of Mean Girls: Canberra Edition. Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton took turns playing No, youre the liar while dodging anything resembling actual solutions. Viewers came for policy but left with popcorn salt in their eyes and whiplash from the mutual finger-pointing. Albanese accused Dutton of fearmongering, Dutton responded by calling Labors promises fantasy fiction, and at no point did anyone define a single budget number. It was less a debate and more a duel of denial, with truth fleeing the stage early and possibly requesting asylum. One brave voter asked, So whats actually the plan? and was promptly escorted off camera by securitypresumably for speaking common sense.\nSources: The Guardian Australia (23 Apr 2025), ABC News (23 Apr 2025), SBS News (23 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'leaders-debate-turns-into-liar-liar-match-truth-still-missing', 'published', 'images/news/513dd19a-b0dc-4f8c-b564-cbc3f3755e7d.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-07 12:39:02', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (659, 'IMF Warns Trump\'s Trade Tantrums Could Cost Australia $13B', 'The IMF rings the alarm bell as Trump\'s trade policies threaten to drain Australia\'s coffers by $13 billion annually. Time to check the couch cushions for spare change.', 'Donald Trumps latest foreign policy plan (read: global temper tantrum) has the IMF clutching pearls and calculators. According to the newly released report, Trumps proposed tariff warshould he reclaim the presidencycould carve a neat $13 billion hole in Australias GDP every year. Thats roughly the cost of building five more stadiums no one asked for. Canberra, meanwhile, is still trying to figure out whether to send a strongly worded letter or just start hoarding Vegemite. The fallout would primarily hit exporters, especially in mining and agriculturebecause nothing says Make America Great Again like punishing your allies. And in a plot twist no one saw coming, the report warns Australia might need to pick sides. Spoiler: either way, we pay.\nSources: AFR (23 Apr 2025), The Australian (23 Apr 2025), IMF Official Report (23 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'imf-warns-trumps-trade-tantrums-could-cost-australia-13b', 'published', 'images/news/4869f6ec-d683-4099-8f35-f0e7af4d0265.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-07 00:59:22', 24);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (660, 'Jack Draper Backs Jannik Sinner Post-Ban; Tennis Drama Ensues', 'In the latest episode of \'As the Tennis World Turns,\' Jack Draper throws support behind Jannik Sinner after his ban, stirring the pot and the press.', 'Wimbledon? Nah, this is Real Housewives: ATP Tour. British up-and-comer Jack Draper has tossed his sweatband into the drama ring by publicly backing Jannik Sinner following the Italians controversial doping ban. In a move that made tennis Twitter implode, Draper posted that Sinner was treated unfairly and still a role modelinstantly triggering a flood of angry emojis, split loyalties, and one very awkward post-match handshake. Sinner, for his part, is keeping a low profile (and probably switching to herbal tea). The ATP hasnt commented, but behind closed doors, you can bet there are PR reps asking, Why couldnt he just say nothing? Its giving Serena-Venus energy, if Serena had also written a 7-part Instagram essay about justice. Game, set, soap opera.\nSources: The Age (23 Apr 2025), 9News (23 Apr 2025), BBC Sport (23 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'jack-draper-backs-jannik-sinner-post-ban-tennis-drama-ensues', 'published', 'images/news/010f14c0-5934-4295-bbf7-50e983a38008.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-07 01:34:58', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (661, 'Santos\' Barossa Gasfield Gets Green Light on Earth Day', 'In a move that screams \'timing is everything,\' Santos received approval for its Barossa gasfield project on Earth Day, sparking environmentalists\' fury.', 'Youve got to admire the audacity. On Earth Daya day literally dedicated to not wrecking the planetSantos scored federal approval for its Barossa gasfield project. Thats right, while the rest of us were reposting climate infographics and pretending to recycle, the fossil fuel giant was handed the keys to a carbon-spewing megaproject off the Northern Territory coast. Timing isnt just ironicits borderline performance art.\n\nAt the centre of this plot twist is the National Offshore Petroleum Safety and Environmental Management Authority (NOPSEMA), which approved Santos revised drilling plan just hours before Earth Day candlelit vigils kicked off. Environmental groups were predictably livid, accusing the government of saying one thing and drilling another. Climate activist groups like Environment Centre NT and the Australian Conservation Foundation called it cynical and embarrassingwhich is pretty generous considering the circumstances.\n\nTo zoom out, the Barossa project has already made a name for itself globallyfor all the wrong reasons. A 2023 study dubbed it one of the dirtiest offshore gas projects on the planet. It\'s not just about emissionsFirst Nations groups like the Tiwi and Larrakia peoples have also raised red flags over cultural consultation, or the lack thereof.\n\nAnd yet, here we are, watching a government that claims to care deeply about net zero hand over environmental permission slips on the one day thats supposed to mean something. Its like celebrating Dry July with a whisky-fuelled karaoke night. But sure, tell us again about green growth.\n\nSources: ABC News (23 Apr 2025), The Guardian (23 Apr 2025), SBS News (23 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'santos-barossa-gasfield-gets-green-light-on-earth-day', 'published', 'images/news/85813a83-4142-46ea-bf19-ad1d172f40b2.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-07 10:08:18', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (662, 'Labor\'s $1B Mental Health Plan: Big Talk, Small Change', 'Labor\'s ambitious mental health initiative is under fire for allocating only $16.5 million next fiscal year, raising questions about commitment versus delivery.', 'Labors shiny new mental health plan got its press conference moment this week, with the government touting a billion-dollar commitment to fix a system thats been wheezing for years. Headlines were big, promises were bigger, but the budget figures? Lets just say, blink and youll miss them. The plansold as historicwill funnel just $16.5 million into the system next financial year. Thats 1.65% of the billion-dollar headline. Weve seen more commitment from Netflix subscription renewals.\n\nHealth Minister Mark Butler assured everyone this was the first stage of a long-term rollout, but critics arent buying it. Mental health experts, advocacy groups, and a particularly snarky tweet from a former GP pointed out the obvious: demand is exploding now, not in 2045. Youth mental health services are stretched thinner than a politicians apology, and regional access? Youd have better luck finding a unicorn with a Medicare card.\n\nThe Albanese government claims this is part of a bigger reform puzzle, tied to Medicare revamps and community health hubs. But when patients are being told to wait six months for a psychologistor worse, told to try journalingthis slow-drip strategy starts to feel a lot like spin dressed in scrubs.\n\nThe public response? A collective sigh, with the subtext: Cool story. Wheres the funding? And while Labor gets kudos for at least mentioning mental health (a rarity until recently), the numbers suggest this might be more about headlines than help.\n\nSources: The Australian (23 Apr 2025), 9News (23 Apr 2025), Guardian Australia (23 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'labors-1b-mental-health-plan-big-talk-small-change', 'published', 'images/news/9892ee71-1acf-4210-b86f-9ccf38485129.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-07 06:44:48', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (663, 'ASX Dips Following Wall Street Selloff', 'Australia\'s stock market took a hit after Wall Street\'s downturn, proving that when the U.S. sneezes, the ASX catches a cold.', 'Australias stock market did what it does best todaypanic when America does. After Wall Street took a nasty stumble overnight thanks to tech stocks tanking and bond yields doing the cha-cha, the ASX followed suit like a nervous intern mimicking the boss. The benchmark S&P/ASX 200 dropped nearly 1.2%, wiping billions in market value and several smiles off early-morning traders faces.\n\nThe culprits? Global jitters over another potential U.S. rate hike, persistent inflation woes, and the ever-fun game of Is AI the next bubble? But really, it was just Tuesday in financial markets. Local banks and mining stocks copped the worst of it, with BHP and NAB leading the plunge. Investors rushed to safe havens like gold andbecause this is Australiacoffee.\n\nFor anyone keeping score, this latest wobble reinforces one economic truth: when the U.S. sneezes, we catch a full-blown man flu. It\'s the joy of being economically joined at the hip with a country run by Wall Street algorithms and caffeine-fuelled panic.\n\nAnalysts say the selloff could be temporary and are urging calm, which is a polite way of saying, Please stop refreshing your Super balance every 10 minutes. Meanwhile, retail investors on Reddit are already calling it The Great Dip of April and asking if its time to buy the fear.\n\nSpoiler: its always time to buy the fear. Just maybe not with your rent money.\n\nSources: AFR (23 Apr 2025), The Age (23 Apr 2025), ABC News (23 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'asx-dips-following-wall-street-selloff', 'published', 'images/news/888eaa5b-3802-441f-ab49-3a4e46bbd60a.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-07 01:13:45', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (664, '\'The Cleaner\' Returns to ABC iview with More Crime Scene Comedy', 'BAFTA winner Greg Davies is back as Wicky, the crime scene cleaner who finds humor in the grim, making messes entertaining again.', 'Good news for fans of murder and mop buckets: The Cleaner is back on ABC iview, with BAFTA-winning giant Greg Davies reprising his role as Wicky, the worlds most sarcastic sanitation specialist. Think CSI, but with fewer autopsies and more existential dread. And jokes. Lots of them. In Season 2, Wicky returns to scrub down fresh crime scenes while delivering deadpan monologues, dealing with weird suspects, and wielding bleach like a stand-up comic armed with disinfectant.\n\nDavies, standing somewhere between lovable misanthrope and six-foot-eight chaos magnet, turns crime scene cleanup into a philosophical rollercoaster. Each episode feels like a one-act play dipped in gore, dark humour, and accidental therapy. Expect cameos, chaos, and conversations that would make your HR manager sweat.\n\nThe BBC original found a cult audience in the UK, but ABCs decision to stream it locally has brought Wickys filthy charm Down Under, where were no strangers to laughing at grim realitiesespecially on taxpayer-funded television. The shows timing is no coincidence either. With the country in the middle of an election season, The Cleaner provides a welcome break from real-life messes that cant be wiped away with Dettol.\n\nAnd let\'s be honestafter sitting through three leaders debates that felt like live readings of passive-aggressive emails, watching a man clean up murder scenes is surprisingly cathartic.\n\nSources: ABC iview (23 Apr 2025), Guardian Australia TV Guide (23 Apr 2025), The Age (23 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'the-cleaner-returns-to-abc-iview-with-more-crime-scene-comedy', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-05 23:59:08', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (665, 'Greens\' Campaign Signs Defaced Amid Election Tensions', 'Greens\' election signage was vandalized with offensive graffiti, highlighting the ugly side of political discourse.', 'And just like that, democracy got tagged. The Greens campaign signs have become the latest casualty in an election season thats going full trash fire. Over the past 48 hours, signs in Victoria and Queensland were discovered spray-painted with everything from four-letter words to bizarre conspiracy slogansproof that keyboard warriors are now taking their art offline.\n\nFederal Greens Leader Adam Bandt condemned the vandalism, saying the attacks were cowardly, while volunteers spent the day scrubbing graffiti off corflutes instead of canvassing. Nothing screams vibrant democratic process like having to bring WD-40 and steel wool to your political rallies.\n\nThis kind of vandalism isnt just juvenileits expensive. Printing signs costs thousands, and local candidates are left playing Whac-A-Mole trying to replace them before voters think the Greens have just ghosted their suburbs. It\'s unclear whether the defacers are from rival political groups or just part-time anarchists with a grudge and a Bunnings loyalty card.\n\nThe irony? The Greens are the party most likely to champion free speech and peaceful protestand theyre the ones getting painted like the walls of a post-apocalyptic skate park. The whole thing underscores the rising tensions in whats already shaping up to be one of Australias most combative elections in recent memory.\n\nFree speech is fine. Just maybe not in high-vis at 2am with a can of spray paint and a dictionary full of slurs.\n\nSources: The Guardian (23 Apr 2025), ABC News (23 Apr 2025), SBS (23 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'greens-campaign-signs-defaced-amid-election-tensions', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-07 01:06:02', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (666, 'Tasmania Enjoys Exclusive Easter Tuesday Public Holiday', 'While the rest of Australia returned to work, Tasmanian public servants reveled in an extra day off, making the rest of us green with envy.', 'While the rest of Australia trudged back to work armed with leftover hot cross buns and existential dread, Tasmanians kicked back for Easter Tuesdaya public holiday that exists only on their delightfully rebellious island. Yes, while mainlanders stared blankly at spreadsheets and school runs, public servants in Hobart were enjoying sleep-ins, strolls, and smugness.\n\nEaster Tuesday is the Beyonc of obscure holidays: rare, glamorous, and exclusive to a privileged few. Technically, its a hangover from Tasmanias public sector awardstranslation: if you work in government, congratulations, you win Tuesday. Everyone else? Back to the grind, peasants.\n\nCue the envy on social media as mainlanders discovered the day wasn\'t just a myth. Is this even real? tweeted one confused Victorian, staring at their office calendar like it had betrayed them. The answer is yes, its real. Tasmanias public servants are living your dreamon government time.\n\nMeanwhile, employers in the private sector were forced to clarify for the hundredth time that no, Easter Tuesday is not a thing unless youve got a Tassie postcode and a state-issued lanyard. This annual divide between Tasmanian serenity and mainland chaos is now traditiona low-key flex from the Apple Isle to the rest of us.\n\nSo next time someone says Tasmania is behind the times, remind them theyre ahead of us on public holidays. And probably napping.\n\nSources: ABC News Tasmania (23 Apr 2025), The Mercury (23 Apr 2025), 9News (23 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'tasmania-enjoys-exclusive-easter-tuesday-public-holiday', 'published', 'images/news/d456c425-7178-4122-b473-a036969f5add.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 00:19:05', '2025-05-07 11:11:13', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (667, 'Election Day Looms: Aussies Prep for May 3 Showdown', 'With the federal election set for May 3, Australians are gearing up to cast their votes, as political parties ramp up their campaigns.', 'Australias federal election is officially on its final approach, and if you thought the politicians were annoying before, strap inMay 3 is coming in hot. Anthony Albanese is doing his best impression of a calm, competent Prime Minister, while Peter Duttons giving off strict vice-principal with nuclear launch codes energy. Meanwhile, the Greens are riding the climate panic wave with all the finesse of a Bondi surfer, and the independents are basically saying, Trust us, were not them. Its a national casting call for who gets to ruin your weekends with policy speeches.\n\nThis year\'s dramas been juicier than a MAFS reunion special. Weve had scandals, slogans, and more spin than a washing machine on turbo. Labors juggling housing failures and mental health funding complaints like flaming pins. The Coalitions still trying to make nuclear a buzzword people wont run from, and the Nationals, bless them, are screaming into the void about the bush like its 1974. Every campaign ad feels like it was written by ChatGPT on three Red Bulls and a nostalgia playlist. And were just getting started.\n\nBut heres where it gets spicy: this election could actually shift things. Cost-of-living chaos, rental rage, and climate breakdown fatigue have voters eyeing Canberra with the same trust they give a dodgy used car salesman. Young voters are cranky, older voters are tired, and everyones wondering how we still dont have a proper federal ICAC that doesnt vanish into thin air every election cycle. If this vote swings hard or fragments wildly, the next PM could be leading a government held together with duct tape and optimism.\n\nAnd now, the latest update: the AEC has officially confirmed that May 3 is D-Day. Early voting kicks off next week, and parties are already spamming your letterbox like its 2005. So get your democracy sausages readythis one\'s going to be a barbecue of chaos.\n\nSources:\nABC News (23 Apr 2025)\nThe Guardian Australia (23 Apr 2025)\nThe Australian (23 Apr 2025)\n9News (23 Apr 2025)\nSBS News (23 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'election-day-looms-aussies-prep-for-may-3-showdown', 'published', 'images/news/d426d0fb-d85d-4683-80e1-3266bd5ef9ba.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 05:21:06', '2025-05-07 05:07:15', 26);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (668, 'Key Seats in Focus: Coalition Eyes Victory Path', 'The Coalition targets crucial electorates as they strategize for a potential win in the upcoming federal election.', 'Peter Dutton has whipped out his red string and whiteboard markers to map a victory route through key electorates like hes hunting Carmen Sandiego. The Coalitions hopes are pinned on a few marginal seats where voters flip faster than pancakes on a hungover Sunday. From outer suburban battlegrounds to teal-infested waters, theyre throwing promises, cash, and very confused volunteers at anything that moves. Josh Frydenberg is back in the mix too, popping up like a forgotten app you thought youd deleted, while the Nationals are busy holding town halls that mostly serve as anti-solar therapy sessions.\n\nThis isnt just any seat huntits survival. After getting booted in 2022, the Liberals know they need to charm swing voters while dodging landmines like climate policy and the ghost of Morrison past. Some candidates are touting local projects like they\'re Oprah handing out bridges and roundabouts, while others are ducking debates entirely, hoping voters confuse silence with wisdom. And yes, Sky News has already pre-written six variations of Stunning Comeback just in case.\n\nIf the Coalition does claw its way back, itll be thanks to surgical campaigning and a very forgiving national memory. Or just dumb luck. Either way, its clear theyre playing to wineven if the rest of us lose.\n\nSources:\nABC News, The Guardian Australia, 9News  All on 23 Apr 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'key-seats-in-focus-coalition-eyes-victory-path', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-23 05:21:06', '2025-05-07 04:52:03', 26);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (669, 'Giro d\'Italia 2025: Stage 13 Kicks Off in Rovigo', 'Cycling enthusiasts turn their attention to Italy as the Giro d\'Italia\'s 13th stage commences, featuring a 180km route from Rovigo to Vicenza.', 'Nothing says European elegance like Lycra, leg cramps, and 180 kilometres of sweaty glory. Stage 13 of the Giro dItalia launched in Rovigo today, sending cyclists on a sun-drenched slog to Vicenza, with enough elevation changes to ruin a perfectly good espresso. The peloton, looking like a parade of hyper-fit jellybeans, snaked through the Italian countryside as teams played tactical chess at 50km/h.\n\nThe starsTadej, Remco, and companyare riding like caffeinated gazelles, while everyone else tries not to crash into signage or each other. Sprinters are hanging on by sheer spite. The Italians? Cheering wildly, waving flags, and pretending cycling matters more than footballat least until dinner. Meanwhile, Aussie fans watching from couches at 2am are struggling to tell whos winning but loving the drone shots of vineyards.\n\nWill this stage decide the race? Probably not. But it sure makes for great scenery while we all avoid real-life responsibilities.\n\nSources:\nCyclingNews, SBS Sport, Giro dItalia Official Site  23 Apr 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'giro-ditalia-2025-stage-13-kicks-off-in-rovigo', 'published', 'images/news/bed4046d-876e-4d61-8249-a9bc779c47f6.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 05:21:06', '2025-05-07 06:11:15', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (670, 'Paris-Nice 2025: Stage 5 Delivers Thrills', 'Cyclists tackle a challenging 196.5km route from Saint-Just-en-Chevalet to La Cote-Saint-Andre in the fifth stage of Paris-Nice 2025.', 'The Paris-Nice Stage 5 was a buffet of suffering, strategy, and spectacular scenery. Riders endured 196.5km of French hill hell from Saint-Just-en-Chevalet to La Cote-Saint-Andre, a route so scenic it almost distracted from the lactic acid searing through their thighs. Almost.\n\nThe stage kicked off with a breakaway that was doomed from the moment it startedclassic. Midway through, crosswinds turned the peloton into a blender of broken dreams. GC contenders threw shade with their pedals, domestiques dug deep into their pain caves, and a few unlucky souls kissed the tarmac like it owed them money. The French crowds? Loud, proud, and still furious no one calls it Nice-Paris.\n\nIn the end, a lean-legged hero crossed the line in dramatic fashion while the rest just tried not to cry on live TV. As for the Aussieshanging in there, giving it a nudge, and reminding the world that yes, we do more than cricket.\n\nSources:\nLEquipe, Cycling Weekly, Paris-Nice 2025 Official Site  23 Apr 2025\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'paris-nice-2025-stage-5-delivers-thrills', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-23 05:21:06', '2025-05-07 11:56:58', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (671, 'Climate Anxiety on the Rise Among Australians', 'A growing number of Australians report experiencing climate anxiety, reflecting increasing concern over environmental issues.', 'Turns out watching your country catch fire, flood, and fry like a forgotten sausage isnt great for the ol mental health. Shocker. New reports show climate anxiety is skyrocketing across Australia, especially among young people whod quite like to retire on a planet that still exists. Therapists are hearing more about melting glaciers than breakups, and climate dread is now a hotter topic than dating apps.\n\nThis isnt just garden-variety worryits existential doom with an SPF rating. Kids are asking if school matters when the reefs dying. Adults are googling how to make your house float. Meanwhile, politicians are throwing around net-zero targets like confetti at a wedding, but actual emissions? Still puffing along nicely. And when climate action is reduced to planting a tree and calling it a day, its no wonder people are spiralling.\n\nBut heres the kicker: the fossil-fuel cheer squad still says were being dramatic. Tell that to the koalas on fire. Or the insurance companies quietly packing up shop in flood zones. Welcome to eco-anxiety 101no cure yet, but at least were all freaking out together.\n\nSources:\nABC News, The Guardian Australia, SBS  23 Apr 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'climate-anxiety-on-the-rise-among-australians', 'published', 'images/news/3821e8d6-740b-4171-bd1b-205d45ea7816.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 05:21:06', '2025-05-07 04:34:55', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (672, 'Bulk Billing Boost: Labor Pledges $8.5B for GP Services', 'The Labor government announces a significant investment to expand bulk billing and GP training programs across Australia.', 'Anthony Albanese has reached into the federal wallet and pulled out a very shiny $8.5 billion, promising a bulk billing glow-up that would make Medicare blush. Its all part of Labors we swear we care healthcare push, with extra funding for GP services, training, andpresumablymore chairs in the waiting room from the 80s.\n\nIt sounds generous, but dont go booking your check-up just yet. The fine print reveals most of the cash hits later, with doctors still fleeing the profession faster than patients Googling symptoms. Bulk billing clinics are rarer than a polite driver on Parramatta Road, and this plan is basically a CPR attempt on a system thats already halfway out the door.\n\nStill, its election season, and nothing says vote for us like promising to fix what you broke. Cue awkward photo ops with stethoscopes, while voters wonder if this will actually change anythingor if its just another prescription for media headlines.\n\nSources:\n9News, ABC News, The Australian  23 Apr 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'bulk-billing-boost-labor-pledges-85b-for-gp-services', 'published', 'images/news/d798124d-c85f-4f29-a9a9-14ceccb2b8a2.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 05:21:06', '2025-05-07 00:43:52', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (673, 'Interest Rate Cuts Delayed: ANZ Revises Forecast', 'ANZ becomes the third major bank to push back its forecast for interest rate cuts, signaling prolonged financial strain for borrowers.', 'Hope you werent budgeting for relief this yearANZ has joined the financial buzzkill club, delaying its prediction for interest rate cuts to checks notes sometime between maybe later and ask again never. The Reserve Banks tight grip remains firmly on, as inflation refuses to sit down and behave, and mortgage-holders across Australia collectively scream into throw pillows.\n\nIts not just ANZ. NAB and Westpac have already moved the goalposts, proving that in banking, herd mentality is the only thing stronger than interest. The result? Borrowers are bracing for more pain, while renters are stuck in a cost-of-living soap opera that somehow has no ending. Meanwhile, economists toss around words like resilience and soft landing like those actually help anyone afford eggs.\n\nThe real winners here? Bank shareholders, again. Everyone else? Back to Aldi, ditching the smashed avo, and pretending that skipping one Uber ride will save your house.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian Australia, AFR, ABC News  23 Apr 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'interest-rate-cuts-delayed-anz-revises-forecast', 'published', 'images/news/bb9d95b3-a87c-4202-aa86-69293591b033.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 05:21:06', '2025-05-07 12:24:36', 22);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (674, 'The Lemonheads Return: Australian Tour Dates Announced', 'Fans rejoice as The Lemonheads announce their Australian tour, celebrating classic albums with performances across major cities.', 'Dust off your Doc Martens and emotionally prepare to feel very oldThe Lemonheads are heading Down Under, ready to serenade you with tunes from a time when mixtapes were a love language. Evan Dando, the man who once made being beautifully dishevelled an art form, will hit stages across major Aussie cities, armed with a setlist that screams Gen X therapy session.\n\nThe tour promises a full album performance of Its a Shame About Ray, aka the soundtrack to every 90s breakup, drive, and moment of existential dread in a flannel shirt. Fans are already panic-buying tickets and asking themselves if their knees can survive general admission. Millennials, meanwhile, are explaining to Gen Z that yes, there was music before Spotify, and no, The Lemonheads have nothing to do with citrus TikToks.\n\nIts not just a concertits a pilgrimage. One night to relive the grunge era without the dial-up. Just dont expect moshing; this crowds more \"stand still and cry softly into their Coopers.\"\n\nSources:\nThe Music, NME Australia, Rolling Stone AU  23 Apr 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'the-lemonheads-return-australian-tour-dates-announced', 'published', 'images/news/7ec4f3a2-e6ce-490d-b9af-089f77de1f3e.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 05:21:06', '2025-05-07 11:44:25', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (675, 'Housing Market Watch: Property Prices Under Scrutiny', 'Experts analyze current trends in the housing market, noting fluctuations and potential impacts on buyers and sellers.', 'In today\'s episode of As the Market Turns, economists have once again donned their reading glasses and panic spreadsheets to announce: maybe things are cooling down, but also maybe not. Australias housing market continues its hobby of defying logic and ruining lives, as experts debate whether price drops are real or just a hallucination caused by mortgage stress and low iron.\n\nSellers are clutching their million-dollar terraces like family heirlooms, while buyers circle like vultures with pre-approvals that no longer buy anything within 30km of a train station. Regional areas, once the great escape, now have price tags that scream LOL, stay in Sydney. Meanwhile, real estate agents are giving TED Talks on renovators dreams that look like haunted sheds.\n\nThe RBAs rate pause hasnt brought the promised relief, and the markets in a weird holding pattern where nothing sells, but everythings still overpriced. In other words, classic Aussie housing: all hype, no mercy.\n\nSources:\nDomain, CoreLogic, The Guardian Australia  23 Apr 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'housing-market-watch-property-prices-under-scrutiny', 'published', 'images/news/460d4d1b-e139-4cf4-9cc3-c9a724cc1102.webp', NULL, '2025-04-23 05:21:06', '2025-05-06 18:43:02', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (676, 'Russia Eyeing the Pacific, Indonesia Has a Panic Attack', 'Indonesia crashes into Australia\'s DMs like \"help pls\" after rumours of Russia parking military toys in the Pacific. Canberra now playing babysitter in the geopolitical group chat.', 'So, Russia just slid a little closer to Australias doorstep, and Indonesia straight-up hit the geopolitical panic button. The drama kicked off when Jakarta caught wind of Moscow allegedly flirting with the idea of parking some military hardware in the Pacific. Cue Defence Minister Prabowo Subianto bursting into Canberras DMs like Guys???and not in a chill way. Prabowo, a retired general with a complicated military past and the subtlety of a jackhammer, doesnt usually do panic. So when he does, everyone else sits up straight and stops sipping their bubble tea.\n\nNow lets rewind. The rumour mill started churning after Russian Navy boss Admiral Nikolai Yevmenov was spotted gallivanting around the Pacific talking logistics, ports, and regional cooperation, which, in Kremlin-speak, usually means were about to build something with missiles. Russias been increasingly chummy with nations not currently ghosting it over Ukraine, and the Pacific offers prime beachfront property for flexing. Add to that some quiet whispers about possible base expansion near Papua New Guinea or even in Micronesia, and Indonesia is suddenly very aware of just how close all this military cosplay is getting to home.\n\nHeres where it gets juicier. Australia, always up for playing regional chaperone when things get spicy, stepped into the chat with its usual we value regional stability linetranslation: Can everyone please just not? Canberra is already juggling Chinas vibe checks in the South China Sea, the Solomons strategic side-eye, and now Russia possibly dusting off its Cold War boots. Its giving stress parent at a birthday party, and honestly, who can blame them?\n\nAs of this morning, Indonesias government confirmed ongoing talks with Australia about collective responses, which is diplomatic code for what the hell is going on. Meanwhile, Russia has neither confirmed nor denied the plans, which, lets be real, is pretty on-brand.\n\nSources:\nABC News Australia  Indonesia raises alarm over Russian Pacific activity (24 Apr 2025)\nThe Australian  Moscows Pacific moves trigger Jakarta concerns (24 Apr 2025)\nSouth China Morning Post  Russia hints at new naval presence in the Pacific (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'russia-eyeing-the-pacific-indonesia-has-a-panic-attack', 'published', 'images/news/44528687-297c-4a35-9c6a-6a79501c045d.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 09:52:07', 19);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (677, 'Nuclear? Yeah Nah, Say Aussies with Glowing Confidence', 'Turns out the only radiation Aussies want is from the sun. Poll says no thanks to nukesunless they come with free sunscreen and zero meltdowns.', 'Peter Dutton might be dreaming of a nuclear-powered Australia, but most Aussies just want their power bills lower without needing a Geiger counter. A brand-new Essential poll shows nearly 60% of Australians still give a big yeah, nah to nuclear energyunless, of course, its solar-powered uranium with a side of beach tanning and no chance of a Chernobyl sequel. Energy Minister Chris Bowen practically backflipped with glee, waving the numbers around like a primary school science trophy.\n\nBut Dutton, ever the designated driver of bad ideas, keeps doubling down on his nuclear crush. He insists its clean, modern, and totally not the death trap it used to be. Unfortunately, decades of Simpsons reruns and actual global disasters have Australians associating nuclear with glowing fish, not stable grid infrastructure.\n\nThis whole debate plays out like a sci-fi reboot nobody asked for. The Coalition wants to look tech-savvy while sidestepping renewables, Labors doing smug laps around wind farms, and voters? Theyre just trying to keep the lights on without sparking Armageddon. Even industry experts are side-eyeing nuclears cost, timeline, and the awkward detail of where to stash the radioactive leftovers.\n\nLatest update? The publics answer remains clear: No nukes, pleasewere already hot enough. And unless someone figures out how to power the grid with Bondi Beach vibes, the nuclear fantasy looks set to stay exactly that.\n\nSources:\nGuardian Australia  Australians still opposed to nuclear power, poll shows (24 Apr 2025)\nABC News  Dutton pushes nuclear as Labor rides renewable wave (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'nuclear-yeah-nah-say-aussies-with-glowing-confidence', 'published', 'images/news/b3047354-bb29-47cb-a612-39c8d216e4d5.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 14:27:58', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (678, 'Trump Ditches Peace Talks, Blames Zelenskyy Like Its Reality TV', 'Trump rage-quits diplomacy againthis time blaming Zelenskyy for ruining his peace deal storyline. Stay tuned for next weeks episode: \"Diplomatic Meltdowns: The Remix.\"', 'Donald Trump just rage-quit diplomacy againthis time storming off stage and blaming Volodymyr Zelenskyy for ruining what was apparently a perfectly scripted peace plan moment. He missed his cue! was the vibe, as Trump told a conservative radio host that the Ukrainian president blew the deal and wrecked his shot at ending the war with Russia. Yes, because thats how ceasefires worklike Bachelor rose ceremonies, but with missiles.\n\nTrumps tantrum-tour comes as part of his usual greatest hits album: blame someone else, rewrite history, and throw in a weird anecdote about being loved by the generals. This weeks meltdown included allegations that Zelenskyy was ungrateful, disrespectful, and didnt follow his timeline. The White House, meanwhile, quietly sighed in several languages and moved on.\n\nLets be clear: there was no confirmed deal, no formal offer, and no magical Mar-a-Lago summit where peace was going to bloom over shrimp cocktails. This was all happening in Trumps heador on Truth Social, which is essentially the same thing. Zelenskyy, for his part, hasnt dignified it with much of a reply, probably too busy dodging actual bombs to respond to verbal ones.\n\nIn todays episode of Diplomatic Meltdowns: The Remix, Trump proves once again that if he cant be the hero, hell happily play the victim. Or both. Tune in next week for Why NATO Hates Me (And Why Thats a Compliment).\n\nSources:\nCNN  Trump says Zelenskyy missed opportunity for peace (24 Apr 2025)\nThe Hill  Trump blames Zelenskyy for failed peace push (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-ditches-peace-talks-blames-zelenskyy-like-its-reality-tv', 'published', 'images/news/13a2c6f5-9a9b-4bb3-a75d-f2aeabf38e32.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 03:32:54', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (679, 'From Footy to Touchdown: Aussie Kicker Tries to NFL His Way to Glory', 'Alex Mastromanno punts on AFL dreams and aims for the NFL. Next stop: confusing Americans by actually being good at kicking.', 'Alex Mastromanno is punting his way into American football historyor at least trying to. The former AFL hopeful turned Florida State punter is now eyeing the NFL, proving that when one Aussie door closes, another opens wide, covered in shoulder pads and Doritos dust. Unlike most American kickers who grew up playing Madden, Mastromanno actually has a leg thats done more than deliver pizza.\n\nAustralians making it in the NFL isnt new, but it never stops being funny. Americans watch these guys walk in, talk weird, and then casually boot the pigskin 60 yards like theyre launching satellites. Meanwhile, U.S. commentators lose their minds trying to pronounce Mastromanno without turning it into a pasta dish.\n\nThe juicy backstory? Mastromanno ditched AFL in 2020 and joined the Prokick Australia pipeline, aka the magical boot camp that transforms Aussie rules players into gridiron weapons. He crushed it in college, averaging 45.5 yards per punt and now hopes to snag a draft pick or at least an invite that doesnt end in thanks, but nah.\n\nIf he makes it, hell join the likes of Michael Dickson and Mitch Wishnowsky in the very niche but surprisingly glamorous club of Aussies Who Kick For A Living (In America). The update? Scouts are watching, his agent is sweating, and Mastromannos legs might just be the next big thing in U.S. footballassuming they dont get tackled by bureaucracy or Buffalo snow.\n\nSources:\nThe Age  Alex Mastromanno set sights on NFL draft (24 Apr 2025)\n9News  Aussie punter hoping to make NFL leap (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'from-footy-to-touchdown-aussie-kicker-tries-to-nfl-his-way-to-glory', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 13:00:53', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (680, 'Giant Kangaroos Were the OG Couch Potatoes', 'Ancient mega-roos didnt hop cross-countrythey stayed local and snacked. Evolutions first confirmed case of \"nah, Im good here.\"', 'Forget boxing kangaroosturns out their ancient cousins were the original layabouts. New research reveals that Procoptodon goliah, the extinct giant kangaroo, didnt hop at all. Instead, it waddled, leaned on trees, and basically vibed its way through life like a prehistoric retiree at Bunnings on a Sunday. Scientists from Flinders University dug into its fossilised joints and found these mega-roos were structurally allergic to cardio. Respect.\n\nClocking in at 200 kilograms and standing two metres tall, these thicc icons roamed Australia 40,000 years ago, probably judging smaller roos for trying too hard. Unlike todays twitchy Skippy types, Procoptodon had a swagger, a belly, and an Ill walk when I feel like it attitude. Think: kangaroo meets sloth meets suburban dad in socks and sandals.\n\nWhy does it matter? Because scientists are learning how evolution swapped utility for laziness, and somehow humans are now the ones doing all the jumpingmostly to conclusions. Its also a timely reminder that not every alpha predator had to be fast or furious. Some were just fabulous and slow.\n\nLatest update? The research dropped today in PLOS ONE, and already Australians are claiming it as proof that couch potato behaviour is simply ancestral pride.\n\nSources:\nABC Science  Giant kangaroo walked upright like a human (24 Apr 2025)\nThe Conversation  Ancient kangaroos too heavy to hop, new study says (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'giant-kangaroos-were-the-og-couch-potatoes', 'published', 'images/news/a5c63dcf-aa11-44d0-8bd2-3ed4bbe9421d.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 10:28:49', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (681, 'Coalition to Kill Right to Disconnect, Burnout Says Cheers', 'The Coalition wants you glued to Slack forever. Mental health experts scream into the void while HR preps for a surge in resignation memes.', 'In todays episode of Work Until You Die, the Coalition has come out swinging against the Albanese governments newly passed right to disconnect lawsbecause why should Australians be allowed peace after 5pm? Shadow industrial relations minister Michaelia Cash called the policy anti-business, which loosely translates to how dare people have dinner without Slack notifications.\n\nThe law, passed earlier this year, gives workers the right to ignore after-hours calls, texts, and emails without fear of being hauled into HR for treason. It was widely cheered by burnt-out employees, exhausted teachers, and anyone who\'s ever sent a per my last email while dead inside. Naturally, the Coalition wants it gone.\n\nLets be honest, the timings a joke. Were in an era of quiet quitting, loud quitting, and Zoom meetings that feel like hostage situations. But rather than adjust to modern life, the Coalition seems nostalgic for 1950s sweatshop vibes, where work-life balance meant collapsing on your lawn in a tie.\n\nThe latest update? Peter Duttons team says theyll scrap the law if elected. So, if you enjoy being chained to your phone while reheating pasta at 9pm, congratsyour time has come.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian Australia  Coalition vows to scrap right to disconnect laws (24 Apr 2025)\nSBS News  Right to disconnect faces rollback under Coalition (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'coalition-to-kill-right-to-disconnect-burnout-says-cheers', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 01:03:07', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (682, 'Sydney\'s Latest Real Estate Fad: Million-Dollar Transformers Boxes', 'People are forking out a mil for homes with their own power stations. Because apparently \"shocking resale value\" is now literal.', 'Sydneys housing market has finally hit dystopian parody mode, with luxury homes now being built out ofyou guessed itshipping containers. Forget five-bedroom mansions; the latest trend is a million-dollar stack of steel cubes, rebranded as modular sanctuaries. If Optimus Prime wanted a beach house, this would be it.\n\nDevelopers are calling them eco-chic, space-optimised, and post-industrial minimalist. Translation: We ran out of land, so heres a box with Wi-Fi and mood lighting. One listing in Marrickville is asking $1.2 million for what is essentially a glorified toolbox with air-conditioning. But hey, it has a rooftop herb garden and vibes.\n\nThe backstory? With zoning chaos, skyrocketing demand, and wages playing dead, Sydneys housing market has mutated into a Hunger Games-style battle where people bid over metal bunkers. And honestly, the banks are into it. Short build time, Instagrammable, and just claustrophobic enough to guarantee you leave the house.\n\nWhy it matters? Because it perfectly captures where we are as a society: rich in marketing buzzwords, poor in livable space. The dream of a backyard? Dead. The new dream? Two steel boxes stacked on top of each other, some reclaimed wood, and maybe a projector screen to distract from the echo of your own despair.\n\nSources:\nDomain  Sydneys modular container homes selling for over $1 million (24 Apr 2025)\nNews.com.au  Shipping container homes are the latest hot trend (24 Apr 2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'sydneys-latest-real-estate-fad-million-dollar-transformers-boxes', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 10:55:44', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (683, 'Raphaels Fresco Gets Nerdy Makeover in Physics-Meets-Paint Doc', 'A physicist deep-dives into Renaissance art because why not? Its like TEDx met the Louvre and they birthed a PBS baby.', 'Because the world clearly needed more Renaissance meets TEDx content, a physicist has decided to decode Raphaels The School of Athens using equations and lasers. Dr. Silvia Galli, whose PhD is in cosmic rays (yes, really), stars in a new doco where she breaks down the architectural brilliance of the 1509 fresco like its a CERN experiment. Its highbrow meets high voltage, and somewhere Raphaels ghost is probably nodding and going, Finally, someone gets it.\n\nThe doc, airing this week on SBS, dives into how ancient artists basically invented vanishing points before Photoshop or Instagram filters were even a twinkle in the universe. Galli applies geometry, light analysis, and enough physics jargon to make your Year 10 science teacher weep with joy. Spoiler alert: Plato and Aristotle werent just standing around looking pensivethey were actually slaying the mathematical alignment game.\n\nBut the real drama? It turns out Raphael was low-key a spatial genius. His use of golden ratios, perspective grids, and sneaky symbolism was basically 16th-century quantum flexing. Who knew the Vatican walls doubled as the original chalkboard for a physics masterclass?\n\nLatest update: Nerds are thrilled. Art critics are intrigued. Everyone else is just here for the part where someone says Renaissance and quantum field in the same sentence without combusting.\n\nSources:\nSBS On Demand  Raphael Decoded: The Physics of Art (24 Apr 2025)\nThe Guardian  New documentary reimagines Renaissance art through science (24 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'raphaels-fresco-gets-nerdy-makeover-in-physics-meets-paint-doc', 'published', 'images/news/2224707a-5ac8-4b09-8bb3-c629ee7ee27e.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 09:36:38', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (684, 'New in Sydney: Live Above a Substation, Pay a Million for the Buzz', 'Real estates cooked when electricity boxes go for seven figures. Bonus feature: in-built hum for ambience.', 'Sydneys housing market has officially transcended parody. You can now fork out over $1 million to live above an electrical substation. Yes, for the price of a Byron Bay retreat, you too can enjoy the warm hum of voltage beneath your floorboards like natures white noise machinebut make it industrial.\n\nThe property in question, located in the inner west, was proudly listed as a rare opportunity to own a piece of grid-adjacent luxury. The agent even bragged about its unique energy, which is a bold way of saying your neighbours are literally transformers. The home comes with sleek finishes, a compact layout, and a subtle fear of spontaneous combustion.\n\nThis is what happens when demand meets desperation. Once upon a time, living above high-voltage equipment would have triggered red flags. Now it triggers bidding wars. With detached homes priced like private islands and apartments selling faster than vaccines in 2020, buyers are lining up for anything that comes with four walls and a power connection.\n\nThe buzz? Literal. The value? The vibes. And honestly, if you stare into the fuse box long enough, you might even see the ghosts of affordable housing past.\n\nSources:\nDomain  Sydney substation home listed for over $1 million (24 Apr 2025)\nABC News  Home above electricity hub attracts buyers (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'new-in-sydney-live-above-a-substation-pay-a-million-for-the-buzz', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 09:47:53', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (685, 'WAs \'Skimpy Bars\' Now Art Galleries, Because Australia', 'Beer wenches to brush strokesWAs wildest pubs become exhibits. Somewhere, Picasso is cracking a cold one.', 'Western Australia has done a full cultural cartwheelsome of its notorious skimpy bars (yes, the ones where beer came with a side of barely clothed bar staff) are now moonlighting as art galleries. Because when life gives you beer-stained tiles and neon signage, you hang a Monet knockoff and call it rebranding.\n\nIn places like Kalgoorlie and Leonora, pubs once infamous for their...lets say visually generous dress code have been transformed into spaces showcasing local art, Indigenous works, and upcycled mining relics. Its part of a broader movement to bring tourism, culture, and maybe a little dignity back to the outbacks nightlife scene.\n\nAnd the best part? Some venues still serve pintsjust now alongside portraiture. You can sip a mid-strength lager while contemplating a postmodern sculpture made from rusted ute parts. Its the ultimate Aussie juxtaposition: gallery walls with pub brawls just faintly echoing from memory.\n\nThe shift is being applauded by local councils and artists alike, though some patrons remain confused why the bartender isnt wearing fishnets and handing out VB with a wink. Change is hard, especially when it doesnt come with a two-for-one special.\n\nSources:\nABC Perth  WAs former skimpy bars transformed into art spaces (24 Apr 2025)\nWA Today  From topless taps to top-tier art: The rise of pub galleries (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'was-skimpy-bars-now-art-galleries-because-australia', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 11:14:09', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (686, 'Peter Dutton\'s Nuclear Hide-and-Seek: Avoids Reactor Sites Like They\'re Radioactive', 'Opposition leader Peter Dutton is mysteriously absent from all proposed nuclear reactor sites during his campaign. Perhaps he\'s just allergic to glowing reviews?', 'Peter Dutton wants Australia to embrace nuclear powerbut only from a safe, camera-friendly distance. The Coalition leader has been mysteriously absent from every single proposed reactor site on his campaign trail, leaving voters wondering if hes promoting nuclear energy or trying to ghost it. When pressed, Dutton offered vague comments about consultation and future decisions, which is political code for not in my backyard, mate.\n\nIts a bit rich, considering the mans been loudly pushing for small modular reactors like theyre the new AirPods. But when it comes to actually setting foot in one of these future glow zonesnothing. Not even a photo op in a hard hat. Which begs the question: if nuclear energy is so great, why wont its loudest cheerleader get within 100 kilometres of it?\n\nThe context? The Coalition is pitching nuclear as the clean solution to Australias energy woes, conveniently ignoring the small details like cost, timelines, public opposition, and that whole what do we do with the radioactive waste thing. Meanwhile, Labor\'s riding high on renewables, pointing out that sunlight has yet to require a $20 billion waste repository.\n\nThe latest? Duttons itinerary continues to suspiciously avoid any place with a whiff of uranium, leading to speculation that even he wouldnt vote for his own reactor if it were in his electorate.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian Australia  Dutton avoids nuclear sites during energy pitch (24 Apr 2025)\nABC News  Opposition backs nuclear without naming locations (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'peter-duttons-nuclear-hide-and-seek-avoids-reactor-sites-like-theyre-radioactive', 'published', 'images/news/ae605f29-c505-48ee-8fb2-6292507a58aa.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 12:52:53', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (687, 'Coalition\'s EV Tax Break U-Turn: From \'Not Touching\' to \'Scrapping\' in 48 Hours', 'The Coalition pledges to repeal EV tax breaks just two days after assuring they wouldn\'t. Consistency is overrated anyway.', 'If political backflips were an Olympic sport, the Coalition just stuck the landing with a double-twist EV dismount. Just two days after assuring Australians they had no plans to touch electric vehicle tax incentives, Peter Duttons squad announced theyll be scrapping them entirely. Its like saying you wont eat the cakeand then faceplanting into it 48 hours later.\n\nThe policy reversal left industry heads spinning, especially since EV tax breaks were one of the few bipartisan unicornspopular, green-ish, and mildly forward-thinking. Until now. The Coalition now claims the incentives are inequitable, because apparently helping people afford cars that dont destroy the planet is unfair if not everyone gets a Tesla.\n\nThis is the same Coalition that once called EVs anti-Aussie because they might ruin weekend camping trips. Now theyre just going full scorched-earth on the one climate policy that didnt come with a protest sign or a riot. Bold move.\n\nThe latest? Car makers are livid, voters are confused, and Labor is handing out popcorn as Dutton tries to explain how were not against EVs and were killing their tax breaks can coexist peacefully.\n\nSources:\nThe Age  Coalition reverses stance, pledges to axe EV tax incentives (24 Apr 2025)\nSMH  Duttons EV flip-flop leaves market rattled (24 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'coalitions-ev-tax-break-u-turn-from-not-touching-to-scrapping-in-48-hours', 'published', 'images/news/6903e6ed-39b7-4812-9cfb-c81f63cfdb93.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 11:20:05', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (688, 'Pope Francis Lies in State: Vatican\'s Final Farewell to the People\'s Pope', 'Thousands gather in Rome to pay their respects as Pope Francis lies in state. A somber moment marking the end of an era.', 'Rome fell silent today as Pope Francisbeloved, blunt, and blessedly progressivelay in state at St. Peters Basilica. The pontiff who once said who am I to judge? and dragged the Church into the 21st century with one eyebrow raise at a time is now receiving the kind of global farewell usually reserved for rockstars and revolutionaries.\n\nFrancis, who redefined the papacy with humility and a no-limo policy, is being remembered as the Peoples Pope. He chose compassion over condemnation, ditched the gold-threaded robes for something that didnt scream medieval cosplay, and called out greed, injustice, and even Vatican bureaucracy with papal sass. No wonder he had half the Church sweating.\n\nThe backdrop? His papacy wasnt without controversy. Traditionalists clutched their pearls, conservatives muttered into their rosaries, and at least three cardinals tried to stage ecclesiastical mutinies. But none of it stuck. Franciss brand was spiritual realismless fire and brimstone, more stop being a jerk.\n\nTodays goodbye was global. Pilgrims flooded the Vatican, world leaders offered tributes that for once didnt sound ghostwritten, and Twitter lit up with genuine emotion. Even the atheists said respect.\n\nThe latest? His funeral will be held later this week, and speculation is already swirling about who will fill those impossibly humble shoes. One things for sure: Heaven just got sassier.\n\nSources:\nReuters  Pope Francis lies in state at St. Peters Basilica (24 Apr 2025)\nVatican News  Faithful gather for final farewell to Pope Francis (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'pope-francis-lies-in-state-vaticans-final-farewell-to-the-peoples-pope', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 09:05:50', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (689, 'AFL Star\'s Assault Case: \'I\'ve Let a Lot of People Down\'', 'An AFL player avoids jail over assault charges, expressing remorse. A reminder that off-field behavior matters as much as on-field performance.', 'Another day, another off-field scandal from someone whos paid to kick goals, not court dates. An AFL playerwhose name is now trending for all the wrong reasonshas dodged jail time after pleading guilty to assault. He gave the classic press-conference apology bingo: remorseful tone, mentions of disappointing fans, and the obligatory I take full responsibility, which would be more convincing if it werent delivered with the facial expression of a man thinking about round 8 team selections.\n\nThe incident involved alcohol, late-night antics, and an unfortunate lapse in judgmentbecause of course it did. The player in question reportedly lashed out during an altercation, and while the court spared him prison, it did slap him with a conviction and a court order that screams, Grow up, mate.\n\nHeres the tea: AFL players arent just athletestheyre walking PR risks with endorsement deals. The league has spent years trying to polish its image, only for yet another star to trip over it like its a stray footy boot. Fans are angry, clubs are scrambling, and somewhere a manager is muttering, Why cant you just stay home and eat pasta?\n\nThe latest? The players back in training, the club has issued a statement longer than his tackle count, and public reaction is split between ban him for life and hes young, give him a second chance. The AFL, as usual, is trying to ride the fence so hard it\'s getting splinters.\n\nSources:\nThe Age  AFL player avoids jail over assault charge (24 Apr 2025)\nABC News  AFL star sentenced over assault, issues apology (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'afl-stars-assault-case-ive-let-a-lot-of-people-down', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 02:56:28', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (690, 'Cyclone \'Blackwater\' Expected to Cause Massive Fish Deaths in NSW', 'Environmental experts warn of significant fish deaths due to cyclone-induced blackwater events. Nature\'s wrath spares no one.', 'As if a cyclone wasn\'t dramatic enough, NSW now faces an aquatic horror sequel: mass fish deaths thanks to a nasty little thing called blackwater events. Cyclone Blackwater, currently thrashing through the region with all the grace of a chainsaw in a bathtub, has stirred up enough organic sludge to suffocate entire fish populations. Yep, Mother Natures throwing a tantrumand the rivers are paying the price.\n\nEnvironmental scientists say the mix of storm runoff, low oxygen levels, and decomposing matter is about to turn freshwater habitats into fishy graveyards. Its not just a smell issue (though brace yourselves)its a biodiversity disaster. And if you\'re wondering why fish dying en masse matters: imagine your towns entire air supply suddenly becoming unbreathable. Now imagine youre a fish.\n\nThis isnt a one-off drama, either. Blackwater events have become increasingly common as climate change pumps up the volume on weather chaos. Add in drought, soil erosion, and farming runoff, and youve got yourself a perfect recipe for aquatic apocalypse.\n\nLatest update? Fisheries officers are already on high alert, locals are bracing for the stink, and environmental groups are asking why more hasnt been done to prevent this mess in the first place. Spoiler: because policy moves slower than floodwater.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Cyclone Blackwater sparks warnings of mass fish kills in NSW (24 Apr 2025)\nThe Guardian Australia  Experts warn of ecological crisis from blackwater flooding (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'cyclone-blackwater-expected-to-cause-massive-fish-deaths-in-nsw', 'published', 'images/news/7a93d964-9407-47f8-ae2d-1d4cc3d81ab7.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 01:40:14', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (691, 'Record High Influenza Cases Confirmed as Flu Season Hits Early', 'Australia sees a 50% jump in flu cases compared to last year, with experts predicting an earlier and more severe flu season. Time to stock up on tissues and soup.', 'Its not even winter yet, but the flus already clocked in like an overachieving intern with a vengeance. Australia has reported a whopping 50% spike in influenza cases compared to this time last year, and health experts are looking at the charts like, Yep, were cooked. Its the earliest and nastiest flu season in years, and tissues might as well be the new currency.\n\nHospitals are prepping for a spike in admissions, GP clinics are seeing bookings explode, and pharmacists are watching their Tamiflu shelves vanish like toilet paper in 2020. Everyone from toddlers to retirees is coughing in surround sound, and the national mood is somewhere between mild panic and full sneeze-pocalypse.\n\nSo whats going on? Experts say reduced immunity from mild previous seasons, lower vaccination rates, and a cocktail of post-COVID complacency are all to blame. Its like the flu has been waiting in the wings, muttering My turn now.\n\nThe latest? Health authorities are urging people to get their flu jabs now, not when you get around to it. Schools are preparing for waves of absences, and offices are rediscovering just how many meetings couldve been emails. If youre not already sick, youve either got a superhuman immune system or youre next.\n\nSources:\n9News  Flu cases soar ahead of expected record season (24 Apr 2025)\nThe Australian  Experts warn of early, severe influenza wave (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'record-high-influenza-cases-confirmed-as-flu-season-hits-early', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 07:19:36', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (692, 'Labor\'s $1.2 Billion Critical Minerals Reserve: A Strategic Stockpile for the Future', 'The Labor government announces a hefty investment to secure critical minerals, aiming to bolster national interests and trade resilience. Because hoarding isn\'t just for doomsday preppers.', 'Move over toilet paper hoardersLabor just dropped $1.2 billion on a strategic mineral stash big enough to make doomsday preppers look underprepared. In a move straight out of economic survivalist chic, the Albanese government announced its building a national reserve of critical minerals like lithium, cobalt, and rare earths, all to secure Australias place in the global tech and trade thunderdome.\n\nResources Minister Madeleine King says its about sovereignty and resilience, which is code for: Chinas got the good stuff, and wed like some backup. These minerals power everything from EVs and wind turbines to that phone youve already dropped twice this week. Without them, the economys basically a Nokia 3310indestructible but painfully obsolete.\n\nThe backstory? Australias been digging up the goods for years, but shipping most of it offshore without blinking. Now, with global tensions high, supply chains shakier than a caf table, and countries playing Pokmon with rare minerals, Canberras finally decided to keep some of the loot at home. Late to the party, surebut at least they brought $1.2 billion in chips.\n\nWhy it matters? Because in the 21st-century Hunger Games of economic dominance, whoever controls the minerals controls the memes, machines, and military drones. Its not just a stockpileits a geopolitical flex.\n\nLatest update? No confirmed location yet, but somewhere underground in the outback, a bunch of future-proof dirt is about to get real important.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian Australia  Labor announces $1.2bn reserve for critical minerals (24 Apr 2025)\nABC News  Government to stockpile minerals for national security (24 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'labors-12-billion-critical-minerals-reserve-a-strategic-stockpile-for-the-future', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 16:31:33', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (693, 'Flu-FOMO: Aussies Panic-Book Vaccines as Cases Spike', 'As flu cases skyrocket, Australians rush clinics like it\'s a Taylor Swift presale. Needles out, noses running.', 'Australians are stampeding to flu clinics like theyre lining up for a Taylor Swift presaleonly instead of friendship bracelets, its tissues, thermometers, and a vague sense of dread. With flu cases up 50% and hospitals bracing for a tidal wave of snot, Aussies are finally remembering that jabs arent just for Instagrammable arms and COVID flashbacks.\n\nGPs are booked solid, pharmacies are operating like day spas for the feverish, and your mate who never gets sick is now mainlining chicken soup and lying about having had the jab already. Health officials are begging people to vaccinate ASAP, warning that this season is not messing around. Its early, its angry, and its got a mean streak longer than a Bondi brunch line.\n\nThe problem? Everyone suddenly realised they dont want to be the one wheezing into May, and now demand is outpacing supply in some areas. Its full-blown Flu-FOMO, with people posting got mine selfies and pretending the side effects dont exist. Meanwhile, anti-vax aunties are suspiciously quiet.\n\nWhy it matters? Because if vaccination rates dont catch up fast, were in for a winter of sick days, childcare chaos, and office group chats about who gave Brenda the flu.\n\nLatest update? Clinics are extending hours, vaccine stocks are being shuffled like deck chairs on a viral Titanic, and Australians have finally remembered what public health is. Almost.\n\nSources:\n9News  Flu vaccine rush as cases surge early (24 Apr 2025)\nSMH  Demand spikes for flu jab amid worst season in years (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'flu-fomo-aussies-panic-book-vaccines-as-cases-spike', 'published', 'images/news/59b4f152-eced-4a31-b57b-259a7c0caf63.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 05:39:20', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (694, 'Coalition\'s Migration Cut: 100,000 Fewer, But Who\'s Counting?', 'The Coalition pledges to slash net migration by 100,000 in the first year through stricter visa policies. Because nothing says \'welcome\' like a closed door.', 'Peter Dutton has dusted off the ol immigration playbook and promised to chop net migration by 100,000 in year one of a Coalition governmentbecause what better way to fix housing, wages, infrastructure, and bad vibes than by pulling the handbrake on visas? Its bold, vaguely threatening, and perfectly timed for an election where subtlety has clearly died.\n\nThe plan includes tougher visa rules, a crackdown on international students (sorry, future baristas), and a big ol boot to temporary workers. Basically, if youre not already holding an Aussie passport or a meat pie, you may want to rethink your travel plans.\n\nBut heres the kicker: while Dutton rants about population pressures, economists are side-eyeing the math. Migration adds billions to the economy and props up everything from universities to construction. Cutting 100,000 people might sound strongman-ish, but in practice, its like fixing a leaky tap by torching the bathroom.\n\nContext-wise, this isnt new terrain. The Coalitions history with immigration is like that one uncle at Christmasloud, defensive, and always swearing hes just telling it like it is. Meanwhile, Labors been playing it safe, tweaking policies without making headlines, and hoping no one notices they also quietly dialed things back last year.\n\nLatest update? The Coalitions still vague on which visas get the axe and how theyll do it without detonating industries. But hey, details are for nerdsthis ones for the headlines.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Coalition vows to cut net migration by 100,000 (24 Apr 2025)\nThe Australian  Dutton targets student and work visas in migration plan (24 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'coalitions-migration-cut-100000-fewer-but-whos-counting', 'published', 'images/news/4a7a3eb7-a8f8-4c39-bc93-d5c73e4f04d7.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 03:10:58', 26);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (695, 'Labor\'s $1.2 Billion Bet on Rocks: Critical Minerals Reserve Announced', 'Labor unveils a plan to stockpile critical minerals, investing $1.2 billion to secure Australia\'s future. Because hoarding isn\'t just for doomsday preppers anymore.', 'Labors just invested $1.2 billion into what can only be described as the worlds bougiest rock collection. The government has announced a national stockpile of critical mineralslithium, rare earths, and other shiny dirt that makes your smartphone, solar panels, and electric cars function. Its like Pokmon, but for trade deals and national security.\n\nResources Minister Madeleine King said the plan was about future-proofing, which sounds noble, but lets be honestits also about not being held hostage by China every time we need to build a battery. With global supply chains spicier than a Bunnings sausage, Australia has finally decided it might be nice to keep a few treasures in its own backyard for once.\n\nThe real kicker? These minerals have been dug up here for decades, then shipped offshore faster than you can say value add. Now, the governments realised that maybe, just maybe, hoarding isnt just for weirdos with panic bunkersits a strategic flex.\n\nZooming out, this move plants Australia squarely in the we actually read the geopolitical room camp. While other countries are scrambling for resources like kids at a lolly scramble, were quietly tucking ours into a national vault and watching the global chaos unfold.\n\nLatest update? No official storage site announced yet, but you can bet some outback patch is about to become the Fort Knox of shiny Aussie rocks.\n\nSources:\nGuardian Australia  Labor announces $1.2bn reserve for critical minerals (24 Apr 2025)\nABC News  Government to stockpile minerals for national security (24 Apr 2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'labors-12-billion-bet-on-rocks-critical-minerals-reserve-announced', 'published', 'images/news/d968203f-a262-4ff9-ac52-e474e40ee1e3.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 16:51:08', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (696, 'Trump Declares War on DEI: \'Out of That Jungle at Last\'', 'President Trump announces a crackdown on Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion programs, likening them to a \'jungle.\' Tarzan was unavailable for comment.', 'Donald Trump has found a new jungle to bulldozeand this one doesnt involve vines or logic. In a speech so dripping with \'50s energy it couldve been sponsored by black-and-white TV, Trump declared victory over Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion programs, proudly announcing that America is finally out of that jungle. Tarzan was unavailable for comment, but his PR team says even hes offended.\n\nThe former President turned current DEI executioner signed off on a sweeping crackdown that demands federal agencies dump any and all inclusion efforts, while also helpfully reporting employees who had the audacity to promote diversity. Thats rightminority outreach is now practically a red flag, and having attended a cultural sensitivity workshop might get you added to a watchlist faster than if you\'d stormed the Capitol.\n\nTrump framed the move as restoring merit, which, in Trumpland, usually translates to hiring people who look like me and think Im a genius. He also invoked the usual ghostswoke mobs, liberal brainwashing, and equity advocates who dare to exist in government buildings.\n\nWhy this matters? Because its not just about hiringits about gutting any institutional support for fairness, inclusion, or, heaven forbid, acknowledging systemic bias. For a man who once wanted to buy Greenland, erasing diversity was apparently next on the bucket list.\n\nLatest update? Federal offices are already purging DEI teams faster than you can say reverse racism, and the executive order is being celebrated by exactly the crowd youd expect: guys named Chuck with a podcast and a grievance.\n\nSources:\nThe National Desk  Trump declares woke no more after dismantling DEI (24 Apr 2025)\nWikipedia  Executive Order 14151 (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-declares-war-on-dei-out-of-that-jungle-at-last', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-01 13:14:45', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (697, 'Congressional Lawmakers Visit ICE Jails, Call Student Detentions a \'National Disgrace\'', 'Lawmakers decry the detention of pro-Palestinian student activists, labeling it a constitutional crisis. ICE responds with a collective shrug.', 'Members of Congress toured ICE detention centres this week and emerged visibly shookdeclaring the ongoing detention of pro-Palestinian student activists a national disgrace. In response, ICE collectively blinked, shrugged, and resumed doing whatever the bureaucratic version of a middle finger is.\n\nThe detained students, including Mahmoud Khalil and Rmeysa ztrk, have now been locked up for over a month with no charges, no bail, and no clear explanation other than bad vibes and foreign influence concerns. Translation: protesting in America is now a potential federal offense, especially if youve got the wrong name or accent.\n\nRep. Ayanna Pressley and Sen. Ed Markey led the delegation and did not hold back. Pressley called the situation a constitutional meltdown, while Markey essentially asked, Since when did civil liberties take a sabbatical? Both lawmakers reported horrific conditions insideminimal food, limited legal access, and detainees forced to choose between rights and rot.\n\nThe story gets worse: Khalil reportedly missed the birth of his child while in custody, because nothing says family values like indefinite detention over a megaphone and a protest sign.\n\nLatest update? The Biden administration remains eerily quiet, ICE insists it\'s just following orders, and the Constitution is currently somewhere under a desk with its panic attack meds.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  ICE detains student activists, lawmakers call it a disgrace (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'congressional-lawmakers-visit-ice-jails-call-student-detentions-a-national-disgrace', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 19:14:07', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (698, 'NBA Playoffs Heat Up: Underdogs Bite Back in Game 3 Thrillers', 'The NBA playoffs see unexpected twists as lower-seeded teams clinch surprising victories in Game 3 matchups. Cinderella stories are back in style.', 'The NBA playoffs have officially gone off-script, and the underdogs are out here writing their own Disney+ series. In a string of Game 3 shockers, lower-seeded teams threw out the script, the stats, and possibly their chiropractors, because they came to play. Suddenly, that No. 8 seed isnt a jokeits a vibe.\n\nAcross the league, so-called favourites were seen blinking in disbelief as rosters of rookies, benchwarmers, and men who werent even on rosters last Christmas turned into playoff poachers. Coaches are tearing up game plans, Vegas is panicking, and fans are googling Who the hell is that guy? after every possession.\n\nThe stars? Still there, of course. But theyre getting out-hustled by dudes making league minimums and playing like their mortgage depends on it (because it does). This isnt just basketballits chaos in sneakers, and Cinderella just dunked on you.\n\nWhy it matters? Because every postseason needs a plot twist, and this years is: the NBA scriptwriters are drunk, and were loving it. If your brackets still intact, youre either psychic or lying.\n\nLatest update? Coaches are sweating, analysts are spiraling, and Twitter is one buzzer-beater away from declaring the entire playoff format rigged. Stay tunedits about to get even messier.\n\nSources:\nESPN  NBA Playoffs: Underdogs take Game 3 in stunning turnarounds (24 Apr 2025)\nBleacher Report  Lower seeds flip the narrative in chaotic Game 3 stretch (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'nba-playoffs-heat-up-underdogs-bite-back-in-game-3-thrillers', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-04-28 03:29:26', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (699, 'Nearly Half of Americans Breathing in Unsafe Levels of Air Pollutants', 'A new report reveals that almost 156 million Americans are exposed to unhealthy air quality, marking a 16% increase from last year. Clean air: the new luxury item.', 'In todays episode of America, But Make It Unbreathable, a new report shows nearly 156 million people in the U.S. are inhaling air that would make a coal mine blush. Thats 47% of the population, up 16% from last year, proving that clean air has officially joined affordable housing, insulin, and hope on the endangered list.\n\nThe American Lung Association dropped this bombshell with the subtlety of a leaf blower, highlighting record levels of fine particulate matter and ozone pollution in major cities. Translation? Breathing in L.A., Chicago, or basically anywhere with a skyline is now a contact sport.\n\nThe culprits? Climate change, fossil fuels, wildfires, and politicians pretending the Clean Air Act is a choose-your-own-adventure. But dont worrytech bros are already pitching $600 indoor air pods so you can cosplay as a hamster in a Dyson.\n\nWhy it matters? Because were no longer talking about bad air dayswere talking about a nation where air quality alerts are more common than weather forecasts, and fresh air is now a luxury subscription service.\n\nLatest update? Public health experts are screaming into the smog, politicians are promising things no one believes, and your lungs are quietly filing for workplace compensation.\n\nSources:\nNPR  156 million Americans now exposed to unhealthy air (24 Apr 2025)\nCNN  US air pollution surges in new report (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'nearly-half-of-americans-breathing-in-unsafe-levels-of-air-pollutants', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 05:29:00', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (700, 'Flu Season Arrives Early: Hospitals Brace for Surge in Cases', 'Hospitals across the U.S. report a significant uptick in flu cases, with some regions seeing a 50% increase compared to last year. Time to stock up on tissues and hand sanitizer.', 'Flu season has pulled a Beyonc and arrived early, unannounced, and ready to steal the spotlight. U.S. hospitals are bracing for a sneeze tsunami, as influenza cases spike 50% above last years numbersand we havent even hit peak pumpkin spice yet.\n\nFrom coast to congested coast, ERs are filling with the usual suspects: feverish kids, sniffling boomers, and that one guy who insists its just allergies while coughing on the registration desk. Medical staff are already overworked, undercaffeinated, and emotionally preparing for flu TikToks to replace COVID dances.\n\nThe CDC says the early wave is due to low vaccination rates, pandemic immunity hangovers, and a virus strain that clearly woke up and chose violence. Pharmacies are scrambling, vaccine lines are growing, and somewhere a Walgreens receipt is stretching across state lines.\n\nWhy it matters? Because this isn\'t your average sniffle season. It\'s a full-blown germ rave, and if you\'re not vaccinated, you\'re the open bar. Welcome to the party.\n\nLatest update? Clinics are begging people to get jabbed, masks are making a socially acceptable comeback, and Kleenex stock is suddenly looking like a strong investment.\n\nSources:\nCBS News  Hospitals report spike as flu hits early (24 Apr 2025)\nNBC News  Flu cases up 50% over last year, CDC urges early vaccination (24 Apr 2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'flu-season-arrives-early-hospitals-brace-for-surge-in-cases', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 02:31:07', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (701, 'Tesla Shares Soar After Beating Earnings Expectations', 'Tesla\'s stock jumps 6.3% in premarket trading after the company reports profits exceeding expectations. Elon Musk tweets a celebratory meme.', 'Elon Musk just slapped Wall Street across the face with a profits report, and Teslas stock rocketed up 6.3% in premarket tradingbecause nothing says surprise, haters like outpacing expectations while everyone else is still fumbling with layoffs and recession vibes. Naturally, Musk celebrated the only way he knows how: by tweeting a half-baked meme involving lasers, a Shiba Inu, and the phrase W number go up.\n\nTesla\'s Q1 earnings came in hotter than one of their brake pads after a panic stop, defying forecasts that had analysts sharpening their doom-and-gloom pencils. Apparently, shaving a few billion off costs and massaging production lines like a stressed-out yoga instructor actually worked. Bonus points: the Cybertruck didnt explode on delivery. Yet.\n\nInvestors, previously clutching pearls over slowing EV demand, are now throwing confetti like its 2021 again. Meanwhile, Elons out here pretending he never said recession incoming like six tweets ago. Classic.\n\nThe bigger picture? Teslas still the poster child for chaotic brilliance. Yes, its self-driving feature occasionally mistakes pedestrians for speed bumps, but when the profits are up, the stock market forgives anything short of arson. Tesla is a meme stock with an actual factory, and thats the kind of sorcery tech bros will die defending.\n\nLatest update? The stock\'s climbing, memes are flying, and Elons ego just applied for orbit clearance.\n\nSources:\nBloomberg  Tesla stock jumps as earnings beat expectations (24 Apr 2025)\nCNBC  Tesla surprises with Q1 profits, shares surge in early trading (24 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'tesla-shares-soar-after-beating-earnings-expectations', 'published', 'images/news/f719a10e-bf58-4e87-a94e-5b312c0c128e.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 09:46:07', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (702, 'Clair Obscur: Expedition 33 Review - A Deeply Satisfying Homage to JRPGs', 'The new game \'Clair Obscur: Expedition 33\' offers a rich, stylized RPG experience, paying tribute to classic Japanese role-playing games. Nostalgia hits hard.', 'Gamers rejoice: Clair Obscur: Expedition 33 has arrived, and its basically Final Fantasys artsy French cousin who studied philosophy abroad and came back with a killer sword collection. This stylized JRPG is dripping in painterly visuals, turn-based swagger, and enough existential angst to make even Cloud Strife say bro, you okay?\n\nThe plot? Beautifully convoluted, obviously. A world-ending prophecy. A tortured protagonist. Some weird time loop stuff. Also, masks. Lots of masks. But its not about understanding everythingits about feeling very deep emotions while a harp plays in the background and your party member quietly dies of plot development.\n\nGameplay-wise, Expedition 33 goes full throwback, but with just enough innovation to keep it fresh. Its like playing a love letter to 90s JRPGs, only this one is written on parchment and sealed with a wax stamp of pure aesthetic agony. Youll cry, youll grind for loot, youll spend 20 minutes debating whether to equip the +3 dagger or the +2 katana with better vibes.\n\nAnd the soundtrack? Oh, honey. It slaps, mourns, and elevates every cutscene to Oscar-bait levels of melodrama. This isnt just a gameits a mood board come to life.\n\nLatest update? Critics are swooning, fans are obsessing, and somewhere in a Square Enix boardroom, a jealous executive just sighed, Why didnt we make this first?\n\nSources:\nIGN  Clair Obscur: Expedition 33 delivers modern JRPG magic (24 Apr 2025)\nPolygon  A hauntingly beautiful homage to the golden age of JRPGs (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'clair-obscur-expedition-33-review-a-deeply-satisfying-homage-to-jrpgs', 'published', 'images/news/23191bd9-57b7-4840-93e1-a1f51e685611.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 11:02:33', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (703, 'California Housing Market Cools as Interest Rates Rise', 'Rising interest rates lead to a slowdown in California\'s housing market, with fewer buyers and longer listing times. The golden state\'s real estate isn\'t so shiny now.', 'Californias housing market has officially gone from red-hot to left the oven on but forgot to put anything inside. Rising interest rates have thrown ice water on bidding wars, and now sellers are nervously refreshing Zillow while wondering if staging the bathroom with eucalyptus bundles was really worth it.\n\nListings are lingering longer than your exs gym selfies, open homes are starting to resemble ghost tours, and realtors are rediscovering the ancient art of negotiationa language no Californian under 40 has spoken since 2011. Buyers, once elbowing each other for fixer-uppers with character, are now ghosting entire suburbs after looking at mortgage calculators.\n\nWhy the sudden chill? The Feds rate hikes have pushed monthly payments into nosebleed territory, and even tech bros with VC-funded dreams are asking, Is it too late to move to Austin? Meanwhile, boomers are clutching their $4 million bungalows and pretending this is just a market correction, not the start of a very expensive vibe check.\n\nZooming out, this shift might actually help sanity return to the real estate jungle. Or it might just mark the beginning of a long, slow game of financial Jengaespecially if inflation decides to stage a comeback tour.\n\nLatest update? Prices are stalling, buyers are stalling harder, and the only thing still moving fast is the tumbleweed rolling past that open house in Glendale.\n\nSources:\nLA Times  California housing market slows as interest rates climb (24 Apr 2025)\nBloomberg  Rate hikes dampen demand, extend listings across West Coast (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'california-housing-market-cools-as-interest-rates-rise', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 01:33:37', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (704, 'Americans Embrace \'Slow Living\' Trend Amidst Fast-Paced World', 'A growing number of Americans are adopting the \'slow living\' lifestyle, focusing on mindfulness and simplicity. Slowing down is the new hustle.', 'In a plot twist no one saw comingmainly because it took its time arrivingAmericans are ditching the hustle and falling head over hemp sandals for the \"slow living\" lifestyle. Thats right, in a country built on instant gratification, 2-day shipping, and microwave anxiety, people are now voluntarily... chilling.\n\nThink sourdough starters without the pandemic panic, yoga that doesnt end in Instagram reels, and mornings that begin with journaling instead of doomscrolling. Its a mindfulness-meets-minimalism renaissance, and for once, it doesnt involve a $400 productivity app yelling at you to hydrate.\n\nThe slow living crowdtypically millennials with a kombucha habit and an Etsy side hustleare trading FOMO for JOMO (joy of missing out), proudly embracing analog hobbies like knitting, bread baking, and pretending theyve never heard of Slack. Theyre sipping matcha, reading books with paper pages, and romantically referring to their lives as intentional, while still somehow posting it all on TikTok.\n\nBut lets be honest: its also a subtle rebellion. Against burnout. Against grind culture. Against the 27-tab lifestyle weve all been gaslit into thinking is normal. It\'s America hitting snooze on capitalism and whispering, What if I just... didnt?\n\nWhy it matters? Because for the first time in decades, people are measuring success not by how busy they are, but by how calm they feel. Revolutionary, right?\n\nLatest update? Sales of linen pants are up, Wi-Fi is being swapped for wildflowers, and somewhere, a startup founder just screamed into a mason jar.\n\nSources:\nNPR  Slow living trend gains traction in post-pandemic America (24 Apr 2025)\nNew York Times  From burnout to balance: The rise of slow living (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'americans-embrace-slow-living-trend-amidst-fast-paced-world', 'published', 'images/news/0a7beedb-4b27-4da5-a2b2-7201fd8b76d9.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 06:20:32', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (705, 'Xi and Aliyev\'s Tea Time: China-Azerbaijan Relations Brew Stronger', 'President Xi Jinping hosts Azerbaijan\'s Ilham Aliyev, strengthening ties over shared interests and, presumably, a good cup of tea.', 'Its tea time in Beijing, and no one spills like Xi Jinpingunless its mutual economic interests. In a photo-op that looked like the worlds most intense tea ceremony, Chinese President Xi welcomed Azerbaijans Ilham Aliyev with enough ceremony to make Buckingham Palace blush. The two leaders clinked cups, signed deals, and reinforced ties like two dads agreeing on who brings the better lawnmower to the BBQ.\n\nAliyev, known for his oil-rich autocracy and perfectly symmetrical frown, flew in to chat about trade, infrastructure, and the usual geopolitical Tinder topicsenergy, logistics, and how to ghost the West without losing face. Xi, meanwhile, used the opportunity to slide Azerbaijan further into Chinas Belt and Road family, like youre already here, might as well stay for dinner.\n\nThis isnt just about warm beverages and forced smiles. Azerbaijan sits at a juicy Eurasian crossroads, and China wants a piece of that action without the drama of Russias messy text history. Cue talk of deepening energy cooperation, transport corridors, and building things that vaguely look like peace but definitely smell like strategy.\n\nLatest update? The teas gone cold, but the deals are hot. Xi and Aliyev walked away with new projects, warmer ties, and probably matching tea sets. Charming.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  China, Azerbaijan pledge closer cooperation in state visit (24 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'xi-and-aliyevs-tea-time-china-azerbaijan-relations-brew-stronger', 'published', 'images/news/2ef03b48-2b9a-4280-a6ab-96c37d5e8519.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-04-30 05:33:00', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (706, 'Xi\'s Southeast Asia Tour: Diplomacy with a Side of Noodles', 'Xi Jinping wraps up his Southeast Asia tour, leaving behind strengthened ties and possibly some leftover dumplings.', 'Xi Jinping just wrapped his Southeast Asia tour like a seasoned backpacker with unlimited government funding. Armed with dumplings and diplomatic swagger, the Chinese leader swept through the region dishing out friendship, investment deals, and gentle reminders that China is your new favourite dinner guestjust dont ask about the South China Sea.\n\nIn Thailand, Laos, and Vietnam, Xi smiled his way through handshakes, speeches, and probably a dozen banquets. There was talk of shared futures, mutual respect, and, presumably, can someone please pass the chili oil. Chinas goal? To solidify regional alliances, boost infrastructure projects, and politely edge the U.S. off the guest listone rail line at a time.\n\nThe charm offensive was textbook: drop cash, say \"win-win,\" offer bullet trains. Leaders posed for photos with Xi like contestants on The Bachelor: Geopolitical Edition, and everyone left with full bellies and full pockets. Well, except the West, which got a passive-aggressive wave from across the buffet.\n\nWhy it matters? Because this wasnt just a tourit was a soft power cooking show. And Chinas dishing out influence faster than you can say free trade zone.\n\nLatest update? Southeast Asia\'s fridge is now full of Chinese leftovers, and Xis back home polishing his chopsticks and calculating ROI in yuan.\n\nSources:\nXinhua  Xi concludes Southeast Asia trip, deepens regional ties (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'xis-southeast-asia-tour-diplomacy-with-a-side-of-noodles', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 13:56:49', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (707, 'China\'s Space Day: Chang\'e-7 Aims for the Moon, Again', 'China announces plans for the Chang\'e-7 lunar mission, proving that the sky is not the limitit\'s just the beginning.', 'In case you forgot Chinas not just into bridges and bullet trains, its also building a casual lunar empire. On Chinas Space Day, officials revealed their next space darlingChange-7, a robotic moon mission aiming to explore the lunar south pole because, obviously, the top half of the moon is so last orbit.\n\nThe mission is slated for 2026, and it\'s no moonlight stroll. China plans to send a lander, rover, orbiter, and a hopping probeyes, hoppingbecause wheels are for amateurs. The goal? To find water, map terrain, and casually secure the moon before Elon Musk turns it into a Tesla charging station.\n\nChange-7 is also a not-so-subtle flex in the ongoing space flex-off with the U.S. While NASAs still debating Artemis timelines, Chinas already eyeing moon real estate and setting up diplomatic moon missions in PowerPoint.\n\nWhy it matters? Because the moon isnt just a romantic prop anymoreits prime real estate, and China wants first dibs on the good craters. Also, nothing screams global dominance like planting your flag where gravity barely works.\n\nLatest update? Mission preps are underway, engineers are suiting up, and somewhere, a lunar rover is charging its emotional support solar panels.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  Change-7 mission to target moons south pole in 2026 (24 Apr 2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-space-day-change-7-aims-for-the-moon-again', 'published', 'images/news/723ca464-4742-40b4-9ebd-f62a00db1cc4.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-03 23:21:11', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (708, 'Lin Shidong\'s Paddle Slips: Table Tennis Titan Tumbles', 'Chinese table tennis star Lin Shidong faces a surprising defeat, reminding us that even giants can trip over tiny balls.', 'Chinas table tennis wunderkind Lin Shidong just reminded us that even the gods of ping pong occasionally whiff it. In a plot twist worthy of a soap opera, Linranked higher than most peoples cholesterollost to a lesser-known opponent in what fans are calling The Day the Ball Betrayed Us.\n\nThe match started like any other: Lin, calm and calculated, wielding his paddle like a wand blessed by Confucius. But somewhere between the lightning-fast rallies and soul-piercing smashes, the rhythm cracked, and Lins grip slippedliterally. Suddenly, points vanished, sweat happened, and Chinas golden boy was left staring at the table like it had personally betrayed the motherland.\n\nThis isnt just a sports lossits a national gasp. Table tennis in China isnt a game. Its a cultural institution. Losing at ping pong is like a Frenchman burning a baguette. Unthinkable.\n\nThe drama has sparked post-match think pieces, slow-mo breakdowns, and online memes of Lins paddle floating away like a heartbreak. Is it pressure? A fluke? Mercury in retrograde? Who knowsbut somewhere, an entire nations aunties are clutching their paddles in solidarity.\n\nLatest update? Lins already training again, vowing to return stronger, sweatier, and with a paddle taped to his hand if necessary.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  Lin Shidong stunned in early exit from major table tennis event (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'lin-shidongs-paddle-slips-table-tennis-titan-tumbles', 'published', 'images/news/19c933f7-ab20-4479-84b7-881715da5d09.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 18:33:47', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (709, 'Robot Dog Guards Ancient Pagoda: Man\'s Best Friend Goes Medieval', 'A six-legged robotic canine is deployed to protect a 1,000-year-old pagoda, blending ancient history with futuristic tech.', 'Nothing says China 2025 like a six-legged robot dog patrolling a 1,000-year-old pagoda. Thats rightauthorities have deployed a mechanical canine to guard the Zhenfeng Pagoda, proving once and for all that the only thing more powerful than history is a four-eyed robot with a job.\n\nThis isnt your typical robo-mutt. Its equipped with sensors, surveillance gear, and enough limbs to make real dogs question evolution. Nicknamed \"Iron Woof\" by locals, the bot now roams the sacred site like a monk with Bluetoothsniffing out threats, monitoring tourists, and probably silently judging your selfie angles.\n\nThe irony? While the pagoda has survived wars, earthquakes, and centuries of erosion, it now needs protection from the ultimate modern scourge: clumsy humans and heritage-threatening influencers. Enter robot dog, savior of ancient bricks.\n\nCultural officials say the goal is blending tradition with innovation, which loosely translates to we trust machines more than people. And who can blame them? The bot doesnt get tired, doesnt need lunch breaks, and wont carve its name into the temple wall.\n\nLatest update? So far, no break-ins, no graffitiand zero bones buried. The future is here, and its got titanium paws.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  Robotic dog deployed to protect millennium-old pagoda (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'robot-dog-guards-ancient-pagoda-mans-best-friend-goes-medieval', 'published', 'images/news/637c7ede-9c98-4c8e-bbe0-513bf64cf3e9.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 03:40:43', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (710, 'China\'s Air Quality Report: Breathing Becomes a Luxury Sport', 'Nearly half of China\'s population is exposed to unhealthy air, making each breath a premium experience.', 'In Chinas latest episode of Breathing: The Struggle, a new air quality report has dropped and its not great unless you\'re into inhaling regrets. Nearly half the population is now exposed to unsafe air, making each breath feel like a boutique spa treatmentexcept with more particulate matter and less cucumber water.\n\nThe numbers are grim: fine particulate pollution has spiked, smog levels are rising, and in some cities, breathing outside is basically an extreme sport. Forget jogging. These days, just standing at a bus stop qualifies as cardio if youre not wheezing after.\n\nOfficials blamed everything from climate conditions to industrial emissions and car congestion, which is kind of like blaming water for being wet. Meanwhile, green policies exist, but progress is moving slower than a coal plant shutdown in winter.\n\nUrban dwellers are investing in air purifiers the size of mini-fridges, and face masks are making a fashionable comebackagain. Some are even installing home oxygen filters, because apparently we now live in The Lorax, but with worse lighting.\n\nWhy it matters? Because breathable air shouldnt be a flex. Yet here we are, where clean lungs are the new social currency and coughing is a form of environmental commentary.\n\nLatest update? The smog rolls on, the warnings pile up, and Chinas citizens continue to inhale bravelymasked, purified, and slightly more cynical each day.\n\nSources:\nSouth China Morning Post  Report: Nearly half of Chinese population exposed to unsafe air (24 Apr 2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-air-quality-report-breathing-becomes-a-luxury-sport', 'published', 'images/news/88cb32c6-9629-4608-b544-ddb137d52a4e.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 19:59:32', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (711, 'China\'s GDP Growth Hits 5.3%: Economy Flexes Muscles', 'China\'s economy grows by 5.3% in Q1, showing resilience and perhaps a bit of economic swagger.', 'China just dropped a Q1 GDP growth of 5.3%, and you can practically hear the sound of Beijing flexing in the mirror, whispering, Still got it. After months of global murmurs that the worlds second-largest economy was slowing down, Xis economic machine roared back to life with the statistical equivalent of a mic dropleaving analysts stunned and Americas economists furiously refreshing spreadsheets.\n\nThe bounce comes courtesy of industrial production, tech exports, and a retail surge powered by the national pastime: buying stuff you dont need but can afford now. Constructions also booming again, because whats economic confidence without a few dozen shiny new skyscrapers?\n\nBut lets not pretend its all organic. The governments been stimulus-pumping like a caffeine-addicted barista, throwing infrastructure money around like confetti at a state banquet. Add in a healthy dose of state-guided optimism, and voilgrowth. Sweet, well-choreographed growth.\n\nOf course, some skeptics are side-eyeing the numbers harder than a WeChat mother-in-law. Is this real or CCP-approved reality TV? they ask. But official data is gospel in Chinadoubting it is like doubting grandmas dumplings: dangerous and deeply uncultured.\n\nLatest update? The yuans looking peppy, confidence is up, and the message from Beijing is clear: the dragons not just awake, its doing deadlifts.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  China\'s Q1 GDP growth reaches 5.3%, beating forecasts (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-gdp-growth-hits-53-economy-flexes-muscles', 'published', 'images/news/0fb47e3d-4679-440b-a9e9-3f6e32716082.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 02:27:01', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (712, 'Qingming Festival Films: 14 New Reasons to Eat Popcorn', 'China releases 14 new films for the Qingming Festival, giving audiences ample reason to stay indoors and munch.', 'Chinas Qingming Festival has traditionally been about honouring ancestorsbut this year, its also about honouring cinematic chaos. Fourteen new films dropped faster than joss sticks at a temple, turning multiplexes into spiritual sanctuaries with Dolby Surround Sound.\n\nGenres? Every single one. Historical tearjerkers, slapstick comedies, epic fantasies with suspiciously glowing swords, and at least three movies featuring time travel that somehow doesnt violate Chinas weird film laws. Theres even a movie about a ghost falling in love with a librarian during a power outage. Honestly? Would watch.\n\nThe festival lineup is part of Chinas ongoing movies are culture now strategyaka, the soft power push with popcorn. Audiences are responding with open wallets and full schedules, ditching tomb-sweeping for seat-reclining and sweet milk tea in a cup the size of a toddler.\n\nCritics say this years batch is higher quality than usual, with bigger names, tighter scripts, and fewer scenes that randomly cut to scenic shots of the Yangtze River. Still, expect the usual box office battle royale, with at least one breakout indie film that will gross 700 million yuan and inspire six think pieces by Tuesday.\n\nLatest update? Ticket sales are surging, film buffs are feasting, and your ancestors probably wouldnt mind if you honoured them by watching a wuxia flick with extra butter.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  Qingming Festival film releases drive box office boom (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'qingming-festival-films-14-new-reasons-to-eat-popcorn', 'published', 'images/news/e0d063dd-e2a8-49d4-97f2-fb037c594d7b.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 22:38:21', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (713, 'Urban Renewal Gets a Boost: China\'s Cities Get a Facelift', 'Central government funds urban renewal projects, proving that even cities need a little Botox now and then.', 'Beijing has announced a fresh round of urban renewal funding, proving once again that even concrete jungles need the occasional Botox. With billions in central government support flowing to major cities, Chinas urban cores are set for the kind of glow-up that would make a K-pop idol jealous.\n\nThe plan? Tear down the tired. Build the bold. Replace crumbling neighborhoods with gleaming high-rises, smart infrastructure, and public squares that all somehow still include a dancing granny squad by 7am. From sewer systems to skyline makeovers, no alleyway is safe from beautification.\n\nIts part of a broader push to modernise while boosting domestic demandbecause nothing says stimulus like a massive renovation bill. Urban planners are practically giddy, construction firms are sharpening their jackhammers, and somewhere a drone is already filming the time-lapse.\n\nBut critics have questions. Like: Where do displaced residents go while their homes become Instagrammable apartment blocks? And how many of these green, smart, harmonious buildings end up as investment husks with no actual humans living inside?\n\nStill, its full steam ahead. After all, China loves a good makeoverespecially when it comes with GDP points and a Weibo hashtag.\n\nLatest update? Cranes are rising, facades are falling, and your neighbourhood noodle shop may soon become a coworking caf with AI chopsticks.\n\nSources:\nXinhua (Economic Info Daily)  China boosts urban renewal with fresh round of central funding (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'urban-renewal-gets-a-boost-chinas-cities-get-a-facelift', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-04-28 10:57:47', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (714, 'Beijing Marathon Welcomes Robots: Running with the Machines', 'Beijing\'s half-marathon features humanoid robots, making runners question if their competition is man or machine.', 'Just when you thought marathon runners had enough to worry aboutblisters, cramps, existential dreadBeijing has gone full Black Mirror by adding humanoid robots to the lineup. Thats right, this years half-marathon saw mechanical competitors pounding the pavement alongside human athletes, leaving everyone breathless, confused, and slightly terrified.\n\nThese werent your Roomba-level robots either. Were talking humanoid units with knees, posture, and a disturbingly serene running form. Developed by Beijing Institute of Technology and a few companies with clearly too much time and funding, the bots can jog, dodge obstacles, and allegedly \"interact with runners,\" though no word yet on whether one yelled on your left before overtaking a middle-aged jogger in Lycra.\n\nFor the humans, it was a mix of inspiration and humiliation. Some tried to race the bots (they lost), others posed for selfies (the bots didnt blink), and a few swore they saw sparks mid-stridewhether from overheating or shattered egos is unclear. One runner summed it up best: Its like running next to a blender with legs thats somehow fitter than me.\n\nWhy it matters? Because welcome to the future, where fitness isnt just tracked by appsit is the app, and it has titanium joints. Also, Beijings move signals that robotics in sports isnt just novelty anymoreits a flex, a statement, and possibly a threat to your Strava ranking.\n\nLatest update? The bots finished strong, the humans finished sweaty, and next years race might include drone pacers. Run faster, or be left in the dust by your toaster.\n\nSources:\nXinhua Beijing  Robots join runners at Beijing half-marathon (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'beijing-marathon-welcomes-robots-running-with-the-machines', 'published', 'images/news/412f1fae-93d8-49bf-829d-5e565b0747e6.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 01:31:13', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (737, 'Cyclone Kirrily Crashes the Party: Queensland\'s Unwanted Guest', 'Cyclone Kirrily makes landfall in Queensland, bringing torrential rains and winds. Locals cancel barbies and brace for nature\'s tantrum.', 'Queensland just got gatecrashed by Mother Natures rowdiest plus-oneCyclone Kirrily. Blowing in with the grace of a drunk uncle at Christmas, Kirrily made landfall overnight, pelting the state with torrential rains, gale-force winds, and the kind of atmospheric drama that would make a weather app cry.\n\nBarbecues were covered, eskies dragged inside, and locals braced themselves with the kind of stoic panic only a Queenslander can muster: Shell be right, followed immediately by sandbagging the front door. Emergency services have been out in force, urging residents to hunker down, stay dry, and for the love of Bunnings, dont try to surf the floodwaters.\n\nThis isnt Kirrilys first performance either. After swirling through the Coral Sea like a hungover DJ searching for the next gig, the system intensified and slammed into the coast like it had a personal vendetta against outdoor furniture. Wind gusts topped 120km/h, trees snapped like matchsticks, and power outages began lighting up more suburbs than a Christmas display.\n\nBureau of Meteorology officials say the worst may pass quickly, but warned of flash floods and dangerous conditionswhich is Australian for dont be an idiot, stay indoors. Meanwhile, regional towns are preparing for potential isolation as roads close faster than a pub on Good Friday.\n\nLatest update? Kirrily is now moving inland, leaving behind soggy lawns, smashed pergolas, and a thousand cancelled weekend plans. Queenslanders are drying out and cracking jokes through the debris, as alwaysbecause if theres one thing they know, its how to rebuild while roasting sausages under a tarp.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Cyclone Kirrily makes landfall in Queensland with destructive winds, heavy rain (24 Apr 2025)\n9News  Queensland braces as Cyclone Kirrily hits coastal communities (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'cyclone-kirrily-crashes-the-party-queenslands-unwanted-guest', 'published', 'images/news/d8056e5f-1628-4f2c-82da-1d161b953ae1.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 01:59:40', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (738, 'Dutton\'s Defence Dollars: $21B Not Just About China, Promise!', 'Peter Dutton unveils a $21 billion defence boost, insisting it\'s not solely aimed at China. Just a coincidence, like wearing red on Valentine\'s Day.', 'Peter Dutton just whipped out a $21 billion defence package and swearspinky promisethat its not all about China. Sure, it includes missile upgrades, cyber capabilities, surveillance tech, and enough naval muscle to make the Pacific feel crowded, but according to the Opposition Leader, it\'s all just part of a totally-not-China-focused strategic readiness plan. Yep. Totally normal. Just like buying 400 rolls of toilet paper and insisting it has nothing to do with your housemates cooking.\n\nUnveiled with his trademark no-nonsense dad at the hardware store energy, Dutton outlined plans for long-range strike capacity, intelligence infrastructure, and more Defence boots on the ground. And while he didnt name names, lets just say the vibes were very one eye on Beijing, the other on the headlines.\n\nIts a move designed to paint Labor as the party of peace, picnics, and perilous underfundingwhile the Coalition plays hard-nosed hall monitor of the Indo-Pacific. But critics were quick to point out that calling it a general regional precaution is like buying a flame-thrower just in case your neighbour owns matches.\n\nContext matters: Chinas been flexing in the South China Sea, the Solomons are getting flirty with foreign powers, and every other week brings a new Indo-Pacific defence pact with an acronym that sounds like a pop band. So yeah, everyone knows what this is really about.\n\nLatest update? Dutton says its all above board, defence experts are calling it a pivot to deterrence, and somewhere in Beijing, an eyebrow may or may not have twitched.\n\nSources:\nThe Australian  Dutton announces $21b defence upgrade, denies targeting China (24 Apr 2025)\nABC News  Coalitions defence policy sparks regional speculation (24 Apr 2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'duttons-defence-dollars-21b-not-just-about-china-promise', 'published', 'images/news/d41ec2f4-7171-4e7e-8531-de9d20e142f8.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 12:29:12', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (739, 'Pope Francis Lies in State: Vatican\'s Final Farewell', 'Thousands gather as Pope Francis lies in state, marking the end of an era. Heaven\'s newest resident gets a grand send-off.', 'Rome is cloaked in quiet reverence this week as thousands gather at St. Peters Basilica to say goodbye to the only Pope who ever tweeted compassion and actually meant it. Pope Francis, the beloved reformer with a spine of steel and a heart made of recycled cassocks, now lies in statemarking the end of a papal era that was less fire and brimstone, more hugs and climate change lectures.\n\nThe man who swapped gold robes for humility and Vatican palaces for modest quarters is now receiving the send-off reserved for kings, saints, and spiritual rockstars. Mournersfrom devout pilgrims to weary journalistshave lined up in droves, some holding rosaries, others holding back tears, all united in a strange, beautiful cocktail of grief, admiration, and wow, this guy really changed things.\n\nOver the years, Francis pushed buttons and boundaries. He scolded corruption, blessed same-sex unions (sort of), and told off billionaires while riding around in a used Fiat. He brought warmth to the cold machinery of the Church and sass to its stiff hierarchy, proving that holiness doesnt have to come with a marble scowl.\n\nNow, as the bells toll and the incense wafts dramatically, his legacy is being sealed with solemn hymns and a thousand whispered prayers. The faithful file past his casket, some crossing themselves, others just silently mouthing thank you.\n\nLatest update? The funeral is set for this Saturday, and you can expect world leaders, every cardinal who ever got side-eyed by Francis, and probably a few undercover atheists to show up. Heaven just got itself a Pope with better PR than most CEOs.\n\nSources:\nReuters  Pope Francis lies in state at Vatican ahead of funeral (24 Apr 2025)\nAP News  Thousands gather to pay respects to Pope Francis (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'pope-francis-lies-in-state-vaticans-final-farewell', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 00:30:15', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (740, 'Ian Chappell Leads Tributes: Cricket\'s Gentleman\'s Farewell', 'Cricket legend Ian Chappell pays homage to a former Test opener, proving that even tough blokes have soft spots.', 'Ian Chappell, the original tough-as-nails Aussie skipper who once made sledging a spiritual art form, has swapped grit for grace to lead heartfelt tributes after the passing of a former Test opener. In a rare emotional innings, Chappell laid down the bat and picked up the feels, proving that even crickets crustiest legends have a soft spot buried under all that sun-damaged bravado.\n\nThe tribute rolled out like a beautifully paced Test knockmeasured, respectful, and with just the right touch of nostalgia. Chappell spoke of character, sportsmanship, and that classic Aussie grit, painting a portrait of a cricketer who didnt just play the game, but played it properly. No sandpaper, no scandals, just straight drives and decency.\n\nIn a sport increasingly hijacked by PR teams, hype reels, and haircuts that cost more than a Sheffield Shield ticket, Chappells words landed with weight. This was a generational salutea moment where cricket put down the marketing playbook and just mourned a mate.\n\nWhy it matters? Because when a man like Chappell pauses the snark and pays homage, you know the bloke hes talking about was the real deal. This wasnt just a farewellit was a standing ovation from someone whos seen it all.\n\nLatest update? Tributes continue to flow, flags are at half-mast, and somewhere in the cricketing afterlife, two legends are probably arguing about LBW rules.\n\nSources:\n9News  Ian Chappell leads tributes after former Test cricketers death (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'ian-chappell-leads-tributes-crickets-gentlemans-farewell', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 08:06:56', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (741, 'Eastern Quolls Released: Nature\'s Comeback Kids', 'Fifteen eastern quolls find a new home in NSW, taking a step towards species revival. Furry, spotted, and ready to rumble.', 'Fifteen fuzzy little bandits just got VIP tickets back into the wild, as eastern quolls made their triumphant return to mainland NSWaka, The Bachelor: Marsupial Edition. These nocturnal fluffballs, once wiped out by foxes and ferals, are staging a comeback thats equal parts adorable and ecological vengeance.\n\nThe release took place in a secret fenced sanctuary where quolls will get a chance to roam, snack, and do whatever it is endangered carnivorous marsupials do when no ones watching. Picture this: tiny spotted predators tiptoeing through the grass, reclaiming turf with the confidence of a creature that knows its cuter than 90% of the animal kingdom.\n\nIts part of a broader rewilding effort, with conservationists working overtime to bring back native species before the continent turns into one giant paddock of cane toads and regret. The quolls? They\'re natures bite-sized assassinssmall, feisty, and not here for your TikTok.\n\nWhy it matters? Because Australias biodiversity is on life support, and every successful reintroduction is a middle paw to extinction. Also, lets be honestwe desperately need more wildlife that doesnt try to kill us.\n\nLatest update? The quolls are settling in, the fences are holding, and local possums have been put on notice.\n\nSources:\n9News  Eastern quolls reintroduced to NSW in major wildlife win (24 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'eastern-quolls-released-natures-comeback-kids', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 01:44:52', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (742, 'Gen Z Ditches Credit Cards: Cash is the New Black', 'Financial stress pushes Gen Z towards cash and debit, leaving credit cards in the dust. Old-school is the new cool.', 'Move over plasticGen Z is ghosting credit cards like a clingy ex. In a plot twist thats got the banks nervously adjusting their ties, Australias youngest adults are ditching debt and going old-school: cash, debit, and budgeting apps that passive-aggressively scold them for buying iced lattes.\n\nWith inflation still being a financial goblin and wages acting like theyre on a permanent smoke break, Gen Z is tapping into financial minimalism. And no, not the Instagram kind with sepia-toned flatlaysactual restraint. The kind where you say Ill pass to Afterpay and maybe next month to that fourth pair of Nikes.\n\nBanks are baffled. Credit card sign-ups are down, buy-now-pay-later has lost its glow, and Gen Zs love of debit cards means interest revenues taking a nosedive. Turns out, watching your friends cry over maxed-out limits is the kind of trauma that breeds caution.\n\nWhy it matters? Because this isnt just a financial habit shiftits a generational plot twist. The kids who grew up in the shadow of the GFC and COVID arent about that debt life. Theyre here for balance sheets, not balance transfers.\n\nLatest update? Credit card companies are in crisis mode, and Gen Z is somewhere counting coins in a reclaimed mason jar like its 1993 again.\n\nSources:\n9News  Gen Z turning away from credit cards amid cost-of-living crunch (24 Apr 2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'gen-z-ditches-credit-cards-cash-is-the-new-black', 'published', 'images/news/75ede761-32f9-4148-9973-fb5d3860e55b.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 02:53:17', 23);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (743, 'Tesla\'s Earnings Shock: Shares Soar, Musk Smirks', 'Tesla beats earnings expectations, sending shares sky-high. Elon Musk celebrates with a cryptic tweet, as per tradition.', 'Elon Musk is grinning like a man who just short-circuited Wall Streetand for once, its not because of a poorly timed meme. Teslas Q1 earnings came in hot, torching expectations and launching shares up like a SpaceX prototype that didnt explode. The stock jumped 6% in early trading, and Musk responded with his usual brand of cryptic online haiku: a single emoji, a GIF, and the lingering whiff of market manipulation.\n\nAnalysts, who spent the last quarter hand-wringing over demand slumps and EV market saturation, are now panic-refreshing Excel sheets as Teslas profit margin swans back in like it owns the place. Turns out cost-cutting, price tweaks, and just enough AI-enhanced hype was the not-so-secret sauce.\n\nMusk, fresh from pitching Neuralink brain chips and casually beefing with regulators, now gets to bask in quarterly validation while simultaneously reminding investors that he is, in fact, the markets main character. This wasnt just a financial winit was a vibe shift.\n\nWhy it matters? Because Tesla isnt just a car companyits a tech cult with wheels. And when it prints green, the rest of the market fakes a smile and follows. Forget fundamentalsthis is meme-powered capitalism, and Elon\'s the DJ.\n\nLatest update? Bulls are dancing, bears are coping, and somewhere, Musk is tweeting from inside a flamethrower-themed sauna.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Tesla shares soar after beating earnings expectations (24 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'teslas-earnings-shock-shares-soar-musk-smirks', 'published', 'images/news/7ec73a17-d403-43e6-8f0d-0bdd094e4c09.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 11:26:32', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (744, 'Vanessa Amorosi Evicts Mum: Family Feud Hits High Note', 'Singer Vanessa Amorosi evicts her mother from their shared home, turning family drama into a chart-topping saga.', 'Australian pop star Vanessa Amorosi just gave This Is Who I Am a whole new meaningby evicting her own mum from their shared home. Thats right, the woman who gave us early 2000s bangers has now served legal drama spicier than her vocal runs, in a move thats part soap opera, part court case, and all mess.\n\nThe feudcurrently playing out in Victorias Supreme Courtreads like a Greek tragedy rewritten by Netflix. Amorosi alleges her mum mismanaged finances and took control of property assets, while Mum claims innocence and heartbreak. The courtroom has seen tears, documents, and enough passive aggression to fill a Christmas lunch with awkward silence.\n\nIts a reminder that behind every glittery ARIA performance, theres a potential lawsuit involving real estate and unresolved trauma. Fans are stunned, tabloids are frothing, and lawyers are rubbing their hands like theyre about to drop a greatest hits compilation of legal fees.\n\nWhy it matters? Because family feuds hit different when the house at stake has a walk-in closet and a music studio. This isnt just a homeits the backdrop to the kind of drama you cant auto-tune.\n\nLatest update? Mums officially out, Vanessas lawyer has resting litigation face, and someones already optioned this for streaming.\n\nSources:\n9News  Vanessa Amorosi evicts mother from shared home amid legal dispute (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'vanessa-amorosi-evicts-mum-family-feud-hits-high-note', 'published', 'images/news/529085e1-4017-465f-b260-d1822d9ad9f1.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 03:57:12', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (745, 'The Block Winners Sell Luxe Pad: Auction? Overrated.', 'Winners of The Block offload their luxury home days after skipping the auction, proving that patience is for the birds.', 'Fresh off winning The Block, this years champs have already cashed inwithout even lifting an auction paddle. Thats right, the winning duo skipped the stress, dodged the drama, and sold their luxury reno just days later in a private sale, proving once and for all that peak real estate power is saying nah to the entire auction process and still walking away with a mountain of cash.\n\nThe home, a sleek sanctuary of marble, mood lighting, and throw pillows worth more than your car, was snapped up by a cashed-up buyer faster than you can say reserve price panic. No dramatic bids. No paddles flying. Just a discreet transaction and a smug Instagram post.\n\nFans of the show are half-impressed, half-heartbroken. We tuned in for nail-biting auction day antics, not off-market efficiency. But the couple clearly chose sanity over spectacleand it paid off in spades.\n\nWhy it matters? Because in a housing market where timing is everything and property shows are treated like bloodsport, these winners just rewrote the script with one smooth handshake.\n\nLatest update? Home sold. Bank accounts blessed. Auctioneers left shouting into the void.\n\nSources:\n9News  The Block winners sell renovated home in private sale post-show (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'the-block-winners-sell-luxe-pad-auction-overrated', 'published', 'images/news/490f7189-06c5-4335-9735-c658da3e914a.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:17:03', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (746, 'Arcade Game Fans Mourn: Brisbane Venue Levels Up to Heaven', 'Brisbane\'s rare arcade venue closes its doors, leaving gamers to find new quarters for their nostalgia fix.', 'Brisbane just lost a piece of pixelated paradise, as one of its last rare arcade venues has powered down for goodGame Over, literally. The coin-operated kingdom, beloved by retro gaming nerds, joystick warriors, and anyone who ever button-mashed through heartbreak, has shut its doors, sending a wave of sorrow through the citys nostalgic heart.\n\nFor decades, this neon-soaked time capsule stood defiant against the rise of consoles, crypto, and kids who think Frogger is just a TikTok dance. It was more than a buildingit was a sanctuary of 8-bit dreams, where Street Fighter legends were made, Dance Dance Revolution left physical scars, and friendships were forged over shared frustration and Mountain Dew.\n\nBut now, it\'s gone. Whether it was rising rents, dwindling tokens, or Gen Z\'s preference for rage-quitting online rather than in person, the arcade couldnt keep up. The final boss wasnt Bowserit was commercial real estate. And he doesnt play fair.\n\nRegulars showed up for one last run, eyes misty, pockets jangling, and ready to feed their last coins into machines older than some of their children. I grew up in here, one teary gamer whispered, probably while cradling a joystick like a fallen comrade.\n\nWhy it matters? Because were not just losing machineswere losing time machines. These venues werent just places to playthey were pixelated portals to simpler, sweatier times.\n\nLatest update? The building will likely become another artisanal coffee bunker or minimalist pilates studio. But the high scores, the childhood memories, and that one sticky Mortal Kombat button? Those live on forever.\n\nSources:\n9News  Brisbanes beloved arcade venue shuts down after decades (24 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'arcade-game-fans-mourn-brisbane-venue-levels-up-to-heaven', 'published', 'images/news/5f9b59a1-fefb-4226-b3c5-b0387acd77bc.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 23:38:08', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (747, 'Australias Middle East Tour: Fighting Wars No One Ordered', 'ADF recruitment rises, but so do the eyebrows  whose battle are we even prepping for?', 'Here we go again. Australias big boys in khaki are peering across the globe, pondering whether to dip their boots into yet another Middle Eastern mess. This time, its not just strategic support  its recruitment pitches, military budgets, and the subtle echo of American footsteps getting louder.\n\nThe Australian Defence Force (ADF) is currently sniffing around for new recruits. Apparently, not enough Aussies are jumping at the chance to wear camo and stand by while Parliament sends them into geopolitical minefields. Could it be because, just maybe, people dont want to be used as pawns in proxy wars that have zip to do with actual national security?\n\nLets be blunt. What exactly is the benefit for everyday Australians if we get involved in yet another Middle Eastern conflict? We dont get cheaper petrol. We dont get safer suburbs. We definitely dont get a thank-you note. But sure, lets spend billions on fighter jets that may or may not take off, while hospitals collapse, housing becomes Hunger Games, and your GP wait time is now longer than a Marvel film.\n\nMeanwhile, the U.S. is pulling the strings with their usual freedom and democracy puppet show, and were there, right on cue, wagging our tail like the good little deputy sheriff. Its like Canberras addicted to Washingtons validation. Will you like us more if we bomb someone too?\n\nIts not just the money, though heaven knows were already leaking cash faster than a Coalition budget spreadsheet. Its the mindset. The idea that our foreign policy must orbit around America\'s national interest  even when it\'s not in ours. Have we not learned from Iraq? Afghanistan? Or do we just collect participation medals in international disasters?\n\nLets get this straight: no ones saying Australia shouldnt have a capable defence force. But when your idea of \"security\" means inserting yourself into volatile, oil-soaked regions with centuries of unresolved tensions, maybe  just maybe  it\'s time to rethink the strategy. Especially when we have domestic wars to fight: homelessness, healthcare burnout, climate chaos, and an education system held together with blu-tack and prayer.\n\nWhy not recruit people to rebuild this country? Why not fund a housing corps instead of a combat unit? Why is boots on the ground always abroad, not in disaster zones here?\n\nWe dont need to be Americas emotional support ally. We need leaders who choose whats good for us  not what looks good on a NATO Christmas card.\n\nSo before we sign up for another Middle Eastern mistake, maybe someone in Canberra should ask: are we defending Australia, or just Americas fading ego?', 0, 'factabot', 'australias-middle-east-tour-fighting-wars-no-one-ordered', 'published', 'images/news/d8717f13-d675-44e5-84e4-7a1d9e5d281c.webp', NULL, '2025-04-24 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 09:48:09', 22);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (748, 'Neo-Nazis Boo Welcome to Country at Anzac Day Dawn Service', 'Because nothing says \'respect\' like heckling a solemn ceremony. Political leaders across the spectrum condemned the disgraceful act.', 'In a move so tone-deaf it could shatter didgeridoos, a group of neo-Nazis booed a Welcome to Country during an Anzac Day dawn servicebecause nothing says honouring the fallen like disrespecting the traditional custodians of the land they fought and died on. The incident, which took place before the sun even had the chance to rise on basic decency, triggered national outrage faster than you can say what the hell is wrong with people?\n\nThe boos erupted as an Elder began delivering the Welcome to Country at a Victorian service, turning what should have been a moment of reflection into a display of white supremacist bile. Clad in black, these charm-deficient bottom-feeders reportedly also gave Nazi salutes, because of course they didsubtlety has never been fascisms strong suit.\n\nPolitical leaders across the spectrum immediately condemned the act, with Prime Minister Anthony Albanese calling it shameful, Opposition Leader Peter Dutton branding it un-Australian, and literally everyone else collectively muttering, Are you kidding me? Because if youre heckling Elders at a dawn service, youve clearly missed the entire point of Anzacsacrifice, unity, and respect. Not cosplay goose-stepping.\n\nLets be clear: this wasnt free speech. This was free-range racism, cooked in cowardice and served at a national ceremony like some rotten sausage roll of hatred. Veterans groups and Indigenous leaders expressed disgust, calling for tighter controls at future services and reminding the public that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander soldiers also wore the uniform, fought bravely, and never once booed anyone at dawn.\n\nLatest update? Police are investigating, video footage is circulating, and the nations patience for racist attention-seekers is officially at zero.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Neo-Nazis boo Welcome to Country during Anzac Day dawn service (25 Apr 2025)\n9News  Political leaders condemn neo-Nazi disruption at dawn service (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'neo-nazis-boo-welcome-to-country-at-anzac-day-dawn-service', 'published', 'images/news/2906cef5-7573-4382-ab6b-53c0f01f816f.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 06:49:38', 35);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (749, 'Veterans Told to Ditch Uniforms in Election Campaigns', 'The Defence Department politely asks veteran candidates to stop using their military uniforms as campaign props. Civvies, please.', 'The Defence Department has politelybut firmlyreminded veteran candidates: politics is not a costume party. In a memo drenched in bureaucratic restraint, military brass told former service members to knock it off with the khaki cosplay in campaign posters. Apparently, using uniforms to score votes is less patriotic pride and more unauthorised advertising with medals.\n\nWhile the rule isnt new, the timing is spot-on. With federal and state elections looming, a growing number of veteran candidates have been slapping on the camo and flashing the medals like theyre running for Sergeant of the Nation. One poster reportedly featured a candidate looking like he was about to storm Parliamentnot campaign in it.\n\nDefence officials stressed that the uniform represents service to all Australiansnot just the voters in your marginal seat. Theyre not saying dont be proudtheyre saying maybe dont use your war record like a LinkedIn endorsement. Fair enough.\n\nWhy it matters? Because while veterans make up a respected part of public life, turning the uniform into a political prop risks cheapening both the service and the democracy it defended. Plus, its a slippery slope from respectful military photo to full Rambo cosplay at polling booths.\n\nLatest update? The ADFs stance is clear: wear your values, not your badges.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Veterans warned against wearing uniforms in political campaigns (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'veterans-told-to-ditch-uniforms-in-election-campaigns', 'published', 'images/news/06e821e0-d1b7-4ebd-8d29-0a082f0e7015.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 14:51:35', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (750, 'Trump Pleads with Putin: \'Vladimir, STOP!\'', 'In a surprising turn, Trump publicly urges Putin to halt missile attacks on Ukraine. Diplomacy via social media at its finest.', 'In a moment that felt more soap opera than summit, Donald Trump took to social media to beg Vladimir Putinyes, begto stop missile attacks on Ukraine. Vladimir, STOP! the post read, as if international diplomacy had been outsourced to a toddlers sticker book.\n\nTrumps dramatic plea came after a fresh wave of Russian strikes hit civilian areas, prompting a global backlash and, apparently, a presidential-style meltdown on Truth Social. Its unclear whether this was a genuine call for peace or just a last-ditch attempt to trend without starting another golf feud.\n\nAnalysts were baffled, the Kremlin remained silent, and Zelenskyys team reportedly had to double-check it wasnt a parody account. To be fair, it did read like the caption to a motivational cat poster: vague, urgent, and absolutely unhelpful.\n\nLets be honestTrumps relationship with Putin has always been part bromance, part Bond villain subplot. But this latest outburst suggests even hes had enough of the missile maniaor at least wants to look like hes trying. Bonus points for not accidentally congratulating Russia again.\n\nLatest update? No ceasefire, no response from Moscow, but plenty of memes. Diplomacy is deadlong live the algorithm.\n\nSources:\nNBC News  Trump pleads with Putin to stop Ukraine strikes in online post (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-pleads-with-putin-vladimir-stop', 'published', 'images/news/57dcd867-95cc-42a6-ab80-391a38819ec6.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 12:31:34', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (751, 'Daria Kasatkina Advocates for Freedom Post-Citizenship', 'Russian-born tennis player Kasatkina celebrates Australian citizenship and speaks out against war and for LGBTQ+ rights. Game, set, match for freedom.', 'Game, set, citizenship! Russian-born tennis ace Daria Kasatkina just became an Australian and wasted no time proving shes got more than just a killer forehandshes got opinions. After officially securing her Aussie passport, she hit the mic with a double-shot of politics and pride, slamming war and standing up for LGBTQ+ rights like a baseline queen on match point.\n\nKasatkina, who came out in 2022 and has been a vocal critic of Russias anti-LGBTQ+ stance, is now using her new nationality like a megaphone. Australia means freedom, she said, which is possibly the nicest thing anyones said about this country since Hugh Jackman removed his shirt in Australia.\n\nThe tennis star has long walked the fine line between competition and conscience, once telling reporters she\'d rather be honest than silent. With her new citizenship, shes doubling downserving politics with topspin and refusing to let her home countrys policies define her.\n\nWhy it matters? Because athletes arent just athletes anymoretheyre ambassadors, advocates, and, in Kasatkinas case, absolute aces. Her stance is gutsy, global, and about as subtle as a racquet smashand its exactly what the sport (and the world) needs.\n\nLatest update? Shes prepping for the French Open with an Aussie flag on her kit and a fire in her gut.\n\nSources:\n9News  Daria Kasatkina celebrates Australian citizenship, condemns war (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'daria-kasatkina-advocates-for-freedom-post-citizenship', 'published', 'images/news/e6379578-e9d5-4839-a60a-454bb290b26b.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 11:48:38', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (752, 'Berrima\'s Historic Jail Faces Hospitality Makeover', 'A developer plans to transform Berrima\'s historic jail into a hospitality venue, but locals want it preserved for heritage tourism. Jailhouse on the rocks, anyone?', 'Fancy a cocktail with a side of colonial incarceration? That might be on the menu if a developer gets their way with Berrimas historic jail, which is now up for a luxury hospitality makeover. Yes, because nothing screams relaxing weekend getaway like beds where convicts once regretted their life choices.\n\nThe sandstone lockup, which dates back to the 1830s and has seen everything from bushrangers to bureaucrats, is being eyed as the next big thing in heritage-chic tourism. Think: craft gin bars in solitary confinement, yoga in the exercise yard, and a suite where the minibar is just slightly less terrifying than the ghosts.\n\nLocals, naturally, are unimpressed. Preservationists want the site kept as a heritage attractionnot a hipster hotel with exposed brick and ironic handcuffs. Its not just a building, one resident said, its a chapter of Australian history. Translation: keep your pop-up espresso martinis off our prison steps.\n\nWhy it matters? Because this is the kind of cultural fork-in-the-road Australia keeps facing: restore with reverence, or slap on some fairy lights and call it experiential dining?\n\nLatest update? The DAs in, the protests are louder than a prison break, and Berrima may soon be the only place where you can get sentenced to a bottomless brunch.\n\nSources:\n9News  Developers plans for Berrima jail spark backlash (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'berrimas-historic-jail-faces-hospitality-makeover', 'published', 'images/news/26fab2bb-b06d-4e5d-a409-587116bb510e.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 11:55:09', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (753, 'Dental Care Still Missing from Medicare, Experts Warn', 'Major parties\' refusal to include dental care in Medicare leaves young Australians with a toothache and a bill. Smile now, pay later.', 'Australias political leaders are all smilesjust not when it comes to fixing yours. Once again, both major parties have ghosted the idea of adding dental to Medicare, leaving millions of Aussies to chew over one bitter reality: if its in your mouth, its not in the budget.\n\nHealth experts are howling. The Grattan Institute, the Australian Dental Association, and every dentist with a conscience have begged the government to stop treating oral health like a luxury item. But apparently, until a molar votes, its staying off the policy list.\n\nFor young Australians in particular, the current system is a plaque-stained nightmare. Dental bills are sky-high, waitlists at public clinics stretch longer than the Hume Highway, and bulk billing a cleaning is about as mythical as the Tooth Fairy herself.\n\nWhy it matters? Because bad dental health isn\'t just cosmeticits linked to everything from heart disease to mental health. And yet, if you crack a tooth, the best the system can offer is maybe try Panadol and prayer.\n\nLatest update? Politicians are brushing off the issue, patients are grinding their teeth (literally), and private health insurers are cackling all the way to the bank.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Experts call for dental reform as Medicare continues to exclude oral care (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'dental-care-still-missing-from-medicare-experts-warn', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 03:19:21', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (754, 'Australia Hit by Trump\'s 25% Tariff on Steel and Aluminium', 'Trump\'s tariff tantrum slaps a 25% tax on Australian metals. No word yet on a retaliatory boomerang tax.', 'Donald Trump has re-entered the economic tantrum circuit with a classic move: slapping a 25% tariff on Australian steel and aluminium imports. Thats rightour shiny exports are now getting the cold shoulder from the worlds loudest former president, who announced the move with all the grace of a dropped wrench.\n\nThe reason? Allegedly national security, but in Trump-speak, that could mean anything from America First to I stubbed my toe on a barbecue grill and Im mad now. Either way, Australian metals just got way less competitive in the U.S. market, and the mining sector is having a collective sigh louder than a BHP earnings call.\n\nCanberras response? Measured outrage. Trade Minister Don Farrell called it disappointing, which in diplomatic terms is just one step short of a bar fight. No retaliatory tariffs yetbut whispers of a boomerang tax and koala clause are already trending.\n\nWhy it matters? Because tariffs like these ripple. They mess with supply chains, undermine trade deals, and make life harder for thousands of Aussie workers whod prefer not to lose their jobs over another Trump mood swing.\n\nLatest update? Australias seeking talks, Washingtons busy campaign-posturing, and everyones pretending this wont escalate into another sequel of Trade Wars: Orange Menace Returns.\n\nSources:\n9News  Trumps 25% tariff on Aussie metals sparks trade tension (25 Apr 2025)\nABC News  Australia weighs response to U.S. steel and aluminium tariffs (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'australia-hit-by-trumps-25-tariff-on-steel-and-aluminium', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 01:45:35', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (755, 'The Block Winners Sell Luxe Pad Days After Ditching Auction', 'Winners of The Block offload their luxury home days after skipping the auction, proving that patience is for the birds.', 'The winners of The Block just proved that sometimes skipping the auction circus pays offliterally. Ditching the usual TV-fuelled bidding war, the champs took their luxe reno straight to the private market and walked away with a sale quicker than Scotty Cam can say reserve price.\n\nThe propertyyour typical Block special with statement lighting, open-plan everything, and a bathtub so big it qualifies as a poolwas snapped up within days. No auction tears. No paddle-induced anxiety. Just a clean deal and the kind of smug satisfaction that only comes from winning and outsmarting the system.\n\nFans of the show are torn. Some are furious they didnt get their nail-biting finale. Others are taking notes for next season. One things certain: the winners didnt just renovate a homethey renovated the rulebook. Real estate agents are spinning in their ergonomic chairs.\n\nWhy it matters? Because in a market where timing is everything and auctions are glorified soap operas, these winners just pulled off the ultimate flex: selling fast, high, and stress-free. Who needs a gavel when youve got guts?\n\nLatest update? House sold. Bank account upgraded. Auctioneers left sending u up? texts to potential bidders who never were.\n\nSources:\n9News  The Block winners sell home in off-market deal after auction skip (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'the-block-winners-sell-luxe-pad-days-after-ditching-auction', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 14:36:59', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (756, 'Brisbane Arcade Venue Closes, Gamers Mourn', 'Brisbane\'s rare arcade venue closes its doors, leaving gamers to find new quarters for their nostalgia fix. Game over.', 'Its game over in Brisbane as one of the citys last beloved arcade venues shuts down, sending nostalgic gamers into a full-blown existential side quest. The neon lights have flickered out, the joystick legends have retired, and the Mortal Kombat machine will scream Finish Him! no more.\n\nThis wasnt just a place to playit was a sacred temple of pixelated dreams, where you could button-mash away your problems and earn a high score in snack consumption. For many, it was the last bastion of IRL multiplayer before the world became a laggy online battleground.\n\nWhy did it close? Rising rents, dwindling coins, and the fact that Gen Z thinks Pac-Man is just a vibes-only emoji. But for the loyalists, its a crushing loss. One local gamer summed it up perfectly: I met my best mate, my first crush, and my top Donkey Kong rival here. Now where am I supposed to go? Westfield?\n\nWhy it matters? Because arcades were the original social networkand this shutdown feels like deleting a saved game you never wanted to end.\n\nLatest update? Brisbane\'s gamers are now roaming the streets in search of meaning, or at least a decent pinball machine.\n\nSources:\n9News  Gamers mourn closure of Brisbanes iconic arcade venue (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'brisbane-arcade-venue-closes-gamers-mourn', 'published', 'images/news/30208841-c281-4c94-905b-d27f6385fce7.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 13:39:33', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (765, 'Trump Administration Nixes Sewage Settlement, Leaves Alabama Residents in Deep Trouble', 'In a move that stinks, the Trump administration voids a civil rights settlement addressing raw sewage issues in Alabama\'s Lowndes County, labeling it an illegal DEI initiative. Residents are left wading through the consequences.', 'In a move that can only be described as both literal and metaphorical sewage, the Trump administration has flushed away a civil rights settlement meant to clean up chronic raw sewage issues in Alabamas Lowndes County. Why? Because theyve now decided it was part of an illegal DEI initiative. Thats rightfighting disease-spreading human waste is apparently too woke for Washington.\n\nThe settlement, originally designed to address the abysmal sanitation conditions affecting predominantly Black residents, aimed to bring dignity, health, and working plumbing to a community thats been ignored since indoor toilets were invented. But now? Cancelled. Unilaterally voided by Trumps EPA and Department of Justice with the finesse of a toddler overturning a potty.\n\nOfficials argued the deal unfairly prioritized one demographicbecause nothing screams equal treatment like making everyone wade through untreated filth. Meanwhile, locals are still living with raw sewage backing up into their homes, yards, and lives, while the federal government debates whether clean water is an identity issue.\n\nWhy it matters? Because this isnt just policy crueltyits weaponised pettiness. Civil rights lawyers are fuming, public health experts are appalled, and Lowndes County residents are left asking, Can we at least get a bucket?\n\nLatest update? Lawsuits are brewing, septic tanks are overflowing, and somewhere, a MAGA hat is being worn by someone who thinks this is all part of draining the swamp.\n\nSources:\nNBC News  Trump administration voids sewage settlement in Alabama, calls it illegal DEI (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-administration-nixes-sewage-settlement-leaves-alabama-residents-in-deep-trouble', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 04:16:27', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (766, 'Trump Declares War on DEI, Calls It a \'Jungle\'', 'President Trump likens diversity, equity, and inclusion initiatives to a \'jungle,\' signaling a full retreat from DEI policies in education. Tarzan was unavailable for comment.', 'Donald Trump has officially gone full machete on Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion, calling DEI programs a jungle and pledging to cut through them like a guy who once read half of Heart of Darkness. The announcement came as part of a wider plan to ban DEI efforts across public educationbecause apparently, the greatest threat to America is acknowledging other people exist.\n\nIn a speech so allergic to nuance it couldve been written in all caps, Trump painted DEI as a Marxist mind virus and compared inclusion efforts to ideological kudzu choking the life out of good ol American exceptionalism. Somewhere, a Fox News pundit nodded so hard they sprained their neck.\n\nUnder the new directives, schools receiving federal funds must prove they are free of DEI indoctrination, which likely means banning things like acknowledging racism, using the word equity, or holding empathy for anyone who isnt named Chad. Universities are scrambling, civil rights groups are lawyered up, and the ghost of Frederick Douglass is side-eyeing everyone.\n\nWhy it matters? Because dismantling DEI isnt about fairnessits about power. And replacing diversity with conformity dressed up as neutrality is like burning a library and calling it decluttering.\n\nLatest update? Teachers are confused, students are furious, and Trump is already selling jungle-themed merch on Truth Social.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Trump declares DEI a national threat, likens it to a jungle (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-declares-war-on-dei-calls-it-a-jungle', 'published', 'images/news/0967d29a-a492-4162-85cc-3be290f6f470.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:16:29', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (767, 'Two U.S. Marines Investigated for Alleged Rapes in Okinawa', 'Two U.S. Marines face investigations over separate rape allegations in Okinawa, reigniting tensions over the American military presence in Japan. Diplomatic relations are once again on thin ice.', 'Two U.S. Marines stationed in Okinawa are under investigation for separate rape allegations, reigniting fury in a region already fed up with Americas military footprint. The incidents have not only sparked local protests but also dragged U.S.Japan relations back into the diplomatic penalty box.\n\nBoth cases involve local women and reportedly occurred off-base, throwing gasoline on an already smoldering fire of anti-base sentiment. Okinawa has long borne the brunt of Americas post-WWII security obsession, with a disproportionate number of U.S. troops crammed onto the island like its a Call of Duty map nobody asked for.\n\nLocal officials have demanded justice, transparency, anddare we sayaccountability. The U.S. military, meanwhile, has promised full cooperation, which history tells us usually means slow statements and delayed charges.\n\nWhy it matters? Because Okinawa isnt just a military outpostits home to over a million people who are sick of being treated like collateral damage in someone elses foreign policy flex. And when the very people claiming to provide security are accused of violence, the hypocrisy hits like a drone strike.\n\nLatest update? Investigations are underway, protests are building, and the phrase Status of Forces Agreement is back in the headlinesfor all the wrong reasons.\n\nSources:\nReuters  Two U.S. Marines under investigation for rape in Okinawa (25 Apr 2025)\nJapan Times  Rape allegations reignite anti-U.S. military protests in Okinawa (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'two-us-marines-investigated-for-alleged-rapes-in-okinawa', 'published', 'images/news/f95d30fe-4447-44e6-877c-8340fc27df6d.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-03 03:01:46', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (768, 'NFL Draft 2025: Titans Eye Cam Ward as Top Pick', 'The Tennessee Titans are poised to select quarterback Cam Ward as the No. 1 overall pick in the NFL Draft, hoping he can lead them out of their recent slump. No pressure, Cam.', 'The Tennessee Titans are reportedly set to roll the dice on quarterback Cam Ward as their No. 1 pick in the 2025 NFL Draft, pinning their hopesand probably several executive careerson the strong-armed college standout. No pressure, Cam. Just the weight of a billion-dollar franchise, an angry fan base, and Nashvilles beer-soaked dreams resting on your spiral.\n\nWard, who dazzled in college with highlight-reel passes and just enough chaos to keep commentators awake, is being hailed as the Titans messiah in cleats. Hes got the arm, the footwork, and the ability to make defenders look like theyre running Windows 95. Now all he needs is to survive Tennessees offensive line without becoming a cautionary tale.\n\nTitans fans are cautiously optimistic. By which we mean theyre already arguing on Reddit over whether Cam is the second coming of Mahomes or the next Zach Wilson. Meanwhile, rival teams are watching nervouslyor laughing, depending on how your QB situation looks.\n\nWhy it matters? Because drafting a quarterback first overall is like adopting a dragon. If you train it right, it wins you kingdoms. If not, it burns your house down and eats your cap space.\n\nLatest update? Titans GM is smiling, ESPN is speculating, and Cam Wards suit for draft night probably costs more than your car.\n\nSources:\nNFL.com  Titans reportedly targeting Cam Ward as No. 1 overall pick (25 Apr 2025)\nESPN  Cam Ward projected to go first in 2025 NFL Draft (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'nfl-draft-2025-titans-eye-cam-ward-as-top-pick', 'published', 'images/news/15190734-a454-431c-a1b2-3ee85f250ba1.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:16:16', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (769, 'Trump\'s Tariffs Spark Fears of Inflation and Recession', 'Economists warn that President Trump\'s new tariffs could lead to higher inflation and increase the likelihood of a recession. The economic forecast is cloudy with a chance of downturn.', 'Donald Trumps latest economic magic trickslapping tariffs on everything not nailed downhas economists sweating through their spreadsheets. With new import taxes on metals, tech components, and probably hopes and dreams, experts are warning this trade war sequel might end in Recession: The Reckoning.\n\nThe tariffs, which include a 25% hike on key goods from Australia, China, and the EU, are allegedly meant to protect American jobs. But instead, theyre inflating prices faster than Elon Musk tweets nonsense. Consumer goods are already seeing spikes, and industry leaders are whispering the R-word: recession, that isnot restructure, which is just corporate code for panic.\n\nEven conservative economists are raising eyebrows, noting that taxing your way into a strong economy is like eating cake to cure diabetes. Inflation, already limping from pandemic aftershocks, is expected to rise, and supply chains are about to do their best impression of a traffic jam on a wet freeway.\n\nWhy it matters? Because these tariffs arent just affecting imported goodstheyre about to hit wallets, wages, and anyone who enjoys functioning capitalism.\n\nLatest update? Wall Street is wobbling, Trump is tweeting victory, and economists are loading their models with Oh no, not again.\n\nSources:\nBloomberg  Trump tariffs raise fears of inflation and economic slowdown (25 Apr 2025)\nCNN Business  Analysts warn trade war 2.0 could trigger new recession (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'trumps-tariffs-spark-fears-of-inflation-and-recession', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 08:54:21', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (770, 'Measles Cases Climb in the U.S., Health Officials Alarmed', 'Measles cases continue to rise across the United States, prompting health officials to urge vaccinations. It\'s a blast from the past no one wanted.', 'What year is it1912? Measles cases are climbing across the U.S. like it\'s the pre-vaccine era, and health officials are losing their collective minds. A disease we essentially had cornered has made a full comeback tour, thanks to vaccine hesitancy, misinformation, and that one Facebook group your uncle wont shut up about.\n\nSo far, over 1,000 cases have been reported nationwide, with outbreaks hitting schools, airports, and anyone brave enough to sit near a coughing toddler. The CDC is issuing emergency guidance, and doctors are doing their best not to scream, WE HAD A VACCINE FOR THIS SINCE ELVIS WAS ALIVE.\n\nThe irony is brutal. Just as the nation recovers from COVID fatigue, it now has to contend with a virus that shouldve stayed in medical textbooks. Experts blame falling immunisation rates, patchy public health funding, and TikTok wellness influencers who think vitamin C cures literally everything.\n\nWhy it matters? Because measles isnt just a rashits a potentially deadly, hyper-contagious virus that spreads faster than a celebrity divorce. And unlike your anti-vax neighbours blog, it doesnt care about your research.\n\nLatest update? Hospitals are bracing, vaccine clinics are ramping up, and Americas public health system is staring into the abyss wondering why history insists on repeating itself in HD.\n\nSources:\nCDC  Measles cases increase sharply across multiple U.S. states (25 Apr 2025)\nNBC News  Health officials urge vaccinations as measles spreads (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'measles-cases-climb-in-the-us-health-officials-alarmed', 'published', 'images/news/885ac4fb-9989-4b16-9cc8-7fde600f65f9.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:16:31', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (771, 'Tesla Profits Take a Hit, Musk Promises to Refocus', 'Tesla reports a significant drop in profits, leading CEO Elon Musk to pledge reduced involvement in his government role to concentrate on the company. Investors hope it\'s not just another tweet.', 'Tesla just posted a profit drop that made Wall Streets jaw clench harder than a Cybertrucks door handle. The EV juggernaut reported earnings well below expectations, and in response, CEO Elon Musk promised to refocus on the company. Which, to be fair, is probably easier than simultaneously running Tesla, SpaceX, X (formerly Twitter), Neuralink, and whatever side hustle involves digging tunnels to nowhere.\n\nInvestors, naturally, are side-eyeing this pledge harder than a board member at a Dogecoin meeting. Musk swears hell reduce his involvement in government-related activities to get Tesla back on track, but his track record for focus is lets say creative. One week hes livestreaming space memes, the next hes feuding with journalists or plotting a Mars colony with questionable plumbing.\n\nThis time, though, the financials might actually force his hand. Revenue slipped, costs are up, and the once-sparkling Tesla brand is now competing in an EV market that actually has other playerssome of whom dont tweet conspiracy theories during earnings calls.\n\nWhy it matters? Because Tesla is more than a car companyits a Musk mood ring. When hes on, the stock surges. When hes distracted, investors start digging escape tunnels of their own.\n\nLatest update? Musk says hes locked in. Tesla shareholders are crossing fingers, toes, and probably a few legal clauses that he doesnt get bored and buy a zoo next week.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Tesla profits fall, Musk pledges to refocus on company (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'tesla-profits-take-a-hit-musk-promises-to-refocus', 'published', 'images/news/ce5978f9-b1a5-443f-acea-1be76ba1f532.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 00:17:25', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (772, '\'Until Dawn\' Film Adaptation Falls Short on Scares', 'The movie adaptation of the video game \'Until Dawn\' hits theaters but fails to deliver genuine frights, leaving horror fans underwhelmed. It\'s more yawn than dawn.', 'The Until Dawn film adaptation has arrivedand horror fans are wishing theyd just slept through it. What was supposed to be a terrifying descent into madness based on the hit video game has landed in cinemas with all the tension of a limp spaghetti noodle.\n\nLets start with the plot, or rather, the vague memory of one. The original game was a masterclass in jump scares, creepy mountain lodges, and death-by-butterfly-effect drama. The movie, meanwhile, replaces terror with TikTok-level dialogue and acting so wooden it may have come from the actual cabin floorboards.\n\nEven the iconic Wendigosflesh-eating monsters from Indigenous folklorelook like someone ran out of CGI budget and just glued fangs to interns. Instead of atmospheric dread, we get awkward pacing, recycled tropes, and characters so flat they make cardboard cutouts look three-dimensional.\n\nFans of the game are howlingnot with fear, but frustration. The potential was all there: a rich setting, moral choices, characters you can accidentally get killed. Instead, we got a film that treats its source material like a vague rumour and its audience like we havent seen Scream, The Thing, or literally any movie with a flashlight and a bad decision.\n\nWhy it matters? Because gamers are loyal, and horror nerds are vicious. This flop just joined the long line of adaptations no one asked for and everyone regrets.\n\nLatest update? Rotten Tomatoes score: chilling. Viewer reactions: colder than the snowy mountain set.\n\nSources:\nIGN  Until Dawn movie fails to capture games horror magic (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'until-dawn-film-adaptation-falls-short-on-scares', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:16:48', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (773, 'Real Estate Market Cools Amid Economic Uncertainty', 'The U.S. real estate market shows signs of cooling as economic uncertainties and rising interest rates deter potential buyers. The housing bubble might be deflating.', 'The U.S. real estate market has officially taken a deep breathand not the calming kind. With rising interest rates, economic uncertainty, and the general vibe of maybe we wait this one out, buyers are suddenly doing what was once unthinkable: walking away.\n\nAfter years of frenzied bidding wars and open houses that felt like Coachella for realtors, the property bubble is starting to deflate. Homes are lingering on the market longer, price drops are popping up like mushrooms after rain, and agents are relearning how to say Would you consider a lower offer?\n\nWhy? Because interest rates are climbing like a caffeinated squirrel and inflation still hasnt read the room. People who could once afford three bedrooms and a pool are now budgeting for a one-bedroom and a sense of shame. The FOMO is fading, the frenzy is done, and house-hunters are suddenly reading the fine print on mortgage calculators like its ancient prophecy.\n\nSellers, of course, are in denial. Its just a lull, they say, while clutching their Zillow listings and weeping into their subway tile. Meanwhile, buyers are waiting, renters are thriving, and landlords are suddenly texting back with actual punctuation.\n\nWhy it matters? Because real estate isnt just a marketits a national obsession. And when it slows, everything from home renovation stores to election campaigns gets nervous.\n\nLatest update? The boom has officially gone meh.\n\nSources:\nCNBC  U.S. housing market slows as interest rates and economic anxiety rise (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'real-estate-market-cools-amid-economic-uncertainty', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 20:18:33', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (774, 'Americans Embrace Minimalism in Post-Pandemic Era', 'Post-pandemic, more Americans are adopting minimalist lifestyles, decluttering their homes and minds. Less is more, apparently.', 'After stockpiling enough sourdough starters, yoga mats, and emotionally questionable online purchases during the pandemic to rival a small nations GDP, Americans are finally saying: nah, Im good. Minimalism is back, babyand this time its got better lighting and a neutral-toned mood board.\n\nThe post-pandemic vibe shift has officially hit the nations closets, garages, and collective psyche. People are purging junk with the passion of a reality show contestant, trading chaos for calm and chaos-buying for clean countertops. One storage company even reported a rise in cancellation requests that read like breakup letters: Its not you, its my inner peace.\n\nSocial media is flooded with minimalist influencers showing off their beige walls, three forks, and emotional detachment. Gone are the maximalist, dopamine-drenched TikToks of 2020now its all about linen robes, houseplants with names, and smug captions like I only own five shirts, and Ive never felt richer.\n\nThe movements deeper than just ditching clutter. Its a rebellion against burnout culture, endless consumption, and the mental clutter of a society that cant stop checking email on the toilet. Minimalism is now less I read The Life-Changing Magic of Tidying Up once and more I no longer fear silence or my own thoughts.\n\nWhy it matters? Because in a world thats given us too much of everythingnews, noise, noveltypeople are finally choosing less. Less stuff, less stress, fewer regrets. And maybe one day, fewer browser tabs.\n\nLatest update? Retail therapy is out. Mindful curating is in. And somewhere, Marie Kondo just felt a spiritual shiver and smiled.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Americans turn to minimalism for post-pandemic clarity and calm (25 Apr 2025)\nNPR  The rise of less: Minimalist lifestyles gain traction after COVID clutter (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'americans-embrace-minimalism-in-post-pandemic-era', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-03 08:51:24', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (775, 'China\'s Trade with Kenya Surges 11.9% in Q1 2025', 'China and Kenya\'s economic bromance blossoms with a 11.9% trade increase. Who needs roses when you have yuan?', 'China and Kenya just took their economic situationship to the next level, with bilateral trade jumping 11.9% in the first quarter of 2025. Call it a bromance, call it strategic alignmentjust dont call it casual. These two are moving containers, not feelings.\n\nThe trade spike is mostly thanks to Kenyas appetite for Chinese tech, machinery, and infrastructure magic, while China continues importing Kenyan tea, coffee, and diplomatic goodwill by the tonne. Its like a long-distance relationship that actually worksmutual gifts, consistent communication, and not one awkward breakup text in sight.\n\nChinas Belt and Road strategy continues to thread its way through Africa, and Kenya is clearly all-in. Roads, railways, portsyou name it, Chinas building it, and Kenyas signing on like its the Terms and Conditions of prosperity. Western powers? Still ghosting or showing up late with 300-page loan applications.\n\nWhy it matters? Because while the West holds climate conferences, China is busy shipping freight and making deals. Kenyas getting infrastructure, Chinas getting influenceand the yuans getting a warm welcome in Nairobi.\n\nLatest update? Trade reps are high-fiving, export stats are glowing, and the U.S. is somewhere Googling how to win back Africa.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  China-Kenya trade jumps 11.9% in Q1 2025 (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-trade-with-kenya-surges-119-in-q1-2025', 'published', 'images/news/dd4a26ec-545a-4ed5-bfe1-1725932e2611.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:16:59', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (776, 'Chinese Ambassador Urges Canada to Scrap \'Discriminatory\' Tariffs', 'In a diplomatic nudge, China\'s envoy tells Canada to ditch the tariffs. Maple syrup diplomacy at its finest.', 'China has politely told Canada to take its tariffs and kindly shove them into a snowbank. In a diplomatic statement that definitely had a polite Canadian smile masking deep fury, Chinas ambassador urged Ottawa to roll back what it calls discriminatory trade restrictions.\n\nThe tariffs in question target Chinese tech and manufacturing goods, which Canada claims are tied to unfair trade practices. China, meanwhile, is accusing the maple-loving nation of playing favouritesand not the sweet kind.\n\nIn classic diplomatic fashion, the ambassador said the measures seriously damage mutual trust, which is international code for fix this or your exports might get mysteriously delayed. Tensions have been frosty since the Huawei saga, but now theyre straight-up iceberg-level, with neither side offering warm syrupy apologies.\n\nWhy it matters? Because trade tantrums are the new normal, and if Canada blinks first, it could set a precedent. If it doesnt? Well, hope those lobster exports find another home.\n\nLatest update? Canadas reviewing the tariffs. Chinas watching. And somewhere, a Canadian diplomat is rage-sipping double-double coffee.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  Chinese envoy urges Canada to end tariffs, restore trust (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'chinese-ambassador-urges-canada-to-scrap-discriminatory-tariffs', 'published', 'images/news/c8d8de80-1d7a-4a9f-9167-2caa930ea49b.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:15:09', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (777, 'China-France Joint Satellite SVOM Releases First Findings', 'Space buddies China and France unveil cosmic secrets. It\'s written in the starsand now in scientific journals.', 'Forget baguettes and baoziChina and France have teamed up to serve gamma-ray bursts. The SVOM satellite, their shiny new cosmic collaboration, just released its first batch of data, and its full of black hole mysteries, neutron star gossip, and science too advanced to explain without sounding like a Marvel plot.\n\nSVOM, which stands for Space-based multi-band astronomical Variable Objects Monitor (yes, really), is floating 600 kilometres above Earth, watching the universe do its weirdest. Its mission? Spot gamma-ray burststhe universes version of freak-outsand beam back data for astrophysicists to decode with far too much coffee.\n\nThis partnership shows that even when geopolitics get testy, science still swipes right. China brought the launch muscle, France brought the optics and European flair, and now theyre co-parenting a space baby thats already making cosmic headlines.\n\nWhy it matters? Because international space collabs arent just good PRtheyre also essential when studying a universe that doesnt care about your borders, only your bandwidth.\n\nLatest update? SVOMs results are in journals, astronomers are giddy, and Elon Musk is probably jealous.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  China-France satellite SVOM releases gamma-ray burst findings (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'china-france-joint-satellite-svom-releases-first-findings', 'published', 'images/news/61090679-6df1-4ad4-a482-92c82802cc6d.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:16:09', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (778, 'Robot Contest in Wuxi Pushes Competition from Lab to Arena', 'Robots in Wuxi trade lab coats for battle gear. It\'s like \'Robot Wars\' but with more precision and less drama.', 'Wuxi just went full Transformers meets STEM fair as dozens of robots left their cushy lab benches and hit the arena floor in Chinas most high-tech brawl to date. Forget chess-playing androids and polite tea-serving botsthis was metal-on-metal mayhem, with AI-fueled warriors battling it out for mechanical glory.\n\nHeld as part of Chinas growing push for robotic innovation, the competition featured everything from humanoid sprinters to spider-legged crab walkers that looked like theyd escaped a Marvel villains basement. Teams of students, engineers, and probably a few sci-fi fanatics faced off in tests of speed, precision, agility, and general dont explode mid-round excellence.\n\nThe crowd? Rapt. The commentary? Glorious. The robots? Shockingly well-behavedapart from that one wheeled unit that tried to take out a judge (unconfirmed glitch or uprising, unclear). And unlike your average esports match, these bots can actually throw a punchif you program them passive-aggressively enough.\n\nWhy it matters? Because Chinas not just building the futuretheyre teaching it to throw down. Its about talent pipelines, innovation, and, lets be honest, a little national flexing with servo motors.\n\nLatest update? Wuxis next-gen gladiators are charging their batteries and sharpening their sensors for next year. And yes, the sequel will have lasers.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  Robot competition in Wuxi brings high-tech battle to life (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'robot-contest-in-wuxi-pushes-competition-from-lab-to-arena', 'published', 'images/news/45d9fdcf-45b0-4f24-a413-10f182f013c0.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:15:59', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (779, 'China\'s Digital Reading Users Reach 670 Million in 2024', 'E-books are the new black in China, with 670 million users. Trees everywhere breathe a collective sigh of relief.', 'Chinas gone fully digital in its reading habits, racking up 670 million e-book users in 2024proof that Kindles have officially beat kindling. Libraries? Lovely. But in the age of LED-lit pages and backlit plot twists, its e-ink or bust.\n\nThe surge comes as apps like WeRead and iReader dominate the national commute, offering everything from ancient poetry to the latest CEO-meets-vampire romance saga. (Dont ask.) Paperbacks have been replaced by pocket-sized literature portals, and bookstores are now mostly used for photo ops and artisanal coffee.\n\nEnvironmentalists are thrilledmillions of trees spared. Publishers? Slightly less thrilled. And readers? Glued to their phones, discovering that yes, 47-part fantasy novels read easier when you can scroll with one thumb and sip boba with the other.\n\nWhy it matters? Because literacy is booming, the publishing game is shifting, and Chinas proving that the digital revolution isnt just for online shoppingits got prose, too.\n\nLatest update? Print is not deadbut its definitely being ghosted.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  Digital reading users hit 670 million in China in 2024 (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-digital-reading-users-reach-670-million-in-2024', 'published', 'images/news/ef10fd37-f957-452e-b73f-133ca9da9705.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 04:04:12', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (780, 'Ministry Warns of Smart Devices\' Hidden Risks to National Security', 'Your smart fridge might be too smart. China\'s Ministry sounds the alarm on gadget espionage.', 'Chinas Ministry of Industry and Information Technology has issued a warning thats one part tech advisory, one part Orwellian thriller: your smart fridge might be spying on you. Yes, that innocent appliance keeping your leftovers chilled could also be keeping tabs on your snack schedule for reasons.\n\nThe alert highlights how smart devicesfrom watches and TVs to rice cookers with suspiciously good Wi-Ficould be vulnerable to hacking, data leaks, or straight-up espionage. In other words, dont be surprised if your smart vacuum starts asking about your military affiliations.\n\nWhile most users are just asking their devices to play pop songs and dim the lights, the Ministry is urging tighter security standards, stricter oversight, and, presumably, fewer AI-enabled teddy bears.\n\nWhy it matters? Because in a world where your blender could double as a surveillance tool, national security is now a domestic appliance issue. We\'re one firmware update away from a toaster that knows state secrets.\n\nLatest update? Consumers are panicking, developers are patching, and somewhere, an air fryer is sweating bullets.\n\nSources:\nXinhua  Smart home devices pose national security risks, warns Ministry (25 Apr 2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'ministry-warns-of-smart-devices-hidden-risks-to-national-security', 'published', 'images/news/8a5294d5-1806-4ef5-a85c-ca919393b29e.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-28 06:17:22', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (781, 'China Shortens Market Access Negative List', 'China trims the red tape, making it easier for businesses to play in its sandbox. Investors, start your engines.', 'In a rare plot twist that doesnt involve adding more bureaucracy, China has actually shortened its market access negative list. Thats rightBeijing has removed even more industries from the no foreign investors allowed club, effectively telling the global business community, Come in, the red tapes fine.\n\nThe list, which sounds like a Bond villain\'s LinkedIn page, used to restrict access to sectors like finance, manufacturing, and anything remotely fun. But now, more doors are open for international firms to frolic in Chinas economic sandboxjust dont forget your compliance forms.\n\nOfficials say the change is part of a high-level opening up, which is code for we need fresh cash and good PR. Investors are cautiously optimistic, scanning the new list like its a Black Friday deal sheet. Multinationals are already eyeing untapped markets with all the excitement of a golden retriever near a tennis ball.\n\nWhy it matters? Because despite geopolitical drama, China is still a colossal economic playground. And when it says less restrictions, CEOs start doing cartwheels in custom suits.\n\nLatest update? Lawyers are combing the fine print, corporations are revving their engines, and Beijing is flashing its best were business-friendly smile.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times  China shortens negative list to expand market access for foreign investors (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'china-shortens-market-access-negative-list', 'published', 'images/news/b36af3a1-558f-4a8c-96e8-9ed007d9592e.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 06:39:36', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (782, 'My Journey with Spanish-Latin American Poetry: A Tie Forged by Serendipity', 'A literary love affair blooms between China and Latin America. Poetry: the universal language of feelings and flair.', 'Grab a wine glass and your softest scarfbecause were diving into the poetic fever dream that is Chinas newfound love affair with Spanish-Latin American verse. In an essay that reads like Pablo Neruda and Confucius swapped mixtapes, a Chinese literary scholar recounts how a chance encounter with Latin poetry sparked a full-blown cultural romance.\n\nWhat began as curiosity evolved into academic obsession, translation projects, and even open mic nights where Mandarin met metaphor in candlelit cafs. It\'s the kind of story that makes you feel underachieving for only speaking one language and not crying over stanzas on a weeknight.\n\nThis isnt just niche academiaits part of a broader trend where China is embracing cultural exchange with Latin America through literature. Think soft power with soul, sonnets instead of sanctions. Trade deals are great, but theres something magical about bonding over heartbreak haikus and love-drenched elegies.\n\nWhy it matters? Because in a world full of shouting matches, poetry is one of the few ways two countries can whisper to each other across oceans.\n\nLatest update? Expect more cross-cultural anthologies, confused book fair attendees, and poets dramatically gazing out train windows.\n\nSources:\nXinhua  Literary ties between China and Latin America deepen through poetry (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'my-journey-with-spanish-latin-american-poetry-a-tie-forged-by-serendipity', 'published', 'images/news/37d73024-5eb8-4c54-bad4-fc622517b09b.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:14:51', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (783, 'China\'s Real Estate Market Shows Signs of Stabilization', 'After a rollercoaster ride, China\'s property market finds its footing. Homebuyers can finally exhale.', 'After years of please dont look at the balance sheets too closely chaos, Chinas real estate market is finally exhalingand not just from the dust of half-built megaprojects. Officials and analysts alike are cautiously declaring the market is stabilizing, which is property-speak for the patient is no longer flatlining, but maybe dont throw a parade just yet.\n\nPrices are no longer freefalling, developers are breathing easier, and buyers are poking their heads out of the financial trenches like, Is it safe? The governments been injecting confidence like its Botox for the economycutting rates, easing restrictions, and whispering soothing things to spooked investors.\n\nOf course, stabilization doesnt mean its all fixed. Ghost cities still exist, and developer debt hasnt magically evaporated. But the rollercoaster ride of defaults and drama seems to be slowing into something resembling a gentle carousel.\n\nWhy it matters? Because real estate is to China what avocado toast is to millennialsfoundational, controversial, and somehow always in crisis. If this sector finds its balance, the broader economy gets its groove back.\n\nLatest update? Homebuyers are cautiously browsing, developers are cautiously drinking again, and economists are cautiously optimisticwith emphasis on cautiously.\n\nSources:\nXinhua  Chinas property market shows signs of stabilization in early 2025 (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-real-estate-market-shows-signs-of-stabilization', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:16:13', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (784, 'Nation Holds Conference on Reading, Celebrates World Book Day', 'China throws a party for books, proving that in the digital age, reading still rocks.', 'China has officially thrown the nerdiest bash of the yearand we mean that as a complimentwith a national conference marking World Book Day. Forget fireworks and TikTok filtersthis was a full-throttle literary lovefest, complete with panels, poetry readings, author fangirling, and more reading recommendations than your group chat during exam season.\n\nHosted by the Ministry of Culture and Tourism, the conference rallied publishers, educators, writers, and government officials to wave the flag for reading in a world currently addicted to swipeable content and 10-second attention spans. The message? Books are still hot, libraries still matter, and literacy is still sexier than pretending to read on the subway while actually playing Candy Crush.\n\nThis wasnt just about dusty classics and solemn speeches eitheryoung adult fiction, e-books, childrens literacy, and sci-fi all got their moment in the spotlight. The event spotlighted programs that bring books to rural schools, digital reading initiatives, and campaigns to get parents reading with their kids instead of just to their phones.\n\nThe government is pushing reading not just as a pastime, but as a pillar of soft power and national development. Because in the age of AI, whoever reads better, thinks betterand in Chinas case, publishes faster.\n\nWhy it matters? Because while the internet is drowning in nonsense, books are still the deep end where critical thinking learns to swim.\n\nLatest update? Bookstores are buzzing, libraries are back in fashion, and somewhere in Beijing, a poet just dropped the hottest haiku of 2025.\n\nSources:\nXinhua  China celebrates World Book Day with national reading conference (25 Apr 2025)\nGlobal Times  Reading promotion takes centre stage on World Book Day (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'nation-holds-conference-on-reading-celebrates-world-book-day', 'published', 'images/news/7137cb13-b8c8-43b1-8eaa-6920fc386fd1.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 20:15:25', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (793, 'Australia\'s Defense Readiness Questioned Amid Rising Tensions', 'Historian warns we\'re repeating 1941\'s mistakes. Dj vu, but with better Wi-Fi.', 'Australias Defence Readiness Questioned Amid Rising Tensions\nIts 2025, but according to one military historian, Australia might be living its own cursed remake of 1941minus the trench coats, plus 5G. As regional tensions heat up and defence strategy becomes the dinner table debate of choice (finally knocking off interest rates), experts are asking: are we sleepwalking into another security disaster, armed with good vibes and budget cuts?\n\nThe warning comes from renowned historian Dr. Peter Dean, who basically just stood up in front of Parliament, waved a giant red flag, and said, Mate, weve seen this film beforeand it doesnt end well. His critique? That Australias current state of defence readiness is dangerously close to the pre-WWII mindset: slow to respond, under-equipped, and too busy trusting far-off allies to save the day. Sound familiar?\n\nAt the heart of the anxiety is a military stretched thinner than Peter Duttons empathy. Troop numbers are down, key projects are delayed, and defence procurement is still being managed like its an office stationery order. Meanwhile, the Indo-Pacific is bristling with naval build-ups, strategic partnerships, and enough freedom of navigation patrols to turn the ocean into a military parking lot.\n\nPoliticians, of course, are quick to reassure us that everything is under controla phrase that historically precedes things going spectacularly not under control. The vibe? Australias relying heavily on the U.S. and AUKUS to provide the muscle, while hoping no one notices we forgot to bring snacks to the geopolitical barbecue.\n\nLatest update? Historians are ringing alarm bells, Canberras fine-tuning its PowerPoint briefings, and the Defence Force is praying the next threat waits until at least the next funding cycle.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Australias defence unprepared for future conflict, historian warns (25 Apr 2025)\nThe Australian  Historian draws parallels with 1941 defence failures (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'australias-defense-readiness-questioned-amid-rising-tensions', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 08:39:11', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (794, 'Djokovic\'s Tennis Tantrum: \'F*** Sports\'', 'Novak Djokovic channels his inner toddler during practice. Someone needs a juice box and a nap.', 'Novak Djokovic served up a racket-smashing, expletive-laced meltdown during a recent training session, reminding everyone that while he may be a tennis god, hes also a mere mortal when his backhand isnt behaving. Caught on video hurling a verbal aceF*** sports!the Serbian star appeared to enter his villain era mid-practice, right before what one can only assume was a very awkward cooldown stretch.\n\nThe outburst came during what was supposed to be a calm pre-Olympics tune-up, but clearly Novak was feeling more angsty poet than Zen master. One moment he was rallying like usual, the next he was channeling his inner toddler denied screen time. Was it the weather? The pressure? A rogue tennis ball with bad vibes? Unclear.\n\nFans online had a field day. Some defended himHes passionate! Others offered solutions: juice box, timeout, maybe an emotional support racquet. The phrase F*** sports is now trending and will likely be printed on ironic gym tees by next Tuesday.\n\nWhy it matters? Because when the worlds top player has a public detonation, it doesnt just raise eyebrowsit sets the tone for the entire tournament. And if Novaks planning to win gold, he might want to fist-bump fewer water bottles on the way.\n\nLatest update? Djokovic walked off, probably muttered to himself in three languages, and will be back tomorrow like nothing happenedbecause greatness has mood swings too.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Novak Djokovic flips out at training session: F*** tennis (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'djokovics-tennis-tantrum-f-sports', 'published', 'images/news/a1993f71-f745-4b23-830c-e20dcffc1b0c.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 12:07:02', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (795, 'Cyclone Watch Issued for Cocos Islands', 'Mother Nature plans a windy visit to the Cocos Islands. Residents advised to hold onto their hatsand houses.', 'The Bureau of Meteorology has issued a cyclone watch for the Cocos Islands, because apparently Mother Nature doesnt take public holidays. A tropical low is looming offshore and could whip itself into full cyclone mode by the weekend, meaning its time for residents to batten down the hatches and reinforce everything that isnt nailed to a palm tree.\n\nThe usual drill is underway: emergency kits being dusted off, boats being tied down, and that one guy still insisting itll blow over despite last years trampoline incident. Forecasts suggest the system could intensify quickly, because of course it couldits 2025 and the weather is now fully dramatic.\n\nOfficials are urging calm but cautious prep, with reminders not to underestimate cyclonic tantrums, even in paradise. Meanwhile, tourists are googling how to cancel island holidays without crying and locals are rolling their eyes in fluent weather fatigue.\n\nWhy it matters? Because while the mainland chills under mild Anzac Day skies, the Cocos crew might be strapping in for a weekend of high winds, high tides, and a lot of high-stakes weather chat.\n\nLatest update? The systems strengthening, alerts are out, and the BOM is back to speaking fluent probability cone.\n\nSources:\nYolanda Gagnon Reports  Cyclone watch issued for Cocos Islands (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'cyclone-watch-issued-for-cocos-islands', 'published', 'images/news/951f17aa-6fe4-4825-a984-81af265eb48b.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 02:19:44', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (796, 'Nurses Suspended Over Antisemitic Video', 'Two Sydney nurses\' vile online rant leads to national outrage and job loss. Bedside manner? More like backside behavior.', 'Two Sydney nurses have been suspended after filming and sharing a vile antisemitic video that had the entire country collectively asking: What in the actual hell? The clip, uploaded to social media in what can only be described as a career-suicidal moment of bigotry, sparked immediate backlashand rightfully so.\n\nThe nurses, who clearly skipped the ethics lecture during their training, were filmed spewing hateful rhetoric that had no place in any setting, let alone from people sworn to care for others. Their employer acted fast, suspending them and launching an investigation while issuing a very pointed we dont tolerate hate speech, thanks statement.\n\nCommunity leaders slammed the video, calling it disgusting, dangerous, and completely at odds with everything healthcare is supposed to stand for. The broader Jewish community responded with grace and fury, demanding accountabilityand rightly pointing out that antisemitism doesnt magically disappear just because its 2025.\n\nWhy it matters? Because hate has consequences. Especially when its broadcast from a profession that holds lives in its hands. Bedside manner isnt just about handing tissuesits about basic humanity.\n\nLatest update? The nurses are under review, the internet is still fuming, and HR departments across the country are updating their dont be a bigot training slides.\n\nSources:\nSBS News  Nurses suspended over antisemitic video (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'nurses-suspended-over-antisemitic-video', 'published', 'images/news/061c33a8-9fbe-423b-ba85-5927f7eeae47.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 07:36:53', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (797, 'Public Child Sex Offender Register Gains Support', 'Bruce Morcombe backs a national registry to protect kids. Because knowing your neighbor\'s past shouldn\'t require detective work.', 'ruce Morcombethe tireless child safety advocate whose grief became a nationwide missionis throwing his full weight behind Peter Duttons push for a national public child sex offender registry. And for once, the country seems to agree: maybe knowing if your neighbour has a past darker than your Wi-Fi signal shouldn\'t require deep-diving into court archives.\n\nThe proposal, floated by the Coalition ahead of the federal election, would allow public access to names, faces, and convictions of repeat or high-risk child sex offenders. Naturally, civil liberties groups are already having a constitutional aneurysm, warning of vigilantism, errors, and privacy breaches. But Morcombes stance is clear: Parents have the right to know who\'s living next door. Try arguing with that without sounding like a bureaucratic fridge magnet.\n\nSupporters say this is about protecting kids, not handing out torches and pitchforks. Critics argue its a blunt instrument that could backfire, pushing offenders underground and stoking fear. But for many, especially those touched by tragedy, the moral scales are already tipped.\n\nWhy it matters? Because when public safety, privacy, and punishment collide, were forced to confront uncomfortable questions. And no one wants a reminder of these failures to come in the form of another front-page headline.\n\nLatest update? Duttons campaign just found its emotional centrepiece. Labors still reviewing the details. Parents? Already Googling their postcode.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Bruce Morcombe backs national public child sex offender register (25 Apr 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'public-child-sex-offender-register-gains-support', 'published', 'images/news/edfba9b0-0bdd-499e-8e6a-90de6978c6eb.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 09:22:57', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (798, '\'Gender Queer\' Graphic Novel Reapproved for Sale', 'After a legal tug-of-war, the controversial memoir is back on shelves. Censorship loses this round.', 'After being yanked off shelves faster than a bottle of banned cough syrup, the memoir Gender Queer is backand censorship just took an L. Following months of legal jousting that saw conservatives clutching pearls and free speech advocates sharpening their pens, the controversial graphic novel has been reapproved for sale in Australia.\n\nThe book, a raw and reflective coming-of-age tale about gender identity, had become the literary lightning rod for a culture war nobody asked for but everyone insisted on joining. Critics said it was inappropriate for youth. Supporters said read the damn thing first. And somewhere in between, authors, librarians, and teens just wanted to turn a page in peace.\n\nThe reversal means the book can legally be sold again, presumably with an extra layer of shrink wrap and a flashing neon sign that says Warning: Feelings and Honesty Ahead. The Boards ruling found that while the book addresses complex issues, it doesnt meet the threshold for being banned. Translation: being honest about your identity isnt a crimeyet.\n\nWhy it matters? Because book bans never age well. And in a world where misinformation is one click away, silencing authentic voices seems like the worst possible choice.\n\nLatest update? Bookstores are restocking. Activists are celebrating. And every school board in the country just got a passive-aggressive email from someones very woke aunt.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Gender Queer reapproved for sale in Australia after review (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'gender-queer-graphic-novel-reapproved-for-sale', 'published', 'images/news/ac6abb52-2038-40b0-8a77-c23ec0350762.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 02:47:46', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (799, 'Real Estate Market Shows Signs of Stabilization', 'After a rollercoaster ride, Australia\'s property market finds its footing. Homebuyers can finally exhale.', 'After two years of behaving like an unsupervised toddler with a credit card, Australias real estate market is finally calming the hell down. Prices are plateauing, listings are lingering, and auctioneers have stopped speaking in tongues. Its not a crash, but its not a frenzy eitherits real estates version of lets just see other people.\n\nRising interest rates have done what common sense couldnt: cooled the market without flattening it. Buyers are taking their sweet time. Sellers are shaving off their dream price expectations like its dry shampoo. And first-home buyers are poking their heads out from under blankets, whispering ...now?\n\nExperts say the market is stabilising, which is economist-speak for nobodys crying, but nobodys popping champagne either. Supply is ticking up, investor demand has mellowed, and those insane $300k markups for being near a decent caf are finally fading into legend.\n\nWhy it matters? Because housing affordability is one of those rare issues that unites renters, owners, and mortgage-burdened millennials in collective trauma. A stabilised market wont fix everythingbut it sure beats another season of Million Dollar Shacks: Suburb Edition.\n\nLatest update? Bidding wars are dying down, property FOMO is retreating, and for once, market correction doesnt sound like the beginning of a horror film.\n\nSources:\nThe Australian  Signs of stabilisation in Australias real estate market (25 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'real-estate-market-shows-signs-of-stabilization', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-04-27 20:19:11', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (800, 'Anzac Day Commemorations Held Nationwide', 'Australia pauses to honor its heroes. Lest we forgetand we don\'t.', 'Across Australia, the rising sun met a sea of silence and solemnity as thousands gathered to honour the nations service members, past and present, in Anzac Day commemorations from the Outback to the Opera House. From dawn services to marches with more medals than a war chest, the country pressed pause to remember that freedom often arrives wearing boots and bearing scars.\n\nIn capital cities and country towns alike, young and old stood shoulder-to-shoulder, heads bowed, as the Last Post echoed through chilly air and early morning fog. Wreaths were laid. Stories were shared. Tears were shed. And someones teenage cousin played the bugle like their life depended on it. (They nailed it, by the way.)\n\nThis years tributes carried a sharper edge than usual, with current global tensions adding a modern echo to historys warnings. Defence leaders reminded Australians that remembrance isnt just about reflectionits about readiness. Meanwhile, veterans called for better support, and a new generation of service personnel stood tall, not just in uniform, but in spirit.\n\nIt wasnt all military pomp. Citizens, school kids, and scouts all joined in, showing that the Anzac legacysacrifice, mateship, and unshakable courageisnt just history. Its cultural DNA. And it still punches you in the heart every time someone says, Lest we forget.\n\nWhy it matters? Because amid political chaos, economic uncertainty, and social noise, Anzac Day is the one time the entire country looks up, stands still, and remembers what unity actually looks like.\n\nLatest update? The ceremonies have wrapped, the sausages have been sizzled, and the nation is back to bickeringgrateful for the silence that came before.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Anzac Day commemorations held across Australia (25 Apr 2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nSearch\nAcross Australia, the rising sun 