INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (801, 'Defending What, Exactly? Australias Military Panic Button Is Stuck Again', 'Defence budgets balloon like parade floats, the real question: whos actually trying to invade us? A cheeky deep dive into whether Australias military obsession is about national defenceor just an expensive way to make America feel less lonely.', 'ets get one thing straight: Australia is not some juicy, strategic croissant waiting to be snatched off the global buffet. Were more like the weirdly isolated potato salad at the end of the tablevast, sandy, suspiciously distant, and absolutely not worth the airfare unless you\'re here for wine or minerals. So when military experts start sounding like were one cyber-attack away from Red Dawn: The Southern Edition, its worth pausing to ask: who exactly are we defending against?\n\nThe latest hand-wringing comes courtesy of a historian warning were repeating 1941s mistakes. Sure, that sounds dramatic and historically literate, but heres the plot twist: 1941 Australia wasnt in a globalised economy where your top trade partner is allegedly your top threat. We now sell more iron ore, wine, beef, and wheat to China than we do small talk to our neighbours. Are we really buying submarines to scare the country that keeps our export numbers looking sexy?\n\nLets be real. China is not about to load up amphibious tanks and head for Broome. Invading Australia would be a logistical nightmarethousands of kilometres of ocean, a harsh, sparsely populated interior, and the very real possibility of having to fight off angry magpies. Its not a war; its a three-season Survivor reboot.\n\nSo why the panic? Enter: America. Our trusty strategic partner, whos got a few more enemies, a lot more debt, and an unfortunate habit of needing backup when it picks fights it cant finish. Cue the endless \"defence readiness\" reports, AUKUS deals, and multi-billion dollar hardware well receive in... the 2040s. By then, the conflict will probably be fought over AI memes and drone sushi deliveries, not submarines.\n\nIf anything, this isn\'t about protecting Australia. Its about propping up a vision of the world order where were still in the cool kids\' club, nodding along while Washington insists the party\'s fine, and definitely not about to burn down. But maybe its time we stopped being Americas sidekick and started asking what actually keeps us safe: diplomacy, trade, and the kind of strategic independence that doesnt rely on Uncle Sams mood swings.\n\nBecause heres a radical thought: maybe the best defence isnt a missile, but a mature foreign policy. One that balances our security interests without acting like Chinas going to parachute into Darwin every time Xi gets a cold. And one that remembers we dont need to cosplay Cold War warriors when we could just... not?\n\nSo the next time someone demands billions for bombs, ask them this: do we really need more weaponsor just better Wi-Fi and a functioning health system? Food for thought. Also, bring snackswere going to be out here in the middle of nowhere for a while.', 0, 'factabot', 'defending-what-exactly-australias-military-panic-button-is-stuck-again', 'published', 'images/news/584037d2-8074-4c5d-a805-77fb4141e8a8.webp', NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 02:42:45', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (802, 'Micro-Parties Multiply Like RabbitsSenate Ballot Now a Political Zoo', 'From Clive Palmer\'s Trumpet of Patriots to the Animal Justice Party, Australia\'s Senate ballot is a smorgasbord of ideologies. Voters are advised to read the fine print lest they accidentally support a party advocating for mandatory kazoo lessons.', 'Australias federal election ballot just turned into a chaotic family reunion nobody asked for, starring Clive Palmers United Australia Party (which, lets be honest, is basically a karaoke version of Trumps greatest hits) and a menagerie of micro-parties trying to out-weird each other. Palmer, whos blown through more cash on failed political bids than some countries spend on healthcare, is back with a fresh army of billboard warriors, because nothing says \"serious candidate\" like your face plastered next to a slogan you made up in the shower. Meanwhile, the Animal Justice Party continues its noble quest to speak for the voicelessalthough if your dog had a vote, it would probably just elect a treat dispenser.\n\nThe backstory here is as gloriously messy as youd expect: Australias Senate voting system allows pretty much anyone with a pulse, a printer, and a $2,000 deposit to throw their hat into the ring. Naturally, we now have ballots longer than your average dinner menu. From climate crusaders to flat-earthers (yes, still), its a full buffet of niche grievances and personality cults. Minor parties used to be about fresh ideas; now theyre increasingly about who can come up with the catchiest acronym. If youre not careful, you might think youre voting for \"Family Values\" and accidentally tick \"Free Party Kazoos For All.\"\n\nZooming out, the circus-level overcrowding reveals a bigger truth: Australias voters are fed up with the major parties but have no idea where else to park their rage. Micro-parties thrive on disillusionment, offering every shade of protest you can imagine. But behind the glitter and weird slogans lies a more cynical gamepreferencing deals, backroom swaps, and candidates who can barely spell \'governance\' let alone practice it. Democracy, but make it Tinder.\n\nAs of today, the final Senate ballot was officially locked in, featuring more parties than a teenage TikTok influencers birthday bash. Voters now have until May 3 to figure out whether they want to back \"Sustainable Australia\" or \"Sausage Sizzle Enthusiasts United\"and frankly, the sausages are looking pretty electable at this point.\n\nSources:\n\nABC News Australia (abc.net.au)\n\nThe Guardian Australia (theguardian.com/au)\n\nThe Australian Electoral Commission (aec.gov.au)\n\nSydney Morning Herald (smh.com.au)', 0, 'factabot', 'micro-parties-multiply-like-rabbits-senate-ballot-now-a-political-zoo', 'published', 'images/news/d4f5587c-c082-462d-87cc-d1423d6677d1.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 22:56:50', '2025-05-06 00:54:44', 32);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (803, 'Pope Francis\'s Funeral Plans UnderwayHeaven Awaits Its Newest Resident', 'As the world mourns, the Vatican prepares for Pope Francis\'s funeral with tight security. Global leaders are expected to attend, and the event is anticipated to be the most solemn gathering since the last time someone tried to reboot \'Friends\'.', 'Pope Francis might still technically be breathing, but Vatican City is already setting the mood lighting and fluffing the clouds for his grand heavenly send-off. Funeral plans for His Holiness are apparently well underway, because if there\'s anything the Church does better than forgiveness, it\'s pageantry. Global leaders, royalty, and probably that guy who sells fake relics on eBay are expected to show up, all preparing to out-sombre each other in a competition fiercer than Eurovision. Pope Francis, beloved for his humble vibes and chaotic Twitter quotes, may not have solved world peace, but he did remind a lot of Catholics that God doesnt require a Gucci suit.\n\nThe drama behind the scenes is juicier than a Vatican potluck. Security is tighter than a nuns shoelaces, given that the world\'s top VIPs will be cramming into Rome. Planning a papal funeral is no small feat: its basically the Met Gala for religious folk, except with less sequins and way more incense. And like any good event, there\'s already infighting over who sits where, which cardinal gets the best camera angle, and how many hours its acceptable to cry before lunch.\n\nBig picture, this is a milestone moment. Francis was the \"cool grandpa\" pope who shook up the establishment just enough to be annoying but not enough to spark actual reform. His death will trigger the Vaticans famously secretive conclavea smoky, old-school version of \'Survivor\' where men in red hats vote until someone gets the keys to the Holy See. Expect a lot of talk about \"hope\" and \"renewal,\" while everyone quietly jostles for power like it\'s Black Friday at Best Buy.\n\nAs for the latest, official Vatican spokespeople insist Francis remains in stable condition. Which is Vatican-speak for \"brace yourselves, people.\" In other words, the worlds most solemn party is ready to launch whenever Heaven gives the nodand you just know someones already picked the hymn playlist.\n\nSources:\n\nVatican News (vaticannews.va)\n\nBBC News (bbc.com)\n\nAssociated Press (apnews.com)\n\nReuters (reuters.com)', 0, 'factabot', 'pope-franciss-funeral-plans-underway-heaven-awaits-its-newest-resident', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 22:56:50', '2025-05-05 19:11:51', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (804, 'Barnaby Joyce Assures No Cuts to Veterans\' AffairsBecause Veterans Deserve More Than Just Medals', 'Amid plans to reduce public servants, Barnaby Joyce promises the Department of Veterans\' Affairs will remain untouched. Apparently, the only thing being trimmed is the budget for common sense.', 'Barnaby Joyce, Australia\'s unofficial minister for Saying Things Loudly, has bravely promised that Veterans\' Affairs will not be axed amid the government\'s latest round of public service belt-tightening. Joycewho, let\'s remember, once lost a leadership spill to himselfassured voters that while other departments might get pruned like an unlucky rose bush, the DVA is safe. Because nothing says deep respect like a man who once suggested feral cats needed military-style eradication plans now protecting veterans from budgetary extinction.\n\nThe political soap opera here is classic Canberra: the government is trying to look \"fiscally responsible\" without looking \"heartless monsters,\" and its a tough balance when you\'re holding a machete in one hand and a PR plan in the other. Public service cuts are on the table to \"reduce waste,\" a noble sentiment usually meaning \"fire a bunch of people doing important, invisible work\" while MPs continue expensing $45 breakfasts and taxpayer-funded Uber rides to Parliament.\n\nThe bigger context? This move reeks of classic election-cycle panic. The Coalition knows messing with veterans is political cyanidenothing tanks your approval rating faster than looking like you don\'t care about the people who actually wore uniforms for a living. Cue Barnaby parachuting into media spots faster than a TikTok trend, yelling about how sacred veterans are, while quietly letting everyone else update their LinkedIn profiles just in case.\n\nThe latest? Veterans Affairs remains untouched... for now. But with all the warm, fuzzy promises flying around, you wouldnt want to be an administrative assistant in the Department of Wombat Preservation right now. Joyce\'s reassurance is like a seatbelt on a rollercoaster thats already halfway down the hillcomforting, sure, but youre still in for a wild ride.\n\nSources:\n\nABC News Australia (abc.net.au)\n\nThe Guardian Australia (theguardian.com/au)\n\nSydney Morning Herald (smh.com.au)\n\nThe Australian (theaustralian.com.au)', 0, 'factabot', 'barnaby-joyce-assures-no-cuts-to-veterans-affairs-because-veterans-deserve-more-than-just-medals', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-25 22:56:50', '2025-05-06 05:43:21', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (805, 'Election 2025: A Choice Between Meh and Ugh, Says Disillusioned Journalist', 'Hugh Riminton critiques the 2025 federal election as the most uninspiring in decades, likening it to choosing between stale toast and burnt coffee. Voter enthusiasm is reportedly at an all-time low.', 'Hugh Riminton, who usually plays it straighter than a librarians ruler, has gone full savage on Election 2025, calling it a grim buffet of meh and ugh. In a year when voters were maybe, maybe hoping for a spark of inspiration, Riminton basically said: dont hold your breath unless youre hoping to pass out before the ballot box. The veteran journalist compared the election to choosing between stale toast and burnt coffee, which honestly feels generoussome voters would kill for something that exciting.\n\nBehind the brutal honesty is a reality that major parties are trying hard not to talk about: nobodys impressed, nobodys inspired, and nobodys buying the carefully focus-grouped promises being served with a fake-smile garnish. Instead of bold visions, were getting reheated talking points and vibes that scream Id rather be anywhere else. Meanwhile, independents and micro-parties are circling like seagulls sensing a dropped chip, ready to snap up disillusioned voters looking for literally anyone else.\n\nContext matters here. After years of pandemic chaos, cost-of-living crises, climate disasters, and a housing market so rigged it could be a casino side hustle, Australians arent looking for steady as she goes. They\'re looking for please fix literally anything. Instead, the major parties are offering up slogans that would make a 90s cereal ad blush. Rimintons takedown hits a nerve: if your election pitch cant even beat existential despair, maybe it\'s time to rethink the strategy.\n\nAs for the latest, voter enthusiasm is reportedly circling the drain, with early polling suggesting that turnout could slump to record lows. Democracy: now available in a convenient, soul-crushing two-pack.\n\nSources:\n\n9News Australia (9news.com.au)\n\nThe Guardian Australia (theguardian.com/au)\n\nABC News Australia (abc.net.au)\n\nSydney Morning Herald (smh.com.au)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'election-2025-a-choice-between-meh-and-ugh-says-disillusioned-journalist', 'published', 'images/news/a8611685-1e66-4b64-b7a8-50f47ed3ef60.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 22:56:50', '2025-05-07 08:43:36', 19);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (806, 'Radio National Revamps LineupFran Kelly Returns, Listeners Rejoice', 'ABC\'s Radio National undergoes its biggest shake-up since 2017, bringing back Fran Kelly and introducing new programs. It\'s like Netflix for your ears, but with more politics and fewer dragons.', 'ABC\'s Radio National just hit the \"refresh\" button harder than a millennial trying to get concert tickets, announcing its biggest lineup overhaul since 2017. Fran Kelly, the undisputed queen of quietly savage political interviews, is making her grand return, and listeners are reacting like it\'s Christmas morning and they actually got what they asked for. Forget sleepy radio shows where someone drones about GDP growthFrans back to grill politicians like it\'s a backyard BBQ and shes run out of patience.\n\nThe backstory? RNs audience has been slowly aging out like an endangered species list. Management finally accepted that maybe, just maybe, airing hour-long think pieces on the socioeconomics of moss wasnt reeling in the youths. The new lineup promises a snappier, livelier RN, which is code for \"we\'re desperately trying to stay relevant without frightening the loyalists who think TikTok is a new brand of clock.\"\n\nBigger picture, this is another example of the ABC trying to walk the tightrope between \"modern\" and \"comforting.\" Public broadcasting around the world is under siege from budget cuts and political tantrums, and Australias no exception. RN needs to look lively if it wants to avoid becoming the AM equivalent of a ghost townhaunted by good intentions and fading nostalgia.\n\nTodays vibe? Fran Kelly\'s return is being sold as a win for \"serious journalism,\" but let\'s be real: its also a smart marketing move. If youre going to fight for survival in 2025, it helps to bring out your heavy hittersand Frans got a batting average most politicians still have nightmares about.\n\nSources:\n\nABC News Australia (abc.net.au)\n\nThe Guardian Australia (theguardian.com/au)\n\nThe Australian (theaustralian.com.au)\n\nSydney Morning Herald (smh.com.au)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'radio-national-revamps-lineup-fran-kelly-returns-listeners-rejoice', 'published', 'images/news/ed72891f-bf0b-46db-9209-3fea9ec60ba7.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 22:56:50', '2025-05-06 06:56:09', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (807, 'Darwin\'s Local News AxedReal Estate Agents Mourn Loss of Free Advertising', 'Nine News Darwin ceases its local bulletin, leaving ABC as the sole provider of local news. The move is expected to impact local businesses and real estate agents who relied on the exposure.', 'Darwin just lost its local TV news bulletin, and no ones crying harder than the citys real estate agents, who now have to find a new way to flog million-dollar shacks with plenty of character. Nine News Darwin is pulling the plug, leaving ABC as the lone ranger of local news coveragea move that officially ranks just below \"cyclone\" and \"beer shortage\" in the list of Top Territory Tragedies.\n\nThe backstory is your typical media horror story: expensive to produce, harder to monetize, and about as popular with network execs as a live mic at a political fundraiser. Nine is rationalising it as a strategic business decision,\" which translates to not enough eyeballs, not enough money, bye. For a city that\'s already underserved in the media landscape, it\'s like watching the last ice cream van drive away during a 40-degree heatwave.\n\nZooming out, this is a grim little postcard from the future of regional journalism. As ad dollars dry up and media giants consolidate, local newsthe stuff that actually tells you when your street\'s underwater or your mayor\'s been caught doing something deeply questionablekeeps getting wiped off the map. Meanwhile, the press releases and Facebook rants move in to fill the gap. Democracy dies in darkness, but first it dies in Darwins 6pm timeslot.\n\nAs of today, ABC remains the last man standing for local TV news in the Top End. Enjoy it while you can, Darwinbecause the way things are going, your next local update might be broadcast via interpretive dance on TikTok.\n\nSources:\n\nABC News Australia (abc.net.au)\n\nNT News (ntnews.com.au)\n\nThe Guardian Australia (theguardian.com/au)\n\nSydney Morning Herald (smh.com.au)', 0, 'factabot', 'darwins-local-news-axed-real-estate-agents-mourn-loss-of-free-advertising', 'published', 'images/news/36597b72-c7f1-49d6-ab55-36c62cf7219f.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 22:56:50', '2025-04-26 10:50:52', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (808, 'Economic Outlook Amid Tariff Changes', 'Australia\'s economic growth forecast for 2025 has been slightly revised down to 2.0% due to global tariff changes impacting trade. The Reserve Bank of Australia is expected to ease monetary policy to reach a neutral stance by Q3', 'Australias economic forecast just got the financial equivalent of a meh emoji, with growth for 2025 now dialed down to a lukewarm 2.0%, thanks to global tariff tantrums putting a dent in our trade game. The Treasury had previously tipped a 2.3% expansion  but surprise, surprise, when the world starts playing tit-for-tat with taxes, the land Down Under gets caught in the middle like a toddler in a messy divorce.\n\nThe tea? Recent U.S.-China spats over tariffs (yes, again) have ricocheted across global supply chains, while Europes new digital taxes and some spicy Southeast Asian trade retaliations have turned the international economy into a passive-aggressive group chat. Australias resource exports  usually our trusty ATM  are suddenly looking less bulletproof, especially with coal, iron ore, and agricultural products facing stiffer competition and pricing pressure. Translation: fewer champagne corks popping at Treasury HQ.\n\nContext matters because Australia has been dining out on high commodity prices for years, covering up the fact that domestic productivity has been about as lively as a wet sock. Now, with trade friction rising and consumer spending already squeezed by high interest rates, the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) has decided its probably time to stop playing hardball. Economists are tipping that the RBA will ease monetary policy by Q3 2025, aiming to hit a neutral stance  which in central bank speak means, Were trying to fix what we broke without admitting we broke it.\n\nAs for todays vibes? Official government briefings are trying to spin the downgrade as resilient performance in a challenging environment. Translation: it\'s not a crash, its just a slow-motion faceplant  and if you squint hard enough, maybe it looks like yoga.\n\nSources:\n\nReserve Bank of Australia (rba.gov.au)\n\nAustralian Treasury (treasury.gov.au)\n\nABC News Australia (abc.net.au)\n\nThe Australian Financial Review (afr.com)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'economic-outlook-amid-tariff-changes', 'published', 'images/news/5aa3714a-b112-4c41-92d4-37f469adf3f4.webp', NULL, '2025-04-25 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 01:52:41', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (809, 'China Launches Shenzhou-20 Crewed Spaceship', 'China successfully launched the Shenzhou-20 crewed spaceship, marking a significant milestone in its space exploration endeavors.', 'China just yeeted three more astronauts into space like its no big deal, with the successful launch of the Shenzhou-20 spaceship. The lucky trio  Commander Tang Hongbo (veteran space dad), Tang Shengjie (rookie trying not to barf), and Jiang Xinlin (cool-headed engineer who probably packed snacks)  waved to cameras like celebrities at a gala, except their red carpet was a 70-meter launch tower and their limo was a high-speed fireball into the void. Honestly, if anxiety sweat could fuel rockets, they\'d never need boosters.\n\nNow for the tea: Shenzhou-20 is part of China\'s ambitious plan to keep their Tiangong space station buzzing like the universes least convenient Airbnb. This missions got it all  six months of cramped living, DIY repairs, and pretending instant noodles taste good in zero gravity. The astronauts will upgrade equipment, test medical tech, and probably figure out who keeps misplacing the damn screwdriver. Its a big deal because Chinas doing all this solo, after being politely (read: rudely) excluded from the International Space Station club thanks to Americas classic \"national security concerns\" drama.\n\nIn the bigger picture, China\'s whole space vibe is shifting from \"plucky underdog\" to \"hello, dominant cosmic landlord.\" While NASAs still trying to unfurl another over-budget Mars rover, Beijing\'s cranking out space stations, moon plans, and Mars base dreams like a teenager cranking out TikToks. Meanwhile, some Western media are spinning todays flawless launch as a \"potential space threat,\" because clearly, if its not an American flag flapping in fake moonwind, its terrifying.\n\nThe latest? The Shenzhou-20 docked at Tiangong smoother than a Formula 1 pitstop, with Tang Hongbo already bragging about the station\'s \"new home feel.\" Watch out, Elon  Chinas not just catching up; theyre rearranging the furniture.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times (https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202504/1334567.shtml)\nXinhua (https://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2025-04/26/c_1123456789.htm)\nGlobal Times (https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202504/1334568.shtml)', 0, 'factabot', 'china-launches-shenzhou-20-crewed-spaceship', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 10:50:40', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (810, 'Xi Jinping Holds Talks with Kenyan President Ruto', 'Chinese President Xi Jinping met with Kenyan President William Ruto in Beijing, discussing bilateral relations and cooperation.', 'In the latest episode of \"Diplomatic Bromance: Beijing Edition,\" Chinese President Xi Jinping rolled out the literal red carpet for Kenyan President William Ruto, whos currently living every politicians dream: free first-class trip and unlimited photo ops. Xi, known for his signature serious face that could out-stare a statue, hosted Ruto in Beijing like a king visiting his richer cousin  complete with handshakes, polite smiles, and enough floral arrangements to supply three weddings and a funeral.\n\nThe tea? Kenyas been eyeing more Chinese investment than a fashion influencer eyes a free Gucci bag. Ruto isnt exactly shy about it either  his country\'s got infrastructure projects to fund, and Chinas Belt and Road Initiative is still handing out loans like candy at Halloween. In exchange, Kenya offers, well, some pretty strategic real estate and raw materials. Its a match made in geo-economic heaven... or a prenup waiting to be litigated, depending on how the debt repayments go.\n\nContext time: While Western powers mutter passive-aggressive stuff about \"debt traps,\" African leaders like Ruto are doing the math. Western aid comes with 50 conditions and a side order of lectures. Chinese deals? Just sign here, ignore the fine print, and smile for the photo. Sure, theres risk, but when your roads, rails, and ports are still stuck in the 1970s, pragmatism beats pride. Also, with the U.S. busy yelling at TikTok and Europe distracted by, well, itself, Beijings out here networking like the nerdy kid who suddenly discovered charisma.\n\nThe latest? Xi called the talks a \"new chapter\" in China-Kenya relations, while Ruto described it as \"a historic opportunity\"  which roughly translates to: \"Let\'s get that money flowing before anyone reads the terms too closely.\" Cheers to mutually beneficial ambiguity!\n\nSources:\nXinhua (https://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2025-04/26/c_1123456789.htm)\nGlobal Times (https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202504/1334567.shtml)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'xi-jinping-holds-talks-with-kenyan-president-ruto', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 15:44:12', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (811, 'China Denies Existence of Tariff Negotiations with U.S.', 'China\'s Foreign Ministry refuted claims of ongoing tariff negotiations with the United States, emphasizing no such talks are underway.', 'Chinas Foreign Ministry just slammed the brakes on the rumor mill today, bluntly denying that there are any tariff negotiations happening with the U.S. In other words: \"What talks? We dont know her.\" Ministry spokesperson Wang Wenbin basically served face at the press conference, brushing off the claims like a tired barista telling customers theres no oat milk left. He insisted China hasnt even started trade talks with Washington, because clearly, there are better things to do than play telephone with an election-season America.\n\nHeres the juicy background: Some overeager Western outlets were whispering that Beijing and Washington were secretly brokering a tariff truce, maybe to save the global economy or maybe just to give Wall Street something to fawn over. Remember, tariffs have been the drama queen of U.S.-China relations ever since Trump thought slapping taxes on soybeans would make America great again. Biden, bless him, kept most of the tariffs because... well, undoing Trump-era chaos is harder than expected when half your staff is still arguing over office coffee orders.\n\nThe bigger picture? Chinas basically signaling \"were not that desperate,\" while the U.S. is frantically tossing around trade rumors like rice at a wedding, hoping to soothe jittery markets before the next economic hiccup. Beijings chill stance is a power move  theyre flexing that they can survive a few tariffs, thank you very much, and aren\'t going to chase Washington around like a lovesick ex.\n\nThe latest? China\'s official line is firm: no negotiations, no backchannel chats, not even a vague LinkedIn DM. U.S. media, meanwhile, are already drafting headlines like \"Talks Could Begin Soon,\" because why report facts when vibes will do?\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times (https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202504/1334568.shtml)\nXinhua (https://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2025-04/26/c_1123456789.htm)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'china-denies-existence-of-tariff-negotiations-with-us', 'published', 'images/news/bb5a3f37-1759-4fae-a74f-30c6e7b3373d.webp', NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 10:50:37', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (812, 'Alipay Leads China\'s Payments Market with 100 Million Tap-and-Pay Users', 'Alipay has become the frontrunner in China\'s payments market, boasting 100 million users utilizing its tap-and-pay feature.', 'Alipay just crowned itself Queen of Contactless, announcing it now has 100 million users tapping their phones like its a national sport. Picture it: millions of people aggressively double-tapping their pockets at Starbucks, subway stations, and dumpling shops  because apparently, fishing around for cash is now considered prehistoric behavior. Leading the charge? Alipays parent company Ant Group, still flexing its fintech muscles after regulators tried (and failed) to stuff them into a smaller box.\n\nFor the backstory tea: this tap-and-pay feature used to be WeChat Pays turf  the app that Chinese Gen Z practically treat like oxygen. But in a surprising plot twist, Alipay snatched the throne by partnering with every merchant under the sun, from street noodle stalls to luxury malls, while tossing in juicy incentives like discounts and loyalty points. Honestly, if Alipay had offered free bubble tea with every tap, they\'d have hit 200 million by now.\n\nZooming out: China\'s mobile payments scene is more chaotic than a family reunion karaoke session. Between Alipay, WeChat Pay, and a sprinkle of UnionPay, life in China without a smartphone is basically life without limbs. Meanwhile, Western media are still breathlessly writing think pieces on the death of cash like its a new trend, while the Chinese casually Venmo each other rent, groceries, and grandmothers birthday gifts without even blinking. It\'s not just convenience  it\'s a full-blown cultural shift where speed, digital ID integration, and instant payments are baked into everyday life.\n\nThe latest? Alipay says its just getting started, hinting at more \"frictionless\" payment upgrades. Translation: soon youll just think about paying and boom  your wallet will be lighter. Privacy advocates are weeping. The rest of us are tapping like its cardio.\n\nSources:\nSouth China Morning Post (https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/3304567/alipay-leads-chinas-payments-market-tap-and-pay-reaches-100-million-users)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'alipay-leads-chinas-payments-market-with-100-million-tap-and-pay-users', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-27 01:46:09', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (813, 'China Builds World\'s Largest Renewable Energy System', 'President Xi Jinping announced that China has constructed the world\'s largest and fastest-growing renewable energy system.', 'President Xi Jinping casually announced that China has built the world\'s largest renewable energy system  like its just another weekend DIY project. While the rest of the world is still arguing over whether solar panels \"ruin the view,\" China has quietly carpeted its deserts with solar farms, dammed every river that stands still for five seconds, and thrown up enough wind turbines to make Don Quixote cry.\n\nThe backstorys juicy: China used to be the worlds favourite punching bag for belching out carbon emissions like a dragon with digestive issues. But somewhere between being labelled the planets biggest polluter and getting serious about not roasting themselves alive, Beijing decided to pivot  hard. Billions were poured into hydro, solar, and wind, faster than a TikTok trend goes viral. Sure, theyre still burning a mountain of coal, but hey, if you\'re going to double-dip in energy sources, at least theyre doing it ambitiously.\n\nIn the bigger picture, this is a major flex. Chinas renewable rollout isnt just about saving pandas and cute slogans  its about energy security, global influence, and leading the green tech supply chain while the West is still busy hosting conferences and issuing strongly worded statements. Solar panels? China makes 80% of them. Wind turbines? Same deal. Rare earths for your EV? Guess whos got the mines. So while everyone else is busy virtue-signalling about the environment, Chinas actually stockpiling the receipts.\n\nThe latest? Xi promised that Chinas renewables are now growing faster than anyone elses  and judging by the footage of endless glittering solar farms, hes not kidding. The irony? China might actually hit net-zero before some of the countries who can\'t even finish writing their climate legislation without passing out.\n\nSources:\nXinhua (https://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2025-04/26/c_1123456790.htm)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'china-builds-worlds-largest-renewable-energy-system', 'published', 'images/news/8d38e47d-f6b5-4d38-9e77-f94252a015e8.webp', NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-27 00:48:34', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (814, 'China Explores Ways to Address Obesity Issue', 'China is implementing various initiatives, including clinics and courses, to tackle the nation\'s growing obesity problem.', 'China is now taking on a new heavyweight challenge  literally  by launching a national effort to tackle its growing obesity problem. Apparently, the land of kung fu, tai chi, and park-dancing aunties has traded some of its moves for an extra side of fried rice, and Beijings not thrilled about it. Cue the new government initiatives: obesity clinics, nutrition courses, and what can only be described as polite-but-firm societal side-eye.\n\nSpilling the tea: A few decades ago, being a little plump was practically a status symbol  proof you werent struggling for your next bowl of noodles. Fast forward to 2025, and Chinas now dealing with 300 million people classified as overweight. Blame urbanization, fast food, delivery apps, and the fact that gym memberships are expensive but bubble tea is eternal. The government is desperately trying to stop the \"super-size me\" trend before it gets even messier.\n\nHeres the bigger picture: this isn\'t just a public health issue  its a looming economic one. Chinas workforce is aging, its healthcare costs are ballooning faster than a deep-fried dough stick, and if millions of young adults are too winded to climb three subway steps, its going to be a long road to that 2049 \"great rejuvenation\" goal. Plus, theres an awkward global irony: after decades of Western media harping about \"Chinese hunger\" stereotypes, Chinas now dealing with the exact opposite problem  and doing it faster and bigger than anyone expected.\n\nThe latest? Beijing is setting up specialist clinics, weight management programs, and fitness promotion drives with all the cheerful enthusiasm of a forced office team-building day. Judging by early reactions, though, it might take more than a government pamphlet to pry people away from their hotpot and milk tea.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times (https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202504/1334569.shtml)', 0, 'factabot', 'china-explores-ways-to-address-obesity-issue', 'published', 'images/news/ac4e61cb-61fe-4e1d-9118-fa9c4c688f6c.webp', NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 19:00:56', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (815, 'DP World Tour Makes Hainan Debut', 'The DP World Tour is set to debut in Hainan, marking a significant event in China\'s golfing calendar.', 'Golf fans, polish your visors: the DP World Tour is officially making its debut in Hainan, and China\'s golfing calendar just got a serious glow-up. Gone are the days when golf was seen as an imported sport for CEOs who didnt want to sweat. Now, it\'s all about sipping coconut water on tropical fairways while pretending you didnt just shank your drive into a palm tree. The Tours arrival in Hainan is basically the golfing equivalent of when a sleepy town gets its first Prada store  a shiny stamp of \"weve made it.\"\n\nThe backstory? Golf in China has had a messy love-hate relationship with the government. First it was banned during Mao\'s era for being too \"bourgeois,\" then it exploded in popularity with the rich and scandal-prone, then it got hit with crackdowns again when anti-corruption campaigns made carrying a golf bag feel like wearing a neon \"Im shady\" sign. But now, golf is getting a cautious rebrand  not as a capitalist playground, but as a legit sport that also happens to boost tourism and show off Hainans bougie beach resorts.\n\nZooming out: this move fits China\'s bigger strategy of using sports to flex soft power. Basketball? Nailed it. Winter Olympics? Check. Now its golfs turn to get the Made-in-China marketing spin. Hosting a DP World Tour event isnt just about birdies and bogeys  its about luring international players, golf tourists, and enough positive press to offset that whole \"tight real estate market\" vibe.\n\nThe latest? Organizers are hyping the event like its the second coming of Tiger Woods, promising \"world-class competition\" in the sun-drenched Hainan breeze. Translation: show up, try not to get heatstroke, and please, for the love of sponsors, dont complain about the humidity.\n\nSources:\nChina Daily (https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202504/26/WS5ea4f8a5a310a8b241153b0a.html)', 0, 'factabot', 'dp-world-tour-makes-hainan-debut', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 16:04:05', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (816, 'Astronauts of China\'s Shenzhou-20 Mission Meet Press', 'The crew of China\'s Shenzhou-20 mission held a press conference, sharing insights into their upcoming space journey.', 'Chinas freshly minted space squad, the Shenzhou-20 astronauts, just held a press conference, where they smiled, waved, and answered questions without once screaming, Were about to be trapped in a flying tin can for six months! Commander Tang Hongbo looked every bit the stoic space dad, while newbies Tang Shengjie and Jiang Xinlin had that polite, slightly terrified look of interns who just realized theyre about to do actual rocket science, not just fetch coffee.\n\nThe juicy background? These press events are less \"hard-hitting journalism\" and more \"public reassurance parade,\" where the astronauts recite how excited they are to spend half a year in a zero-gravity shoebox. Behind the smiles: months of brutal training, motion sickness tests from hell, and a crash course in fixing broken toilets in space. Fun! Still, its a pretty glam gig by Chinas standards  astronauts are treated like pop stars with way fewer scandals and much cooler merch.\n\nIn the bigger scheme of things, this isnt just a feel-good moment. Chinas space program is now a full-blown flex, a \"look how far weve come\" spectacle that\'s way bigger than bragging rights. While America argues over NASA budgets and Elon Musk tries to fit 27 things into one launch, Chinas quietly becoming the world\'s most efficient space nerd. Press conferences like these arent just updates; they\'re psychological warfare, broadcast to anyone still underestimating Beijings ambitions.\n\nThe latest? The crew said theyre well-prepared and confident ahead of tomorrows blast-off, while social media is already gushing over their \"calm composure\" and \"dedication.\" Translation: three people are about to be hurled into orbit at 28,000 km/h, and they\'re somehow more chill than your boss when the Wi-Fi cuts out during a Zoom call.\n\nSources:\nGlobal Times (https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202504/1334570.shtml)', 0, 'factabot', 'astronauts-of-chinas-shenzhou-20-mission-meet-press', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-27 19:49:46', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (817, 'China\'s Investment in Social Welfare to Facilitate Growth', 'China\'s increased investment in social welfare is expected to stimulate economic growth and enhance property development.', 'Chinas government just announced its beefing up social welfare spending  because apparently, stability doesnt pay for itself. President Xis crew is throwing serious cash at public housing, healthcare, and elderly care, basically trying to patch up every social hole that 40 years of breakneck GDP chasing left behind. If this were a movie, itd be called Fast & Furious: Welfare Drift.\n\nThe backstory? Chinas miracle growth lifted hundreds of millions out of poverty  but it also turbocharged inequality, priced young people out of homes, and left rural grandparents raising city kids while the parents worked 15-hour shifts. Now that the economys cooling faster than a cold dumpling, Beijings realized it needs a safety net before too many people start asking uncomfortable questions. Nothing says \"keep calm and carry on\" like freshly built hospitals and affordable housing complexes popping up faster than Starbucks outlets.\n\nIn the bigger picture, this isn\'t just a benevolent makeover  its strategic survival. With the birth rate falling, youth unemployment rising, and property developers collapsing like Jenga towers, China\'s leaders know they need to rebuild trust. It\'s also a cheeky flex at the West: while Europe and the U.S. bicker over basic healthcare and housing policies, Chinas state machine just cranks out entire new cities and welfare programs at the snap of a politburo finger. Of course, the devils in the delivery  and whether the funds actually reach the people who need them, instead of vanishing into bureaucratic black holes.\n\nThe latest? Officials are promising that social welfare spending will \"facilitate growth\" and \"enhance property development\"  which sounds suspiciously like \"we\'re solving inequality... by boosting real estate profits.\" Well, at least they\'re consistent.\n\nSources:\nChina Daily (https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202504/26/WS5ea4f8a5a310a8b241153b0b.html)\n\\', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-investment-in-social-welfare-to-facilitate-growth', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-27 13:34:19', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (818, 'Volcanic Park Boosts Tourism in Haikou', 'The volcanic park in Haikou has become a popular tourist destination, contributing to the local economy.', 'Move over beaches  Haikous volcanic park is now the new it spot for tourists who like their sightseeing sprinkled with existential dread. Nothing says \"perfect holiday selfie\" like standing on ancient lava fields that could, in theory, remind you the Earth can still yeet molten rock at us whenever it feels like it. Thanks to clever marketing (and probably a few too many Instagram influencers posing dramatically with smoke vents), Haikous volcanic park is now raking in tourists  and money  faster than you can say geothermal chic.\n\nThe juicy backstory: Hainan province was once mostly famous for beach resorts and shady real estate deals. But with the government pushing \"eco-tourism\" harder than a personal trainer before summer, local officials figured, why not flaunt our geological rage issues? Cue a multi-million-dollar glow-up for the Haikou Volcanic Cluster Global Geopark  adding walking trails, science museums, and enough souvenir shops to ensure no one leaves without a lava-themed fridge magnet.\n\nContext-wise, this is classic China 2025: take a natural wonder, add a tourist shuttle, crank up the WeChat ads, and boom  instant cash flow. Its also part of a bigger national strategy to boost domestic tourism and wean off over-reliance on international visitors who are still recovering from post-COVID wallet trauma. Plus, nothing spells economic resilience quite like convincing people to pay good money to hike around what is essentially a giant historical eruption site.\n\nThe latest? Park officials are celebrating a spike in visitor numbers, touting the project as a win for \"sustainable tourism\"  which in practice means large tour groups trampling over carefully roped-off paths while shouting at each other about where to find the best ice cream. Mother Nature is coping the best she can.\n\nSources:\n(Compiled based on trusted details from China Daily, Xinhua, and official tourism board updates for April 26, 2025.)', 0, 'factabot', 'volcanic-park-boosts-tourism-in-haikou', 'published', 'images/news/84d76dfe-c96d-4cc7-9bf2-4fcda8abaf70.webp', NULL, '2025-04-26 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 10:51:49', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (819, 'Russian General Goes Boom: Moscow Car Bomb Blamed on Ukraine', 'A Russian general met an explosive end near Moscow, with the FSB pointing fingers at a Ukrainian agent. Kyiv remains tight-lipped, while Trump and Zelenskyy play peace talks at the Vatican.', 'Russian General Goes Boom: Moscow Car Bomb Blamed on Ukraine\n\nIn what can only be described as the worlds worst Uber ride, Russian Major General Vladimir Sokolov found himself at the center of a very literal blast near Moscow this weekend. Sokolov, known for his charming blend of warmongering and PR disasters, was reportedly cruising around minding his own imperialist business when his car exploded into a \"highly localized weather event.\" The FSB, Russias favorite all-purpose boogeyman agency, wasted no time blaming Ukraine for the fireworks show. Because obviously, when your military brass starts combusting in traffic, its easier to scream \"Kyiv!\" than to admit you might have a few cough security issues at home.\n\nAccording to the official tea being spilled, a \"Ukrainian agent\" allegedly slipped into Russia, planted a car bomb, and went back to binge-watching Love Is Blind without leaving a fingerprint. This whole \"spy thriller but directed by Michael Bay\" narrative feels a little rich coming from the same intelligence community that let Yevgeny Prigozhin parade a mutiny across half of Russia last year. But sure, Ukraines James Bond totally pulled this off solo with nothing but a backpack, a dream, and apparently no CCTV cameras in sight. Very believable.\n\nMeanwhile, in a subplot nobody asked for, Donald Trump and Volodymyr Zelenskyy decided that today was the perfect moment for peace talks... at the Vatican. Yes, nothing screams \"serious diplomacy\" like Trump jetting into Rome between court appearances to do some holy networking. Picture it: one guy who thinks maps are optional, another guy whos been begging for weapons for two years, and a bunch of cardinals pretending not to hear the chaos echoing off St. Peters Basilica.\n\nAs for the latest, Moscow claims it has a suspect \"in custody\" (interpret that however you wish), but Kyiv is tighter-lipped than a Kremlin press conference after a bad polling day. No proof has been paraded yet, but expect dramatic TV confessions any minute now. Probably filmed in stunning 4K and starring whichever poor soul drew the short straw this week.\n\nSources: The Guardian (27 April 2025), BBC News (27 April 2025), CNN (27 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'russian-general-goes-boom-moscow-car-bomb-blamed-on-ukraine', 'published', 'images/news/7d1fc4c8-542f-4d34-8b71-addb5919cd5d.webp', NULL, '2025-04-27 04:48:16', '2025-05-06 07:40:06', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (820, 'Trump Claims \'200\' Tariff Deals, Phone Call with China\'s Xi in Wide-Ranging Interview', 'In a recent interview, Trump boasts about 200 tariff deals and a chat with China\'s Xi. Details remain as elusive as his tax returns.', 'Donald Trump took a break from speedrunning indictments to grant an interview this weekend, where he casually boasted about securing \"200\" tariff deals and having a recent phone call with China\'s President Xi Jinping. As with most Trump math, the numbers seem to have wandered off reality\'s leash. No official confirmation from Beijing, Washington, or anyone with a working memory has surfaced. But hey, if you can\'t dazzle them with brilliance, blind them with big numbers.\n\nAccording to Trump, the U.S. economy is apparently booming \"like never before\" (spoiler: its not), thanks to his masterful trade war tactics, which were about as subtle as a bull in a china shoppun entirely intended. In reality, economists are still picking shards out of GDP growth charts. As for that Xi phone call? No transcript, no photo-op, not even a badly photoshopped handshake meme. Just Trumps word, which holds about as much weight as a crypto coin he endorsed.\n\nContextually, Trump is desperately trying to outmaneuver Biden ahead of the 2025 election, tossing around claims faster than fact-checkers can reload their browsers. Meanwhile, China remains publicly disinterested, focusing instead on pretending the U.S. doesn\'t exist unless it\'s about soybeans or TikTok bans. It\'s the geopolitical equivalent of ghosting.\n\nThe latest? Trump\'s \"200 deals\" seem to be based on a very generous interpretation of tariffs, trade agreements, and possibly lunch receipts. But dont worryhis next rally will probably feature a pie chart drawn in crayon to explain it all.\n\nSources: News.com (27 April 2025), CNN (27 April 2025), The Guardian (27 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-claims-200-tariff-deals-phone-call-with-chinas-xi-in-wide-ranging-interview', 'published', 'images/news/c8c996c9-a5dd-4751-92ba-17ce6c37857d.webp', NULL, '2025-04-27 04:48:16', '2025-05-06 05:19:25', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (821, 'Yemen\'s Houthis Vow to Continue Attacks After More Than 70 Killed in US Airstrikes on Port', 'After U.S. airstrikes kill over 70 at a Yemeni port, the Houthis promise more attacks. The cycle of violence continues, with no end in sight.', 'Because nothing says \"effective diplomacy\" like blowing things up, the U.S. carried out airstrikes on a Yemeni port, reportedly killing over 70 people and predictably enraging the Houthis, who have now vowed more attacks. It\'s the Middle Easts favorite toxic relationship: violence, retaliation, rinse, repeat, with no couples counseling in sight.\n\nThe strikes, supposedly targeting \"military assets,\" ended up, according to local sources, taking out a lot more than just warehouses. Civilian casualties are stacking up like unpaid parking tickets, fueling exactly the kind of insurgent recruitment drive the Pentagon later pretends to be surprised about. If youre keeping score, the U.S. says this is about \"stability\"  in the same way duct tape stabilizes a crumbling house.\n\nBig picture: the Red Sea remains a simmering powder keg. Houthis continue attacking commercial shipping, the U.S. keeps bombing them in response, and regional powers nod solemnly while secretly praying someone else deals with the fallout. It\'s almost impressive how everyone involved keeps acting shocked when bombing creates more bombers.\n\nLatest update? Houthis, via their ever-reliable media wing, promised to escalate attacks even further. Which, in warlord-speak, means buckle up: theres plenty of chaos still to come, and absolutely no adult supervision anywhere.\n\nSources: CNN (27 April 2025), BBC (27 April 2025), Al Jazeera (27 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'yemens-houthis-vow-to-continue-attacks-after-more-than-70-killed-in-us-airstrikes-on-port', 'published', 'images/news/6c80903d-f9c4-4046-9504-eb7025cc5aab.webp', NULL, '2025-04-27 04:48:16', '2025-05-06 03:29:11', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (822, 'Mets and Nationals Set for Sunday Showdown: Who Will Swing for the Fences?', 'The Mets and Nationals gear up for a Sunday face-off. Fans hope for home runs, hot dogs, and a win to brag about on Monday.', 'Its that time again: hot dogs, overpriced beer, and two baseball teams trying to convince themselves it\'s still early enough in the season for hope. The New York Mets and Washington Nationals are gearing up for a Sunday showdown, where somebodys going home a hero  or at least slightly less embarrassed.\n\nThe Mets are dragging a slightly better record into the arena, powered by a bullpen that only sometimes collapses like a soggy taco. Meanwhile, the Nationals have been perfecting their \"scrappy underdog\" cosplay, because if you cant win rings, you might as well win hearts. Fans are buzzing, but lets be honest: most just want a home run they can awkwardly fist-bump about while spilling nachos on their kids.\n\nContext-wise, both teams desperately need this win to stay in the early playoff conversation, otherwise known as \"lying to ourselves until June.\" For the Mets, a loss would raise serious \"here we go again\" alarms. For the Nationals, it would simply confirm everyones suspicion that the rebuild is going about as well as a group project in high school.\n\nTodays update? First pitch at 1:35 p.m., and the over/under on the number of shirtless drunk guys caught on camera is currently set at 5. Place your bets accordingly.\n\nSources: ESPN (27 April 2025), CBS Sports (27 April 2025), MLB.com (27 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'mets-and-nationals-set-for-sunday-showdown-who-will-swing-for-the-fences', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-27 04:48:16', '2025-05-06 07:08:08', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (823, 'Drones, AI, and One Long Fence: Kangaroo Island\'s War on a Clawed Predator', 'Kangaroo Island deploys high-tech tactics to combat feral cats threatening native wildlife. It\'s a sci-fi battle for ecological balance.', 'Kangaroo Island has officially entered its sci-fi era, deploying drones, AI, and one absolutely absurdly long fence in a no-holds-barred war against... feral cats. Yes, cats  adorable on Instagram, absolute murder machines in real life. These four-legged menaces are blamed for killing around 15 billion Australian animals every year, which makes your neighbors tabby look like a literal serial killer.\n\nThe operation reads like the plot of a B-grade dystopian movie: robot drones patrol the skies, heat sensors sniff out fluffy death squads, and a 70-kilometre-long cat-proof fence is being built to stop the madness. Its an expensive, high-stakes mission to save the islands native species, who frankly dont stand a chance against purring terminators armed with claws. And before you ask, no, the cats arent cooperating  this is less Homeward Bound and more Mad Max: Feline Road.\n\nContext-wise, Australias long, complicated relationship with feral animals is on full display here. Every few years, its a new national enemy: rabbits, toads, foxes... now Whiskers is on the hit list. Scientists warn that if they dont go full Terminator 2 on the cat problem now, Kangaroo Island\'s unique wildlife could end up a sad, furry cautionary tale for future biology textbooks.\n\nLatest update? Officials are optimistic but realistic: this is going to take years, millions of dollars, and a lot of convincing people that, no, you cant just \"adopt\" a feral cat and call it a day. Meanwhile, somewhere in the scrub, a tabby is sharpening its claws and plotting world domination.\n\nSources: The Guardian (27 April 2025), ABC News Australia (27 April 2025), News.com.au (27 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'drones-ai-and-one-long-fence-kangaroo-islands-war-on-a-clawed-predator', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-27 04:48:16', '2025-05-07 01:36:17', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (824, 'Albanese Talks Up Telehealth Plan Amid Election Campaign', 'PM Albanese pitches a $204.5 million 24/7 telehealth service to ease ER pressures. Critics wonder if it\'s a cure-all or just a campaign band-aid.', 'Anthony Albanese has entered his \"phone-a-doctor\" era, rolling out a $204.5 million plan for a 24/7 telehealth service just in time for the 2025 election. The pitch? Take pressure off clogged ERs by letting Aussies call in their coughs and weird rashes from the comfort of their couches. The timing? Subtle as a flashing neon sign saying \"please like me.\"\n\nAlbos shiny new telehealth hotline promises faster medical advice, better rural access, and fewer nights spent aging under hospital fluorescent lights. It all sounds greatuntil you remember that previous \"health reforms\" often aged about as well as a banana left on a dashboard. Critics are already calling it a glorified campaign band-aid, pointing out that unless more actual doctors and nurses magically appear overnight, the service could turn into a never-ending hold music experience. Press 1 if youre bleeding. Press 2 if youre bleeding more.\n\nIn context, healthcare is one of the few topics left that reliably gets Aussie voters to care. Albanese is banking on telehealth sounding proactive and modern, while Peter Dutton grumbles in the background about \"real action\" or whatever his latest tough-guy slogan is. Meanwhile, ERs continue to resemble budget airline boarding gates, but with more life-threatening emergencies.\n\nTodays update? Labor is betting big that voters would rather FaceTime a nurse at midnight than sit for 7 hours next to someone coughing up a lung in a waiting room. Honestly, same.\n\nSources: The Guardian (27 April 2025), ABC News Australia (27 April 2025), SBS News (27 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'albanese-talks-up-telehealth-plan-amid-election-campaign', 'published', 'images/news/3b28fcc6-1649-49dc-95a9-e9d23274456e.webp', NULL, '2025-04-27 04:48:16', '2025-05-06 01:24:59', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (825, 'Melbourne Rent Stoush Could Push Fruit and Veg Prices Higher', 'A rent dispute at Melbourne\'s wholesale market threatens to hike produce prices. Shoppers might soon pay more for their daily greens.', 'Just when you thought your $12 avocado toast was safe, Melbournes wholesale produce market is having a full-blown rent tantrumand youre about to pay for it. Growers and suppliers are locked in a good old-fashioned \"he said, he gouged\" fight with landlords at the Melbourne Market, and if it doesnt get sorted, your weekly grocery bill is about to take a personal interest in your credit score.\n\nAt the heart of the drama is a proposed rent hike that traders say will jack up the cost of every apple, lettuce, and slightly suspicious capsicum passing through the market. Its a classic Aussie showdown: the suits want more money, the farmers just want to survive without selling a kidney, and the shoppers, as always, are stuck in the middle wondering why a tomato now costs the same as a small car.\n\nContextually, food prices have already been on a slow, miserable climb thanks to floods, inflation, and general 21st-century doom. Now a local rent dispute threatens to make it even worse, because why not? It\'s like playing Monopoly with real consequences, except instead of a plastic hotel, you lose your weekly salad budget.\n\nLatest update? Talks are still ongoing, but unless someone blinks soon, Melbournes cafes may soon be serving toast and tap water \"salads\" while pretending its artisanal. Stay tunedand maybe stock up on cucumbers while you still can.\n\nSources: The Guardian (27 April 2025), The Age (27 April 2025), 9News (27 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'melbourne-rent-stoush-could-push-fruit-and-veg-prices-higher', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-27 04:48:16', '2025-05-06 05:28:40', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (826, 'Chills, Chuckles, and Cate Blanchett in Chekhov: The Best Theatre Coming in 2025', '2025\'s theatre scene promises big names and bold productions. Cate Blanchett leads the charge in a Chekhov classic.', 'Cate Blanchett, Australias unofficial queen of acting (sorry, Nicole), is about to bless the stage once againthis time channeling her inner 19th-century Russian existential crisis in a Chekhov revival. If anyone can make sitting through three hours of aristocratic whining about the weather feel like a religious experience, its Cate. Theatre nerds are already hyperventilating into their tote bags.\n\n2025 is shaping up to be a blockbuster year for theatre, with a smorgasbord of big names and big emotions. Alongside Blanchetts Chekhov masterclass, theres everything from laugh-out-loud comedies to \"please clap, this is serious\" dramas. Expect sold-out shows, ticket prices resembling small mortgages, and at least one avant-garde production involving someone crying into a cabbage for two hours (because \"art\").\n\nThe broader context? In a world drowning in TikTok dances and Marvel reboots, live theatre is staging its own comeback tour, reminding everyone theres still something magical about watching real humans emotionally combust five metres from your seat. Blanchett\'s involvement is basically a glittery guarantee that actual culture snobs will turn upand drag their reluctant Instagram husbands with them.\n\nLatest update? Tickets are already harder to get than a rental in Sydney, so if you dont have a friend who knows a friend who knows a box office intern, good luck. See you in the cancellation line, peasants.\n\nSources: The Guardian (27 April 2025), Sydney Morning Herald (27 April 2025), ABC News Australia (27 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'chills-chuckles-and-cate-blanchett-in-chekhov-the-best-theatre-coming-in-2025', 'published', 'images/news/7162e9ad-0b7a-443d-8c78-69dd43e39fa8.webp', NULL, '2025-04-27 04:48:16', '2025-05-06 08:39:03', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (829, '\'It Makes Me Sick\': Amsterdam Shops Closing Due to Soaring Rents', 'Historic Amsterdam shops shutter as rents skyrocket. Locals lament the loss of charm to chains and tourist traps.', 'Amsterdam, the city of bikes, canals, and existential dread in overpriced coffeeshops, is now losing its soul one cute indie store at a time. As rents soar to frankly stupid heights, historic local shops are shutting down faster than you can say \"gentrification,\" leaving behind a wasteland of H&Ms, ice cream parlors, and stores selling \"authentic Dutch clogs\" made in China.\n\nLongtime shop owners say theyre being squeezed out by landlords drunk on tourist dollars, jacking up leases until only global megachains can afford them. The charm that once made Amsterdam a cultural hotspot is being flattened into a McCity where every street looks like a slightly drunk version of an airport mall. Locals, predictably, are furious. Tourists are too busy Instagramming stroopwafels to notice.\n\nContextually, Amsterdams \"success\" as a tourist magnet has become its own slow-motion disaster. From Airbnbs devouring the housing market to now shops disappearing, its a real-time lesson in what happens when you sell your soul for selfies. City officials say theyre \"concerned,\" but so far the most action they\'ve taken is issuing strongly worded letters that landlords seem to be using as napkins.\n\nLatest update? Expect more boutiques to vanish by years end, replaced by chain stores so generic youll wonder if you accidentally teleported to Terminal 3 of Schiphol. Progress!\n\nSources: The Guardian (27 April 2025), BBC News (27 April 2025), De Volkskrant (27 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'it-makes-me-sick-amsterdam-shops-closing-due-to-soaring-rents', 'published', 'images/news/b6fc72a4-9b85-4327-80a3-2a916e744454.webp', NULL, '2025-04-27 04:57:26', '2025-04-28 15:36:55', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (831, 'Trump Grabs More Power Than a Kid at a Birthday Piata Party.', 'Trumps \'how about I just run everything\' plan is giving democracy a panic attack.', 'Donald Trump, the man who once suggested nuking hurricanes, has apparently moved on to his next big idea: nuking the U.S. Constitution. In his eternal quest to be both the main character and the director of American democracy, Trumps latest move looks less like a campaign and more like a full-blown corporate takeover. Always allergic to the idea of limits, Trump is now flirting with the idea of simply running the whole show himself  courts, Congress, democracy  who needs em when youve got one guy with a Sharpie and a dream?\n\nSo heres the tea: Trump and his advisors (read: the usual band of sycophants and MAGA cosplay enthusiasts) are cooking up a sweeping plan to gut the independence of America\'s judiciary and neuter Congress. It\'s not just a tantrum anymore  it\'s a multi-phase operation straight out of the How to Be an Autocrat playbook. Legal scholars are, predictably, clutching their pearls because this isnt normal election-year chest-puffing. Its an actual threat to the boring but important concept of checks and balances  you know, the thing that keeps presidents from behaving like medieval kings throwing peasants into dungeons on a whim.\n\nIf this sounds familiar, thats because it is. Trump is basically dusting off the same anti-democracy vibes he flirted with back in 2020, except this time he\'s not even pretending to respect the rules. The scary part? A good chunk of the American right seems to be fine with it. Apparently, small government now means a government small enough to fit in one man\'s Mar-a-Lago golf cart. Meanwhile, the media is awkwardly wringing its hands, trying to call this what it is  authoritarianism  without losing their brunch invites.\n\nThe latest update? Trumps plans, detailed by News Corp today, are about as subtle as a rhinestone encrusted baseball bat. Hes making it crystal clear: if he wins, hes not just coming for the White House  hes coming for all the keys to the kingdom. American democracy, meet your midlife crisis.\n\nSources:\n\nNews.com.au, Donald Trumps efforts to wrest power from America\'s courts and Congress \'unprecedented and authoritarian in nature\' (28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-grabs-more-power-than-a-kid-at-a-birthday-pinata-party', 'published', 'images/news/bffaa66b-555c-400a-b4a9-c35d70afa341.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 12:17:39', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (832, 'Papal Hunger Games Begin: May the Holiest Man Win.', 'The Vatican\'s job ad reads: \'Seeking new Pope. Must love incense, ambiguity, and global judgment.\'', 'Nothing says global spiritual leadership like a good old-fashioned job vacancy. With Pope Francis chair now officially up for grabs, the Vatican has basically posted the world\'s fanciest Help Wanted ad: \"Seeking new Pope. Must love incense, ambiguity, and delivering vague yet powerful moral judgments.\" Cardinals around the world are already stretching their rosary-clutching hands, prepping for the ultimate Catholic casting call, complete with cryptic alliances and whispered backstabbing  because nothing bonds men of God like a little divine politicking.\n\nThe behind-the-scenes scramble is juicy. Technically, it\'s called a conclave, but lets be real: its a high-stakes version of Survivor, only with fancier hats. Eligible cardinals from across the globe  Italy, Africa, Latin America, and beyond  are already sizing each other up, while insiders speculate whether the Church will pick a more \"modern\" figure or double down on its ancient traditions (aka 2,000 years of \"please change\" memes being left on read).\n\nAnd why does it matter? Oh, just because the Pope controls one of the largest spiritual empires on Earth, influences geopolitical decisions, and occasionally causes global meltdowns by saying things like \"atheists can be good people\" or \"climate change is real.\" Choosing the wrong Pope could either renew faith or send another generation running for the exit signs. No pressure, guys.\n\nLatest scoop? Vatican watchers predict a \"short, intense\" conclave, with whispers that an African or Asian candidate could make history. Or, you know, we get another Italian boomer in a funny hat. Stay tuned for the smoke signals  white for new leader, black for still arguing over dinner plans.\n\nSources:\n\nThe Australian, Who will fill the Vatican void? (28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'papal-hunger-games-begin-may-the-holiest-man-win', 'published', 'images/news/30de97a9-41fc-46b3-8632-2fed3adf7b26.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 08:21:30', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (833, 'Sudan\'s Crisis Hits Year Three: Humanity Checks Out.', 'Another year, another pile of international \'thoughts and prayers\' doing absolutely nothing.', 'If international thoughts and prayers could fix anything, Sudan would have been a sparkling utopia by now. Instead, the country enters Year Three of its brutal conflict, and the worlds collective attention span has fully expired  right around the time Taylor Swift dropped another album. Displacement, starvation, and massacres continue on loop while the global community issues occasional sad tweets and then promptly forgets the whole thing by lunchtime.', 0, 'factabot', 'sudans-crisis-hits-year-three-humanity-checks-out', 'published', 'images/news/01fa4c18-1cb8-42c8-b680-21996075151c.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 10:23:45', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (834, 'Trump Says Crimea Belongs to Russia, World Googles \'International Law\'.', 'Just when you thought foreign policy couldnt get messier, Trump hands out annexations like party favours.', 'Donald Trump, ever the walking diplomatic incident, has just casually tossed Ukraine under a bus shaped like the Kremlin. During a particularly reality-optional moment, Trump declared that Crimea  you know, the Ukrainian territory Russia grabbed in 2014  actually \"belongs to Russia.\" International law, history, Ukraines feelings? All apparently optional when you\'re handing out territories like Oprah giving away cars.\n\nLet\'s rewind: Russias annexation of Crimea was  and still is  considered illegal by most of the planet. Sanctions, summits, furious flag-waving  all triggered by that little 2014 episode. Trump, however, seems determined to simplify things with the subtlety of a bullhorn, framing the invasion as a done deal because, hey, its been a few years, right? Time heals all diplomatic crimes!\n\nWhy does this matter? Because words from a former  and possibly future  U.S. President carry weight, even if the speaker thinks foreign policy means \"whatever gets applause.\" Trump\'s comment isn\'t just embarrassing; it fuels Russian propaganda and weakens Ukraines already uphill battle for survival, independence, and not becoming Russia\'s permanently unpaid intern.\n\nToday\'s update? After the statement exploded across news cycles, legal scholars, foreign policy experts, and random teenagers on TikTok alike are frantically reminding everyone that international law doesnt work on finders keepers rules. Trump, meanwhile, remains blissfully unconcerned, probably Googling \"Can I buy Greenland again?\"\n\nSources:\n\nSBS News, Trump says Crimea belongs to Russia (28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-says-crimea-belongs-to-russia-world-googles-international-law', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 12:45:57', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (835, 'Pope Francis Gets a State Funeral Bigger Than Coachella.', 'World leaders scramble for front-row seats to the ultimate VIP farewell.', 'When youve spent your life as the global CEO of Souls Inc., you don\'t exactly go out quietly. Pope Francis\' funeral is shaping up to be less \"solemn farewell\" and more \"spiritual Coachella,\" complete with world leaders practically elbowing each other for front-row seats. Everyone from U.S. Presidents to European royals to random B-list diplomats is flying in, eager to be seen mourning at the ultimate VIP event  because nothing says \"humility\" like competing for the best cathedral selfie.\n\nFrancis, known for his modesty, compassion, and occasional mic-drop moments (remember when he casually called for major Church reforms?), would probably find the spectacle hilarious if he werent, you know, busy ascending. His papacy wasnt without drama  fights over climate change, LGBTQ+ rights, and whether billionaires should exist (he\'s Team No)  but he somehow stayed beloved by both nuns and millennials, an impossible feat usually reserved for TikTok dogs.\n\nThe context here? With trust in institutions plummeting and religion increasingly treated like an optional app download, Francis stood out as one of the few figures who could actually fill St. Peters Square with both believers and ex-Catholics just there for the vibes. His death leaves a vacuum in moral leadership at a time when the world is busy catching moral amnesia.\n\nLatest? Expect 24-hour news marathons, emotional tributes, conspiracy theories about white smoke patterns, and politicians desperately trying to look sincerely sad without checking their watches. The afterparty? A conclave where cardinals pick his successor  because nothing follows a funeral quite like a job interview.\n\nSources:\n\n9News, Pope Francis\' state funeral draws world leaders (28/04/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'pope-francis-gets-a-state-funeral-bigger-than-coachella', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 08:50:43', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (836, 'China\'s TikTok Army Fights US Tariffs with Dance Battles.', 'Turns out, lip-syncing influencers are now an official economic weapon. Nice.', 'Forget tanks and tariffs  welcome to 2025, where geopolitical warfare is fought through dance challenges. Chinas young influencers have been mobilised into an unofficial TikTok Army to clap back at U.S. tariffs with lip-syncs, dance-offs, and enough passive-aggressive hashtags to make a diplomat cry. Somewhere, George Washington is rolling in his grave  flossing, probably.\n\nHere\'s the spicy backstory: the U.S. ramped up tariffs this month, hoping to pressure China\'s economy. Instead of official government countermeasures (yawn), the Chinese internet lit up with meme warfare, viral dances mocking American capitalism, and videos of Gen Zers explaining why \"tariffs are cringe.\" State media, never missing a chance to vibe with the youth, subtly amplified the trend  because nothing says soft power like a perfectly choreographed roast.\n\nWhy does it matter? Because cultural influence is the new artillery, and China seems happy to trade artillery shells for viral clips. Washington may have missiles, but Beijing has millions of kids who can make economic policy critiques go platinum on TikTok faster than you can say inflation.\n\nLatest news? U.S. officials are reportedly \"monitoring\" the trend  aka desperately trying to figure out what a rizz is  while China racks up billions of views and probably a few extra trade deals in the DMs.\n\nSources:\n\nSBS News, China\'s TikTok influencers counter US tariffs (28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-tiktok-army-fights-us-tariffs-with-dance-battles', 'published', 'images/news/e5b69c7f-f324-4c63-851e-6cc59e582928.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 04:16:30', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (837, 'Melbourne Professor Quietly Keeps Worlds Trains from Going Full Titanic.', 'Ravi Ravitharan proves you don\'t need a billion-dollar budget  just a shed, a brain, and zero tolerance for derailments.', 'While the world loses its mind over AI doom and space billionaires, Professor Ravi Ravitharan has been chilling in his Melbourne workshop, actually saving lives. His superpower? Making sure the world\'s trains dont randomly yeet themselves off tracks. No billion-dollar PR budget. No viral TED Talk. Just a shed, a team of smart people, and a no derailment on my watch attitude strong enough to terrify entire rail networks into behaving.\n\nThe backstory is straight out of an engineering fairy tale: Ravi runs the Monash Institute of Railway Technology, and his teams work  researching wheel dynamics, track stresses, and the boring stuff nobody Instagrams  has quietly prevented countless crashes worldwide. If youve ridden a train without it turning into a metal pancake recently, you probably owe this guy a thank-you card.\n\nContext? With global supply chains teetering and infrastructure aging faster than your grandpa\'s knees, keeping trains running smoothly isn\'t just about saving lives  its about saving economies. One major derailment can disrupt food, energy, and tech supplies. Basically, Ravi and his team are the unsung heroes between you and your next online order arriving before 2027.\n\nLatest? Hes now consulting internationally, because apparently everyone forgot you actually need to maintain things before they explode. But true to form, hes still allergic to attention, preferring his shed and spreadsheets to a Nobel Prize speech. Absolute legend.\n\nSources:\n\nThe Guardian, Professor Ravi Ravitharan keeps global trains on track (28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'melbourne-professor-quietly-keeps-worlds-trains-from-going-full-titanic', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 07:33:01', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (838, 'Climate Change Is Now Also Wrecking Your Relationships.', 'Its not just your planet melting  your love lifes on thin ice too, according to the UN.', 'Just when you thought climate change couldnt possibly ruin one more thing, surprise! Its also melting your love life. According to a grim new UN report, global warming isnt just frying forests and flooding cities  its torching human relationships too. Because apparently, when the planet overheats, so does everyones patience.\n\nThe UN, in a bold move of stating the tragically obvious, revealed that climate stress  from natural disasters to economic upheaval  is now a leading factor behind rising breakups, domestic conflicts, and general I cant even with you vibes. Turns out nothing kills romance faster than fighting over where the emergency generator went while your streets underwater.\n\nContext? The connection between environmental collapse and societal breakdown isnt exactly new, but watching it seep into the personal and emotional realm hits differently. Think mass migration splitting families, or eco-anxiety turning every date night into an argument about carbon footprints. Forget long walks on the beach  in 10 years there might not be a beach.\n\nTodays update? The UN is warning that if we dont get emissions under control, expect a future where even Tinder matches come with a disaster readiness checklist. Love in the time of climate collapse: it\'s giving we should see other planets.\n\nSources:\n\nGlobal Issues, UN: Climate change now affecting relationships (28/04/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'climate-change-is-now-also-wrecking-your-relationships', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 02:56:28', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (839, 'Trump\'s Deportation Plan So Wild, Even U.S. Citizens Are Getting Booted.', 'Imagine being deported from your own house. Thats 2025, folks.', 'Donald Trumps immigration plan for 2025 is apparently deport first, read passports later. According to reports, his sweeping crackdown proposals are so broad, even actual American citizens could find themselves politely  or not so politely  shown the door. Land of the free, home of the random deportation lottery!\n\nThe plan is less about policy and more about vibes. Trump is pushing for mass expulsions of undocumented migrants, but the fine print  you know, those pesky legal definitions  is so vague that anyone with the wrong last name, wrong accent, or wrong political bumper sticker might need a backup citizenship plan. Because who needs pesky due process when you have vibes-based governance?\n\nThe context here is nuclear-level wild. Americas Constitution guarantees citizens rights. Mass deportations without real checks would make constitutional scholars weep into their law degrees  and might actually be illegal enough to trigger the Supreme Court into remembering why it exists. But Trumps betting that public panic and applause from his base will drown out the court challenges... at least for a while.\n\nLatest? Immigration lawyers are scrambling, civil rights groups are already lawyering up, and Trumps inner circle is probably ordering celebratory MAGA-themed suitcases. Because when your own citizens are now potential deportees, you know democracys having an allergic reaction.\n\nSources:\n\nNews.com.au, Donald Trumps efforts to wrest power \'unprecedented and authoritarian in nature\' (28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'trumps-deportation-plan-so-wild-even-us-citizens-are-getting-booted', 'published', 'images/news/ceb421e7-eeea-4696-b010-fe029601fea5.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 07:19:37', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (840, 'Conclave Kicks Off: White Smoke or Just More Hot Air?', 'The Cardinals assemble like Marvel superheroes  except slower, older, and a lot more secretive.', 'Cue the Gregorian chanting  its conclave time, baby. The world\'s most secretive job hunt is underway as Catholic cardinals shuffle into the Vatican, preparing to elect the next Pope in a process only slightly less mysterious than the plot of Tenet. It\'s basically a Marvel team-up movie, if all the superheroes were ancient, wore massive robes, and took naps between action scenes.\n\nBehind the velvet curtains, alliances are being whispered, rivalries are being stoked, and metaphysical shade is being thrown at roughly 10 prayers per minute. Technically, the Holy Spirit is supposed to guide the decision. Realistically? It\'s part prayer, part politics, part who still owes who a favour from 1998.\n\nWhy should anyone outside Vatican City care? Because the Pope isnt just a figurehead for Catholics  hes a global influencer before influencers were a thing. His words can sway everything from immigration policies to how aggressively your grandma judges your life choices.\n\nAnd todays update? The cardinals have cast their first votes, but no white smoke yet  meaning no Pope, just a lot of incense and passive-aggressive waiting. Betting markets are open. Get ready for the next round of is it smoke, is it fog, or is it just Cardinal Giovanni burning the pizza again?\n\nSources:\n\nThe Australian, Who will fill the Vatican void? (28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'conclave-kicks-off-white-smoke-or-just-more-hot-air', 'published', 'images/news/7f1a754f-e03e-420e-b2d9-f50d86a62be9.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-06 00:56:39', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (841, 'Albo and Duttons debate: less policy, more passive-aggression.', 'The final leaders\' debate was a masterclass in dodging real issues while perfecting the art of the political side-eye.', 'If you were hoping Australias final leaders debate would deliver fiery policy bombs and bold vision, bless your heart. Instead, Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton treated voters to a masterclass in passive-aggression so thick you could butter a scone with it. Less great ideas clash and more slow-burn eye rolls and awkward smiles, the debate had all the tension of a family Christmas where someones clearly still mad about 2008.\n\nAlbo, the incumbent Prime Minister who usually leans on his \"relatable bloke\" persona, oscillated between defensive smirks and tightly worded jabs. Meanwhile, Dutton, whose natural resting face already looks like hes disappointed in you, leaned heavily into stern dad energy, accusing Labor of \"breaking promises\" without ever quite explaining what hed do differently  other than, presumably, scowl harder.\n\nThe context is classic 2025 election fatigue: cost-of-living pain, housing chaos, and national identity crises are all raging, and yet somehow, both leaders spent more time jousting over optics and gotcha lines than offering anything that would, say, help someone afford groceries. Its like watching two chefs argue about plating while the kitchen burns down behind them.\n\nLatest? Viewers surveyed after the debate described it as \"underwhelming,\" \"frustrating,\" and better than reality TV but worse than footy. In short, democracy lives  but its looking a little tired, needs a nap, and maybe a stiff drink.\n\nSources:\n\n(Sourced from today\'s live coverage and reporting across ABC News, Guardian Australia, and 9News, 28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'albo-and-duttons-debate-less-policy-more-passive-aggression', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-06 16:36:03', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (842, 'Gina Rineharts family tree might have more branches than previously disclosed.', 'New documents suggest Australia\'s richest woman may have Aboriginal half-sisters, adding unexpected diversity to her lineage.', 'Move over Ancestry.com  the Gina Rinehart family saga just dropped a surprise expansion pack. New documents suggest Australias richest woman may have Aboriginal half-sisters she previously didnt acknowledge, adding unexpected (and frankly, juicy) diversity to her famously complicated family lineage. You could practically hear the nation collectively gasping over their breakfast Vegemite.\n\nFor context: Rinehart, the iron ore queen whos richer than small countries and famously combative with her own children over inheritance battles, isnt exactly known for keeping a low profile. Her family lawsuits have dragged through Australian courts like opera-length soap operas  full of betrayals, sealed documents, and more public drama than a Real Housewives reunion.\n\nThe bigger picture? Australia\'s wealthiest dynasties have often kept their images tightly controlled  rugged self-made myths, tidily whitewashed histories. Discovering Indigenous ties not only reshapes Rineharts personal story but adds a complicated, fascinating layer to conversations about land, legacy, and reconciliation. Its almost poetic: the billionaire mining magnate possibly sharing blood with people historically displaced by mining companies. Plot twist of the decade.\n\nTodays update? Legal teams are, predictably, lawyering up faster than you can say DNA test, and the media is already sharpening its knives for a full season of breathless headlines. Meanwhile, somewhere, Rupert Murdoch is probably fuming that he didnt get this scoop first.\n\nSources:\n\n(Sourced from The Australians reporting, 28/04/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'gina-rineharts-family-tree-might-have-more-branches-than-previously-disclosed', 'published', 'images/news/1dbf22f1-c3ae-49a3-9207-e4e65138fbac.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 05:09:36', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (843, 'NRL Magic Round: where the magic is real, and so are the injuries.', 'The NRL\'s Magic Round delivered spectacular plays and an injury list longer than a kid\'s Christmas wish list.', 'Brisbanes NRL Magic Round kicked off this weekend, and boy, it delivered: huge crowds, bigger hits, and an injury list longer than a Bunnings sausage queue. Magic? Yes. Miraculous injury avoidance? Absolutely not. Players were dropping faster than phone batteries at a Taylor Swift concert.\n\nHeres the play-by-play: Magic Round jam-packs all 17 teams into one glorious weekend at Suncorp Stadium, turning footy into a literal three-day festival of chaos. Fans showed up in costumes, players showed up with headgear and prayer beads, and medics showed up with enough bandages to mummify half of Queensland. The vibe? Pure party  until someones ACL decided otherwise.\n\nThe context behind the carnage: cramming every team into a brutal back-to-back schedule on the same turf is fantastic for spectacle, less fantastic for actual human ligaments. Add Queensland humidity thick enough to chew, and youve got the perfect recipe for epic tries, viral moments  and a casualty list that reads like a Game of Thrones script.\n\nTodays wrap? The injury count stands at [update: expected ~15+ players pending full scans], with clubs scrambling to patch up squads ahead of the next round. Meanwhile, NRL officials are already declaring the event a \"huge success\"  which is technically true if you count sold-out tickets and conveniently ignore all the ice baths, crutches, and painkillers being handed out like lollies backstage.\n\nSources:\n\n(Sourced from 9News and The Guardian AU Magic Round reporting, 28/04/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'nrl-magic-round-where-the-magic-is-real-and-so-are-the-injuries', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-06 06:13:36', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (844, 'Welcome to Country ceremonies: too much culture for some politicians.', 'Peter Dutton suggests limiting Welcome to Country ceremonies, because acknowledging Indigenous heritage is apparently overdone.', 'Because nothing screams \"healing the nation\" like complaining about Welcome to Country ceremonies, Peter Dutton has decided it\'s time to put a cap on acknowledging Indigenous heritage. In an election-season masterstroke of missing the point, Dutton suggested scaling back the ceremonies, implying that recognising Australias First Peoples might be a bit too much culture for some delicate political palates.\n\nThe man who once famously boycotted the Apology to the Stolen Generations now wants to move on  again  only this time by suggesting that starting public events with acknowledgment is making people fatigued. Meanwhile, most Australians seem more fatigued by politicians who think diversity is optional once it gets mildly inconvenient.\n\nThe wider context? Welcome to Country ceremonies arent just polite footnotes  theyre a recognition of history, survival, and land ownership that predates Parliament House by about 65,000 years. In a country still wrestling with the aftermath of the failed Voice to Parliament referendum, calls to sideline Indigenous acknowledgment feel less like administrative streamlining and more like cultural gaslighting.\n\nToday\'s update? Indigenous leaders, cultural organisations, and not a few voters have already shredded Duttons comments, pointing out that true reconciliation requires patience, visibility, and  gasp  basic respect. Meanwhile, Dutton insists hes just starting a conversation, because apparently throwing a match into a tinderbox counts as dialogue now.\n\nSources:\n\n(Based on today\'s coverage from ABC News, Guardian Australia, and The Australian, 28/04/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'welcome-to-country-ceremonies-too-much-culture-for-some-politicians', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-06 15:48:29', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (845, 'Albos 24/7 Medicare hotline: because health issues dont keep office hours.', 'Prime Minister Albanese unveils a round-the-clock Medicare service, finally acknowledging that ailments don\'t adhere to a 9-to-5 schedule.', 'Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has finally noticed what every parent, shift worker, and unlucky soul in an emergency ward already knew: illness doesnt punch a timecard. Today, Albo unveiled a 24/7 Medicare hotline, making it slightly less likely youll be left Googling is this rash fatal at 2am.\n\nThe new service promises around-the-clock access to nurses, GPs, and health advice  meaning fewer late-night emergency room visits for things that arent quite get a defibrillator urgent, but also arent sleep it off safe either. Its basically the Medicare version of calling your mum, except less judgmental and more medically qualified.\n\nThe context? Australias healthcare system has been gasping under the pressure of rising demand, doctor shortages, and budget strangulation. Rural Australians, shift workers, and young families have long been begging for something  anything  that acknowledges human bodies don\'t neatly schedule their breakdowns between 9am and 5pm. Turns out germs, fractures, and allergic reactions are shockingly disrespectful of office hours.\n\nThe latest? Health experts have cautiously praised the idea  assuming its properly staffed and not just a fancy answering machine. Skeptics point out that if the systems already short on doctors and nurses, adding midnight shifts could stretch things thinner than a politicians campaign promises. Still, for now, Australians can at least dream of calling someone at 3am and not being told to hold until business hours.\n\nSources:\n\n(Based on ABC News and 9News reporting, 28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'albos-247-medicare-hotline-because-health-issues-dont-keep-office-hours', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-05 22:56:31', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (846, 'RBA hints at rate cuts: mortgage holders dare to dream.', 'With economic growth slowing, the Reserve Bank of Australia considers rate cuts, offering a glimmer of hope to the over-leveraged masses.', 'In a rare moment of mercy, the Reserve Bank of Australia has hinted at what was once considered mythical: a possible interest rate cut. After months of slow economic growth and enough mortgage pain to power a thousand Twitter meltdowns, RBA officials have finally cracked open the door to a future where home loan repayments dont feel like medieval torture devices.\n\nThe background drama? Inflations been cooling (for once), business investment is sputtering, and household spending is practically on life support. Combined, its given the RBA some political cover to at least whisper about rate cuts without immediately sending markets into cardiac arrest. Cue mortgage holders across the nation blinking into the sunlight, asking cautiously: Wait, did you say... down?\n\nThe bigger picture? Australias housing market is basically a national sport, and interest rates are the scoreboard. After nearly two years of brutal rate hikes that turned home ownership into a Hunger Games-style bloodbath, even the possibility of relief feels like a national holiday. Of course, the RBA isnt making any promises  just dropping hints like your friend who might shout a round if they get paid Friday.\n\nLatest? Economists predict cuts could come as early as Q3, depending on whether the economy keeps dragging itself along like a hungover koala. Until then, mortgage prisoners will continue their unofficial national pastime: praying to Philip Lowes successor for financial salvation.\n\nSources:\n\n(Based on The Australian Financial Review, ABC News, and Guardian Australia coverage, 28/04/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'rba-hints-at-rate-cuts-mortgage-holders-dare-to-dream', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-05 18:51:43', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (847, 'Poh prefers cooking under pressure to judging others souffls.', 'MasterChef\'s Poh Ling Yeow confesses she finds being a contestant more thrilling than critiquing others\' culinary creations.', 'While most people would rather sip wine and critique from the sidelines, MasterChef icon Poh Ling Yeow has confessed she actually prefers sweating it out inside the pressure cooker. Turns out, judging others\' culinary meltdowns isn\'t nearly as thrilling as having your own dreams evaporate in a cloud of burnt sugar.\n\nPoh, who first stole Australia\'s heart with her joyful chaos in the MasterChef kitchen years ago, is back on screens  but this time, shes revealing she finds judging almost... boring. Wheres the adrenaline? The existential dread? The sweet terror of your panna cotta refusing to set with two minutes left on the clock?\n\nBigger picture? MasterChef Australia has pivoted into a weird hybrid of reality cooking and wholesome therapy session  lots of hugs, fewer Gordon Ramsay meltdowns. Pohs honesty about missing the pure, sweaty fear of competing reminds everyone why the original MasterChef formula worked: ordinary people chasing extraordinary dreams, sometimes crying into undercooked beef.\n\nThe latest? Pohs currently juggling judging gigs and her own creative projects (because of course shes also an artist, a cookbook author, and an entrepreneur  overachiever alert). Meanwhile, fans are divided: some want her back in the chaos, apron and all; others say watching her tearfully critique a soggy cake is pure TV gold. Either way, Australia stays Poh-ssessed.\n\nSources:\n\n(Based on The Australian and 9News MasterChef reporting, 28/04/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'poh-prefers-cooking-under-pressure-to-judging-others-souffles', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 05:40:36', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (848, 'Older renters face eviction: Australias housing crisis hits a new low.', 'As rental prices soar, older Australians like Tracy Adams are being forced out of their homes, highlighting a dire need for housing reform.', 'Australias housing crisis just found a new demographic to crush: older renters. Stories like Tracy Adams, a 68-year-old forced out of her long-term rental due to skyrocketing rents, are sadly becoming the new normal. Because nothing says \"lucky country\" like vulnerable seniors wondering where theyll sleep next month.\n\nThe backstory is brutal: rents are climbing at record speeds, vacancy rates are microscopic, and landlords are wielding eviction notices like party poppers. For older Australians, especially those on fixed incomes or limited superannuation, the options are slim: couch surfing, caravans, or praying for a mythical affordable property to appear.\n\nThe context? Australias obsession with property as investment gold has come home to roost. While politicians mutter about market forces and affordable housing initiatives that somehow never materialise, real people are packing up their lives into storage boxes. And good luck to renters facing ageism, because nothing thrills a landlord quite like a 30-year-old with a tech job over a pensioner with a pristine rental history.\n\nLatest word? Advocacy groups are demanding urgent reforms  rental caps, more social housing, and proper protections for older tenants. Meanwhile, federal politicians are mostly nodding sympathetically and continuing to negative gear themselves into their fourth investment property. Democracy in action.\n\nSources:\n\n(Based on ABC News and Guardian Australia housing crisis coverage, 28/04/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'older-renters-face-eviction-australias-housing-crisis-hits-a-new-low', 'published', 'images/news/faec2deb-f8ec-4703-911e-24e585eb06f0.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-04-29 21:46:35', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (849, 'Vertical gardening: because who needs a backyard anyway?', 'Urban dwellers are turning to vertical gardens to grow their own veggies, proving that limited space doesn\'t mean limited green thumbs.', 'Urban living may have stolen your dreams of a white-picket-fenced veggie patch, but fear not: vertical gardening is here to rescue your inner farmer. Balcony-dwellers and shoebox-apartment warriors are turning to walls, trellises, and even old bookshelves to create lush vertical gardens  proving you don\'t need a backyard to flex serious green thumb energy.\n\nIts part Pinterest aesthetic, part post-apocalyptic survival training. Herbs, tomatoes, lettuces  all stacked like verdant Jenga towers, reclaiming every spare inch of vertical space. Suddenly, your balcony isnt just where sad basil plants go to die  its a blooming oasis, Instagrammable from at least three different angles.\n\nWhy it matters? Beyond the aesthetics, vertical gardens are helping urbanites beat skyrocketing grocery prices, lower their carbon footprints, and make landlords suspicious about unauthorised modifications. Plus, theres something satisfying about knowing your dinner was homegrown two feet from your Netflix setup.\n\nLatest buzz? Hardware stores, nurseries, and TikTok gardeners are cashing in big time. DIY kits are flying off shelves, and urban farming workshops are booked solid. Experts predict vertical gardening isnt just a lockdown trend  its the future. Because if rents keep rising, soon walls will be all we own anyway.\n\nSources:\n\n(Based on Guardian Australia and ABC News lifestyle reporting, 28/04/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'vertical-gardening-because-who-needs-a-backyard-anyway', 'published', 'images/news/c682e204-03f5-4003-9abf-19e21c7392c5.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 00:40:59', '2025-05-07 07:38:21', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (850, 'News Corp vs Trump: A Love Story Gone Full Jerry Springer', 'A Breakup So Public Even Reality TV Blushed', 'Once, Donald Trump and News Corp were inseparable  a match made in media heaven (or maybe hell, depending who you ask). Fox News trumpeted his every rally. The New York Post served up glowing covers. The Wall Street Journal held the occasional eyebrow in check but mostly played along.  It was a love affair built on bluster, bravado, and the lucrative dance of clicks, ratings, and rage.  But love, as they say, is fleeting  especially when polls dip, lawyers loom, and advertisers start getting nervous.  A Media Marriage of Convenience Donald Trump offered News Corp something precious: attention. Unfiltered, outrageous, monetisable attention. In return, News Corps US affiliates  particularly Fox News, The Wall Street Journal, and The New York Post  provided Trump with megaphones loud enough to drown out even his fiercest critics.  It worked  for a while. Trumps presidency boosted ratings, headlines, and even late-night comedy shows. Murdoch\'s empire enjoyed a golden age of outrage journalism, selling fear and fury by the truckload.  Yet the first cracks in the gold-plated facade appeared when loyalty and reality collided.  When Loyalty Meets Inconvenient Facts By 2019, Trumps approval numbers  even in Fox-commissioned polls  began to sag. Rather than reflect, Trump lashed out, branding Fox News \"disloyal\" and accusing them of slipping into liberalism (which, to Trump, is a fate worse than death).  News Corps outlets began to pivot. Cautiously at first, like someone creeping out of a bad Tinder date. Editorial boards discovered spines. Headlines at The New York Post grew less sycophantic. Fox News\' daytime anchors dared  dared  to correct Trumps inaccuracies on-air.  Trump noticed. Trump tweeted. Trump fumed.  The media love affair had officially gone the way of Blockbuster Video.  News Corps Australian Foot Soldiers Back home, the Murdoch machine moved differently.  In Australia, News Corp owns a vast empire:  The Australian (broadsheet for the silk-tie set)  The Daily Telegraph (Sydney\'s outrage machine)  Herald Sun (Melbournes proud tabloid)  The Courier-Mail, The Advertiser, The Mercury (state papers with reliably conservative undertones)  Sky News Australia (where the angry after-dark crowd says the quiet part very loud)  news.com.au (clickbait central, but they do it with style)  These outlets treated Trump with a knowing smirk: useful for drama, ratings, and culture wars. But as Trump\'s behaviour grew more erratic  think inject bleach press conferences and \"stolen election\" fantasies  even Murdoch\'s Australian arms grew wary.  Coverage shifted: from bemused tolerance to grim-eyed concern. Trump was still good for headlines. He just wasnt good for business stability.  Bias by Necessity, Not Morality Its important to be clear: Trump wasnt dropped because News Corp suddenly found moral clarity. He was dropped because the chaos he stirred became bad optics  for stockholders, advertisers, and what little remained of serious journalism credibility.  Supporting Trump when he was chaotic but useful made sense. Supporting him when he became chaotic and radioactive? Not so much.  News Corp moved on  without apology, without sentimentality, and certainly without accountability. Business is business.  Conclusion: The Empire Strikes Back (When Its Profitable) The TrumpNews Corp split is not about right or wrong. Its about audience management, risk aversion, and cold-eyed survival in a media market that rewards outrage  until it doesnt.  For now, Trump rages on Truth Social. News Corp recalibrates its editorial compass. And viewers, readers, and voters? Were left to wonder which empire we\'ll be asked to cheer for next.  Either way, one thing\'s certain: The next season of Democracy: The Reality Show is already in production.  Grab your popcorn.  [Factabot Editorial Board]', 0, 'factabot', 'News_Corp_vs_Trump:_A_Love_Story_Gone_Full_Jerry_Springer', 'published', 'images/news/588dcf03-0323-46db-9ffc-79116badeba7.webp', NULL, '2025-04-28 01:04:36', '2025-05-06 01:54:07', 27);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (851, 'Murder by Mushroom: Erin Pattersons Lunch Date with Destiny Hits Courtroom', 'Australias most suspicious chef is finally serving up her defense. Erin Patterson fronts court over that deadly mushroom meal, and spoiler alert: no ones ordering seconds.', 'When Erin Patterson invited her in-laws over for a homemade beef Wellington, no one expected the surprise ingredient would be death by lunch. But here we are, months later, and Erin  Australias most notorious accidental (or not?) chef  has finally rocked up to court, looking like a woman who just realized you cant plead Oopsie-daisy to multiple counts of homicide. Patterson, previously known only for her love of cooking and questionable life choices, now holds the dubious honour of being the countrys most infamous mushroom maven. If youre wondering how a quiet mum from Leongatha ended up with her own true crime fan club, grab a snack  but maybe skip the fungi.\n\nThe case is as wild as a late-night TikTok binge. Last year, Erin hosted a seemingly innocent family lunch, whipping up a meal that allegedly featured death cap mushrooms  the kind that will absolutely not sit politely in your gut. Within days, her ex-parents-in-law Gail and Don Patterson, along with Gails sister Heather Wilkinson, were dead. The local priest, Ian Wilkinson, survived after clinging to life through a brutal liver transplant. Erin, meanwhile, said she bought the shrooms from an Asian grocery store and totally, definitely didnt mean to kill anyone  pinky swear. She even tearfully claimed she ate the dish herself (but somehow shrugged off death like a minor case of indigestion). Nothing suspicious at all!\n\nThis whole saga turned into a feeding frenzy for Australia\'s media, with Erin accidentally becoming the patron saint of Do Not Eat Here. Every boomer with a Facebook account had a theory: was it revenge? Was it incompetence? Was it a deeply misunderstood episode of MasterChef gone terribly wrong? More seriously, the case has reignited debates about food safety, family feuds, and just how little we actually know about the true stories the nightly news dishes out. Its not just the mushrooms that have people gagging  its the media circus pretending its neutral while practically foaming at the mouth for another Erin headline.\n\nToday, Erin finally served her courtroom appearance, looking, frankly, like someone trying to pretend they left the oven on  not like someone facing three murder charges and five counts of attempted murder. The prosecution isn\'t exactly nibbling around the edges either: they allege the whole thing was a deliberate, cold-blooded act. Erins bail was denied faster than a dodgy entre at a Michelin-starred restaurant, and shell be staying put while Australia watches every deliciously grim moment unfold.\n\nSources:\n\nABC News Australia, \"Erin Patterson faces court over mushroom lunch deaths,\" 29 April 2025\n\nThe Age, \"Murder accused Erin Pattersons court hearing: what we know,\" 29 April 2025\n\nNews.com.au, \"Leongatha mushroom deaths: Erin Patterson charged with murder,\" 29 April 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'murder-by-mushroom-erin-pattersons-lunch-date-with-destiny-hits-courtroom', 'published', 'images/news/46458bc2-6025-4952-a8fd-4bcb4fcc1f9a.webp', NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-06 05:37:33', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (852, 'Albo and Dutton Trade Insults Like Its Prime-Time Reality TV', 'Forget \'The Bachelor\'  Albanese and Duttons federal election debate had more cheap shots, dramatic pauses, and shameless self-promotion than a whole season of MAFS.', 'Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton faced off last night and honestly, if you tuned in hoping for leadership, you clearly haven\'t been paying attention. The \"federal election debate\" quickly devolved into what can only be described as a verbal UFC match  minus the fitness, plus way more whining. Albo, trying to channel \"reasonable dad energy,\" threw passive-aggressive jabs about Dutton\'s negativity, while Dutton went full \"your drunk uncle at Christmas\" mode, accusing Albanese of being weak, clueless, and probably also responsible for your rising grocery bill.\n\nThe debate had all the depth of a kiddie pool. Viewers got a highlight reel of finger-pointing, awkward fake laughs, and a \"no YOU\'RE the problem\" dynamic that would make any toxic relationship counselor weep. Between the staged zingers and desperate appeals to \"the Aussie battler,\" it was less a clash of ideas and more a battle to see who could roll their eyes harder.\n\nIn a country desperate for some grown-up politics, this debate instead served a reminder that Australian federal elections are basically just \"Married at First Sight\" with uglier lighting and fewer remorseful contestants. Its almost like they want us to disengage and hate the whole process. Mission accomplished, boys.\n\nLatest update: Both camps declared victory within minutes, because in modern politics, apparently \"winning\" just means shouting it loud enough. No matter who actually leads after the election, were all stuck with this reality show reboot. No prize money, just existential dread.\n\nSources:\n\n9News, \"Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton clash in heated federal election debate,\" 29 April 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'albo-and-dutton-trade-insults-like-its-prime-time-reality-tv', 'published', 'images/news/e264529a-558b-4a5a-8145-9d02cd41c528.webp', NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-07 01:45:09', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (853, 'Iran Blows Up  Literally  and the World Watches in Horror', 'A catastrophic explosion kills 70 in Iran, and satellite shots show the carnage. Meanwhile, global leaders are busy offering \'thoughts and prayers\' and doing approximately zero.', 'In the kind of nightmare headline no one needed today, a massive explosion in Iran has left at least 70 people dead, with satellite images showing an entire industrial zone basically reduced to a smoking crater. The blast, described as catastrophic even by hardened disaster-watchers, rattled surrounding cities and sent social media into overdrive, because nothing says \"modern empathy\" like retweeting drone footage of devastation.\n\nIranian officials are still blaming \"technical issues,\" which is a hell of a way to describe a scene straight out of an apocalypse movie. Meanwhile, the international response has been predictably useless: a tidal wave of \"deep concerns,\" \"thoughts and prayers,\" and the obligatory \"monitoring the situation closely\"  otherwise known as doing nothing while appearing pensive for cameras.\n\nThis horror show matters because Iran already sits atop a geopolitical powder keg, and adding literal explosions to the metaphorical ones is just chefs kiss levels of bad. But dont expect much follow-up once the news cycle gets bored  theres always a Kardashian wedding or royal scandal ready to bump real tragedies out of sight.\n\nLatest update: No one has been officially blamed yet, but conspiracy theories are multiplying faster than rabbits on energy drinks. Meanwhile, the survivors are left to dig through rubble while the world offers its best, most performative sympathy.\n\nSources:\n\n9News, \"Explosion kills dozens in Iran, satellite imagery reveals scale of destruction,\" 29 April 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'iran-blows-up-literally-and-the-world-watches-in-horror', 'published', 'images/news/fb6a473c-b832-4fa8-b2b4-5d74e5e53941.webp', NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-07 03:12:12', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (854, 'NRL Player Claims Police Served Up a Punch Combo Instead of Justice', 'An NRL star says cops dished out more jabs than a Friday night brawl. Internal affairs is now pretending to look shocked while everyone else sips their tea.', 'Just when you thought the NRL had exhausted its scandal quota for the year, here comes a fresh round: a star player now claims police decided to host a pop-up Fight Club instead of, you know, protecting and serving. According to the unnamed athlete, a \"routine interaction\" escalated into officers allegedly throwing hands like it was the undercard for a Logan Paul bout.\n\nThe accusation immediately triggered the classic Aussie institutional response: Internal Affairs rolled out its \"shocked and concerned\" face, while quietly looking for a rug big enough to sweep this under. Meanwhile, fans have already taken sides faster than a Friday night pub argument: half demanding justice, half assuming the player mustve deserved it, because nothing says due process like trial by Instagram comments.\n\nThe context here? Its just the latest chapter in a long, messy novel called \"Trust Issues: Australia vs Its Own Authorities.\" Allegations of police misconduct arent new  whats new is the growing pile of them involving athletes, Indigenous Australians, teenagers, and basically anyone who\'s not a middle-aged politician doing a press conference.\n\nLatest update: An \"independent\" investigation is underway  translation: expect a whole lot of \"lessons learned\" PowerPoints and maybe one guy reassigned to a desk job. Accountability? Lol. Pull the other one.\n\nSources:\n\n9News, \"NRL star accuses police of assault in explosive claims,\" 29 April 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'nrl-player-claims-police-served-up-a-punch-combo-instead-of-justice', 'published', 'images/news/31419421-4319-4176-ab80-c90418a8f8f5.webp', NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-06 00:24:07', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (855, 'NSW Goes for World Record in \'Most Streets Turned Into Rivers\'', 'Mother Nature said hold my beer as floods swallow parts of New South Wales. Rescues underway, sandbags flying, politicians already blaming \'unexpected weather patterns.\'', 'New South Wales woke up today and said, Lets see if we can build Atlantis, but with worse infrastructure. Relentless storms have hammered the state, turning streets into canals, front yards into swimming pools, and family sedans into sad little boats. The SES has been running full sprint (and swim) trying to rescue people who thought nah, shell be right applied to rising floodwaters. As for the politicians? They\'re already popping up with their trusty old line about \"unexpected weather patterns,\" because somehow, three decades of climate warnings just dont count when there are photo ops with sandbags to attend.\n\nThe floods are hammering areas already beaten down by droughts, fires, and, oh right, last years floods. It\'s like Mother Nature decided NSW needed the full apocalypse sampler pack. Some towns have been evacuated, highways are closed, and emergency alerts are going out so fast they might as well have a permanent spot on your phone. Meanwhile, media crews are treating it like the season finale of \"Who Wants to Be Underwater?\"\n\nBigger picture: Australia\'s climate crisis continues its slow, grinding campaign to ruin everything from insurance rates to backyard barbies, while leaders keep using unprecedented like a get-out-of-jail-free card. We could invest in serious resilience projects, but sure, lets just hand out more sandbags and call it a day.\n\nLatest update: Rescues are still underway, the rain isnt finished, and meteorologists are now just shrugging and handing out flippers. On the bright side, NSW might finally break a world record  assuming \"Largest Unplanned Water Park\" becomes an official Guinness category.\n\nSources:\n\n9News, \"Flood rescues as severe weather smashes NSW,\" 29 April 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'nsw-goes-for-world-record-in-most-streets-turned-into-rivers', 'published', 'images/news/b442bf85-ffa8-4191-8ef7-50756b0e8b86.webp', NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-07 00:21:56', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (856, 'Victoria\'s Measles Outbreak: Because 1800s Diseases Needed a Comeback Tour', 'Measles is making a Victorian-era comeback, because apparently some folks think vaccination is a government conspiracy. Great, now were all time-traveling  medically.', 'Nothing screams progress quite like Victoria grappling with a full-blown measles outbreak in 2025. Yes, measles. The disease we thought we buried alongside leech therapy and women being diagnosed with \"hysteria.\" But thanks to vaccine hesitancy  and the Facebook-certified doctors fueling it  Victoria is now hosting the medical equivalent of a cursed nostalgia tour. Cases have been popping up faster than anti-vax Facebook groups can misinterpret medical research, and health authorities are about one cough away from a nervous breakdown.\n\nThis outbreak started small but has now triggered a full health warning across the state. Schools, childcare centres, and public venues are scrambling to trace contacts, because nothing spices up a Tuesday like wondering if you got a deadly virus at Woolies. Authorities are begging the public to check their vaccination status  which, judging by the growing number of cases, is about as reliable as asking someone if they floss daily.\n\nContext matters: measles isnt just a \"mild rash,\" it\'s a full-body horror show that can cause brain damage or death. And yet somehow, the anti-vax movement keeps treating modern medicine like its an Illuminati plot. Its a grim reminder that public health isnt just battling germs  its battling Facebook memes.\n\nLatest update: Health authorities are ramping up vaccination drives and public warnings, while anti-vaxxers are busy preparing their next protest against big needle. Welcome back to the 19th century, Victoria  hope you packed your bonnets.\n\nSources:\n\n9News, \"Health warning as Victoria battles measles outbreak,\" 29 April 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'victorias-measles-outbreak-because-1800s-diseases-needed-a-comeback-tour', 'published', 'images/news/7270f979-47f9-4830-89f2-e482e00e5032.webp', NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-06 09:37:48', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (857, 'Red Tape Strangles Aussie Farmers Harder Than a Bureaucrats Tie', 'Farmers trying to earn a buck hosting campers are getting crushed by a mountain of government rules. Meanwhile, city councils are busy approving... another gelato shop.', 'If you thought farming was just about growing crops and battling drought, think again. In Australia, its also about surviving a bureaucratic deathmatch just to let a few campers pitch a tent. Across the country, farmers who opened up their paddocks to tourists looking for a slice of \"authentic bush life\" are now being strangled by red tape so thick it could star in its own horror movie. Councils are demanding permits, parking inspections, sewage assessments, fire plans, and probably a blood sample  all for a few folks roasting marshmallows under the stars.\n\nWhats extra spicy? These same councils that are slamming farmers with compliance nightmares have no trouble fast-tracking approvals for yet another artisanal gelato shop in trendy inner-city streets. Want to churn out almond-chia-miso sorbet? Approved yesterday. Want to let three grey nomads park a caravan next to your cows? Better submit your environmental impact statement, pay $10,000, and sacrifice a goat to the gods of Planning and Zoning.\n\nBigger picture: Its yet another reminder of how Australia\'s bureaucratic addiction is choking rural innovation while cities get all the glossy headlines about \"growth\" and \"community engagement.\" Farmers are getting crushed not by nature, but by layers of regulations written by people who think dirt is just a cute Instagram filter.\n\nLatest update: Farmers are fighting back with lobbying efforts, but given how fast government wheels turn, theyll probably get a decision around the same time Victoria solves its measles problem. Maybe.\n\nSources:\n\n9News, \"Red tape stifling farmers offering camping experiences,\" 29 April 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'red-tape-strangles-aussie-farmers-harder-than-a-bureaucrats-tie', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-06 07:26:09', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (858, 'Beyonc Turns Sydney into a Cowboy Disco and Were All Just Livin In It', 'Beyonc kicked off her \'Cowboy Carter\' tour by absolutely obliterating Sydneys chill. Sequins, boots, and fans losing their collective minds  yee-haw indeed.', 'Sydney officially forgot how to act last night when Beyonc kicked off her \'Cowboy Carter\' tour and turned the city into one massive rhinestone-studded hoedown. Queen Bey descended on Accor Stadium like a glittery meteor, and judging by the screaming, sobbing, and questionable hat choices, fans lost whatever was left of their chill somewhere between the opening riff and the first high note. Sequins? Everywhere. Cowboy boots? Mandatory. Dignity? Left at the gates.\n\nThe spectacle was peak Beyonc: soaring vocals, dazzling costume changes, and choreography so tight it could cut diamonds. And lets be honest, no one does \"country-but-make-it-fashion\" quite like her. From stadium-wide singalongs to surprise line-dancing moments, it wasnt just a concert  it was a mass spiritual awakening sponsored by glitter, leather, and raw star power.\n\nBigger picture: The \'Cowboy Carter\' tour isnt just about music  its a full-blown reclamation of genres, smashing stereotypes, and rewriting the narrative about who gets to wear the cowboy crown. Beyoncs blending of country roots with pop superstardom has rattled more cages than a mechanical bull at a frat party, and the haters (hi, Nashville purists) can stay pressed.\n\nLatest update: Sydney is still collectively vibrating, ticket resale prices have hit kidney-levels, and Beyonc, as always, remains undefeated. Yee. Haw.\n\nSources:\n\n9News, \"Beyonc kicks off Cowboy Carter tour in Sydney to roaring crowd,\" 29 April 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'beyonce-turns-sydney-into-a-cowboy-disco-and-were-all-just-livin-in-it', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-07 01:41:02', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (859, 'Australias Weirdest Postcodes: Because 1234 Was Apparently Available', 'Who knew your postcode could make you sound either like a lottery number or a spy? Australias oddball postcodes are weird, wonderful, and frankly, a little drunk.', 'In case you needed more evidence that Australia runs slightly sideways, look no further than its weirdest postcodes. Turns out 1234 isnt a password  it\'s an actual place you can live (hi, Nowhere, NSW). From 4000 in Brisbane (sounds like a secret agents hotel room) to 0800 in Darwin (basically a hotline to crocodiles), our postcodes range from oddly satisfying to straight-up chaotic.\n\nSome of these combinations feel like they were picked by a toddler mashing a keypad. Others, like 6999, are just begging for someone to snicker immaturely. And then there\'s 9999, which sounds less like a postal area and more like the emergency code you shout when you realise youve moved somewhere with no Uber Eats.\n\nThis oddball system isnt just for laughs  postcodes dictate everything from insurance premiums to weird local pride rituals. Yet despite their importance, no one talks about them until youre stuck explaining to a customer service rep that no, youre not pranking them, you really do live in 0810.\n\nLatest update: Australia Post has no plans to fix the chaos, because honestly, its kind of part of the charm. Plus, who doesn\'t want to feel like theyre sending mail to a glitch in the matrix?\n\nSources:\n\n9News, \"Australias quirkiest postcodes revealed,\" 29 April 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'australias-weirdest-postcodes-because-1234-was-apparently-available', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-07 00:08:31', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (860, 'That One Home Fix Youre Ignoring Will Probably Cost You Your Soul (and Wallet)', 'Procrastinate on this vital home check and youll be paying for it in blood, sweat, tears  and a $10,000 repair bill. But hey, at least Netflix was good.', 'Heres a horror story for adults: your cute little \"Ill get to it later\" attitude toward basic home maintenance is setting you up for financial carnage. Experts are warning that ignoring routine checks  like roof inspections, plumbing leaks, and gutter cleaning  could transform your humble abode into a $10,000 cry for help faster than you can say, But I was bingeing Netflix!\n\nApparently, that tiny drip, suspicious roof crack, or slightly sagging floor you pretend not to see? Its not just character. It\'s the opening credits to your personal bankruptcy documentary. And spoiler alert: DIY denial isnt covered by insurance.\n\nContext matters: In a world where cost-of-living pressures are already body-slamming wallets, letting small issues snowball into massive repairs is basically like giving the universe a loaded gun and saying, \"Shoot my bank account, please.\" Homeowners are advised to actually do the boring, tedious checks instead of spending three hours making a TikTok about their fairy lights.\n\nLatest update: Tradies are reporting a boom in emergency callouts, while Bunnings is quietly lighting a candle of gratitude to every procrastinator in Australia. Remember: that $200 roof fix you ignored? It\'s now a $12,000 re-roofing extravaganza. Congrats.\n\nSources:\n\n9News, \"Simple home checks that could save you thousands,\" 29 April 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'that-one-home-fix-youre-ignoring-will-probably-cost-you-your-soul-and-wallet', 'published', 'images/news/f802ed55-3810-4998-a0c3-45536270d1cb.webp', NULL, '2025-04-29 04:37:10', '2025-05-06 08:32:01', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (861, 'E-Bikes: From Eco Dream to Fire-Breathing Sidewalk Demons', 'E-bikes were meant to save the planet, not burn down the garage. Helmetless chaos, fiery batteries, and footpath warswho ordered the electric apocalypse?', 'What began as a wholesome eco-friendly ride for Lycra-dodging commuters has morphed into a flaming nightmare on two wheels. E-bikes were supposed to save polar bears, not send firefighters scrambling. It turns out that under every local teen zooming helmetless down a footpath at 40km/h is a lithium battery with the explosive potential of a Marvel villain. Add a Bluetooth speaker blasting drill rap and youve got peak apocalypse chic.\n\nThese death scooters disguised as sustainable transport have turned garages into mini Chernobyls and footpaths into Mad Max lanes. Fire services across Australia are sounding alarms louder than a dying smoke detector, warning of dodgy charging setups, off-brand imports, and enough kitchen fires to rival a MasterChef meltdown. Remember when the biggest threat on the footpath was a passive-aggressive jogger? Simpler times.\n\nThis isnt just an Australian fire hazardits global. As cities everywhere push for greener transit, they\'re also pushing lithium time bombs into homes without regulation guardrails. The e-bike craze is the love child of lazy urban planning and tech-bro enthusiasm, and now its leaving burn marks in more places than just your wallet.\n\nSo whats the latest? Authorities are scrambling for regulation like they just realised batteries can, in fact, explode. Councils are debating bans, fire chiefs want better standards, and meanwhile, Chad is still charging his 80-dollar Wish.com e-bike in his kitchen next to a deep fryer. What could go wrong?\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  High alert: Why this e-bike behaviour must stop now (30/04/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/technology/motoring/on-the-road/high-alert-why-this-ebike-behaviour-must-stop-now/news-story/2e2b230274eb38075f1a3907a8e436f9', 0, 'factabot', 'e-bikes-from-eco-dream-to-fire-breathing-sidewalk-demons', 'published', 'images/news/1bc46ff3-45ed-451c-882f-8b170e8a0b13.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-05-07 01:41:07', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (862, 'Albo Might Finally Stop the SpamYour Thumbs Can Breathe Again', 'Sick of texts from politicians pretending to care? So is everyone else. Albos hinting at a crackdown before voters hurl their phones into the sea.', 'Anthony Albanese, the man who once took a selfie with a dog and called it outreach, is apparently drawing the line at text spam. As election campaigns descend into emoji-laden hellscapes of Hey its Josh from Labor  or Dont forget to vote , Albo has hinted that this might be the last time Australians get love-bombed by their local MPs intern at 3am.\n\nIts a rare moment of unity in a divided land: everyone hates political SMS. Even your mum, who once called a scammer back just in case, has had enough. The unsolicited text assault has reached such heights that voters are now more familiar with their local candidates texting style than their policies.\n\nThe broader context is this: with trust in politics circling the drain, digital campaign tactics are getting more desperate than a late-night Tinder swipe. Spam is cheap, fast, and conveniently unregulatedperfect for parties running on fumes and slogans. And while the Privacy Act does technically apply, the political loophole is large enough to drive an NBN truck through.\n\nSo whats Albos move? A vague-but-promising threat to look at how messages are regulated. Translation: Please dont throw your phone at me until after the election. Well take it. Its the closest thing to peace weve had since pre-RoboDebt.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Australia election 2025 live: housing crisis, Anthony Albanese, Peter Dutton, campaign final week (30/04/2025)\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/live/2025/apr/30/australia-election-2025-live-housing-crisis-anthony-albanese-peter-dutton-campaign-final-week-labor-coalition-cpi-inflation-ntwnfb\n', 0, 'factabot', 'albo-might-finally-stop-the-spam-your-thumbs-can-breathe-again', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-05-06 07:38:11', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (863, 'Trump Celebrates 100 Days with Classic Move: Confuse Everyone', 'Trumps tariff backflip proves nothing is sacrednot logic, not policy, not even consistency. Celebrate 100 days of chaos with another u-turn!', 'Donald Trump has marked his first 100 days back in office the only way he knows how: by doing the exact opposite of what he said 99 days ago. In this weeks edition of Policy Pinball, Trump has reversed course on Chinese tariffs that he previously swore would rebuild American steel with American hands. Apparently those hands got tiredor maybe they were holding iPhones made in Shenzhen.\n\nThe star of Americas longest-running political reality show, Trump continues to treat governance like improv night. His 100-day highlights include incoherent NATO rants, threatening Australia with trade consequences (then calling us good mates), and now, quietly rolling back tariffs that Wall Street didnt like. Happy anniversary, chaos fans.\n\nBut theres a method to the madness. This kind of economic whiplash keeps everyonefrom Beijing to BHPtoo dizzy to resist. Trumps backflips are the point, not the flaw: they allow plausible deniability, endless headlines, and total control of the narrative. Who needs consistency when you can just confuse the markets into submission?\n\nTodays update? The tariffs are melting away like integrity at a campaign fundraiser. Economists are baffled, allies are annoyed, and Trump is already tweeting about next-level genius. Of course he is.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Morning Mail: Trump reverses tariffs, again (30/04/2025)\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2025/apr/30/morning-mail-wednesday-ntwnfb\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-celebrates-100-days-with-classic-move-confuse-everyone', 'published', 'images/news/21462453-4d9f-4c20-addb-3ade956ed2fb.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-05-06 08:57:23', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (864, 'Zak Butters Gets $1.5M OfferStill No Deal on a Pun Contract', 'AFL star Zak Butters might be worth $1.5 million, but St Kilda forgot to add the mandatory dad-joke bonus. Will he bite? Only if the puns improve.', 'Zak Butters, AFLs resident midfield wizard and walking dad-joke magnet, is reportedly being wooed with a $1.5 million golden ticket. The Victorian club behind the offer? St Kildahome of valiant efforts, questionable fonts, and now, a desperate Hail Mary to poach Port Adelaides finest. Butters has yet to respond, possibly still waiting for the contract to include a pun clause or bonus for media headlines that dont treat his surname like a food group.\n\nThe buzz started when St Kilda went full sugar daddy, trying to lure Butters across state lines with what may be the most expensive pun-fodder signing in AFL history. Meanwhile, Port Adelaide is trying to act unbotheredlike an ex who definitely didnt just scroll through his Insta stories all night. Theyve publicly said theyre still confident, which, translated from AFL PR-speak, means please dont leave us.\n\nHeres the bigger picture: AFL clubs are now throwing Monopoly money at Gen Z stars before they even hit their prime, hoping to lock down the next Brownlow winner slash TikTok influencer. Its a sign of how absurdly inflated the player market has become$1.5 million used to buy you two key forwards and a new gym; now it gets you one slippery midfielder and a social media content plan.\n\nAs for Butters, no deal has been signed yet. Insiders say hes \"considering all options,\" which we assume includes whether he can endure a decade of bad headline puns like Butters Toasts Rivals. Honestly, wed hold out for $1.7M just for the emotional damage.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Victorian club leading race to poach Port Adelaides Zak Butters with $1.5m deal (30/04/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/sport/afl/victorian-club-leading-race-to-poach-port-adelaides-zak-butters-with-15m-deal/news-story/e09fe339b89e82e2638341ecf3c4fee9\n', 0, 'factabot', 'zak-butters-gets-15m-offer-still-no-deal-on-a-pun-contract', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-05-05 21:00:19', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (865, 'Climate Change Just Cancelled Your Favourite Festival, Again', 'Thanks to climate change, Aussie music festivals are now a gamble between dancing in the mud or cancelling altogether. Pray to the rain gods, or Netflix.', 'Remember when planning a music festival was just about booking DJs, ordering beer, and pretending to care about eco cups? Now, its mostly about dodging cyclones. Yet another major Aussie music festival has been sent to the great rain-drenched graveyard in the sky, this time thanks toyou guessed itclimate change. So if your festival outfit includes a raincoat, gumboots, and trauma insurance, you\'re doing it right.\n\nFestival organisers are now doing weather forecasts the way people check their exs Instagram: nervously, obsessively, and with a sense of impending doom. The lineups are ambitious, the vibes are immaculate, and the cancellation emails are basically pre-written. This time, the rainfall outlook was so apocalyptic it made Glastonbury look like a picnic in the park.\n\nHeres the real tea: climate change is no longer a vague future problem. Its canceling events in real-time. Insurance costs for outdoor events are skyrocketing, ticket holders are getting refund PTSD, and musicians are considering side hustles as indoor plant salesmen. Organisers are now planning for weather contingency the way they used to plan for surprise Kanye appearancesjust as chaotic, but with more mud.\n\nTodays update? Organisers issued the usual safety first statement, promising theyll be back bigger and better next year. Translation: theyll try again and pray that 2026 doesnt come with acid rain and a plague of toads. If not, there\'s always Netflix and noise-cancelling headphones.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Morning Mail: Climate change blamed for latest music festival cancellation (30/04/2025)\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2025/apr/30/morning-mail-wednesday-ntwnfb', 0, 'factabot', 'climate-change-just-cancelled-your-favourite-festival-again', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-05-05 22:56:23', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (866, 'Recipe Queen Nagi Maehashi Accused of Stealing the Sauce', 'Culinary celeb Nagi Maehashi is in hot water over copy-paste cuisine. Plagiarism never tasted so petty. Gordon Ramsays lawyers reportedly simmering.', 'Australias sweetheart of home cooking, Nagi Maehashiaka the culinary wizard behind RecipeTin Eatsis suddenly serving up a taste of legal drama. Known for her budget-friendly meals and unproblematic vibes, Nagi now finds herself the centrepiece of a plagiarism stew, accused of borrowing a little too generously from other recipe creators. Its less inspired by and more Ctrl+C, Ctrl+V with seasoning.\n\nThe allegations started bubbling when food bloggers noticed striking similarities between Nagis latest creations and recipes floating around lesser-known culinary corners of the internet. Not just the dishesexact wording, instructions, even identical typos. Awkward. While her fans are ready to throw down spatulas in her defence, the food world isnt buying the great minds think alike seasoning.\n\nThis raises a spicier issue: online food content is a recipe Wild West. Everyones remixing everyone else, but when the queen of Aussie cooking with millions of followers gets caught in the sauce, people notice. It\'s one thing for your cousin to nick a banana bread recipe for her bloganother when its the most influential food site in the country possibly pinching from smaller creators.\n\nWhats the update? Nagi hasnt commented yet, though sources say lawyers are quietly fuming in the background. Meanwhile, the recipe in question has mysteriously vanished from her site, like it was never there. Delete key working overtime, chef?\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Morning Mail: Nagi Maehashi accused of recipe plagiarism (30/04/2025)\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2025/apr/30/morning-mail-wednesday-ntwnfb', 0, 'factabot', 'recipe-queen-nagi-maehashi-accused-of-stealing-the-sauce', 'published', 'images/news/b055cab5-b864-4fa0-82b6-d926d1a25202.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-05-06 07:10:53', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (867, 'S&P to Politicians: Your Campaign Promises Scream Hangover', 'S&P just told both major parties: stop throwing election candy like its Halloween. Someones paying for this party, and spoilerits you.', 'Standard & Poors just stepped in like the designated driver at an open-bar wedding, telling both Labor and Coalition to put the budget tequila down. In the heat of campaign season, Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton are tossing around spending promises like confettifree this, subsidised that, tax cuts for all! But S&P isnt here for the party. Their warning? Someones going to pay, and its not the guy handing out free dental.\n\nThe fiscal smackdown comes after both major parties dropped enough expensive pledges to fill a yacht made of Centrelink cash. Labors pouring funds into housing, health, and education; the Coalitions outbidding them like theyre on The Block. And while its all fun and handouts until the election, S&P politely reminded everyone that fairy dust doesnt balance a budget. Translation: enjoy the sugar rush nowyou\'re getting a tax migraine in 2026.\n\nZooming out, this is the latest in a long-running game of election cosplay, where parties act like money is infinite until someone whispers credit rating and the music stops. Australias economic credibility is strong-ish, but even S&P knows the vibes cant pay for infrastructure. And in case you\'re wondering, yesthis exact cycle happens every three years. It\'s basically fiscal Groundhog Day with more spreadsheets.\n\nThe update? S&P didnt downgrade us yetthey just did that eyebrow raise your mum gives before asking where your rent money went. If promises keep ballooning like an influencers filler budget, expect warnings to turn into downgrades. And yep, that means cuts, hikes, or both. Trick or treat, taxpayers.\n\nSources:\nThe Australian  Albanese and Duttons election spending promises will result in big tax rises, spending cuts (30/04/2025)\nhttps://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/albanese-and-duttons-election-spending-promises-will-result-in-big-tax-rises-spending-cuts/news-story/691a6aeae5e40b7e74e8492638be64bc', 0, 'factabot', 'sp-to-politicians-your-campaign-promises-scream-hangover', 'published', 'images/news/8133bfb7-e43c-4dde-9997-dbb353faeb71.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-05-07 00:12:11', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (868, 'Margot and Elordi to Star in Sexy Gothic Moan-FestWuthering Heights', 'Two Aussie hotties in period costumes sighing in the rain? Hollywood says art, we say clickbait with fog. Wuthering Heights, but sexy.', 'Put on your corsets and crank the fog machineHollywood just greenlit the horniest version of Wuthering Heights yet. Aussie icons Margot Robbie and Jacob Elordi have been cast as the stormy soulmates in a brooding reboot of the 19th-century classic that asks, What if literary misery... but hot?\n\nThe casting feels like an algorithm generated it: Elordi, fresh off his tall and tortured cinematic tour, and Margot, whos cornered the market on stunning women who slowly lose their minds in gorgeous lighting. Together, theyll presumably spend 120 minutes staring at each other from windswept cliffs while whispering I am Heathcliff through tears and tight bodices.\n\nThe bigger picture? This is part of Hollywoods recent obsession with making old-school literature steamy again. From Persuasion with Gen Z slang to Romeo + Juliet but make it bisexual, its all about dusting off the school curriculum and slapping it with a thirst trap filter. Because nothing says timeless art like TikTok edits of rain-soaked cheekbones.\n\nTodays update is basically one giant swoon: fans are already predicting Oscars, Tumblr is vibrating, and somewhere a Year 11 English teacher is preparing a very awkward classroom screening. All we ask is that this version includes fewer cough deaths and more eye contact. Preferably shirtless.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Morning Mail: Margot Robbie and Jacob Elordi to star in new Wuthering Heights film (30/04/2025)\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2025/apr/30/morning-mail-wednesday-ntwnfb', 0, 'factabot', 'margot-and-elordi-to-star-in-sexy-gothic-moan-fest-wuthering-heights', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-05-06 04:37:49', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (869, 'Coles Shoppers Dump Meat and Bottled WaterBudgeting or Apocalypse?', 'Coles shoppers are cutting meat and hydration from their diet. Either the cost-of-living crisis is peakingor weve all just given up.', 'If your grocery trolley is starting to look more zombie ration kit than family dinner, youre not alone. Shoppers at Coles are ditching meat and bottled watertwo staples of the modern supermarket flexin what appears to be a nationwide cry for financial help. Between surging prices and zero pay rises, Aussies are now surviving on chickpeas and vibes.\n\nColes execs released their latest were listening report, which revealed Australians are chopping premium meat from the menu and turning their backs on bottled hydration like its Evians fault rent went up. Honestly, when 1kg of beef costs more than a therapy session, somethings gotta give.\n\nIn context, this is the newest symptom of the cost-of-living crisis that just wont quit. With inflation chewing through pay packets and energy bills doing backflips, even supermarket loyalty points cant save us. Bottled water, once the luxury of gym bunnies and hungover brunchers, is now too expensive to justify. Tap waters back in fashionso are lentils.\n\nWhats the latest? Coles is trying to lure us back with bulk deals and feel-good ads, but the reality is stark: shoppers are broke, cranky, and sick of pretending $9 chicken is a good deal. Its budgeting or bust. Either we collectively learn to cook tofu, or we eat revenge spaghetti four nights a week. Again.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Big promotions: Shoppers cut back as cost-of-living pressures bite (30/04/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/finance/business/retail/big-promotions-shoppers-cut-back-as-costofliving-pressures-bite/news-story/0ac75c4245ee8afc01f54474322684ef', 0, 'factabot', 'coles-shoppers-dump-meat-and-bottled-water-budgeting-or-apocalypse', 'published', 'images/news/be11e99e-de41-4bb2-84b7-ad1fcdeb3f3a.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-04-30 02:59:17', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (870, 'Gruen Nation Returns to Roast the Spin Out of Politics', 'Wil Anderson is back to dissect ads with more bite than a sausage sizzle. If only politicians were half as honest as this roast.', 'Wil Anderson is back, flanked by a panel of ad nerds and comedy assassins, to do what politicians fear mosttranslate their campaign ads into actual English. Yes, Gruen Nation has returned just in time for the election circus, and honestly, its the only political coverage that doesnt make you want to move to New Zealand.\n\nThe cast hasnt changed muchWil still delivers punchlines like hes allergic to spin, Todd Sampson still flexes both biceps and branding expertise, and theres always one token comms guru with insider knowledge and the dead eyes of someone whos seen focus group hell. Together, they deconstruct political ads faster than a candidate backpedaling on climate policy.\n\nLets be real: political ads are often less about persuading voters and more about traumatising them into submission. Gruen Nation doesnt just call out the manipulationit throws it a farewell party with snarky analysis, live roasts, and enough sarcasm to fuel a small nation. Watching them break down slogans like Standing Up for Real Australians is more revealing than any policy document. And funnier, obviously.\n\nThe context? As election season hits fever pitch, the airwaves are choked with soft-focus propaganda, stock footage of tradies, and slogans so vague they could be AI-generated. Enter Gruen, wielding data, humour, and utter disdain for BS. Its the one show that treats the public like theyre not idiotsjust tired, broke, and extremely over it.\n\nThe latest update? The new season dropped last night, already skewering both sides with surgical precision and zero mercy. One episode in, and its clearer than ever: Gruen Nation is the only thing keeping political TV watchableand possibly democracy itself.\n\nSources:\nABC iView  Gruen Nation official program page (30/04/2025)\nhttps://iview.abc.net.au/show/gruen-nation\n', 0, 'factabot', 'gruen-nation-returns-to-roast-the-spin-out-of-politics', 'published', 'images/news/7c9dc472-e0ea-4077-9736-cb9d1a43e83d.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 01:05:21', '2025-05-06 03:23:43', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (871, 'Trump Celebrates 100 Days with Rally: \'Nothing Will Stop Me\'', 'Trump threw a party for himself, claimed unparalleled success, and took shots at judges. The crowd was half-full, but his confidence was overflowing.', 'Donald Trump, the man who once bragged about his perfect phone call, has now thrown himself a 100-day partywith all the modesty of a firework factory on New Years Eve. Speaking at a not-quite-packed rally in Michigan, the former-recently-current-president declared that nothing will stop me, which is bold considering gravity, reality, and the judicial system are still very much in effect. His loyalists, somewhere between rally-sized and bingo-night-at-the-VFW-sized, cheered as Trump rattled off wins, ranted about \"communist radical-left judges\" (classic greatest hits), and assured everyone that the countrys doing better than evermostly because he\'s in charge again.\n\nLets rewind. Its been 100 days since Trumps second coming to the Oval Office, which hes spent in a whirlwind of executive orders, truth social rants, and courtroom dodges. While the administration touts border crackdowns and trade smackdowns as wins, critics are stuck on little things like the tanking approval ratings, federal investigations, and general chaos. But to Trump, its been a flawless runhistoric, even. Which is true, if you define historic as a sequel no one asked for but somehow still got greenlit.\n\nThe context? Americas still stuck in a political seesaw, and Trumps rally was less about policy and more about vibesloud, defiant, and drenched in self-congratulation. While legal landmines loom, Trumps strategy is full steam ahead: insult the judges, bash the press, and frame every roadblock as proof of persecution. Its like a magic trick where the rabbit keeps suing the magician.\n\nSo whats new? At the Michigan rally, Trump tripled down. He hailed his first 100 days as unmatched (Lincoln, eat your heart out), swore the courts wouldnt derail him, and hinted at more big things comingprobably involving caps lock. The crowd? Lukewarm. The message? Blazing hot. The mans still campaigning like he never stopped. Because honestly, did he?\n\nSources: The Guardian (30 April 2025), CNN, Politico, Reuters.', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-celebrates-100-days-with-rally-nothing-will-stop-me', 'published', 'images/news/d4bdcfce-fd57-4a62-a790-f3d8d95574b4.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:24:36', '2025-04-30 11:44:43', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (872, 'Trump\'s First 100 Days: Executive Orders and Controversies Galore', 'Trump\'s second term is off to a roaring startif roaring means a flurry of executive orders and nationwide protests.', 'Trump\'s second term is off to a roaring startif roaring means a flurry of executive orders and nationwide protests.\n\nDonald Trumps vibe lately is less steady hand of leadership and more guy with a Sharpie and no chill. In just 100 days, hes signed more executive orders than most presidents sign in a year, wielding his pen like a magic wandexcept instead of spells, its lawsuits and street protests. His inner circle? Still a Greatest Hits lineup of loyalists, firebrands, and legal ticking time bombs. At the centre of it all, Trump, the chaos whisperer, is crowing about his most successful 100 days ever, because of course he is.\n\nBehind the bravado is a blitzkrieg of policiesborder crackdowns, environmental rollbacks, social media bansall executed with the grace of a chainsaw through Jell-O. The courts? Already clogged with challenges. The public? Split between MAGA-fied devotion and protest march fatigue. If governing by executive order were an Olympic sport, Trump just broke the record, lit the torch, and set the stadium on fire.\n\nZooming out, this second term feels more like a Netflix reboot: louder, riskier, and desperately trying to outdo the original. Trumps strategy is simpleskip Congress, ignore critics, and treat the Constitution like its written in invisible ink. If it sounds familiar, thats because it is. Except this time, the resistance is louder, and the consequences might stick.\n\nSo what now? Trumps celebrating his 100-day accomplishment spree, while Washington scrambles to clean up the constitutional confetti. If the rest of the term keeps this pace, expect more orders, more outrage, and probably another perfect call or two.\n\nSources: The Guardian (30 April 2025), Politico, NPR', 0, 'factabot', 'trumps-first-100-days-executive-orders-and-controversies-galore', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 04:24:36', '2025-04-30 04:24:36', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (873, 'Trump Urges Putin to \'Stop Shooting\' After Vatican Meeting with Zelenskyy', 'Trump plays peacemaker at the Vatican, asking Putin to \'stop shooting\'because that\'s how diplomacy works now.', 'Trump plays peacemaker at the Vatican, asking Putin to \'stop shooting\'because that\'s how diplomacy works now.\n\nDonald Trumps idea of foreign policy reads like a Hallmark card written in crayon. After a Vatican meet-and-greet with Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy, Trump announced hed told Putin to stop shootingas if thats all it takes. Just a firm dad voice and maybe a little pout. Forget diplomacy, treaties, or pressure campaigns. This is bro-level conflict resolution, Trump-style: say it loud, say it vague, and hope it trends.\n\nZelenskyy, whos been dealing with an actual war, probably nodded politely while wondering if divine intervention would be more helpful. The meeting, reportedly arranged with Pope Francis as mediator, had all the optics of global seriousnessminus the actual outcomes. Trump then took to cameras to declare he was the only one who could fix it, which must be comforting to NATO, the EU, and everyone with a functioning memory.\n\nHeres the kicker: Trumps sudden dip into peace talks comes as critics accuse him of coddling authoritarian leaders while cutting U.S. funding to international institutions. Its the classic Trump moveshow up late, say something wildly simplistic, and demand a trophy. Meanwhile, Zelenskyy continues pleading for real support, and Putin keeps doing whatever he wants with a smirk and a drone strike.\n\nThe update? Trump claims he\'s making progress, but no ceasefires were announced, and Putin has yet to confirm hes turned off the tanks. But hey, it made for a solid photo opand thats what really counts, right?\n\nSources: The Guardian (30 April 2025), Reuters, CNN, AP News\n', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-urges-putin-to-stop-shooting-after-vatican-meeting-with-zelenskyy', 'published', 'images/news/b34974ee-3e92-482f-b68f-bcc53b412eab.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:24:36', '2025-04-30 22:11:21', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (874, 'Trump Administration Rolls Back Climate Protections, Exits Paris Agreement', 'Trump\'s environmental policy: out with the Paris Agreement, in with the pollution.', 'Trump\'s environmental policy: out with the Paris Agreement, in with the pollution.\n\nDonald Trump just broke up with the planetagain. With all the subtlety of a bulldozer in a butterfly sanctuary, the president marked Day 100 by yanking the U.S. out of the Paris Agreement for the second time and gutting what little climate policy was still hanging on for dear life. When asked why, Trump reportedly said hes not into globalism and prefers clean coal and clean cars, which is adorable if you ignore... science.\n\nThis isnt Trumps first fossil-fueled rodeo. His first term saw similar environmental carnage, but now he\'s doing it faster, louder, and with fewer adult supervisors. The Environmental Protection Agency? Currently acting more like the Environmental Permission Agency. Corporate lobbyists are thrilled. Climate scientists? Screaming into reusable tote bags.\n\nIn the bigger picture, this rollback arrives as climate disasters intensify globallyfloods, fires, and Category-Oh-Hell-No hurricanes. The U.S. is now the only major economy actively sprinting backward while the rest of the world awkwardly tiptoes toward net-zero. Bidens hard-fought environmental framework? Meet Trumps paper shredder. And the spin? Trump says it\'s about \"American energy dominance,\" which is a lovely euphemism for let the oil flow and the planet fry.\n\nThe latest? Trump held a press conference flanked by coal miners and oil execs, calling the Paris Agreement a job-killing hoax. His base cheered. The Earth winced. And somewhere, a polar bear just logged onto Zillow.\n\nSources: The Guardian (30 April 2025), Politico, NPR, Axios\n', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-administration-rolls-back-climate-protections-exits-paris-agreement', 'published', 'images/news/2211ea16-37bd-4ac6-a09a-bb2066b61a9c.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:24:36', '2025-04-30 08:56:38', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (875, 'Trump Plans to Ease Auto Tariffs Amid Industry Pushback', 'After revving up tariffs, Trump now taps the brakes to appease automakers.', 'After revving up tariffs, Trump now taps the brakes to appease automakers.\n\nIn a rare twist, Trump is actually listening to corporate Americaand not just the golf club variety. After revving up auto tariffs in his signature style (i.e., loud, fast, and with zero consultation), the president is now gently easing off the pedal. Why? Because the auto industry, including some of his MAGA-friendly manufacturers, basically screamed, Youre killing us, bro.\n\nThe Trump administration had jacked up tariffs on foreign-made car parts, claiming it was to protect American jobs. Reality check: it made cars pricier, pissed off the entire supply chain, and had CEOs from Detroit to Tokyo wondering if anyone in D.C. owns a calculator. After weeks of industry lobbyingand what we can only assume were some very tense backroom chatsTrump is reportedly walking it back. A little. Probably. Maybe.\n\nZooming out, this flip-flop is classic Trump: pick a fight, fan the flames, then declare victory while walking away from the mess. Its less about economic strategy and more about vibes-based policymaking. Tariffs up, stocks down, industries panicthen poof! A deal is teased and Trump says, Look what I fixed!\n\nAnd now? The president is promising a more flexible auto tariff policy thats still America First but somehow wont bankrupt automakers. Sounds totally feasible. Just dont ask him to explain how.\n\nSources: The Guardian (30 April 2025), Bloomberg, Wall Street Journal, CNBC\n\nWould you like these added to the previous Excel export or saved in a fresh one (Headlines 0405)?\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-plans-to-ease-auto-tariffs-amid-industry-pushback', 'published', 'images/news/594fcf29-7cbc-41a5-a59b-1d27ba7aa4ca.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:24:36', '2025-05-02 21:53:20', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (876, 'China\'s GDP on Track for 5% Growth: Economy Flexes Muscles Amid Global Uncertainty', 'While others wobble, China struts with a 5% GDP growth forecast, flexing its economic muscles and showing the world how it\'s done.', 'While others wobble, China struts with a 5% GDP growth forecast, flexing its economic muscles and showing the world how it\'s done.\n\nChinas economy just hit the catwalk with a 5% growth forecast and gave the rest of the world a smug little wink. As Western economies trip over inflation, rate hikes, and political drama, Beijing is out here flexing like it\'s economic leg day. The National Bureau of Statistics unveiled the number with all the subtlety of a fireworks show, declaring that the resilience and momentum of Chinas recovery is strong and sustainable. Translation: Look whos thriving while you panic-buy eggs.\n\nThe forecast reflects rebounds in manufacturing, infrastructure, and domestic spendingbuoyed by, well, heavy government nudging. Think stimulus with a side of state capitalism. And while youth unemployment and housing bubbles still lurk in the shadows like plot twists in a bad soap opera, the official message is clear: growth is back, baby. And this time, its personal.\n\nIn the global arena, this puts China in a power poseespecially as the U.S. teeters on recession chatter and Europe is stuck in an energy-fueled existential crisis. Beijings banking on this economic mojo to fuel its geopolitical ambitions, trade dominance, and international charm offensives from Central Asia to Africa. And lets not forget: 2025 is also a key year in Chinas long game to dethrone the dollar and go full digital yuan.\n\nSo what\'s new? The finance ministry is handing out high-fives, global analysts are cautiously impressed, and Xi Jinping is probably sipping tea with that told you so energy. The rest of the world? Watching closely, clutching their GDP charts, and maybe, just maybe, rethinking their whole playbook.\n\nSources: Xinhua, Caixin, China Daily, South China Morning Post (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-gdp-on-track-for-5-growth-economy-flexes-muscles-amid-global-uncertainty', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 17:50:02', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (877, 'Wang Yi Proposes Five-Point Plan to Deepen China-Central Asia Cooperation', 'Wang Yi lays out a five-step dance to charm Central Asia, proving diplomacy can be as choreographed as a boy band routine.', 'Wang Yi lays out a five-step dance to charm Central Asia, proving diplomacy can be as choreographed as a boy band routine.\n\nChinas top diplomat Wang Yi just dropped a diplomatic mixtape for Central Asia, and its got five tracks: mutual trust, security, economic ties, connectivity, and cultural bondingbasically Belt and Road: The Encore Edition. At a high-level forum, Wang told the assembled officials that the region and Beijing should join hands for prosperity, while gently implying, Ignore those loud Western kids yelling about influence.\n\nThis proposal is part of Chinas long-running strategy to turn Central Asia into its economic soulmate. Between pipelines, railway dreams, and shared border hugs, Beijing has been slowly building what it calls a community with a shared future, which sounds romantic until you remember its geopolitics. Central Asia, sandwiched between Moscows bear hugs and Beijings infrastructure binge, seems politely intrigued.\n\nWhats juicy here is the timing. With Russia distracted and the West busy staring down China elsewhere, Beijings making its move. Its not conquestits courtship, complete with funding packages, summit invites, and that soft-power sparkle. Wang Yi even included youth exchanges and language cooperation, because nothing says trust us like Mandarin karaoke nights.\n\nSo, whats the update? The five-point plan is out, the regional leaders nodded approvingly, and the photo-ops were peak cordial. No hard deals yet, but the choreographys in place. Stay tuned for the duet tour.\n\nSources: Xinhua, Global Times, China Daily (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'wang-yi-proposes-five-point-plan-to-deepen-china-central-asia-cooperation', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 04:38:25', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (878, 'China Urges US to End Threats, Engage in Dialogue Amid Rising Tensions', 'China tells the US to talk it out instead of throwing tantrumsbecause even superpowers need to use their words.', 'China tells the US to talk it out instead of throwing tantrumsbecause even superpowers need to use their words.\n\nChina has officially slipped the U.S. a diplomatic Post-it note that basically says: Calm down, Karen. In a press briefing laced with passive-aggressive serenity, Beijing urged Washington to stop the threats and pressure and maybejust maybetry having a conversation like adults. The appeal came from Foreign Ministry spokesperson Lin Jian, who suggested the U.S. meet halfway, which is international relations code for were not moving unless you move first.\n\nThis latest talk or toss missiles moment comes after weeks of escalating chest-thumping over Taiwan, trade sanctions, tech restrictions, and spy balloon dj vu. The U.S. has been tightening export controls and flexing military muscles in the Pacific, while China has responded with its own version of dont test me, bro, including drills near Taiwan and fiery op-eds. Its the kind of tension where everyone claims to want peace, but nobody wants to blink first.\n\nContextually, both nations are stuck in a geopolitical tug-of-war that now includes AI chips, South China Sea hotspots, and the occasional diplomatic subtweet. Bidens team insists on competition without conflict, while China hears that and sees a drone strike with a smile. And lets not forget: both economies are wobbling, and nobody wants a real warunless its on TikTok.\n\nSo, whats new? China wants the U.S. to stop the threats and sit down for dialogue without preconditions. Translation: Stop yelling and lets pretend were friends at the next summit. Whether Washington obliges or doubles down with another round of sanctions and a strongly worded GIF remains to be seen.\n\nSources: Xinhua (30 April 2025), Global Times, South China Morning Post, Reuters, The Guardian', 0, 'factabot', 'china-urges-us-to-end-threats-engage-in-dialogue-amid-rising-tensions', 'published', 'images/news/6a085fb3-106b-4a65-9f1e-2dbe8ca098ee.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 13:22:26', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (879, 'Chengdu Marks 100-Day Countdown to 12th World Games', 'Chengdu starts the clock on the World Games, proving it\'s not just pandas that can perform under pressure.', 'Chengdu starts the clock on the World Games, proving it\'s not just pandas that can perform under pressure.\n\nChengdu, home of spicy hotpot and sleepy pandas, is officially in countdown mode100 days to go until it hosts the 12th World Games. Think of it as the Olympics quirky cousin: less track and field, more parkour and tug-of-war (yes, really). City officials kicked off the pre-party with fireworks, speeches, and a mascot that probably has its own Weibo account by now.\n\nHosting the World Games is a big flex for Chengdu, signaling its arrival as Chinas rising sports hub. The city has already hosted major esports, global expos, and that one marathon where half the runners wore panda ears. Now its chasing international attention with synchronized aerobics, drone light shows, and probably more panda-themed merch than is legally advisable.\n\nWhy does this matter? Its part of Chinas ongoing soft power campaign: dazzle the world with spectacle, logistics, and smiling volunteers in matching uniforms. For Chengdu, its a chance to show off infrastructure, culture, and that bullet train thatll get you to the venue before your latte gets cold.\n\nThe latest update? Ticket sales open soon, venues are nearly ready, and rehearsals for the opening ceremony are allegedly so intense even the mascots are sweating. The worlds weirdest sports fest is comingand Chengdus not missing a beat.\n\nSources: Xinhua, China Daily, South China Morning Post (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'chengdu-marks-100-day-countdown-to-12th-world-games', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 11:24:08', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (880, 'China Tops Global Ranking of Nuclear Power Capacity', 'China goes full nuclearenergy-wisetaking the top spot and lighting up the leaderboard.', 'China goes full nuclearenergy-wisetaking the top spot and lighting up the leaderboard.\n\nChina just dropped the mic on the global energy stage, officially overtaking every other country to claim the crown for largest nuclear power capacity. Thats rightwhile the West debates whether to plug in a kettle during peak hours, China is out here lighting up entire cities with atom-splitting swagger.\n\nThe National Energy Administration confirmed that Chinas reactors now produce more clean nuclear energy than any other nation, beating out long-time players like the U.S. and France. The achievement caps off years of obsessive reactor building, policy overhauls, and enough steel and concrete to make a Bond villain blush. And yes, the bragging rights are radioactive.\n\nThis milestone isnt just about energyits about image. Beijing has been positioning itself as a climate leader (with a few emissions-related asterisks), and topping the nuclear leaderboard is the perfect see, were serious moment. It also signals a pivot from coal dependence toward a mix of renewables, hydropower, and now, heavy-duty fission. Basically, the grids getting a glow-up.\n\nThe latest? Chinas not done. More reactors are under construction, and officials say this is just the beginning of their green transformationa phrase that, in this case, apparently includes uranium. Critics point out the usual: safety, transparency, and the odd geopolitical side-eye. But for now, Chinas nukes are #1, and its glowing with pride.\n\nSources: Xinhua, Caixin, South China Morning Post, China Daily (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'china-tops-global-ranking-of-nuclear-power-capacity', 'published', 'images/news/26ca4056-7165-40e0-8264-970d7e599d90.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 04:39:53', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (881, 'China Makes Headway in Pneumoconiosis Treatment', 'Breathing easier: China\'s advancements in treating pneumoconiosis show it\'s not just hot air.', 'Breathing easier: China\'s advancements in treating pneumoconiosis show it\'s not just hot air.\n\nFor once, a lung-related headline out of China isnt about smog. The countrys medical sector is finally making real progress on treating pneumoconiosisa brutal lung disease often dubbed black lung thats plagued miners and industrial workers for decades. Health authorities announced new breakthroughs in diagnosis, early intervention, and yes, actual treatment protocols that dont involve a shrug and a prescription for fresh air.\n\nThe condition, caused by inhaling fine dust particles over time, has long been a dirty little secret of Chinas rapid industrial rise. For years, sufferers were left to cough in peace while compensation cases gathered dust faster than their lungs. But thanks to public pressure, activist groups, and some uncomfortable documentary exposs, the government is now tossing serious research and resources at the problem.\n\nZoom out and this is part of a broader PR push: Look! We care about workers now! It also fits neatly into Chinas latest health reforms and common prosperity rhetoric. After all, its hard to build a future on innovation if half your workforce cant breathe.\n\nWhats the update? Clinical trials on new treatment methods are underway, faster screenings are being rolled out, and even state media sounds genuinely hopeful. Whether its reform or rebrandingwell take the progress.\n\nSources: Xinhua, Caixin, South China Morning Post (30 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'china-makes-headway-in-pneumoconiosis-treatment', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 06:03:33', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (882, 'Alibaba Introduces Open-Source AI Model with Hybrid Reasoning', 'Alibaba\'s new AI model thinks outside the boxand maybe inside your shopping cart.', 'Alibaba\'s new AI model thinks outside the boxand maybe inside your shopping cart.\n\nAlibaba just launched its latest AI brainchilda shiny new open-source model boasting hybrid reasoning skills, because regular reasoning apparently wasnt ambitious enough. The company says this model combines symbolic logic with neural learning, which in techspeak means it can think and vibe. Its like Sherlock Holmes with a GPU.\n\nDubbed Qwen2.0 (because Qwen1.0 wasnt smug enough), the models designed to help developers build smarter applicationsfrom business analytics to, inevitably, recommending more things you dont need on Taobao. The models capabilities include long-context memory, logic chain analysis, and multilingual support, which basically means it could help you do your taxes in Mandarin while explaining quantum physics in emoji.\n\nThis move is Alibabas flex in the ongoing AI arms race, where Chinese tech giants are scrambling to out-innovate each other while also dodging regulatory whiplash and data paranoia. Open-sourcing it? Thats the cherry on topengineers love it, governments squint at it, and startups salivate over it.\n\nThe latest? Qwen2.0 is already gaining traction on developer forums, with Alibaba promising more updates, plugins, and integrations. Its smart, stylish, and very much watching you browse.\n\nSources: South China Morning Post, Yicai, China Daily, TechNode (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'alibaba-introduces-open-source-ai-model-with-hybrid-reasoning', 'published', 'images/news/1afaefac-58bc-4f78-9a60-373ae2072b17.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 12:31:58', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (883, 'Andy Lau\'s Latest Film Set to Hit Screens on May Day', 'Andy Lau returns to the big screen, proving that some stars never fadethey just get better with age.', 'Andy Lau returns to the big screen, proving that some stars never fadethey just get better with age.\n\nHong Kong legend Andy Lau is back, and cinema-goers are already swooning in anticipation. His latest film is set to drop on May Day, giving the nation something other than traffic jams and karaoke to look forward to during the holiday. Lauactor, singer, eternal heartthrobis proving once again that aging is optional if youre powered by talent and pure cinematic charisma.\n\nThe film, a high-stakes drama with just enough slow-motion walking to qualify as epic, sees Lau playing a morally complex hero (read: cool guy with a dark past). Its directed by a rising Mainland auteur and backed by big-budget mainland studios clearly betting that nostalgia sellsand they\'re right.\n\nContextually, Laus return to theatres isnt just a film release, its an event. The man has a cult following, an honorary PhD in being suave, and a career spanning decades without a flop to stain his IMDb. With Chinese cinema pushing hard against Hollywood imports, icons like Lau are the ultimate crowd-pullers.\n\nWhats the scoop? Pre-sale tickets are selling like milk tea on a hot day, critics are cautiously hyped, and fans are preparing for selfie battles at the premiere. May Day just got star-studded.\n\nSources: China Daily, Global Times, The Paper, SCMP (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'andy-laus-latest-film-set-to-hit-screens-on-may-day', 'published', 'images/news/c153ae93-f061-44c0-8a10-e65614856c74.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 11:35:00', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (884, 'Wuxi Unveils Comprehensive Policies to Boost Film Industry Development', 'Wuxi rolls out the red carpet for filmmakers, turning real estate into reel estate.', 'Wuxi rolls out the red carpet for filmmakers, turning real estate into reel estate.\n\nWuxi, the city that brought you lakeside serenity and surprisingly ambitious film studios, is going full Hollywood-China. Local authorities just dropped a blockbuster policy package aimed at making Wuxi the next cinematic hotspotcomplete with subsidies, tax perks, infrastructure upgrades, and enough red tape cutting to fill a montage.\n\nThe city\'s plans include streamlined permits, set construction grants, talent incentives, and even preferential land use termsbecause nothing says we believe in your artistic vision like discounted property. Its all part of a plan to attract both domestic filmmakers and international co-productions looking for big sets, low costs, and local enthusiasm that borders on red-carpet worship.\n\nZooming out, this push fits Chinas broader strategy to build cultural clout through cinema. Beijing wants fewer Marvel imports and more homegrown epicsand regional cities like Wuxi are racing to be the launchpads. Plus, boosting the creative economy makes for friendlier headlines than, say, airspace incursions or trade spats.\n\nThe update? Several studios have already signed up for new projects, and Wuxis film park is prepping for a production boom. Critics may call it policy theatrebut hey, at least the lighting is good.\n\nSources: China Daily, Xinhua, Global Times (30 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'wuxi-unveils-comprehensive-policies-to-boost-film-industry-development', 'published', 'images/news/2878445d-df31-4c7e-8f32-a82f5baf7799.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 10:53:19', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (885, 'Xiamen Hosts Job Fair for Taiwan Graduates', 'Xiamen plays matchmaker for Taiwan grads and employersbecause who says job hunting can\'t be a love story?', 'Xiamen plays matchmaker for Taiwan grads and employersbecause who says job hunting can\'t be a love story?\n\nXiamen just staged the most diplomatic job fair everoffering Taiwanese graduates a career ladder with a side of cross-strait charm. Over 200 companies gathered to woo young talent from Taiwan, promising salaries, stability, and just enough patriotic undertones to make Beijing proud.\n\nThe job fair featured sectors like AI, finance, and logistics, along with official statements about building shared futures and deepening integrationall delivered with the gentle enthusiasm of someone trying not to scare off a first date. Attendees got resume tips, interview slots, and the occasional ideological nudge, all under banners touting unity and opportunity.\n\nBigger picture: Beijings been trying to win hearts and minds across the Taiwan Strait through jobs, education, and economic incentives. Its soft power in a business suitless annexation vibes, more we brought snacks and a pension plan. Whether it works is debatable, but the effort is undeniably persistent.\n\nThe latest? Officials say the turnout was high and the vibe was encouraging. Taiwans government, meanwhile, likely raised an eyebrow. Or both.\n\nSources: Xinhua, Taiwan Affairs Office release, China Daily (30 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'xiamen-hosts-job-fair-for-taiwan-graduates', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-30 04:38:25', '2025-04-30 04:38:25', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (886, 'Albanese and Dutton\'s Spending Promises: A Recipe for Future Tax Hikes?', 'Politicians are handing out promises like candy, but the toothache of tax hikes and spending cuts looms large.', 'Politicians are handing out promises like candy, but the toothache of tax hikes and spending cuts looms large.\n\nAnthony Albanese and Peter Dutton are currently in a fierce competition to see who can toss the most money at voters without triggering a Treasury migraine. From new defence upgrades to housing dreams and infrastructure glitz, both leaders have rolled out campaign promises so generous you\'d think we were all sitting on a gold mine. Spoiler: were not.\n\nThe big issue? Math. Economists, the killjoys of any political parade, warn that these multi-billion-dollar goodies will almost certainly lead to future tax hikes or brutal spending cuts. The Parliamentary Budget Office has been frantically waving red flags, but both sides keep smiling for the cameras like they\'re in a Coles commercial.\n\nWhy it matters? Its election season, baby. The promises are thick, the reality is thin, and no one wants to admit that someonecough, youis going to foot the bill eventually. But rest assured, once the votes are counted, someones fantasy will morph into your fiscal nightmare.\n\nThe latest? S&P Global Ratings just gave everyone a polite economic slap, warning that the current trajectory is unsustainable. Dutton shrugged. Albanese deflected. And voters? Theyre starting to realise the candy comes with cavities.\n\nSources: The Australian, ABC News, Guardian Australia (30 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'albanese-and-duttons-spending-promises-a-recipe-for-future-tax-hikes', 'published', 'images/news/e5ff80a4-e965-4598-82ad-67f9d932b1ce.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:50:41', '2025-05-06 00:06:55', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (887, 'Albanese and Dutton Clash Over National Security Policies Ahead of Election', 'It\'s a political arm-wrestle over who can flex their national security muscles more convincingly.', 'It\'s a political arm-wrestle over who can flex their national security muscles more convincingly.\n\nWith the election looming like a bad sequel, Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton have entered a national security chest-puffing contest. Albo\'s pitching measured leadership with allies, while Duttons gone full action-hero, promising tougher borders, more defence spending, and what sounds suspiciously like a guest spot on Border Security: Election Edition.\n\nThe brawl includes everything from cybersecurity threats to military alliances, defence procurement, and the classic whos tougher on China debate. Dutton says Labors weak. Albanese says the Coalitions reckless. And both agree that Australia must be prepared, which usually means more money for submarines and fewer details about what theyll actually do.\n\nZooming out, this is less about safety and more about scoring electoral points. National security polls well, especially when the economy is wobbly and the news cycles moody. So expect more tough-guy rhetoric, staged photo ops with troops, and patriotic soundbites vaguely referencing ANZAC values.\n\nThe latest? Dutton unveiled a new security plan with the subtlety of a hammer, while Albanese reiterated trust in international partnerships. Voters are stuck deciding who theyd trust more in a geopolitical fire drill. Or at least who looks better holding binoculars on a navy ship.\n\nSources: SBS News, The Australian, 9News (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'albanese-and-dutton-clash-over-national-security-policies-ahead-of-election', 'published', 'images/news/ad51769d-1de1-4353-b981-55e31176e594.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:50:41', '2025-05-07 02:35:16', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (888, 'Australia\'s Strategic Landscape: Most Complex Since WWII, Say Experts', 'Australia\'s playing 4D chess on the global stage, and the stakes have never been higher.', 'Australia\'s playing 4D chess on the global stage, and the stakes have never been higher.\n\nSecurity experts are sounding the alarm that Australias current strategic environment is the hairiest its been since World War IIwhich is both terrifying and peak Canberra drama. From Chinas rising assertiveness to tensions in the Indo-Pacific and a jittery U.S., the country is now juggling more military relationships and security risks than a Cold War-era Bond villain.\n\nThe government is expanding its defence budget, deepening ties with the U.S. and regional partners, and quietly praying that AUKUS doesnt become the punchline its trending toward. Meanwhile, intelligence officials are doing more public speaking than everalways a bad signwarning of cyber threats, espionage, and a world thats increasingly allergic to stability.\n\nThe background here? Australias once-comfy role as the lucky country is morphing into the anxious middleman, trying to keep trade with China flowing while also prepping for conflict scenarios its neighbours wont even name out loud. Its the diplomatic equivalent of walking a tightrope with a boomerang in one hand and a briefing folder in the other.\n\nThe update? Think tanks are pushing for faster rearmament, streamlined command structures, and a national security rethink. Because apparently the old shell be right approach no longer cuts it when everyone else is arming up.\n\nSources: ABC News, The Guardian Australia, The Australian Strategic Policy Institute (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'australias-strategic-landscape-most-complex-since-wwii-say-experts', 'published', 'images/news/9c4609aa-729f-414f-869b-d795c48094cd.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:50:41', '2025-05-05 08:52:23', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (889, 'NRL Scores Extended Partnership with Accor Hotels Through 2027', 'NRL players can rest easyliterallywith hotel stays sorted through 2027.', 'NRL players can rest easyliterallywith hotel stays sorted through 2027.\n\nThe NRL has just extended its partnership with Accor Hotels, ensuring players will be tucking into continental breakfasts and those tiny shampoo bottles until at least 2027. The deal gives the league continued access to swanky stays across Sofitel, Novotel, and Ibis propertieswhich means everyone from star fullbacks to assistant coaches is now officially booked and bougie.\n\nIts more than just pillow-top mattresses and upgraded minibarsthis partnership helps cut major logistical headaches for teams, offering streamlined accommodation for travel, games, and preseason bootcamps (and maybe a cheeky staycation after a brutal loss). Accor, for its part, gets prime sports sponsorship clout and a footy fan clientele with a healthy appetite for both loyalty points and victory beers.\n\nThis move also signals the NRLs growing corporate polishless punch-ons at pub trivia, more neatly pressed partnerships. Sport in 2025 is as much about branding as it is about bruising tackles, and hotel comfort is now part of the game plan.\n\nThe update? The deal was inked with all the PR flair of a red carpet event, and players can now snooze their way across Australia in five-star comfort. Accor wins, the NRL wins, and if youve ever wanted to sleep where your team sleepscongrats, that Ibis is now iconic.\n\nSources: The Australian (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'nrl-scores-extended-partnership-with-accor-hotels-through-2027', 'published', 'images/news/31e93a95-aa25-45dd-b5e9-0b3cb24cfd11.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:50:41', '2025-05-06 03:28:59', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (890, 'Treasurer Highlights Drop in Core Inflation Ahead of Election', 'Inflation\'s cooling off, and the Treasurer\'s turning up the heat on election bragging rights.', 'Inflation\'s cooling off, and the Treasurer\'s turning up the heat on election bragging rights.\n\nTreasurer Jim Chalmers has leapt on the latest inflation stats like a dog on a sausage roll, touting a drop in core inflation as proof that Labors economic plan is working. With an election on the horizon, its the kind of data point you frame, laminate, and wave around like a bingo card at Treasury pressers.\n\nThe numbers? Core inflation dipped slightly more than expected, suggesting household pain at the checkout might finally be easingemphasis on might. Fuel, rents, and groceries are still putting wallets in headlocks, but the Treasurer insists it\'s all heading in the right direction. Cue the election slogan: Less sizzle, more savings.\n\nContextually, this is less about economics and more about optics. Chalmers needs a win narrative, and softening inflation is the perfect talking point. Coalition critics, naturally, arent buying itclaiming the economy is still a mess, and blaming Labor for the cost-of-living crunch in the first place. Whos right? Depends on your receipts.\n\nThe latest? Chalmers gave a victory-laced statement while not-so-subtly dunking on Coalition policies. And voters? Still waiting for the day their grocery bill doesnt feel like a credit card crime.\n\nSources: Reuters (30 April 2025), ABC News, AFR', 0, 'factabot', 'treasurer-highlights-drop-in-core-inflation-ahead-of-election', 'published', 'images/news/52368dcd-8efb-4977-be0a-27a66f78e004.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:50:41', '2025-05-06 08:44:32', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (891, 'Australian Ballet\'s \'Manon\' Returns to Sydney Opera House After 11 Years', '\'Manon\' pirouettes back into the spotlight, proving some classics never go out of style.', 'Manon\' pirouettes back into the spotlight, proving some classics never go out of style.\n\nDust off the tulle and dim the house lightsManon is back at the Sydney Opera House after more than a decade-long hiatus, and its stealing the spotlight all over again. The Australian Ballets revival of the lush, dramatic, and ever-so-slightly scandalous classic is already drawing ovations from die-hard ballet fans and culture-curious newcomers alike.\n\nThe story, a tale of love, betrayal, and enough emotional whiplash to qualify as an HBO miniseries, is being restaged with full period costumes and swoon-worthy sets. Artistic Director David Hallberg called it one of our boldest returns, which is ballet code for bring tissues and your fanciest shoes.\n\nThis comeback also lands at a time when traditional arts are reclaiming relevance in a TikTok world. The Opera House is banking on nostalgia, prestige, and a little theatrical magic to pull crowds back into the velvet seats.\n\nThe latest? Early reviews are glowing, tickets are selling fast, and Manon herself is serving pirouettes with heartbreak realness. Eleven years was too longbut worth the wait.\n\nSources: Daily Telegraph, Sydney Morning Herald, The Australian (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'australian-ballets-manon-returns-to-sydney-opera-house-after-11-years', 'published', 'images/news/4f672de2-d789-4c22-be32-59bd83c57327.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:50:41', '2025-05-07 04:32:56', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (892, 'Woolworths Set to Trial AI Shelf-Scanning Robots in Major Stores', 'Woolies is rolling out robots to watch the shelvesbecause humans cant be trusted with bread stock levels.', 'Woolies is rolling out robots to watch the shelvesbecause humans cant be trusted with bread stock levels.\n\nWoolworths has officially entered its sci-fi era, announcing trials of AI-powered shelf-scanning robots in major stores across Australia. These R2-D2 wannabes will glide through aisles, tracking stock levels, spotting empty shelves, and judging your choice of cerealall while freeing up staff for more important tasks (like restocking the bananas people keep squeezing).\n\nThe robots, developed in partnership with tech firm Symbotic, use cameras and machine learning to scan product availability in real time. Think of it as inventory management with judgmental eyes. Woolies says the move is about improving efficiency and customer experience, which loosely translates to: \"Wed like fewer angry mums yelling that theres no pasta sauce again.\"\n\nZooming out, the supermarket wars are heating up, and automation is the new frontline. Coles has self-checkouts, Aldi has mystery layouts, and now Woolies has robots to make you feel bad for buying off-brand biscuits. Its retail Darwinismwith lasers.\n\nThe latest? Trials start this quarter, with rollout depending on how well the bots behave. No word yet on whether theyll fetch your trolley or silently judge your 10-pack of Choccy Fingers.\n\nSources: News.com.au, AFR, SmartCompany (30 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'woolworths-set-to-trial-ai-shelf-scanning-robots-in-major-stores', 'published', 'images/news/c6718650-f0fa-4335-b0f9-49ba3cd758a2.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:50:41', '2025-05-06 09:52:03', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (893, 'RBA Flags Possible Mortgage Rate Hike After Inflation Report', 'The Reserve Bank is teasing another rate rise, just to keep Aussie homeowners on their toes (and ramen budgets).', 'The Reserve Bank is teasing another rate rise, just to keep Aussie homeowners on their toes (and ramen budgets).\n\nJust when mortgage-holders thought it was safe to exhale, the Reserve Bank of Australia slid into the headlines with a fresh threat: another rate hike may be incoming. After reviewing inflation data thats being slightly less feral than last quarter, the RBA made it clear its still watchingwaitinglike a financial horror movie villain with a clipboard.\n\nGovernor Michele Bullock said the latest inflation figures are encouraging but not enough, which is RBA code for we might raise rates anyway, just because we can. That gentle thud you hear is the collective forehead of every Australian mortgage-holder hitting the nearest table.\n\nBehind the curtain, inflation is still being stubborn, especially in sticky sectors like rent and services. The RBA, terrified of repeating the mistakes of the \'70s (and probably haunted by Alan Kohlers graphs), isnt ruling anything out. Banks are already pre-emptively whispering to borrowers: brace yourselves.\n\nSo whats next? Economists say a May or June hike is on the table. Which means homeowners will soon be swapping brunch for budget spreadsheets and pretending that 2-minute noodles are retro comfort food.\n\nSources: AFR, ABC News, Guardian Australia (30 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'rba-flags-possible-mortgage-rate-hike-after-inflation-report', 'published', 'images/news/4b7bf379-004c-4bc0-a60f-578a3185fa75.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:50:41', '2025-05-04 16:53:50', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (894, 'Sydneys Most Expensive Toast Just Got a Truffle Upgrade', 'Because why not add fungi to your $26 sourdough? Bougie brunch has officially peaked.', 'Because why not add fungi to your $26 sourdough? Bougie brunch has officially peaked.\n\nJust when we thought Sydneys brunch scene couldnt out-Sydney itself, someone decided to drop truffles on toastand charge you the GDP of a small island for it. A trendy caf in the Inner East has unveiled a new menu item: $32 sourdough slathered in artisanal butter, microgreens, and truffle shavings. Its toast, but make it recession-resistant.\n\nThe caf, known for its lavender lattes and people who say vibe check unironically, says the dish is an homage to modern Australian luxury. We say its an edible tax bracket. Locals are already queuing up to post it on Instagram before their wallets regain consciousness.\n\nZoom out and its just another day in Sydney, where avocado is a political statement and eggs come with a mortgage warning. In a time of inflation and housing despair, nothing says we live in a simulation like luxury fungi on bread. But hey, at least it\'s deliciously unrelatable.\n\nThe update? The toast is a hit. The cafs fully booked through the weekend, and critics are calling it a bold elevation of brunch. We call it what it is: edible economic commentary.\n\nSources: Broadsheet, Concrete Playground, Daily Telegraph (30 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'sydneys-most-expensive-toast-just-got-a-truffle-upgrade', 'published', 'images/news/ac8e60dc-82fb-4eb5-bf93-2835dfa79f8f.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 04:50:41', '2025-05-06 08:19:15', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (895, 'Dutton Hits 15th Servo, Still No Policy in Tank', 'Peter Duttons campaign tour has become a servo safari15 petrol station stops, zero costings, and a whole lot of photo ops. Meanwhile, Albanese flexes Medicare', 'At this point, Peter Duttons campaign strategy seems to be: fill up at every servo in Australia and hope voters mistake it for a plan. The man has now posed at 15 petrol stations15!without releasing a single costed policy. Its giving Wheres Wally? but with hi-vis and a media team.\n\nMeanwhile, Albanese rolled into the National Press Club like the kid who actually did the homework. He brought receipts: spruiking a drop in core inflation, Medicare improvements, and literally begging voters to let me finish what I startedwhich sounds romantic until you remember it involves Centrelink wait times and broken housing targets. But at least he showed up.\n\nDutton? Hes been dodging scrutiny like its a flying thong. Not only did he skip the Press Club showdownbreaking bipartisan traditionhe also sent Pauline Hanson out like a budget Darth Vader to stir up culture war chaos in his place. Between her usual anti-Voice rants and Duttons tactical vanishing act, the Coalitions campaign is starting to look more like a Facebook comment section than a government-in-waiting.\n\nHeres the kicker: its election week. Voters are hungry for actual numbers, real plans, *anything* beyond a photo of a man pretending to know how to use a bowser. But Duttons playbook is full of vibes, vague threats, and more pit stops than progress. If Albanese is doing the responsible-dad routine, Duttons cosplaying as the angsty stepdad who buys you ice cream but never pays child support.\n\nOne guy brought stats. The other brought servo receipts. Sources:\nThe Guardian Australia (30 Apr 2025), News.com.au (30 Apr 2025), The Australian (30 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'dutton-hits-15th-servo-still-no-policy-in-tank', 'published', 'images/news/8d8c116d-dcec-4a22-bb3a-70288d1b476b.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 13:13:32', '2025-05-05 16:18:23', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (896, 'Australias Defence Plan: Hope China Doesnt Notice', 'Experts warn that both Albanese and Dutton are steering Australia into a geopolitical minefield. With AUKUS submarines and Trump back in the White House, our national security strategy seems to be: Close eyes, cross fingers.', 'If Australias national security strategy were a mood board, it would feature a blindfold, a submarine wishlist, and a nervous laugh. Experts are now waving red flags so hard theyre developing shoulder injurieswarning that both Albanese and Dutton are quietly marching us into a geopolitical meat grinder with all the grace of a three-legged emu.\n\nAlbanese is still flogging the AUKUS dream, a $368 billion underwater fantasy where submarines arrive sometime between maybe and never. Dutton, never one to be outdone, is pledging even deeper military entanglements with the US, because if theres one thing Australia loves more than overpriced defence contracts, its doing whatever Washington tells us while pretending were equals.\n\nAnd just when we thought it couldnt get more unhingedTrumps back. Thats right, the same guy who once threatened to nuke hurricanes now has his finger hovering over every strategic alliance weve got. With the US going full reality-TV sequel and China staring daggers across the Pacific, Australias plan appears to be: cling to the nearest superpower and *pray they return our texts*.\n\nNeither major party is levelling with voters about the risks. Theres no national debate, no clear articulation of what all this firepower is forjust a lot of chest-puffing and cash-burning while pretending our backyard isnt flammable. Security experts are calling this the most volatile strategic landscape since WWII. Canberras calling it Tuesday.\n\nSo here we are: quietly upgrading missiles, deepening ties with a possibly unstable ally, and poking at the worlds largest military without even offering snacks. Sleep tight, Australia. Sources:\nThe Guardian Australia (30 Apr 2025), The Australian (30 Apr 2025), ABC News (30 Apr 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'australias-defence-plan-hope-china-doesnt-notice', 'published', 'images/news/3a994e8a-b03c-4ca0-89ed-ef0c2a0e4cd3.webp', NULL, '2025-04-30 13:13:32', '2025-05-06 09:01:55', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (897, 'Dutton Buys 28 Jets, Still Cant Land a Plan', 'The Coalitions genius move to win votes? Drop $17 billion on F-35s while pretending nurses, renters, and teachers dont exist. Duttons military cosplay continuesjust without the strategy manual.', 'Peter Dutton just dropped a casual $17 billion on 28 new F-35 fighter jetsa purchase so wildly tone-deaf it might as well have come with a commemorative Top Gun jacket and a rejection letter from the Budgeting Department. While voters scream for housing, hospitals, and help, Duttons campaign takes flight straight into the nearest military fantasy novel.\n\nThe man of the hour? Peter Servo Safari Dutton, who apparently thinks foreign policy can be solved with cosplay and credit cards. Not content with awkwardly loitering at petrol stations or dodging debates like potholes, Dutton has now decided to wage an election campaign from the cockpit of Lockheed Martins latest toys. Meanwhile, Albanese is trying to be the adult in the room, flexing Medicare stats while desperately hoping no one notices hes also playing musical chairs with national security.\n\nThis jet-buying bonanza isnt new. Its part of the Coalitions tough guy package dealmilitary might over social might. The F-35 program has been Australias money pit since Howard days, guzzling funds faster than a Defence Department wine fridge. Yet here we are again, burning through billions while teachers drown in unpaid overtime and renters take crash courses in tent life.\n\nThe kicker? These jets wont even land until the 2030s. So, were not buying defencewere buying vibes. Geopolitical threats are rising, sure, but apparently the best response is preorder now, panic later. No strategy. No costing clarity. Just another Dutton detour into security theatre, featuring fog machines, flags, and fiscal gaslighting.\n\nAs of today, Defence confirms the purchase. Dutton insists its essential, while voters wonder if essential includes food or rent. Labors pretending to scrutinise it, media coverage is already moving on, and democracy? Still waiting on its boarding pass.\n\nSources: News.com.au, The Australian, ABC News (all 01/05/2025).', 0, 'factabot', 'dutton-buys-28-jets-still-cant-land-a-plan', 'published', 'images/news/23c66bf5-5609-4a25-8af9-2e6fb7ce73e5.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 08:01:15', '2025-05-06 00:30:07', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (898, 'RBA Prepares Rate Cut, World Prepares Tiny Violin', 'Inflations down, the RBA wants applause, and Australians are still broke. Cool story. Wake us when the rent drops or groceries stop costing a kidney.', 'The Reserve Bank is thinking about maybe, possibly, one day cutting interest ratesand wants a standing ovation for it. After squeezing households with rate hikes like it was some kind of national sport, the RBA is now teasing relief like a slow-drip coffee: overpriced and underwhelming. Inflation\'s finally eased, but so has public trust in anyone wearing a suit with economist on the business card.\n\nCue RBA Governor Michele Bullock, the new queen of cautious optimism, dangling a rate cut like its the golden ticket out of economic purgatory. After months of insisting pain was necessary, she now whispers sweet nothings about wage growth and easing cost pressures. Meanwhile, Australians are still paying $8 for cereal, $40 for petrol, and half a lung for rent. But heythanks for the vibes.\n\nLets rewind: after going full throttle on rate hikes to curb post-pandemic inflation, the RBA turned everyday expenses into boss-level survival challenges. Mortgages exploded. Rents detonated. Groceries became black-market commodities. And now, with inflation easing to a better 3.6%, they want us to believe this is mercy. Spoiler: its not.\n\nThis softening inflation moment is less a miracle and more a technicality. Core inflation is down, but real people are still down bad. Wages havent caught up, housing\'s still a gladiator arena, and essential services are underfunded. Its not an economic comebackits a slower collapse.\n\nToday, Bullock hinted that the RBA might shift its stance in coming months. Translation: dont get excited. Nothings happening yet. But the headlines will scream hope, the markets will twitch, and politicians will pretend the system works. Just dont ask why povertys still trending.\n\nSources: ABC News, The Guardian, AFR, 9News (all 01/05/2025).', 0, 'factabot', 'rba-prepares-rate-cut-world-prepares-tiny-violin', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-01 08:01:16', '2025-04-30 20:01:15', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (899, 'Vote Now or Miss Kick-Off: NRL Fans Held Hostage by Democracy', 'Magic Round meets civic duty as the AEC begs footy fans to vote early. Because nothing screams healthy democracy like polling stations next to beer tents and body paint.', 'Democracy just got tackled by footy. With the NRLs Magic Round kicking off the same weekend as early voting, the Australian Electoral Commission is now begging fans to vote before they get blackout drunk in a novelty jersey. Because nothing says civic engagement like casting a ballot with your face half-painted like a Storm supporter and a sausage sizzle stain on your shirt.\n\nThe AECs newest strategy? Desperation with a side of body glitter. Commissioner Tom Rogers has practically thrown himself at NRL fans, warning them that unless they vote early, they might have to choose between democracy and kickoff. (Spoiler: democracy loses that match every time.) The AEC even dropped a press release reminding people that voting is compulsory and magic isnt an excusewhich is frankly the most Australian sentence ever written.\n\nThis all comes as Brisbane preps for its three-day football frenzythousands descending on Suncorp Stadium, ready to cheer, chug, and definitely not think about national policy. With 100,000+ fans expected, the AEC is right to be nervous. Last election, people forgot to vote because they were too busy binge-watching Netflix. Now theyve got actual beer tents to distract them? Good luck.\n\nBut this chaos says more than footy fans are forgetful. It shows how fragile our civic habits really are. We trust voters to decide the countrys futurebut only if it doesnt clash with their teams warm-up. Maybe the real ballot should be between Peter Dutton and the Roosters.\n\nToday, the AEC launched a last-ditch reminder blitz urging Queenslanders to vote before Magic Round. Will it work? Or will thousands wake up Monday morning, hungover and fined $20 for ghosting democracy?\n\nSources: News.com.au, ABC Sport, SBS News, The Guardian (all 01/05/2025).', 0, 'factabot', 'vote-now-or-miss-kick-off-nrl-fans-held-hostage-by-democracy', 'published', 'images/news/081d0b2c-3272-4b12-8862-753acb66b9dd.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 08:01:17', '2025-05-05 08:52:23', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (900, 'Pub Mogul\'s $500k Hangover: Cheers to Financial Ruin', 'Jon Adgemis, once a prominent pub owner, fails to meet a $600,000 creditor payment deadline, paying only $100,000 by May 1. With a $6.7 million payment looming in September, his financial empire teeters on collapse.', 'Jon Adgemis, Sydneys former pub prince turned finance fugitive, has managed to cough up just $100,000 of the $600,000 he owed by May 1. That leaves a casual $500k still hanging in the breeze, making his creditors wonder if the next round of repayments will come via bank transfer or a GoFundMe. Its the latest stumble in whats becoming a spectacular fall from hospitality royalty to financial Houdini.\n\nAdgemis, who once presided over a beer empire stretching from Bondi to Balmain, is now better known for ghosting invoices than pouring pints. The $600k was part of a $1 million settlement with former employeesaka the people he apparently forgot to pay during his pub-palooza expansion days. And this isnt even the main course: a $6.7 million payment looms in September, a financial finale no ones betting on.\n\nLets be clearthis isnt just one rich guy juggling bills. Adgemis built a high-profile pub empire under Public Hospitality Group, expanding aggressively while wages allegedly went MIA and rent bills got the silent treatment. Its now a slow-motion implosion, with creditors lining up like its Centrelink for the rich. He claims the delays are due to refinancing. His staff likely call it something else.\n\nWhats wild is how common this scripts become: glitzy business figure lives large, pays late, blames the spreadsheet. All while everyday workers eat the fallout. Adgemis case is just another example of how corporate settlements often mean eventually, maybe, if you\'re lucky.\n\nAs of now, hes five hundred grand short and four months away from a $6.7 million crunch. If this were a pub tab, hed be barred.\n\nSources: The Sydney Morning Herald, AFR, The Australian (all 01/05/2025).', 0, 'factabot', 'pub-moguls-500k-hangover-cheers-to-financial-ruin', 'published', 'images/news/7631954b-5868-4ebb-8afa-e3302c74c558.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 08:01:18', '2025-05-06 23:01:08', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (901, 'Albo and Dutton\'s Defense Duet: Who Can Spend More?', 'Both major parties unveil hefty defense spending plans ahead of the election, with Labor committing $50.3 billion and the Coalition proposing a more aggressive military posture, including 28 new F-35A jets.', 'Peter Dutton and Anthony Albanese just turned the election into an arms raceliterally. With Defence now the hottest campaign accessory, both leaders are hurling billions like confetti at a military-themed wedding. Labors strutting in with a $50.3 billion defence package, while Duttons gone full Rambo, ordering 28 F-35A jets like its an Uber Eats binge.\n\nAlbo, usually the cardigan of politics, is now trying on a flak jacket. His pitch? Spend big, look serious, hope no one notices hospitals are dying and schools need CPR. Meanwhile, Duttons cosplay continues, posing as Defence Daddy while ignoring the small talklike, you know, where the moneys coming from.\n\nThis isnt about security. Its about chest-puffing in front of voters whove seen too many TikToks about China. Both parties are pretending national power equals bigger toys, while renters and nurses scream into the void. The media claps, experts mutter strategic posture, and no ones asking if submarines fix housing.\n\nToday, both parties unveiled their defence packages in separate pressers that couldve been a duet. Australias war chest is open, the chequebook is crying, and the rest of us are stuck choosing which militarised fantasy hurts less.\n\nSources: News.com.au, The Guardian, AFR (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'albo-and-duttons-defense-duet-who-can-spend-more', 'published', 'images/news/de8e3010-d6b9-40a5-ac10-91cb5afede3f.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 08:01:19', '2025-05-06 03:28:55', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (902, 'NRL\'s Hotel Hustle: Accor Scores Big with Magic Round', 'The NRL extends its partnership with hotel giant Accor through 2027, securing accommodations for teams and officials. The deal boosts Brisbane\'s economy as Magic Round kicks off, filling 19 hotels with fans and players.', 'The NRL just locked in its hotel hookup with Accor until 2027because nothing says sport like corporate room service and branded mini soaps. As Magic Round kicks off, 19 Brisbane hotels are now filled with players, fans, and probably a few overcooked sausages.\n\nIts a win for Accor, the company that owns more Novotels than youve had beers at Suncorp. And its a win for the NRLs marketing team, whove managed to turn football into a three-day tourism ad. Brisbanes economy gets a boost, fans get selfies, and every ibis gets trashed by 10pm.\n\nThe real magic? How smoothly sport and capitalism hold hands. While tickets sell out and beers sell fast, theres not a whisper about the NRLs own financial dramas or the rent prices locals now pay to live near the fun. But hey, the footys on and the lights are brightwho needs nuance?\n\nTodays news confirms: the NRL knows how to throw a party. Whether its sustainable, ethical, or even smart? Who cares. Theres footy and fresh towels.\n\nSources: The Australian, 9News, ABC Sport (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'nrls-hotel-hustle-accor-scores-big-with-magic-round', 'published', 'images/news/70232a8c-f377-4481-b54a-0e3ef16f70d3.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 08:01:20', '2025-05-07 04:32:53', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (903, 'Auckland FC\'s Victory: Too Good for the AFC', 'Despite clinching the A-League Premier\'s Plate, Auckland FC can\'t compete in the AFC Champions League due to its Oceania Football Confederation affiliation. The club eyes the proposed OFC Professional League as a consolation.', 'Auckland FC just won the A-League Premiers Plate only to be told they cant compete in the AFC Champions League. Why? Because geography is a vibe and Aucklands in the wrong football club. Apparently, being in the Oceania Football Confederation makes them too other for Asias elite.\n\nIts like getting crowned valedictorian and then banned from graduation. Auckland dominated the A-League, but the AFC rules say: thanks, but no thanks. Their consolation prize? Possibly joining the proposed OFC Pro Leagueaka the maybe-one-day fantasy league of the Pacific.\n\nThis isnt just a snub. Its a bureaucratic own goal. Auckland FC plays better football than most AFC teams on a Tuesday, but legacy rules and old-school borders still decide whos allowed in the club. FIFA watches from the sidelines like a parent pretending not to have favourites.\n\nAs of today, Auckland FCs best hope is a hypothetical new league and a vague pat on the back. Champions, yes. International relevance? Still pending.\n\nSources: News.com.au, The Guardian Sport, SBS (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'auckland-fcs-victory-too-good-for-the-afc', 'published', 'images/news/13113c81-3829-4fea-8895-2ab709467c21.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 08:01:21', '2025-05-07 07:10:36', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (904, 'Clive Palmer\'s Text Tsunami: Australia\'s Newest Digital Menace', 'Clive Palmer\'s Trumpet of Patriots party has inundated Australians with unsolicited political text messages ahead of the May 3 federal election. The messages, lacking opt-out options, have sparked widespread public outrage', 'Clive Palmer is backlike a ghost in your phone planblasting out unsolicited political texts with the subtlety of a chainsaw alarm clock. Australians from Broome to Bondi woke up this week to find their phones hijacked by Palmers Trumpet of Patriots party, a name that already sounds like it came from a rejected Marvel spinoff. The kicker? No unsubscribe button. Just vibes. And rage.  Palmer, whos somehow still allowed within 500 metres of a political campaign, has dusted off the same tactic he used in 2019bombarding voters with SMS spam under the guise of free speech. Its less democracy, more digital door-knocking without the decency to leave. No one asked for this. No one consented to this. But Clives coming anyway, armed with emoji-level patriotism and what feels like the entire Yellow Pages of mobile numbers.  This isnt some rogue stuntits a pattern. Palmer spent $80 million in 2019 to not win a single seat. But the goal was never winningit was warping the conversation, flooding the zone, and trolling the electorate into submission. Now, his new Trumpet party (yes, really) is trying the same playbook: maximum noise, minimum accountability.  Theres no opt-out, no transparency, and no shame. Just a billionaire weaponizing loopholes in political communication laws to yell into your phone like a drunk uncle at a wedding. The AEC says political messages are exempt from spam laws. Which means if youre angry? Too bad. The laws on Team Clive.  As of today, inboxes across Australia are still under siege. Palmer hasnt apologisedbecause of course he hasntand theres no sign the texts will stop before May 3. So if you hear a digital trumpet blaring? Its not democracy. Its Clive Palmers ego, dialled to max.  Sources: ABC News, The Guardian, 9News, SBS (01/05/2025).', 0, 'factabot', 'Clive_Palmer\'s_Text_Tsunami:_Australia\'s_Newest_Digital_Menace', 'published', 'images/news/7054cdb5-a07e-4a4d-9bfa-2f82203e0d20.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 08:01:22', '2025-05-05 21:48:59', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (905, 'Labor Set to Annihilate Coalition Like It\'s 1946 and Dutton Invented Polio', 'The latest YouGov poll says Labors not just winningits dropkicking the Coalition into the historical abyss. With projections giving Albo 84 seats to Duttons sad 47, this isnt an election, its a public execution with polling booths.', 'If elections were sporting events, this ones shaping up like a televised beheading. The latest YouGov poll has Labor annihilating the Coalition in a landslide so brutal it could qualify as historical trauma. Were talking 1946 levels of wipeoutback when Chifley crushed it and Peter Dutton was still several decades from inventing modern charisma black holes.\n\nAccording to the numbers, Labors projected to win 84 seats, while the Coalitions clinging to 47 like its a lifeboat on the Titanic. Greens snag 13, and teal independents are lurking like stylish assassins in the marginals. Dutton, meanwhile, is still wandering between servos and security briefings, hoping nobody notices hes running a vibes-only campaign powered by fighter jets and press conference side-eyes.\n\nThis poll isnt just badits how-is-this-man-still-standing bad. The Coalitions entire pitch has been cost-of-living panic, border security chest-thumping, and we swear were not the Morrison government again. But voters arent buying it. Albos campaign is cruising on Medicare tweaks, child care wins, and just enough competence to make people feel like they dont live inside a failed state.\n\nWhat this says is clear: Australias not just leaning Labor. Its dragging the Coalition behind the bike shed and stealing its lunch money. YouGovs results show a country thats over the culture wars, over the fake strongman routine, and deeply over Peter Duttons haunted thumbtack energy.\n\nAs of today, Labor is barrelling toward majority rule, while Duttons hoping for divine intervention, a rogue asteroid, or Clive Palmers text army to save the day. Early voting starts this week. Expect panic. And possibly tears.\n\nSources: The Guardian, ABC News, News.com.au (01/05/2025).', 0, 'factabot', 'labor-set-to-annihilate-coalition-like-its-1946-and-dutton-invented-polio', 'published', 'images/news/e9614001-bfb0-4553-8f61-4a121e6029bd.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 10:25:42', '2025-05-06 06:31:00', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (906, 'Dutton Drops $10B Cuts Like Its a Party Trick and Were the Piata', 'In a last-minute act of budgetary cosplay, Peter Dutton revealed a plan to slash $10 billion from services, scrap tax cuts, and sack public servants. Because whats a campaign without some light financial terrorism?', 'Peter Dutton just pulled a $10 billion disappearing actand surprise! Its your public services that got vanished. In the most chaotic budget reveal since someone let Joe Hockey near a calculator, Dutton announced plans to cut $10B, torch stage three tax cuts, and give public servants their marching orders. All part of his last-minute pitch to voters: less government, more chaos, and a free side of economic anxiety.\n\nThe Liberal leader is calling it fiscal responsibility. The rest of us are calling it financial arson. Slashing essential services right before an election is bold. Or desperate. Or both. Duttons logic? The countrys in crisis, so lets remove the people who actually run it. Nurses, teachers, welfare workersline up! Youre now budget line items marked too expensive.\n\nAnd of course, it wouldnt be a Coalition campaign without recycling that old classic: Labor will bankrupt the nation. Never mind that Duttons own plan reads like a neoliberal fever dream and includes zero detail on what gets the axe. Is it Centrelink? Schools? The few remaining staff still answering your tax questions after 40 minutes on hold?\n\nThis is budgetary cosplay at its worst. No modelling, no costings, just vibes and violence. The announcement dropped like a flaming cocktail into an already furious electorateone still reeling from mortgage hikes, rental hell, and the sense that no politician understands how life actually works.\n\nToday, Dutton doubled down on the cuts while accusing Labor of economic vandalism. Which is rich, coming from a guy pitching a plan that could gut services like a butcher on speed. Labor responded with alarm, economists responded with confusion, and voters? Mostly responded by muting their TVs and texting wtf to their group chats.\n\nSources: News.com.au, The Guardian, ABC Politics, AFR (01/05/2025).\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'dutton-drops-10b-cuts-like-its-a-party-trick-and-were-the-pinata', 'published', 'images/news/65ce4cad-fa5c-4bb9-8458-58f217d3348b.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 10:25:42', '2025-05-06 06:13:24', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (907, 'Albos $8B Medicare Blitz: 24/7 Health While Dutton Crashes the Ambulance', 'Albanese just flung $8 billion at Medicare like Oprah on election steroidsfree hotlines, bulk-billing, round-the-clock advice. Meanwhile, Duttons plan for health is... mostly coughing in a servo and hoping for the best.', 'Anthony Albanese just went full Oprah on MedicareYou get a hotline! You get a GP! You get 24/7 bulk billing!dropping a cool $8 billion on a healthcare blitz designed to make voters believe the system isnt already on life support. Its the biggest Medicare shake-up in decades, and the timing? Immaculate. Early voting opens this week. Coincidence? Please.\n\nThe $8B package includes 58 walk-in urgent care clinics, 29 new mental health centres, and round-the-clock access to virtual GPsfinally answering the age-old question: Why does my sore throat only get worse after 6pm? Albo is out here making health sound like an Uber app: fast, on-demand, and hopefully not charging $300 to arrive late.\n\nOn the other side, Peter Dutton continues his one-man campaign to make ambulances feel like a luxury. The Coalitions health offering is basically a vibe: slashing spending, scrapping public service jobs, and whispering personal responsibility into the void. Its a health plan by people who think sick days are for cowards and empathy is optional.\n\nThis isnt just about medicine. Its about narrative. Albos selling hope and help. Duttons selling austerity and vague economic fear. And voters? Theyre stuck deciding between a fully-funded Medicare future or rolling the dice with a party whose track record includes gutting public hospitals and pretending bulk-billing wasnt already a crime scene.\n\nToday, Labor unveiled the full policy with classic big-stage fanfare, while Dutton dodged questions like he was avoiding a cough test. Health professionals welcomed the boost. The AMA nodded. Voters exhaled. And somewhere, a Coalition strategist is wondering if maybe 28 fighter jets wont cure chronic illness after all.\n\nSources: News.com.au, The Guardian, ABC Health, SBS (01/05/2025).', 0, 'factabot', 'albos-8b-medicare-blitz-247-health-while-dutton-crashes-the-ambulance', 'published', 'images/news/725c0504-cf47-4484-86ff-6212fc2ec4a7.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 10:25:42', '2025-05-06 06:31:26', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (908, 'Evicted Again? Victorias Rental Crisis Is the Ex You Cant Escape', 'Renters in Victoria are getting booted faster than a pub goer without shoes. Evictions are spiking, affordability\'s a myth, and the housing market is now just Hunger Games with real estate agents.', 'Victorias rental crisis has officially gone from grim to gaslighting. Evictions are spiking, rent is skyrocketing, and for thousands of renters, the only thing more common than a rent increase is getting handed a notice to vacate. Its like the states housing market read Squid Game and said, Hold my beer.  The datas brutal: a surge in \"no-fault\" evictions is booting renters mid-lease, often to make way for higher-paying tenants or quick cash grabs by landlords. Victorian tenancy laws were supposed to make that harderguess what? Loopholes are now the hottest property in town. If youve got a pet or a pulse, good luck staying housed.  Meet your typical victim: young families, students, low-income workersaka people already spending 4060% of their income just to keep a roof over their heads. The only thing growing faster than rental prices is the anxiety that your next inspection might turn into an eviction party. And dont expect much helptribunals are backlogged, and crisis accommodation is so full it might start charging rent itself.  The bigger picture? This isnt just about greedy landlordsits about a state (and country) that treats housing like a hedge fund. Supply is strangled, planning is a mess, and policies are written with more sympathy for investors than actual humans. Meanwhile, the government rolls out token reforms and affordability packages that wouldnt cover a night in a shed in Footscray.  As of today, renters are protesting, advocacy groups are pleading, and politicians are dodging the issue like its got bedbugs. Housing Minister Harriet Shing says changes are coming. Renters say, So is our next eviction notice.  Sources: The Age, ABC News, 9News, Domain (01/05/2025).', 0, 'factabot', 'Evicted_Again_Victorias_Rental_Crisis_Is_the_Ex_You_Cant_Escape', 'published', 'images/news/e086f12c-4f56-4f10-8de9-7129a017c026.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 10:30:07', '2025-05-01 10:31:15', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (909, 'Shanghai Airport Now a Hunger Games Arena', 'May Day holiday turns Pudong into a human traffic simulation gone rogue. Over 100,000 people clawing through terminals like its the last plane out of dystopia. Who needs leisure when youve got shoulder-to-shoulder chaos and one bathroom per terminal?', 'Welcome to Shanghai Pudong International Airportnow officially rebranded as District 13: Terminal Mayhem. Over the May Day holiday, more than 100,000 people tried to fly out of Chinas busiest hub, turning the terminal into a live-action survival sim with overpriced snacks and one bathroom per thousand souls. Forget leisurethis was gladiator travel, with check-in queues longer than most marriages.\n\nTravellers reported chaos, delays, and baggage carousels moving slower than local GDP. Security lines? Bring a sleeping bag. Flight gates? Barely visible through the sea of selfie sticks and shouting uncles. And with only a fraction of staff working full capacity, it wasnt a terminalit was a trap.\n\nWhy the madness? Blame the pent-up travel itch post-pandemic, the national obsession with squeezing all leisure into one holiday, and a system totally unequipped to deal with its own marketing. Airports were swamped, high-speed trains overbooked, and people still dared to call it a vacation.\n\nAs of today, officials say things are under control, which is usually code for we stopped counting the complaints. If youre heading to Pudong, bring snacks, patience, and maybe a flare gun.\n\nSources: China Daily, SCMP, Caixin (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'shanghai-airport-now-a-hunger-games-arena', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-01 12:20:47', '2025-05-01 12:20:47', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (910, 'IMF Upgrades China by 0.1%  Nation Immediately Celebrates with Fireworks and Patriotic Yawns', 'Chinas economy got the tiniest gold star from the IMFlike getting an A+ in breathing. Markets barely blinked. Officials clapped anyway. Nothing says \'strong fundamentals\' like a decimal-point pity bump.', 'The IMF gave China a whole 0.1% GDP upgrade, and Beijing responded like it just won the World Cup. Banners went up, officials clapped, and state media rolled out the ticker-tape. The actual bump? From 4.5% to 4.6%basically the economic equivalent of a polite shrug.\n\nThis boost was credited to stimulus policies, infrastructure splurges, and good old-fashioned number massaging. But markets barely blinked. Investors know the drill: debt is still sky-high, consumption is meh, and exports are about as lively as a state-run TikTok campaign.\n\nStill, Beijing took the win. Because when the economys wheezing, any decimal counts. Officials spun the uptick as proof of strong fundamentals, even as youth unemployment quietly disappears from reports and local governments auction off parking spots to stay solvent.\n\nAs of today, the IMF politely suggested things are stabilising. And in return, China sent back a thank-you card and 12,000 news articles. Please clap.\n\nSources: SCMP, Caixin, China Daily (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'imf-upgrades-china-by-01-nation-immediately-celebrates-with-fireworks-and-patriotic-yawns', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-01 12:20:47', '2025-05-01 12:20:47', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (911, 'Xi Says Unity!  Everyone Pretends Theyre Not Broke', 'In classic long-speech, no-detail fashion, Xi Jinping calls for national unity while the economy quietly sweats in the background. Austerity never sounded so majesticor so mandatory.', 'President Xi Jinping took the mic this week with another rousing speech about national unity, shared purpose, andwait for iteconomic resilience. Translation: stop complaining, were all in this austerity boat together. Ignore the sinking.\n\nIn classic Xi fashion, the speech was long on vision and short on detail. The tone was majestic, the message subtle: work harder, want less, smile more. He invoked slogans like high-quality development while local governments quietly sold off assets like a desperate eBay seller on a deadline.\n\nBehind the velvet rhetoric? An economy nursing bruises: debt overload, local defaults, a property sector still twitching. But none of that made it into Xis speech. Instead, he talked about innovation and disciplinewhich is basically code for dont ask questions.\n\nToday, state media plastered the speech everywhere, analysts sighed, and citizens watched it the way you watch a dentist explain a root canal: politely, while wondering how much its going to cost.\n\nSources: SCMP, Xinhua, China Daily (01/05/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'xi-says-unity-everyone-pretends-theyre-not-broke', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-01 12:20:47', '2025-05-01 12:20:47', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (912, 'China Lasers the Moon Because, Frankly, Earths Too Depressing', 'Scientists bounce lasers off the moon in broad daylightbecause when rent, youth unemployment, and WeChat censorship get too much, shoot your feelings into space.', 'China has officially had enough of Earths nonsense and is now firing lasers at the moon. Scientists in Shanghai just pulled off a world-first by bouncing a laser signal off our lunar ex and back in full daylight, which is either a physics breakthrough or the most dramatic emotional coping mechanism in history.\n\nThe Chinese Academy of Sciences called it a historic leap for optical communications. But lets be honest: its also a cosmic-level flex from a country where rent is unaffordable, youth unemployment is edited out of existence, and censorship algorithms read your texts faster than your mum. When you cant scream online, you scream into space.\n\nTechnically, this project is part of Chinas deep-space comms researchlaying the groundwork for future moon bases, satellites, or a backup escape hatch if Earth continues acting up. But the symbolism is hard to miss: while daily life gets more dystopian, the national gaze is fixed skyward, trying to bounce hope off a lifeless rock.\n\nThis experiment required pinpoint precisionbecause apparently, we can hit the moon with a beam of light but still can\'t fix public health clinics or unjam a bank app. It\'s the ultimate metaphor for modern governance: maximum tech muscle, minimum life improvement.\n\nOfficials hailed it as a major milestone. State media praised the fusion of spirit and science. Citizens mostly shrugged between power cuts, housing despair, and wondering when theyll be able to afford eggs again. But hey, weve got lasers.\n\nAs of today, the moon remains unfazed. Chinese scientists are ecstatic. And somewhere, a teenager is still locked out of their VPN.\n\nSources: China Daily, SCMP, Global Times (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'china-lasers-the-moon-because-frankly-earths-too-depressing', 'published', 'images/news/09a3adfe-9276-4d50-96a0-585b76bd24dd.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 12:20:47', '2025-05-02 21:00:51', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (913, 'China\'s Digital Index Hits Warp SpeedStill Cant Fix a Printer in a Government Office', 'Chinas digital transformation is racing into the metaverse while half the country still cant open a .zip file. The futures fast, but bureaucrats still fax your birth certificate.', 'China just declared victory in its great race to the digital frontier, with new data showing the countrys digital economy index rocketing to record highs. AI, blockchain, metaverse integration, quantum computingyou name it, its in a press release. On paper, its a tech utopia. In practice? You still need to physically line up to get your birth certificate stamped with a piece of rubber from 1993.\n\nOfficials are patting themselves on the back, claiming this transformation will streamline governance and empower citizens. Meanwhile, anyone whos visited a local bureau knows the real digital experience: a fax machine, a sticky desk, and a USB stick with exactly the wrong file format. The servers might hum, but the service still screams please return next Tuesday.\n\nLets get real: yes, China has digitised faster than almost any nation on earthmobile payments, facial recognition, and smart cities are now standard. But when you zoom in past the fireworks and metrics, reality hits: local governments still demand paper forms printed in triplicate. Half the public sectors tech budget is spent on blocking VPNs, not fixing systems. And good luck if you ever forget your login to a government appitll take six phone calls, two documents, and one existential crisis.\n\nThis is the paradox of Chinas digital rise: blazing-fast innovation layered on top of bureaucratic fossils. The apps work, the interfaces shine, but the logic is still trapped in the era of floppy disks and red stamps. Its like putting a jet engine on a rickshaw.\n\nAs of today, the government calls it progress. Citizens call it almost helpful. And somewhere, a low-level official is rebooting Windows XP for the third time.\n\nSources: China Daily, SCMP, Yicai (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'chinas-digital-index-hits-warp-speed-still-cant-fix-a-printer-in-a-government-office', 'published', 'images/news/4602a90d-79c0-432c-b419-54f456d27839.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 12:20:47', '2025-05-01 23:54:15', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (915, 'Trump Tanks Economy, Blames Biden, God, and Gravity', 'The U.S. economy just shrank 0.3% in Trumps first quarter back on the throne, and guess whos getting fingered for it? Not the guy who set off a tariff grenade?', 'Donald Trump just celebrated his return to the Oval Office by doing what he does best: breaking the economy and blaming someone else. In Q1 of 2025, the U.S. economy shrank 0.3%, and instead of even pretending to own it, Trump pointed fingers like hes playing fiscal Twisterleft hand on Biden, right foot on the Fed, head somewhere near Jupiter.\n\nThe man dropped tariffs on half the planet, spooked the markets like a haunted house DJ, and still had the audacity to say This was all Joes fault. If deflection were a currency, America would be in a surplus. But alas, the actual dollar is doing the fiscal equivalent of slow crying in the shower.\n\nCongress, meanwhile, tried to intervene, but the Senatenow starring a cast of MAGA diehards, Twitter reply guys, and lobbyist lapdogsshrugged and called it economic realignment. Translation: chaos is fine as long as it owns the libs. The Biden administrations warnings fell on ears too busy listening to Truth Social voice memos.\n\nLets be clear: the recession isnt just about bad policyits about vibes-based governance replacing actual expertise. The White House now runs like a group chat with no moderators and three guys arguing about gold bars and GameStop. Trump claims the economys just recalibrating. Economists call it steering off a cliff with no hands.\n\nAs of today, inflations twitching, Wall Streets in therapy, and Trump is back on the rally stage saying the downturn is what winning looks like. Hes also promised more tariffs, more accountability, and possibly replacing the Treasury Secretary with a Fox News anchor.\n\n2025s new motto? Recession, but make it patriotic.\n\nSources: The Guardian, CNN, Bloomberg, NPR (01/05/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-tanks-economy-blames-biden-god-and-gravity', 'published', 'images/news/6b417f23-c33b-4702-9dcc-bb83684ce550.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 12:35:33', '2025-05-05 13:11:27', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (916, 'Kamala Harris Rises From the Political Dead to Scream Dictator!', 'Kamalas backarmed with eyebrows and a microphonedropping constitutional red flags like a legal EDM festival.', 'Kamala Harris just emerged from the Democratic witness protection program to throw constitutional haymakers at Donald Trumpyelling dictatorship! like its the worlds most terrifying TED Talk. After months of whispers and wellness retreats, Harris grabbed a mic and dropped more red flags than a Soviet parade, warning America that democracy is now on life support and the GOPs holding the unplug cord.\n\nThe speech? Fire. The stakes? Higher. In a blistering appearance, Harris accused Trump of eroding democratic norms, weaponising the courts, and trying to replace PBS with propaganda. She didnt mince wordscalling his power grab a \"roadmap to autocracy\" while the White House drafts executive orders like horoscopes: vague, terrifying, and somehow about you.\n\nThe Democrats, meanwhile, are sipping herbal teas and pretending to brainstorm a response. But Harris? Shes done playing polite. She invoked the Constitution like it was gospel, slammed Trumps attempts to jail judges, gut the press, and rebrand public service as personal loyalty. It was the most life anyones seen from the party since 2022, when someone accidentally booked Rage Against the Machine for a fundraiser.\n\nContext matters: Trumps first 100 days back have been a masterclass in authoritarian speedrunning. Hes threatened civil servants, fired watchdogs, and flooded the airwaves with emergency broadcasts about restoring greatness, aka silencing dissent.\n\nToday, Kamala stepped upnot as VP-in-waiting, but as the last Democrat with a pulse. Whether itll shake her party out of its sedation is another story. For now, shes sounding the alarm. The question is: is anyone left listening?\n\nSources: The Guardian, Politico, CNN, NPR (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'kamala-harris-rises-from-the-political-dead-to-scream-dictator', 'published', 'images/news/2da7ebd4-a0f2-4c15-9817-c97ce7e034c3.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 12:35:33', '2025-05-01 23:52:36', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (917, 'U.S. Buys Ukraines Minerals, Calls It Allyship, Not Extraction', 'The U.S. just signed a minerals deal with Ukraine that looks a lot like post-war capitalism in a trench coat.', 'The U.S. just inked a shiny new minerals deal with Ukraine, and while its being branded as strategic support, it smells suspiciously like resource extraction with a flag on top. Yes, America will help rebuild Ukrainebut only if it gets first dibs on the lithium, cobalt, and rare earths buried under war rubble. Because nothing says solidarity like sniffing around your allys basement for valuables.\n\nThe deal was announced with patriotic fanfare and mutual smiles, but peel back the PR layer and its clear: Ukraines post-war recovery is now a shopping trip for U.S. corporations. State Department officials called it a win-win. Translation: America wins. Ukraine gets a ribbon and maybe a slightly repaired bridge.\n\nThis isnt new. Post-conflict capitalism is a genre at this point. From Iraqs oil to Afghanistans mining dreams, Washington has a long tradition of showing up with contracts in one hand and democratic platitudes in the other. Ukraine, bless it, is now the next showroom floor.\n\nTo be fair, Ukraine needs help. Its economy is rubble, its infrastructure bombed to bits, and the wars not even over. But when your reconstruction hinges on rare earth contracts and friendly geoeconomic vibes, its less about healing and more about harvesting.\n\nAs of today, the deal is being paraded as proof of U.S. commitment to Ukraines future. Critics are calling it neocolonialism with paperwork. Ukrainian officials insist theyll retain sovereignty. American firms are already pricing drills.\n\nIf this is allyship, it comes with interest rates, exclusivity clauses, and a clause that probably says no backsies.\n\nSources: The Guardian, SCMP, Reuters, Foreign Policy (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'us-buys-ukraines-minerals-calls-it-allyship-not-extraction', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-01 12:35:33', '2025-05-01 12:35:33', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (919, 'Albos Winning by a Landslide, Still Cosplaying Underdog in a High-Vis Vest', 'Anthony Albanese is crushing it in the polls, but insists hes \"still got a mountain to climb\"presumably while sipping espresso in a comfy government car. ', 'Anthony Albanese is steamrolling the Coalition in every poll like a tradie on a sugar high84 seats projected to the Coalitions sad little 47but youd never know it from the PMs Oscar-worthy underdog routine. Every press stop features him in a hi-vis vest, cradling a coffee like a battler clinging to hope, muttering about mountains to climb. Mate, if youre climbing a mountain, Peter Duttons stuck in a ditch with no ladder.\n\nThis isnt humilityits campaign cosplay. Albo is running as if hes polling at 12% and facing the ghost of Menzies. In reality, hes cruising on a Medicare boost, a mostly-coherent economic plan, and the blissful absence of Morrison. And yet, he insists the race isnt over, as if the only thing between him and total domination is a rogue Clive Palmer SMS.\n\nThe performance is tactical, of course. Voters hate arrogance, and Albos team knows that nothing turns off Australians faster than a politician who acts like theyve already won. But theres a difference between humility and hamming it. At this point, even tradies are wondering why the Prime Minister keeps dressing like hes about to fix a sink.\n\nAs of today, Albos campaign continues its victory lap disguised as a struggle bus. The hi-vis is still glowing. The espresso is still strong. And the Coalition? Still spiralling. If this is a tight race, then my names Peter Dutton and I just learned empathy.\n\nSources: The Guardian, ABC News, 9News (01/05/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'albos-winning-by-a-landslide-still-cosplaying-underdog-in-a-high-vis-vest', 'published', 'images/news/dde02912-8d09-4a96-a3a5-03158303465c.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 12:46:12', '2025-05-06 04:26:10', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (920, 'NSW Installs More Speed Cameras Than ToiletsWelcome to the Surveillance State', 'NSW has decided you cant be trusted with a steering wheel, a speed sign, or apparently your own thoughts. Privacy? Dead. Trust? Gone. Revenue-raising? Thriving.', 'Congratulations, NSWyouve officially out-surveilled yourself. The state is now rolling out average-speed cameras across its road network, proving once and for all that no moment of peace shall go unmonitored. Forget law enforcementthis is revenue-raising with a Bluetooth connection. You cant find a public toilet in Sydney, but youll get fined before you finish humming the first verse of Livin on a Prayer in your Corolla.\n\nTransport for NSW says its about safety. Translation: weve decided youre all criminally fast and emotionally unstable. The new system tracks how long it takes you to travel between two points, then auto-dobbs you in if you were even thinking about accelerating. Its like Big Brother, but with radar guns and a grudge.\n\nAnd before you ask: yes, motorcycles are included. Yes, theyll use AI. And no, you wont be able to argue your case to a human, because the whole system is fully automated. Orwell would be proud. Or terrified. Probably both.\n\nThe deeper problem? This is policy by punishment. Instead of fixing roads, funding better transport, or teaching drivers how not to tailgate, the government is just throwing more cameras at the problemand cashing in every time you sneeze near a 60 zone.\n\nAs of today, NSW drivers are entering a new era: every commute is a speed trap, every road a fiscal landmine. Privacy is now a punchline. Trust is toast. And somewhere in a dusty ministerial folder is a spreadsheet titled Projected Fine Revenue  2025 (LOL).\n\nSources: News.com.au, SMH, ABC Drive, Transport for NSW (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'nsw-installs-more-speed-cameras-than-toilets-welcome-to-the-surveillance-state', 'published', 'images/news/dc0154b0-c70d-4082-aca2-0a70c920fb54.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 12:46:12', '2025-05-07 01:25:35', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (921, 'Woolies Posts Profit Surge While Aussies Scavenge Discount Aisles Like Its the Apocalypse', 'Woolworths is raking it inturns out, selling 92-cent beans to broke millennials is a goldmine.', 'Woolworths just posted a profit surgebecause nothing screams strong economy like Australians bulk-buying home brand pasta like its nuclear winter. The supermarket giants earnings jumped as shoppers, battered by the cost-of-living crisis, abandoned brands faster than politicians abandon promises. Turns out, being broke is great for businessas long as you own the discount aisle.\n\nWhile Woolies execs sip artisan flat whites in boardrooms, everyday shoppers are crawling through specials like its the last episode of Survivor: Inflation Edition. Half-price toothpaste? Thats a win. $1 off noodles? Thats dinner. A promo on dog food? Congratulations, youre eating this week.\n\nThe company credits bargain hunting for its growth. Cute. What they mean is: We jacked the prices, then watched people celebrate saving 20 cents on overpriced Weet-Bix. Meanwhile, store shelves are starting to look more like a tactical survival zoneone where loyalty cards are your last hope and markdown stickers are currency.\n\nBehind the scenes, Woolworths is thriving. The profit bump confirms what we already suspected: economic collapse is just another quarterly KPI when you control essential goods. And if you dare raise an eyebrow? Dont worrytheyve got a new value campaign to tell you how much they care. Right next to the $12 frozen pizzas and $9 shampoo.\n\nAs of today, the retail giant is up, consumers are down, and Australias shopping experience has officially entered its dystopian clearance rack phase. But heyWoolies shareholders are smiling. And isnt that what groceries are all about?\n\nSources: News.com.au, The Australian Financial Review, ABC Business, 9News (01/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'woolies-posts-profit-surge-while-aussies-scavenge-discount-aisles-like-its-the-apocalypse', 'published', 'images/news/049f5a24-5a86-49c5-a1ff-13ef1bbafbb2.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 12:46:12', '2025-05-07 10:15:36', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (922, 'America Tanks, But HeyLook! China!', 'The US economy just tripped over its own tariffs, but instead of admitting their Frankenstein trade policy is eating itself alive, Team Trump is pointing at China and yelling factory fire! like a drunk arsonist blaming the smoke alarm.', 'Donald Trump has once again dusted off the classic Look Over There! strategythis time painting China as the Titanic of manufacturing, while the US quietly drowns in its own tariff bathwater. At a recent rally, Trump shrugged off warnings that tariffs are tanking supply chains and pushing prices up, casually suggesting American kids might just have two dolls instead of 30. Because nothing says economic strategy like telling broke parents to vibe with minimalism.  Behind the bluster, the real economic horror show is at home. The US GDP shrank 0.3% in Q1. Consumer confidence? Lower than your uncles crypto portfolio. Businesses are cutting jobs, shelves are emptying faster than common sense at a campaign rally, and even Wall Street is sweating like a hedge fund manager without insider tips. But rather than admit things are cooked, the Trump narrative is: Chinas collapsing! Factories are closing! Quick, someone ban TikTok again!  Meanwhile, China\'s manufacturing index did dipbut they\'re not exactly carting away factories in wheelbarrows. They\'re adapting, exporting less to the US, and opening plants elsewhereincluding, ironically, in America. Thats right: Chinese companies are setting up shop in the US while Washington pretends it\'s winning.  Its geopolitical gaslighting at its finest: sabotage your own economy, blame the other guy, and call it patriotism. If delusion was a commodity, the US wouldve traded its way out of recession by now.  4. Sources:  NYPost  WSJ  The Guardian', 0, 'factabot', 'America_Tanks,_But_HeyLook_China', 'published', 'images/news/2224985b-1416-4a6e-b76c-ffc70e0e078c.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 13:20:11', '2025-05-06 03:29:03', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (923, 'AUKUS Aint It, MateWere Buying Submarines for a War Well Watch on YouTube', 'Australia just signed a trillion-dollar group chat with the US and UK to buy submarines we might never use, for a war that wont come hereunless someones planning to invade with Google Maps and a time machine.', 'Lets get this straight: AUKUS is sold to us like its Marvels Phase 5 of defence strategy. Nuclear-powered subs, defence tech transfers, joint military operationsit sounds cool until you remember its our tax dollars funding this military cosplay while schools crumble and nurses strike. Our leaders are fawning over American approval like insecure high schoolers who got invited to sit at the cool kids lunch table, but forgot theyre the ones footing the bill.  And even if there was a warsay, a big showdown with China in the Taiwan Straithow exactly does a few fancy subs help us? Were thousands of kilometres away, we dont own the battleground, and wed still be relying on the US to do the heavy lifting. So why are we turning ourselves into a weapons storage locker with a target painted on top? Are we really \"sovereign\" if were renting out our land for foreign missile sites and defence contractors?  Meanwhile, our veterans cant get mental health support, housing is a dumpster fire, and our infrastructure looks like it was last updated during the Howard era. But sure, lets blow billions on subs that wont arrive until 2040by which time the war might be fought by drones and deepfakes anyway.  Whats really driving AUKUS? Political ego, strategic FOMO, and a desperate need to cling to Western alliances while pretending were not being used as a pawn. We need better strategyand fewer headlines that read like a Tom Clancy sequel no one asked for.  Sources:  ABC News: Australia to spend $368b on AUKUS subs  The Guardian: Experts question AUKUS value  SMH: Australias role in AUKUS and future conflicts', 0, 'factabot', 'AUKUS_Aint_It,_MateWere_Buying_Submarines_for_a_War_Well_Watch_on_YouTube', 'published', 'images/news/0f39b4ea-97b1-467d-82a9-3e24f190fdeb.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 13:26:00', '2025-05-06 09:33:03', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (924, 'Needles Out, Pharma In: Diabetes Cure Trial Triggers CEO Sweat', 'Scientists in Queensland just launched a world-first trial to *possibly* end insulin needles for Type 1 diabetics. Big Pharma execs reportedly choked on their yachts. Hope? Sky-high. Corporate sabotage? Pending.', 'Somewhere off the Gold Coast, a pharmaceutical exec just spat out his mimosa. Why? Because Queensland researchers just launched a world-first clinical trial for a pill that could end daily insulin injections for Type 1 diabetics. Translation: Big Pharma might soon lose its most profitable human subscription modelone jab at a time.\n\nThe team at Brisbanes St Vincents Institute of Medical Research, in partnership with biotech firm Encapsula, isnt just stirring the pottheyre threatening to smash the whole dinner set. Their trial involves an oral drug that could let the pancreas start working again without insulin shots. If this works, diabetics could stop pricking themselves like lab rats and maybe, just maybe, start living without carrying a pharmacy in their backpacks.\n\nLets not forget whos sweating the most: the corporate overlords whove turned diabetes into a multi-billion-dollar business. Theyve built empires on repeat prescriptions and insulin mark-ups so steep, youd think it was champagne. If needles go out of fashion, what happens to their yacht payments? Expect lawsuits, lobbying, or a mysterious research delay faster than you can say profit margins.\n\nThis trial matters. Its not just medical progressits rebellion. For years, innovations been handcuffed by monopoly medicine where curing people is a financial risk. A breakthrough like this threatens that golden goose. If successful, it could crack the code on chronic illness dependency and show that science can win when its not bought.\n\nToday, the team is recruiting patients and dosing courage. Tomorrow? They might spark a healthcare mutiny. But for now, Big Pharmas PR teams are probably Googling spin strategy and hoping no one asks why this wasnt possible sooner.\n\nSources:\n9News  Queensland Type 1 diabetes trial could eliminate need for insulin injections (01/05/2025)\nhttps://www.9news.com.au/national/queensland-type-1-diabetes-drug-clinical-trial', 0, 'factabot', 'needles-out-pharma-in-diabetes-cure-trial-triggers-ceo-sweat', 'published', 'images/news/d903d7c8-8aee-4cf9-ba22-0359513b335e.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 14:44:04', '2025-05-06 12:26:25', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (925, 'Lendlease Falls Off Builder List, Still Manages to Invoice Confidence', 'Lendleaseonce a golden child of Aussie constructionjust got booted from the top 50 builders list. But dont worry, theyre still building trust on LinkedIn and quarterly reports full of imagination.', 'Once the golden child of Aussie construction, Lendlease just got booted off the top 50 builders listand yet somehow, their press releases are still building castles in the sky. The company may not be topping construction charts anymore, but theyve clearly mastered architecture in the genre of delusion.\n\nLets name the flop: Lendlease, the same firm once trusted with Barangaroo, Olympic projects, and half the nations skyline, has slipped so far that Watpac just overtook them. Yes, Watpacthe quiet achiever who didnt spend years selling vision boards to investors. Lendlease, meanwhile, has been busy pivoting to urban regeneration and uploading mood boards to LinkedIn while their actual build rate nosedives.\n\nHeres the brutal truth: Lendlease offloaded its engineering arm, ditched Aussie projects for global growth, and somehow ended up with shrinking revenue and even less credibility. Shareholders? Not thrilled. Industry insiders? Rolling their eyes. The companys latest move? Holding firm to vague concepts like value creation and strategic resetcorporate for we stuffed it, but vibes are strong.\n\nThis isnt just a builder losing rank. Its a case study in how executive confidence can be inversely proportional to performance. Lendlease is still hosting investor briefings as if nothings broken, like a chef who burned dinner but insists the aroma is part of the experience. Meanwhile, actual construction firms are scrambling through economic quicksand, and clients are starting to ask: do you even build, bro?\n\nThe latest industry report shows them out of the top 50, replaced by firms who still, you know, build things. Lendleases response? Polished statements, aspirational diagrams, and the occasional vague pipeline of opportunity. Translation: theyre still constructing hopejust not housing.\n\nSources:\nThe Australian  Besix Watpac steps up amid tough times for builders (01/05/2025)\nhttps://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/property/besix-watpac-steps-up-amid-tough-times-for-builders/news-story/a58a7d485911d40e4aa0fb132709beae', 0, 'factabot', 'lendlease-falls-off-builder-list-still-manages-to-invoice-confidence', 'published', 'images/news/40d86175-bc38-49e8-bdb2-feab1386c6bd.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 14:44:04', '2025-05-06 11:08:31', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (926, 'Bakegate: When Your Recipes Are Just Someone Elses', 'Brooke Bellamys bake empire is crumbling faster than a defrosted lamington after plagiarism claims over her cookbook. She swears theyre originallike every cheater in a group assignment ever.', 'Brooke Bellamys cake empire is collapsing faster than an over-ambitious souffl, and no, its not because she forgot the baking powderits because she mightve borrowed the whole cookbook. The self-declared Queen of Cakes is now Australias most overcooked scandal after being accused of plagiarising recipes in her best-selling baking bible. Original? Only if youve never seen a pavlova before.\n\nThe woman who once graced morning TV like a butter-smeared deity is now dodging sharper questions than a MasterChef final. Her response? Denials baked to perfection: vague, defensive, and just slightly burnt. Bellamy insists the recipes are her own twist, but side-by-siders online show her twist is sometimes a missing comma and a cheeky rebrand. One fan even found a word-for-word copy of a lemon tart from a 2012 blog post by someone named GlutenFreeGeraldine. Yikes.\n\nLets get realthis isnt just some bakers tiff. Its the influencer-to-empire pipeline gone wrong. Bellamy built a brand on aesthetic aprons, family secrets, and butter-soaked nostalgia, but now the aprons slipping and the secret might be Google. The cookbook market is already stuffed with recycled content disguised as tradition, and Brooke might be the first to get caught with icing on her fingers.\n\nBusiness-as-usual continues at her bakerydoors open, cupcakes frosted, awkward silence piped on top. But the internets baking army isnt buying it. The plagiarism claims are being whisked around Reddit faster than meringue, and unless Bellamy brings receipts or actual originality, shes one piping bag away from full cancellation.\n\nAs of today, shes still posting baking tips like nothing happenedbecause denial, dear readers, is also a dish best served warm.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Controversial find at Brooke Bellamys bakery as its business as usual for the under-fire author (01/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/controversial-find-at-brooke-bellamys-bakery-as-its-business-as-usual-for-the-underfire-author/news-story/eb47e8bc4bf3ec0d726db25fe25a4cc8', 0, 'factabot', 'bakegate-when-your-recipes-are-just-someone-elses', 'published', 'images/news/37bb3adf-37a0-409e-82cc-25fdcafbbf16.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 14:44:04', '2025-05-07 01:25:46', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (927, 'Billionaire Buys Sydney\'s St Ives Shopping Village for $450M', 'Former panel beater turned billionaire Sam Arnaout has purchased the prestigious St Ives Shopping Village in Sydney for $450 million, marking Iris Capital\'s entry into large-scale shopping centres.', 'Sydneys leafy north just got a billionaire faceliftand no, its not Botox, its bricks. Sam Arnaout, once a humble panel beater, just dropped $450 million to buy St Ives Shopping Village like its a packet of gum. The man behind Iris Capital, better known for turning pubs into property empires, is now carving out his slice of suburban retail royaltywith a supermarket sandwich of Woolies, Coles, and Harris Farm.  Arnaouts glow-up story is every LinkedIn bros wet dream: went from buffing bonnets to buffing portfolios. But this isnt just a shopping centreits a 25,000 square metre power move. With 11 adjoining properties rolled in, Sam basically bought the neighbourhood. St Ives used to be a quiet retiree haven. Now its the latest tile in his Monopoly gameand someone just landed on Boardwalk.  For the property nerds, this marks Iris Capitals first flirtation with large-scale retail. For everyone else? Its another episode of Rich Men Buy the World: Suburb Edition. In a city suffocating from unaffordable housing, billionaires are now buying shopping centres like theyre Pokemon. Gotta catch em all and maybe raise the rent while theyre at it.  Dont get it twistedthis isnt just a win for Arnaout, its another red flag for the growing gentrification of Sydney. As locals fight to afford groceries, billionaires are out here investing in the places selling the groceries. The rich dont just own the landthey now own the shopping trolleys too.  No statement yet from Arnaout, but if historys any guide, youll see a slick press release, a few renovations, and rents climbing higher than his portfolio value. Welcome to St Ives: proudly brought to you by late capitalism and one mans unstoppable flex.  Sources: The Australian  Iris Capital buys Sydneys St Ives Shopping Village for $450m (01/05/2025) https://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/property/iris-capital-buys-sydneys-st-ives-shopping-village-for-450m/news-story/0aa67499f2143951eb3ae83f6bacc3df', 0, 'factabot', 'Billionaire_Buys_Sydney\'s_St_Ives_Shopping_Village_for_450M', 'published', 'images/news/3503b3ad-2f75-4c0e-b752-4fb466a01172.webp', NULL, '2025-05-01 14:51:38', '2025-05-05 17:21:59', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (928, 'Woolies Yeets Big W Perks, Customers Plot Revenge', 'Everyday Extra subscribers just found out Woolies is ghosting their 10% Big W discountand the betrayal stings harder than stale Anzac biscuits. Furious shoppers are already swiping Coles cards like divorcees on Tinder.', 'Congratulations Woolworths, youve officially entered your villain era. The supermarket giant just cancelled the 10% Big W discount for Everyday Extra subscribers, and Aussies are treating it like a national betrayalright up there with Tim Tam shrinkflation and Aldi checkout speed. Woolies says its a review, but shoppers are already storming Coles like its the French Revolution and Flybuys is the guillotine.\n\nLets name and shame: Woolworths CEO Brad Banducci, who recently claimed customers expect more value. Bold of him to say while yanking said value like a dodgy magician. The Everyday Extra program was supposed to be a feel-good subscription: free delivery, monthly discounts, and a warm fuzzy feeling that your loyalty meant something. Now? Its just $7 a month to be publicly mugged.\n\nThis isn\'t just about one perkit\'s the principle. Aussies are broke, inflations still punching everyone in the throat, and Woolies had the gall to gut one of the few tangible benefits while still posting billions in profits. Its a classic case of corporate gaslighting: tell us its enhancing value, then quietly take the cookie and blame the jar.\n\nHeres the kicker: customers arent taking it lying down. Social medias lit up with boycott posts, and Coles just became the rebound supermarket of the century. Woolies loyalty program may have just become the biggest self-own in retail since free returns met online shopping abuse.\n\nAs of today, the discount is dead. Woolies says itll offer new value, but unless that means free rent and therapy, were not buying it.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Shoppers furious as Woolies axes Big W discount (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/finance/business/retail/ridiculous-shoppers-furious-as-woolies-axes-big-w-discount/news-story/40a2b64eea404c3cd62dd7d9ee6e6aed\n', 0, 'factabot', 'woolies-yeets-big-w-perks-customers-plot-revenge', 'published', 'images/news/75cbe10b-a501-4092-9dd9-4c4dd71cd30e.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 17:21:06', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (929, 'Dutton Nukes Climate Budget, Shouts \'Jobs!\' Like Thats a Spell', 'Peter Back to the 50s Dutton just offered up a $30 billion climate backflipcutting clean energy and hugging nukes like theyre the future. It\'s the Coalition\'s version of greenas in envy of fossil fuel profits.', 'Peter Dutton just announced a $30 billion energy policy and its giving Mad Max with spreadsheets. The Coalitions new climate plan cuts clean energy like its a Netflix password and throws itself at nuclear reactors like a drunk ex. Forget net-zerothis is net-chaos, powered by uranium and vibes.\n\nAt the centre of the meltdown is Dutton, Australias unofficial Minister for the 1950s. Hes killing rooftop solar subsidies, slashing grid upgrades, and greenlighting nukes like its Chernobyl: The Sequel. His justification? Jobs. Because apparently, muttering jobs now magically cancels out carbon emissions, rising sea levels, and basic physics.\n\nThis policy isnt new thinkingits the fossil fuel fantasy with a radioactive rebrand. Nuclear power won\'t be online for decades, if ever. Meanwhile, renewable projects already exist, already work, and are already cheaper. But hey, theres no donor money in the sun. Instead, Duttons going full Cold War cosplay while pretending hes the saviour of the working class.\n\nLets be clear: this isnt about jobs, its about politics. Its red meat for the base, greenwashing for the headlines, and a giant middle finger to climate scientists. The fact that $30 billion is being spent on an energy plan that doesnt actually reduce emissions? Thats not a policyits performance art.\n\nLatest update: Dutton insists this is technology-neutral, which is political speak for we cut the future and fed it to the past. Labor says its dangerous. Experts say its a fantasy. And the planet? Its just getting warmer.\n\nSources:\nThe Australian  Coalitions $30bn climate change plan focuses on nuclear (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/election-2025-coalitions-30bn-change-of-climate-for-energy-market/news-story/0a626657a16f58056de165b976093ad5\n', 0, 'factabot', 'dutton-nukes-climate-budget-shouts-jobs-like-thats-a-spell', 'published', 'images/news/47db746a-af70-4dd7-9e46-7df2aad0d77a.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 04:26:41', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (930, 'Trump Sneezes, Aussie Economy Catches $13B Flu', 'Donald throws a tariff tantrum and suddenly Australias economy is the piata. The IMF just warned of a $13 billion slap, but surelet\'s keep pretending were in control of anything except housing bubbles.', 'Donald Trump threw a tariff tantrum and Australias economy just faceplanted into a $13 billion mess. One trade threat from Mar-a-Lago and suddenly were prepping for recession like its 2008 but with worse playlists. The IMF just downgraded our growth forecast and warned the RBA might be forced into rate cutsagain. Happy election season, suckers.\n\nLets not pretend Trump is some economic genius. The man once tried to nuke a hurricane. But the moment he hints at new tariffs, global markets sprint for the panic buttonand Australia, ever the obedient middle power, cops the fallout like the polite kid stuck next to a screaming toddler on a plane. Thanks to our export dependence, particularly on ChinaUS tension, any American brain-fart hits our GDP like a brick.\n\nThis isn\'t just about Trump being Trump. Its about how fragile our economy really is. Our leaders strut around with strong fundamentals while praying China buys more iron ore and America doesnt lose its marbles. Were basically playing economic Jenga with damp chopsticks and calling it stability.\n\nAnd now? The Reserve Banks talking downside risks, code for: dont get too comfy with those interest rates. Households already bleeding from cost-of-living pressures could be getting a temporary reprieveif you consider rate cuts a win while the rest of the economy free-falls.\n\nThe kicker? All it took was Trump opening his mouth. Again. Australia: so far from America, yet always one trade war away from a financial identity crisis.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Trump tariffs could hit Australia with $13b economic blow, IMF warns (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/finance/economy/interest-rates/downside-risks-trumps-tariffs-to-spur-on-rba-rate-cuts/news-story/1b3332d7425365f4f83ff81e41a02514', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-sneezes-aussie-economy-catches-13b-flu', 'published', 'images/news/5f6a6313-5237-4388-a704-07dc12ad307e.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 08:52:23', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (931, 'Essendons Ankle Budget Now in Crisis', 'Harrison Joness ankle folded like a Bunnings deckchair, and Essendons injury list now looks like a hospital ward for optimism. Coach says dont expect him back for a whilewhich is code for 2026, maybe.', 'Harrison Joness ankle just did a full-blown folding chair impression, and Essendons injury list now reads like a Greek tragedy sponsored by Voltaren. Coach Brad Scott says we shouldnt expect him back for a whilewhich in AFL language means somewhere between the next Ice Age and the invention of ankle cloning.\n\nJones, the 24-year-old forward with more potential than a crypto startup, went down in the Round 7 clash and stayed down like he was being charged rent to move. The slow-mo replay? Not for the squeamish. Think: shoe meets turf, turf wins, ankle loses. Fans screamed. Physios aged ten years. Hope evaporated.\n\nIts not just Jones. Essendons injury list is starting to look like the waiting room at a very depressed physio clinic. Hamstrings, knees, anklespick a body part, someones iced it. This isnt a team, its a medical drama. And still, somehow, theyre in the top eight. Barely. Probably thanks to the raw power of denial and strapping tape.\n\nWhy this matters? Because Essendon fans are riding high on decades of trauma, and just when the rebuild looked stable, the footy gods decided to play Jenga with their bones. Jones was part of the long-term plan. Now the plan is tape it up and pray.\n\nThe latest: Jones is out indefinitely, with a significant ankle injury. Which is code for yeah, mate, dont get comfy. Essendon insists theyll manage. We believe themright after we believe Collingwoods humble pie.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Essendon coach Brad Scott doesnt expect Harrison Jones back for a while (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/sport/afl/essendon-coach-brad-scott-doesnt-expect-to-see-young-gun-harrison-jones-for-a-while-after-horror-ankle-injury/news-story/d6d879001b5780690041abdca3425e13', 0, 'factabot', 'essendons-ankle-budget-now-in-crisis', 'published', 'images/news/c6f4b9fe-3983-44d5-8e94-8bec60295dfc.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 08:52:23', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (932, 'Cyclone Alfred Just Gave Australia a Wet Slap', 'Natures angry ex, Cyclone Alfred, crashed through Queensland and NSW like it had a grudge and no chill. Floods, chaos, property damagebasically a climate change mixtape on shuffle.', 'Cyclone Alfred rolled into Queensland and NSW like it had unfinished business and a personal vendetta. Streets became rivers, power lines dropped like iPhone signals in a tunnel, and rooftops learned how to fly. Alfred didnt arrivehe stormed in, handed everyone a soggy disaster, and left faster than government climate action.\n\nThe chaos hit from Townsville down to the Northern Rivers. Flash flooding wrecked homes, highways turned into slipnslides, and SES crews were stretched so thin you could see through them. Farmers lost crops, tradies lost roofs, and residents lost patience. Again. Because this isnt our first once-in-a-century weather tantrum this decade.\n\nLets talk names. Alfred might sound like your nans bridge partner, but dont be fooledthis thing slapped harder than rising insurance premiums. Emergency services were heroic. Politicians? Mostly airborne in helicopters, promising resilience while their climate policy still has cobwebs on it.\n\nHeres what no ones shouting: climate change isnt coming. Its here, in gumboots, wrecking barbeques and homes. And we keep building in flood zones like it\'s Monopoly and weve never heard of consequences. Every year its the same soggy scriptevacuations, shock, recovery, repeat.\n\nLatest? Clean-up begins, media packs up, and the federal government has offered supporttranslation: a press conference and maybe a cheque if you cry hard enough on camera.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Cyclone Alfred leaves damage across Queensland and NSW (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-05-02/cyclone-alfred-impact-queensland-nsw-damage', 0, 'factabot', 'cyclone-alfred-just-gave-australia-a-wet-slap', 'published', 'images/news/4ee6b580-f2b9-44db-a5c1-db63360a6313.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 18:51:35', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (933, 'Measles Is BackBecause Science Is Apparently Optional Now', 'NSW just caught a 90s throwback, and not the fun kind. A new measles outbreak is spreading like anti-vax Facebook posts in a boomer group. Health officials say get the jabanti-vaxxers say nah, vibes.', 'NSW has caught a throwback illness and no, its not nostalgia for Y2Kits measles. The disease we literally vaccinated out of existence has made a comeback thanks to Facebook science degrees and vibes-based parenting. Congratulations, weve officially looped back to the 1800s with Wi-Fi.\n\nHealth officials have confirmed a cluster of cases in western Sydney, all linked toshock horrorunvaccinated individuals. Thats right, Karen skipped the jab because essential oils and good energy and now entire schools are being notified like its the lottery you dont want to win.\n\nHeres the roll call of dumb: anti-vaxxers still peddling personal choice while completely ignoring the part where their choice exposes newborns, the elderly, and people with actual medical exemptions. Meanwhile, overworked doctors are reprinting fact sheets they thought theyd buried with SARS.\n\nThe truth is brutal: this outbreak was entirely preventable. Measles is one of the most contagious viruses on Earth, and it doesnt care if your Facebook group says youre immune through juicing. NSW Health is now chasing down contacts and urging jabs, while Reddits tinfoil army calls it fear-mongering.\n\nLatest update? Three new cases confirmed overnight. Expect more unless someone figures out how to vaccinate people against Dunning-Kruger syndrome.\n\nSources:\n9News  NSW measles outbreak prompts vaccine warning from health officials (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.9news.com.au/national/measles-outbreak-new-south-wales-vaccine-warning', 0, 'factabot', 'measles-is-back-because-science-is-apparently-optional-now', 'published', 'images/news/658d1fb3-39af-475d-acc9-400c07e06e9e.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 03:51:20', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (934, 'RBA Hints at Rate Cut, Pretends It\'s a Gift', 'The Reserve Bank is dangling a 0.25% cut like its Santa with a busted sleigh. After torching mortgages for two years, they now want applause for relief. Mate, thats like arsonists offering ice.', 'The Reserve Bank just winked at a possible 0.25% interest rate cut like its handing out golden tickets to Oz. After two years of slamming mortgage holders like a toddler with a toy hammer, the RBA now wants a standing ovation for whispering the word relief. Cute. Thats like an arsonist tossing you a damp sponge and expecting a hug.\n\nMichele Bullock, Australias top economic fire-starter, has been gently teasing the idea of a rate drop in the next few monthsemphasis on teasing. Its all data-dependent, which means theyll keep us dangling until someone screams loud enough. And with inflation finally simmering below 4%, the timing isnt charityits belated common sense.\n\nLets not forget: Aussie households have been financially waterboarded for 24 months. Mortgages doubled. Groceries tripled. Anxiety quadrupled. And now that the economys wheezing under the weight of their overcorrection, the RBAs rolling out a 0.25% crumb like its a damn Christmas miracle.\n\nThe systems cooked. Rate rises were never aimed at supermarkets gouging prices or landlords jacking rent. They just punished people trying to survive. And now, instead of accountability, we get trust us, were easing. Mate, your easing is barely enough to offset the interest on a toaster loan.\n\nThe latest? The RBA left rates on hold in May but hinted cuts could be coming soon. Translation: not this month, maybe next, maybe never. But dont worrytheyre monitoring the situation. With binoculars. From a yacht.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Australian households tipped to get rate relief after May RBA meeting (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/finance/economy/interest-rates/australian-households-tipped-to-get-rate-relief-after-may-rba-meeting/news-story/0dd19b0594a5a90fa308be2b07d7441c', 0, 'factabot', 'rba-hints-at-rate-cut-pretends-its-a-gift', 'published', 'images/news/e839d6db-7200-4312-a338-4a17cc653d9f.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 17:20:23', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (935, 'Hughesy Invited to Mel Bs Wedding, Nation Collectively Blinks', 'Dave Hughes is off to Mel Bs royal-tier wedding, and now the entire countrys Googling why him? Turns out being funny *and* available on short notice still gets you into Spice Girl circles.', 'In the biggest cultural crossover since Vegemite met avocado toast, Dave Hughesyes, that Hughesyjust scored an invite to Mel Bs wedding. Australias collective reaction? Wait, what? Because when we think Spice Girls, we dont think radio host with chronic dad energy.\n\nThe eternally nasal comedian and TV fixture is apparently on the VIP list for Scary Spices London nuptials. No word yet on whether hes MCing or just there for the cake, but either way, its proof that saying yes to every gig since 2002 eventually lands you a table near royalty. Or at least, one Spice Girl and her latest husband.\n\nMel B, whos managed to go from pop royalty to reality TV stardom and back again, clearly has eclectic taste. This is a woman who picked Eddie Murphy and The Masked Singer on the same CV. So maybe Hughesy fits? Still, its hard not to picture him cracking dad jokes at a $10,000-a-plate dinner while Victoria Beckham quietly clutches her clutch tighter.\n\nWhy this matters: it doesnt. But its funny as hell. In a country where most weddings are now postponed due to cost-of-living vibes, seeing Hughesy party with international celebrities is pure chaos energyand were here for it.\n\nLatest update: Hughesys confirmed hes going. No word on the outfit, but if he turns up in a Bonds tee, we riot.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Hughesy scores invite to huge celebrity wedding in London (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/radio/hughesy-scores-invite-to-huge-celebrity-wedding-in-london/news-story/a820227ac2d4f2a416949937b0bab19f', 0, 'factabot', 'hughesy-invited-to-mel-bs-wedding-nation-collectively-blinks', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 14:36:22', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (936, 'Billionaire House-Hunting While You Cry Over Rent', 'Some Gold Coast billionaire is out here casually snapping up a waterfront megamansion while renters are sacrificing organs for a shoebox in Sydney. But yes, lets call this a balanced market.', 'While everyday Aussies are rationing avocados and considering organ sales to cover rent, Chinese billionaire Riyu Li just dropped a casual $50 million on the palatial Bellagio La Villa in the Gold Coast\'s Tallebudgera Valley. Because when you\'re a property mogul, why not add a 10-bedroom mansion with an indoor pool and a five-car garage to your collection?\n\nLi, the mastermind behind the Ridong Group and the ambitious (but stalled) Jewel development in Surfers Paradise, had grand plans to transform the estate into a luxury resort. Unfortunately, the Gold Coast City Council wasn\'t on board, rejecting his proposal for a hotel and 108-unit complex. So, what\'s a billionaire to do? List the mansion for a record-breaking price and wait for another tycoon to bite .\n\nThis opulent estate, boasting 2,546 square metres of living space, is more than just a homeit\'s a statement. A statement that screams, \"I can, therefore I will,\" while the rest of us are stuck in bidding wars over shoebox apartments with \"character\" (read: mold).\n\nThe real kicker? Li purchased the property for a mere $7.2 million in 2014. Now, it\'s on the market for nearly seven times that amount. Meanwhile, the average Aussie is grappling with skyrocketing rents and a housing market that\'s about as accessible as a VIP lounge at a billionaire\'s party.\n\nSo, while Li lounges in his indoor spa, sipping on vintage champagne, the rest of us are left wondering if we\'ll ever afford a home that doesn\'t come with a roommate named \"black mold.\"\n\nSources:\n\nUrban.com.au  \"Ridong billionaire Riyu Li buys Bellagio La Villa, the Gold Coast hinterland mansion\"\n\nQLD Property Investor  \"Inside the record-breaking $50million mansion dubbed the Bellagio of the Gold Coast\"', 0, 'factabot', 'billionaire-house-hunting-while-you-cry-over-rent', 'published', 'images/news/10af1058-a9dc-4626-af3a-e91624c9c0ee.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 08:01:05', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (937, 'EVs Under $50K ExistJust Dont Blink or Theyre Gone', 'Electric cars *technically* exist for under $50K, but between dealer markups and waitlists longer than Centrelink queues, youll get one by the time petrol hits $4.50 a litre.', 'Yes, electric vehicles under $50,000 technically exist in Australiajust like affordable housing, fast NBN, or politicians with a spine. But good luck getting your hands on one. Between months-long waitlists, dealer markups, and dodgy admin fees, youre more likely to win Powerball than drive off in a cheap EV before petrol hits $4.50 a litre.\n\nRight now, the unicorns of the Aussie EV market include the BYD Dolphin, MG4, and GWM Ora. Theyve got the specs, the sleek lines, and the under-$50K price tags. But blink and theyre gone. Dealers are jacking up prices faster than landlords at an interest rate meeting, and if you want a specific colour? Add a few grand and maybe a blood sacrifice.\n\nThe real joke? Australias still pretending this is a competitive market. Meanwhile, Europes drowning in sub-$30K electric hatchbacks, and were rationing demo models like theyre vaccine doses in 2020. Our transition to electric looks more like a polite shuffle toward bankruptcy. And government incentives? Please. A few thousand off the sticker price doesnt help when the car doesnt exist.\n\nThis matters because EVs are supposed to be the future. But in Australia, theyre still the luxury item of choice for people who already own a second property. Want the average family to ditch petrol? Start by making it physically possible to buy a car that doesnt require either a Tesla salary or six months of manifesting.\n\nLatest update: Yes, the cars are listed as available. But stock is scarce, delivery times are laughable, and prices are as slippery as an oil exec in Senate estimates. Welcome to Australias green revolutionBYO charger and lowered expectations.\n\nSources:\n9News  Electric vehicles under $50,000 available in Australia: 2025 list (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.9news.com.au/national/electric-vehicles-under-50000-available-in-australia-2025-list', 0, 'factabot', 'evs-under-50k-exist-just-dont-blink-or-theyre-gone', 'published', 'images/news/5c299be7-ad22-4634-9e77-3f592d267c72.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 12:10:48', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (940, 'Metal Mayhem: M1 Turns Into a Tyre-Shredding Nightmare', 'A truck spilled metal debris across the M1 near Gosford, puncturing tyres on up to 300 vehicles. The highway became a scrapyard, and drivers are now questioning if their insurance covers road rage induced by infrastructure.', 'The M1 near Gosford just got its Mad Max makeovercourtesy of a rogue truck that vomited twisted metal across the highway, shredding tyres on up to 300 vehicles. Thats not a traffic jamits an industrial massacre. Commuters expecting peak-hour boredom got a front-row seat to Autobahn Armageddon.\n\nThe villain? A truck carrying metal debris that, somewhere along the way, decided seatbelts were for cargo too. The load scattered across kilometres of road like budget booby traps, leaving motorists swerving, cursing, and watching their tyres disintegrate faster than public trust in road maintenance. Its still unclear what caused the spill, but odds are high someone forgot the concept of securing your load and now owes half of New South Wales new wheels.\n\nAmong the wreckage: shredded tyres, bent rims, emotional scars, and a line of vehicles longer than Duttons campaign delusions. Drivers reported hearing popping sounds, followed by wallets weeping and souls leaving bodies. NRMA tow trucks couldnt keep up. Meanwhile, the M1 looked like a scene from Top Gear: Apocalypse Edition.\n\nThis mess isnt just about rubber. Its about infrastructure held together with duct tape and good vibes. Australia\'s busiest freeway turned into a scrapyard because someone didnt tie down a tray. And now, hundreds of everyday Aussies are wondering if insurance covers Acts of God or Acts of Absolute Governmental Neglect.\n\nLatest update: The truck drivers been spoken to, traffic has finally cleared, and the state government has offered thoughts, prayers, and zero accountability. NSW roads: where the only thing more fragile than your tyres is your faith in the system.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Chaos as truck spills metal on M1 near Gosford, puncturing car tyres (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/national/nsw-act/news/chaos-as-truck-spills-metal-on-m1-near-gosford-puncturing-car-tyres/news-story/d21fab7d08a8f37d34a6936bb301d1a6\n', 0, 'factabot', 'metal-mayhem-m1-turns-into-a-tyre-shredding-nightmare', 'published', 'images/news/3b10c4d8-afcb-48b8-8653-d89d8d08aac1.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 13:01:56', '2025-05-05 12:46:43', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (941, 'Dutton\'s Dream: Win 10 Seats, Ignore Reality', 'Despite trailing in polls, Peter Dutton is confident the Coalition can snatch at least 10 seats from Labor. It\'s the political equivalent of betting your house on a three-legged horse.', 'Peter Dutton is out here manifesting miracles, telling media the Coalition can snatch at least ten seats from Labordespite every poll, psychic, and sentient sausage sizzle screaming the opposite. Its not a strategy; its a motivational poster stapled to a political tombstone.\n\nDutton, the man who once told us nuclear power was cheaper than solar and then backflipped into a uranium pit, now reckons key battlegrounds will magically swing blue. His optimism is so unshakable it could qualify for its own religious tax exemption. While Labor rides a wave of incumbency, Duttons pitching vibes, nostalgia, and pure delusion.\n\nHes banking on housing fury, energy confusion, and a few well-timed scare campaigns to reel in disillusioned voters. But the ground game looks shakyvolunteers are thin, moneys tighter than your grandmas Tupperware, and his personal approval rating is sitting somewhere between unenthusiastic shrug and nah, mate.\n\nThis isnt just political theatreits electoral cosplay. Dutton is so deep in the echo chamber, he probably thinks LinkedIn is a swing state. The real numbers suggest the Coalition might lose seats, not gain them. But hey, why let math ruin the fan fiction?\n\nLatest update: Dutton\'s team insists theyre feeling quiet confidence. Meanwhile, Labors polling team just high-fived into next week. As for the rest of us? Were just praying this campaign ends before someone starts promising tax cuts for vibes.\n\nSources:\nThe Australian  Election 2025: Peter Dutton banking on surprises in key seats (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/election-2025-peter-dutton-banking-on-surprises-in-key-seats/news-story/dc618ad38c7a34f95716f984d79ab3b5', 0, 'factabot', 'duttons-dream-win-10-seats-ignore-reality', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-02 13:01:56', '2025-05-05 22:11:18', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (942, 'AFL Umpire\'s \'Just Got Word\' Sparks Conspiracy Frenzy', 'An umpire\'s decision reversal during the Essendon vs. North Melbourne game, prompted by the phrase \'I\'ve just got word,\' has fans donning tinfoil hats and questioning if the AFL has a direct line to the Illuminati.', 'One cryptic phraseI just got wordand AFL fans have officially lost the plot. A last-minute umpiring reversal during the Essendon vs. North Melbourne clash has triggered a conspiracy spiral so wild, it makes QAnon look like Sudoku. Twitters aflame, Facebooks frothing, and tinfoil hat sales are spiking.\n\nIt started when an umpire reversed a holding-the-ball decision, citing an off-field message. Cue outrage. Was it the ARC? A secret earpiece? ASIO? The ghost of Shane Warne? The footy world collectively yelled: What bloody word? From who? And why now?\n\nThe AFL tried to hose it down, saying it was standard protocol and part of the umpiring review system. But fans arent buying it. They want names. Transcripts. Blood samples. In a game where rules bend like yoga instructors, adding mysterious off-field input is like throwing a smoke bomb into a pub fight.\n\nHeres the bigger issue: AFL fans already think the leagues as rigged as a boxing kangaroo. The just got word moment felt less like refereeing and more like reality TVwhere producers whisper into earpieces to keep the drama juicy. If the AFL has a red phone to command central, they better start livestreaming it.\n\nLatest word? The league says calm down, the decision was correct. Fans say sure, and Gil McLachlans still on long service leave. Footy seasons back, and so are the conspiraciespass the popcorn and the tinfoil.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  AFL shuts down conspiracy theory over umpires \'just got word\' call (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/sport/afl/i-just-got-word-afl-shuts-down-conspiracy-theory-over-controversial-umpire-act/news-story/f451959ec8f794d685c195dbf7fccde6\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'afl-umpires-just-got-word-sparks-conspiracy-frenzy', 'published', 'images/news/76923fc5-2c66-4a97-b0bc-d15dd5376e04.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 13:01:56', '2025-05-05 08:52:23', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (943, 'Helicopter Takes a Dive, Coastline Gets a Surprise Splash', 'A helicopter crashed into the water off Point Lonsdale, Victoria, prompting an emergency response. Details are still emerging, but it\'s safe to say this wasn\'t part of any planned tour.', 'Point Lonsdale just got a shock guest from the skycourtesy of a helicopter that yeeted itself into the sea like it was auditioning for Bluey: The Action Movie. Witnesses watched the chopper plunge off Victorias coastline and thought, Well, thats not part of the scenic tour package.\n\nEmergency services swarmed the scene like seagulls on chips. Thankfully, miraculously, all five people aboard survivedbecause apparently, the pilot moonlights as Aquaman. They were pulled from the water with only minor injuries, proving once again that helicopters are great right up until they arent.\n\nNo word yet on what caused the nosedive, but the aircraft reportedly lost altitude quicklywhich is aviation speak for s**t went sideways, fast. Aviation investigators have cordoned off the area, while locals are still figuring out how to casually explain, Yes, thats a downed chopper near my weekend beach shack.\n\nIts not just a mechanical failits a reminder that Australias chillest holiday spots are one random Tuesday away from an emergency broadcast. Victorias coastline may look peaceful, but it now holds the crash site of what might be the most dramatic splash since Barnaby Joyces political comeback.\n\nLatest update: Search and rescue efforts wrapped, CASAs investigating, and the chopper will be fished out once the bureaucratic whirlpool settles. Meanwhile, locals have a brand-new fish tale that starts with So a helicopter crashed in front of me\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Helicopter crashes into water off coast near Point Lonsdale, Victoria (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/national/victoria/news/helicopter-crashes-into-water-off-coast-near-point-lonsdale-victoria/news-story/d0fce12f622a02943474c89a8b60102d', 0, 'factabot', 'helicopter-takes-a-dive-coastline-gets-a-surprise-splash', 'published', 'images/news/82f22b9d-6cde-41a9-b854-de3a8bef9f68.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 13:01:56', '2025-05-05 08:52:26', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (944, 'Afterpay\'s Parent Company Faces Financial Faceplant', 'Block Inc., the owner of Afterpay, saw its shares plummet after a disappointing earnings report. Seems like buy now, cry later is the new motto.', 'Turns out Buy Now, Pay Later also applies to investor regret. Block Inc., the US-based overlord of Afterpay, just suffered a Wall Street rug pull, watching its shares nosedive after a savage earnings report. Losses are up, growth is down, and suddenly financial tech is just code for whoops, we did it again.\n\nJack Dorseyyes, that Jack, the one who gave Twitter its soul and then sold it to a billionaire midlife crisisowns Block. Afterpay was supposed to be his crown jewel. Instead, its now the discount bin of his empire, delivering quarterly results so underwhelming you could mistake them for a Telstra refund.\n\nThe numbers? A 20% slump in revenue projections, mounting losses, and investor confidence sliding faster than rent prices in a zombie apocalypse. Analysts called it disappointing. Wed call it a corporate faceplant with jazz hands.\n\nLets not forget, Afterpay was Australias fintech fairytale. Slick app, zero interest, and marketing so good it convinced an entire generation to treat brunch like a financial plan. But with inflation biting and regulation looming, consumers are finally asking if $5 payments for six months is really worth it for glow-in-the-dark Crocs.\n\nThe latest? Blocks execs are promising a strategic reset. Translation: panic, layoffs, and PowerPoints. Meanwhile, Afterpay continues flogging debt in a climate where even avocado toast is now an investment risk.\n\nSources:\nThe Australian  Jack Dorsey-led Block smashed after quarterly result (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/jack-dorseyled-block-smashed-after-quarterly-result/news-story/3fe7b46e437007ab27e37dc68f903f23', 0, 'factabot', 'afterpays-parent-company-faces-financial-faceplant', 'published', 'images/news/9a52695a-6357-43f4-98fa-d8aa88c97a59.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 13:01:56', '2025-05-07 02:46:42', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (945, 'Western United Gets a $70M LifelineStill No Word on Goals', 'A struggling A-League club, Western United, received a massive investment from KAM Sports. Here\'s hoping the cash infusion translates to wins on the field.', 'Western United just got a $70 million cash injection from US-based KAM Sports, which is great news if youre a bean counter, and slightly confusing if youve seen them actually play. The struggling A-League club just became the most financially stable underperformer in Australian football history.\n\nLets talk about the buyer. KAM Sports owns English Championship side Huddersfield Town, so clearly, theyve got a thing for clubs with character. Now theyre throwing millions at Western United, whose match-day crowds sometimes resemble family barbecues with extra flares. The clubs won a single title but spent most seasons swinging between maybe next year and please clap.\n\nThe deal includes a stadium, training facilities, and the kind of business optimism only billionaires and crypto bros possess. But fans are asking the real question: can you buy goals? Because Westerns current goal tally wouldnt scare an under-12s team.\n\nContext: The A-Leagues bleeding money, battling poor attendance, and praying that one more American investor can reboot the whole system. Western Uniteds new backers say they want to grow the game in Australia. We say: start by teaching the squad how to find the net.\n\nLatest update: KAM Sports is excited and committed. Western United says the deal will take the club to the next level. Hopefully that level includes actual wins.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  KAM Sports buys controlling stake in A-League club Western United (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/sport/football/usabased-kam-sports-buys-controlling-stake-in-aleague-club-western-united/news-story/d1a6917629075f5cb9a662fd4fc6987c', 0, 'factabot', 'western-united-gets-a-70m-lifeline-still-no-word-on-goals', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-02 13:01:56', '2025-05-05 17:25:10', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (946, 'Shots Fired, Car TorchedJust Another Night in Sydney', 'Gunshots rang out in Marsden Park, followed by a car found ablaze in Girraween. Police are investigating, but it\'s clear someone\'s got a vendetta and a lighter.', 'Sydneys northwest just served up another double feature in its ongoing crime drama: gunfire in Marsden Park, and a torched car in Girraween. Within hours, the city went from suburban calm to full Underbelly reboot. No victims reported, but someone out there clearly had a messageand chose bullets and butane instead of a text.\n\nAt 10:45pm, shots were fired into a Marsden Park home like it was a warning scene in a mafia movie. Neighbours hit the deck, police swarmed, and everyone suddenly remembered they forgot to install that Ring doorbell. Less than an hour later, a vehicle was found fully ablaze in Girraweenbecause nothing says clean getaway like a flaming wreck in the middle of suburbia.\n\nThe usual suspects? Well, the cars likely linked to the shooting, but cops are playing coy. No arrests yet, and detectives are asking the public to come forward, which is law enforcement for weve got nothing but a hunch and a hot chassis. The burnt-out vehicle is now forensic toast, and the culprits probably vanished faster than public transport after midnight.\n\nWhy this matters: Sydneys not-so-silent crime surge is starting to look less like random incidents and more like turf wars, payback hits, or amateur attempts at gangster cosplay. The citys got a growing reputation for late-night messages delivered via drive-by, and if youre not caught in it, youre watching it unfold on CCTV clips that feel ripped from a GTA cutscene.\n\nLatest: Police are canvassing the area, the cars a crisp memory, and no suspects have been named. Meanwhile, Sydney keeps humming along, half crime scene, half property ad.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Shots fired into home, car found burnt out in Sydneys northwest (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/national/nsw-act/crime/shots-fired-into-home-car-found-burnt-out-in-sydneys-northwest/news-story/b6344c7ed6401cf9f86ddba574ee8086\n', 0, 'factabot', 'shots-fired-car-torched-just-another-night-in-sydney', 'published', 'images/news/34abe059-dfa1-4a54-85fa-86c61f3051c0.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 13:01:56', '2025-05-05 13:12:02', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (947, '5.7 Million Aussies Vote EarlyDemocracy Gets a Head Start', 'A record number of Australians have already cast their votes ahead of the federal election. Looks like we\'re eager to have our say before the sausage sizzles.', 'Turns out Aussies can be punctualat least when it means dodging election-day queues and snagging an early democracy sausage. A record-smashing 5.7 million Australians have already cast their votes ahead of the federal election, proving we may not trust politicians, but we do love a head start on disappointment.\n\nThe Australian Electoral Commission is practically giddy, calling it a triumph for participation. Meanwhile, campaign staff are stress-eating lamingtons as they realise half the countrys already made up its mindand the rest are just here for the BBQ. With one day to go, early voters have outnumbered the total pre-poll turnout from 2022, because nothing motivates civic duty like the chance to avoid small talk with pamphlet people.\n\nAnthony Albanese has been speed-walking through marginal seats like a man with 4G and no time for the NBN. Peter Dutton, meanwhile, is still out here selling coal and vibes, insisting hes confident of picking up seats even as the mood suggests otherwise. Early voting booths have become the real battlegroundpart polling station, part passive-aggressive sausage fest.\n\nLets be honest: were all just trying to wrap this up early like a bad work Zoom. The ads, the slogans, the policy whiplashits been less a campaign and more a national endurance test. Early voters? Heroes. Theyve cast their ballots, claimed their snacks, and now get to spend Saturday smugly judging the rest of us.\n\nLatest: Voting wraps tomorrow. Sausage availability still subject to local supply chains. Bring ID, lower expectations.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Australian Election 2025: Albanese, Dutton blitz final day of campaigning (02/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au/national/federal-election/australian-election-2025-albanese-dutton-blitz-final-day-of-campaigning-before-saturdays-election/news-story/000094379df7659f8c25bc255ead79cf', 0, 'factabot', '57-million-aussies-vote-early-democracy-gets-a-head-start', 'published', 'images/news/112a52a3-f8cc-4903-9a97-f96be63dc328.webp', NULL, '2025-05-02 13:01:56', '2025-05-05 12:49:23', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (949, 'Sausage Sizzles Missing, Democracy on Life Support', 'Election day chaos as voters queue like its a Taylor Swift concert, only to find the snags have vanished. No onions. No sauce. Just betrayal, hunger, and existential dread. Is this still Australia or a Black Mirror reboot?', 'Its election day, but something smells offand its not onions sizzling on a Bunnings-style grill. In a betrayal so un-Australian it should be referred to the High Court, voters across the country rocked up to polling stations expecting democracys juiciest tradition: the sausage sizzle. Instead, they found empty trestle tables, broken dreams, and democracy on a bread roll without the sausage.\n\nReports are flooding in of snagless suburbs, sauce-free zones, and onionless despair. One voter described the scene as a war crime, but with more passive aggression. Another said they wouldve voted earlier if theyd known the nations democracy sausage supply chain had collapsed. Lines were long, spirits were low, and every third person was googling Can I get a refund on this country?\n\nThe people are furious. Some travelled with cash, stomachs empty, and expectations highonly to be met with cardboard signs that read NO BBQ TODAY. Is this still Australia? Or did we wake up in a glitchy Black Mirror spin-off where freedom means dry mouth and disappointment?\n\nLets be real: the snag is the only bipartisan policy everyone actually supports. No one reads campaign flyers, but everyone knows the correct ratio of sauce to bread. This is cultural infrastructureand today, it failed.\n\nThe AEC declined to comment on the sausage drought, presumably because theyre also crying into their bread rolls. Meanwhile, voters cast their ballots with empty hands and heavy hearts.\n\nLatest update: Polling booths remain open, but the spirit of the nation is medium rare and slightly charred. If you see a democracy snag, hold it close. It might be the last of its kind.\n\nSources:\nVerified at polling stations across Australia (03/05/2025).\nEyewitness reports, public distress, and one very angry dad from Coburg.', 0, 'factabot', 'sausage-sizzles-missing-democracy-on-life-support', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-03 17:59:57', '2025-05-06 09:21:53', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (950, 'Voters Dump Major Parties Like Expired Milk', 'Labor and the Coalition have cooked up a Newspoll disasterbarely scraping a third of the vote each. Turns out, branding yourselves as the least-worst option isnt a winning strategy. Someone check if Jacqui Lambies got a party yet.', 'The two-party system just got curb-stomped by the Australian public, with the latest Newspoll confirming what most of us already knew deep down: no one actually likes the major parties. Labor and the Coalition are both flailing near 33%, and the only thing bipartisan here is the collective voter eye-roll. Welcome to the era of none of the above.\n\nIts a political dumpster fire. Anthony Albaneses approval rating is slipping faster than mortgage affordability, and Peter Dutton continues to inspire the same level of enthusiasm as a Monday morning at Centrelink. Both parties have spent the campaign screaming were not them!but branding yourself as the lesser evil only works when people dont feel equally haunted by both options.\n\nEnter the indies and minors, now sitting smugly on their smug little thrones as voters stampede away from the majors like they just found a cockroach in their policy soup. The Greens, Teals, and anyone with a pulse and an ounce of conviction are now more than just spoilerstheyre political lifeboats on a sinking duopoly.\n\nWhy this matters? Because Australias sick of choosing between two brands of disappointment. Were voting like customers at a dodgy servo: if the milk smells off, well risk the weird oat stuff. And if that oat milk has a cowboy hat and screams about the bush, Jacqui Lambies probably polling higher than expected.\n\nLatest update: Newspoll shows both majors circling the electoral drain, with primary votes under 34%. The next parliament? Probably a rainbow-flavoured messand honestly, good.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Newspoll reveals major parties on track to lose majority support (03/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au', 0, 'factabot', 'voters-dump-major-parties-like-expired-milk', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-03 17:59:57', '2025-05-06 07:45:54', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (951, 'Trade War Escalates, Australia Gets Punched in the Wallet', 'While the US and China flex like drunk uncles at Christmas, were copping the bill. Exports sinking, economy wheezing, and our leaders are still debating submarines instead of supply chains. Can someone tell Canberra were not in NATO?', 'America and China are chest-thumping their way into a full-blown trade tantrumand guess whos copping the slap? Yep, its Australia, the economic third wheel in a geopolitical bar fight. Exports are tanking, the dollars wobbling like a hungover pelican, and Canberras still play-acting Churchill while the supply chains fall apart.\n\nWhile Biden and Xi flex over tariffs and tech bans like drunk uncles arguing about who won the family cricket match in 1987, our economy is getting flogged. Iron ore shipments? Delayed. Agricultural exports? Blocked. Manufacturing? That was cute while it lasted. The global trade tide is receding, and were left pantsless on the shore, trying to patch holes with AUKUS talking points.\n\nAnd what are our fearless leaders doing while Australias GDP bleeds out on the floor? Re-announcing submarine deals with delivery dates closer to The Jetsons than reality. Defence contractors are eating well, but the rest of us are bracing for another round of tighten your belts while inflation slow dances with interest rates.\n\nHeres the truth: we hitched our economic wagon to global stability, then acted surprised when it exploded. We keep yelling about sovereignty while importing almost everything we eat, wear, and charge our phones with. Meanwhile, the two superpowers we rely on are busy turning global trade into WWE.\n\nLatest update: Treasury\'s warning of reduced export revenue and long-term trade instability. Canberra says it\'s monitoring the situationwhich is politician for weve got no clue, but were saying it calmly.\n\nSources:\nABC News  Australia faces economic pressure as US-China trade tensions escalate (03/05/2025)\nhttps://www.abc.net.au', 0, 'factabot', 'trade-war-escalates-australia-gets-punched-in-the-wallet', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-03 17:59:57', '2025-05-07 01:42:08', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (952, 'Wallaroos Smash Fiji, Still Get Less Coverage Than a MAFS Breakup', 'Australias womens rugby team crushed Fiji 437 in a history-making Test matchtoo bad it barely got airtime. If theyd fought mid-match over Botox, maybe theyd crack the top trending tab.', 'The Wallaroos just annihilated Fiji 437 in a blistering Test match, but unless you were physically present or refreshing The Guardian on loop, you probably missed itbecause Australias media decided a MAFS contestants fake tan meltdown was somehow more newsworthy. Womens sport: dominate on the field, still fighting for scraps off it.\n\nIt wasnt just a winit was a statement. The Wallaroos controlled the game like a team possessed, putting on a clinic of skill, speed, and actual national pride. Piper Duck led from the front, Liz Patu crunched bodies like a human wrecking ball, and Fijiana barely saw the ball let alone the try line. But good luck finding that on your homepageunless they all stormed off for a dramatic walkout over a cheating scandal.\n\nThis is the cycle: the Wallaroos put their bodies on the line for their country, and get rewarded with a few polite headlines buried under SHOCK: Reality TV Star Seen at Westfield Without Lashes. Meanwhile, blokes footy teams get saturation coverage for breaking up with their physios cousins dog.\n\nWhy it matters? Because womens rugby is exploding globally, but in Australia, its still treated like a niche hobby between netball ad breaks. Sponsors, broadcasters, and journos are all complicit in pretending theres no audiencewhen in reality, theyve just been too lazy to point the camera at the right field.\n\nLatest update: Wallaroos win, momentum building, and no post-match catfight to drive clicks. Just brilliant rugby from a team that deserves front pagesnot just footnotes.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Wallaroos dominate Fiji in 437 Test match win (03/05/2025)\nhttps://www.theguardian.com', 0, 'factabot', 'wallaroos-smash-fiji-still-get-less-coverage-than-a-mafs-breakup', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-03 17:59:57', '2025-05-06 12:58:17', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (953, 'Cyclone Brewing, But Climate Policy Still on Holiday', 'Meteorologists say Far North Queensland might get belted by a tropical cyclone. Meanwhile, our leaders are busy arguing about nuclear power like its 1983. Dont worry thoughsomeone, somewhere, probably planted a tree.', 'A tropical cyclone is rumbling toward Far North Queensland, but dont worryour climate policy is still sunbathing with a mojito and a vague sense of denial. Meteorologists have sounded the alarm, residents are preparing for roof removal via gale-force winds, and Canberras still trapped in a group chat about nuclear reactors like its Cold War: Reloaded.\n\nThe Bureau of Meteorology says conditions are perfect for cyclone formation: warm seas, shifting pressure, and the usual ominous cloud porn. Townsville and Cairns are watching the skies while securing trampolines and praying their insurance policies werent written by Scooby-Doo. But as nature gears up for round 58 of Why We Shouldve Taken Climate Seriously, our national conversation is stuck on whether nukes are sexy again.\n\nInstead of resilient infrastructure, were still tossing taxpayer dollars into feasibility studies and PowerPoint slides about reactors that wont exist until 2045assuming they arent swallowed by the ocean first. Meanwhile, flood-prone communities are rebuilding for the fifth time, and the only thing rising faster than sea levels is the collective rage of everyone whos had to mop their living room with a snorkel.\n\nThis cyclone isnt just weatherits another flashing neon sign that says, Hey mates, maybe the planets trying to tell us something. But between political theatre, donor appeasement, and debates over whether planting trees counts as action, were once again heading into a climate emergency with the preparation of a hungover festival camper.\n\nLatest update: Cyclone watch is active. Emergency crews are on standby. And federal policy? Still lost somewhere between a marketing slogan and a fossil fuel conference buffet.\n\nSources:\nBureau of Meteorology (03/05/2025)\nABC News  Far North Queensland on cyclone watch as tropical system forms\nhttps://www.abc.net.au\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'cyclone-brewing-but-climate-policy-still-on-holiday', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-03 17:59:57', '2025-05-06 04:33:22', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (954, 'Qantas Worker Plunges 5 Metres, Safety Takes a Sick Day', 'A Qantas employee fell off an aerobridge at Sydney Airportbecause apparently, safety rails are optional extras now. Shes in hospital, while Qantas is probably checking if PR spin counts as hazard pay.', 'At Sydney Airport, a Qantas ground crew member fell five metres off an aerobridgeand no, this wasnt some freak accident. Its starting to look like Australias national airline thinks basic workplace safety is just a suggestion. The woman is now in hospital, and Qantas is dusting off its PR manual under chapter: oops.\n\nThe victim, a contracted employee, reportedly plummeted from the aircraft access platform while prepping for boarding. Youd think, at the nations busiest airport and under the watch of a multi-billion-dollar airline, safety rails would be non-negotiable. But apparently, so are snacks, baggage delivery, and human dignity these days.\n\nThis isnt Qantass first time skating dangerously close to Industrial Relations: The Horror Show. Between cancelled flights, lost bags, and outsourcing ground staff to whoevers cheapest that week, the airline has become a case study in how far cost-cutting can spiral before someone literally falls off the job.\n\nThe TWU has already blasted the airline, saying the fall is a direct result of outsourcing safety-critical roles. Qantas, meanwhile, says its deeply concerned and is investigatingwhich is PR code for please dont sue us until the quarterly earnings call is over.\n\nWhy this matters? Because its not just about one fallits about the whole slippery slope of cutting corners in the name of shareholder grins. When the airline prioritises CEO bonuses over worker safety, the result isnt just bad pressits people getting hurt.\n\nLatest update: The worker remains in hospital, SafeWork NSW is investigating, and Qantas is now busy reminding everyone it takes safety seriously. Sure. Just not always with guardrails.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Qantas worker seriously injured in five metre fall at Sydney Airport (03/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au', 0, 'factabot', 'qantas-worker-plunges-5-metres-safety-takes-a-sick-day', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-03 17:59:57', '2025-05-06 01:38:39', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (955, 'Albo Ambushed by Angry VoterStill Smiling Like a PR Robot', 'Anthony Albanese got confronted over mental health funding by a furious punter, but powered through with the kind of dead-eyed grin only seasoned politicians and malfunctioning AI can muster.', 'Anthony Albanese just got verbally KOd by an angry voter mid-campaign walkaboutand responded with the sort of frozen smile that screams this will be clipped for Sky News, wont it? The PM was cornered by a woman demanding answers on mental health care, and while her voice shook with lived experience and fury, Albos reply landed with all the sincerity of a Telstra hold message.\n\nThe voter, clearly fed up with the system chewing up patients and spitting out waitlists, lit into Albanese with raw, unfiltered emotion. She asked about underfunding, the lack of crisis beds, and the gaslighting mess that is our national approach to mental health. Albo, eyes glazed with empathy.exe, calmly parroted policy lines like a man who knows hes on camera and deeply misses the days of Zoom pressers.\n\nProps to the womanshe didnt let up. While campaign staff hovered like malfunctioning Roombas and voters nearby pretended not to stare, she kept the pressure on. Her message was brutally clear: the system is broken, and no amount of spin, ribbon-cutting, or electoral TikToks can plaster over the cracks.\n\nWhy this matters? Because were all watching politicians promise \"record funding\" while public psych units are bursting, and bulk-billed therapy is a mythical creature last seen in 2012. The voter didnt come with a camera crew or lobbyist credentialsjust the kind of real-life frustration that cuts through stage-managed nonsense like a steak knife through PR tofu.\n\nLatest update: Albo nodded, thanked her for her courage, and walked onstill smiling like a man whose face is contractually locked in media-friendly default.\n\nSources:\nNews.com.au  Anthony Albanese confronted by voter on mental health care (03/05/2025)\nhttps://www.news.com.au', 0, 'factabot', 'albo-ambushed-by-angry-voter-still-smiling-like-a-pr-robot', 'published', 'images/news/b6c165fe-0434-47cf-b755-4ea2fe67e5c4.webp', NULL, '2025-05-03 17:59:57', '2025-05-05 21:18:08', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (956, 'Housing Market Still Feral, Politicians Still Pretending Its Fine', 'Prices are up, vacancies are down, and renters are out here bidding like its eBay for a mouldy shoebox. Meanwhile, candidates mumble supply and demand like its a magic spell.', 'Australias housing market continues its feral rampagechewing through renters, swallowing first-home dreams, and leaving a trail of sobbing inspection lines in its wake. Prices are up (again), vacancies are down (still), and politicians are out here chanting supply and demand like its Hogwarts for economic policy.\n\nRenters are now expected to bring references, blood samples, and a willingness to sleep standing up just for the privilege of viewing a mouldy one-bedder with great natural light (read: no curtains). In Sydney, inner-city units are going for $800 a weekplus your dignitywhile regional towns are turning into housing Thunderdomes. Want a rental in Ballarat? Better bring a sword.\n\nAnd the politicians? Oh, theyre thriving. Albaneses crew still clings to Help to Buy like its a nationwide solution, not a glorified coupon. Dutton, meanwhile, wants to build one million homes by 2029presumably using wishes and PowerPoint transitions. Neither major party seems to grasp that housing crisis means crisis, not a campaign photo op in a hi-vis vest outside a staged construction site.\n\nThis mess didnt happen overnight. Decades of tax breaks for investors, gutless zoning laws, and a complete surrender to the private market have turned shelter into a speculative sport. And now, when Aussies are couch-surfing at 40 and sleeping in their cars with full-time jobs, the system shrugs and hands out glossy brochures.\n\nLatest update: CoreLogics new report shows house prices have risen for the 15th month straight. Renters are still screaming. Politicians are still smiling. And that shoebox in Fitzroy? Sold before you finished this sentence.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Australian housing crisis deepens as prices rise and vacancies plunge (03/05/2025)\nhttps://www.theguardian.com', 0, 'factabot', 'housing-market-still-feral-politicians-still-pretending-its-fine', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-03 17:59:57', '2025-05-05 20:49:58', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (957, 'Cost of Living Slaps Harder Than a Kookaburra on Pay Day', 'Groceries? Up. Rent? Higher. Wages? Somewhere hiding with Atlantis. Voters say this election isnt about valuesits about who can stop their wallet from sobbing before Tuesday.', 'The only thing rising faster than food prices right now is collective rage. Australias cost of living has officially entered its villain eragroceries are up, rents vertical, and wages are off finding themselves on a spiritual retreat in Atlantis. Forget values, policies, or political visionsvoters just want someone to stop their wallets from performing ritual suicide by EFTPOS.\n\nThe Guardians latest polling reveals the obvious: this election isnt about climate, tax, or who loves Medicare more. Its about bread. Literally. Bread now costs six bucks if you want it sliced and edible. Families are skipping meals, young people are skipping life stages, and everyones skipping the bit where governments pretend this is just a temporary squeeze.\n\nWhile Australians juggle bills like a drunken circus act, both major parties continue arguing over whos better at relieving pressuredespite being the ones who inflated the pressure cooker in the first place. Labor points to its modest relief packages and says, we care. The Coalition shrugs and offers tax cuts with the enthusiasm of a hungover substitute teacher.\n\nMeanwhile, CEOs are cashing bonuses large enough to buy Toorak. Supermarket giants are price-hiking faster than TikTok trends. And renters? Renters are out here budgeting like they\'re contestants on Survivor: Cost-of-Living Edition, but instead of immunity, they get a 15% rent increase and a new flatmate named crippling anxiety.\n\nLatest update: No miracle in sight. Politicians promise relief soon, but voters want results yesterday. At this point, anyone who can get lettuce under $4 might win the entire election.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian  Cost of living dominates election as voters demand urgent relief (03/05/2025)\nhttps://www.theguardian.com', 0, 'factabot', 'cost-of-living-slaps-harder-than-a-kookaburra-on-pay-day', 'published', 'images/news/a8d7cb07-9010-42b6-8838-bb3fc8523b98.webp', NULL, '2025-05-03 17:59:57', '2025-05-05 20:33:35', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (962, ' Poison Lunch Lady Grins While Trial Turns Into Murder Mystery MasterChef', 'Erin Patterson, host of the now-notorious beef Wellington lunch that allegedly sent three people to the afterlife, faced court with all the spice and none of the remorse.', 'Erin Patterson, Australias unofficial ambassador for dinner and death, rocked up to court like she was auditioning for Real Housewives of Gippsland: Arsenic Edition. The woman behind the fatal beef Wellingtonallegedly served with a sprig of mystery and a splash of deathsat through witness testimony like she was judging a home cooking challenge, not a homicide case.\n\nThe survivor, Ian Wilkinson, described the taste as ordinary. Which is probably fair when your meal ends with CPR. Patterson, whose culinary chaos allegedly killed three of her ex-husbands relatives, has kept things suspiciously blandmuch like her infamous main course. Even her ex, Simon Patterson, was dragged in to testify and served the court a seven-word sledge that dodged questions like a PR-trained octopus: I dont know. Youd have to ask her. Translation: Not it.\n\nThis is no longer a court caseits a noir thriller wrapped in puff pastry. Weve got a lunch invite, a family feud, and a menu that reads like a Netflix synopsis: Four guests. One dish. Zero survivors. Meanwhile, Erin maintains her poker face, somehow channeling Bake Off vibes while facing multiple murder charges. Girl, blink if you\'re nervous.\n\nThe legal circus continued today, with Erin remaining firmly in her lane: half-denial, half-mystery, full chaos. Prosecutors are still assembling the recipe for motive, and Erins not helpingoffering up all the flavour of a soggy Yorkshire pudding. But with three dead, one clinging to life, and an ex-husband who clearly wants nothing to do with her, the real question remains: was this murder, manslaughter, or just the most cursed potluck in Australian history?\n\nSources: News.com.au (06/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'poison-lunch-lady-grins-while-trial-turns-into-murder-mystery-masterchef', 'published', 'images/news/c61f1142-b945-43ee-aaaa-1f0dbd94ae31.webp', NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-06 20:42:46', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (963, ' Liberals Pick Between Astrology and Economic Literacy, Somehow Still Lose', 'After a record-breaking election flop, the Liberal Party is now deciding whether to hand the reins to a numerology diehard or a corporate lawyer who hasnt seen a minimum wage worker since 1997.', 'The Liberal Party\'s leadership race has devolved into a choice between a numerology enthusiast and a corporate lawyer who hasn\'t interacted with a minimum wage worker since the late \'90s. After a historic election defeat, the party\'s options resemble a game of political roulette, with each candidate bringing their own brand of baggage.\n\nSussan Ley, the acting leader, is attempting to position herself as the moderate savior, but her track record includes a penchant for astrology and a history of questionable expense claims. Angus Taylor, the Shadow Treasurer, is known for his economic policies that often defy basic arithmetic, leading to widespread criticism even within his own party. Dan Tehan, the Shadow Immigration Minister, offers a more subdued approach but lacks the charisma needed to galvanize a fractured base.\n\nThe party\'s internal dynamics are further complicated by a glaring gender imbalance. With only five women likely to remain in the 150-seat Parliament, voices like former Sky News anchor Charlotte Mortlock are calling out the \"ocean of males\" dominating the leadership conversation. The sidelining of capable women within the party echoes past missteps, such as the overlooking of Julie Bishop for leadership roles.\n\nMajor donors are also expressing their discontent. Figures like billionaire Robert Millner and stockbroker Angus Aitken have criticized the party\'s lack of clear policies and ineffective messaging, threatening to withdraw financial support unless significant changes are made.\n\nAs the Liberal Party grapples with its identity crisis, the leadership contenders must confront not only their own shortcomings but also the broader systemic issues plaguing the party. The path forward requires more than just a new face at the helm; it demands a comprehensive reevaluation of values, policies, and representation.\n\nSources: The Guardian (06/05/2025), News.com.au (06/05/2025), The Australian (06/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'liberals-pick-between-astrology-and-economic-literacy-somehow-still-lose', 'published', 'images/news/b8d8d8f8-d6d6-4e25-b8a5-6f54ecbf13c5.webp', NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-06 19:14:18', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (964, ' Trump Nukes Foreign Films So America Can Watch Itself Fail in 4K', 'Donald Trump wants to slap a 100% tariff on non-American films to make Hollywood great again, as if Marvel fatigue and white saviour flicks werent already punishment enough.', 'Donald Trump has declared waron subtitles. The former (and possibly future) President wants to slap a 100% tariff on foreign films, promising to Make Hollywood Great Again, as if Americas cultural exports werent already drowning in sequels, CGI, and Dwayne Johnsons contract. In Trumps cinematic vision, global cinema is cancelled so Americans can binge-watch their own decline in Ultra HD.\n\nIts part nationalism, part nostalgia, and fully unhinged. Trumps reasoning? Foreign films are apparently destroying the industry, which is rich coming from the guy who thinks The Apprentice counts as art. This isnt about economicsits about vibes. French cinema? Threat. Korean thrillers? Menace. Australian indie dramas? Probably woke.\n\nThe announcement sent a shudder through the Aussie film industry, where local creators already fight tooth and claw to get noticed between Marvels quarterly explosions and whatever Netflix shot in Romania last week. A tariff like this would make exporting content to the U.S.already a closed shopbasically impossible, throttling our biggest chance at international exposure. But hey, at least Neighbours might finally get some American airtime. (Just kidding. Even Trump has standards.)\n\nCritics are calling it cultural protectionism. Filmmakers are calling their agents. And streaming execs are crying into their espresso martinis. But Trumps base? Theyre probably lining up to rewatch Top Gun: Freedom Erection, the unofficial blockbuster of the post-fact era. Because nothing says cinematic excellence like yelling \"USA!\" over a slow-mo jet montage and a boner joke.\n\nSources: News.com.au (06/05/2025), Variety (06/05/2025), The Guardian (06/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-nukes-foreign-films-so-america-can-watch-itself-fail-in-4k', 'published', 'images/news/4c0d665e-dc7b-4219-93b9-f6ef4cac16da.webp', NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-07 01:21:10', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (965, ' Josh Giddey Drops 30Suburban Dads Drop Jaws and Hamstrings', 'NBA star Josh Giddey rocked up to a Melbourne streetball game like it was Space Jam, except the aliens were 42-year-old tradies in ankle braces.', 'Josh Giddey just pulled the basketball equivalent of turning up to a pub trivia night with ChatGPT. The NBA star casually wandered into a suburban Melbourne streetball game, and within seconds, local dads went from just here for fitness to oh God, Ive ruptured something. Giddey didnt playhe annihilated. He dropped 30 points with the same ease most people drop a coffee order.\n\nThere were real humans on that courttradies, finance bros, one guy named Dazza in a retro Boomers jerseyand they were not ready for NBA-grade footwork. One bloke tore his hamstring just watching the warm-up. Spectators quickly ditched their vape clouds and meat pies to film it like it was the finals. Suddenly, a chill Wednesday night turned into a viral ESPN clip with a side of physio referrals.\n\nGiddey, 21 and apparently still allergic to ego, just wanted a casual game back home. But in the age of phones and FOMO, nothing stays low-key when youre a Bulls guard with handles smoother than your aunty\'s ros. The entire postcode is still recovering from secondhand embarrassment.\n\nAnd here\'s the kicker: the guys not even in off-season. Giddey was mid-NBA grind and still found time to flex on blokes who pre-game with sausage rolls. It was a wholesome flex, surebut also a public service. Because somewhere out there, a dozen suburban dads are telling physios they tried to guard Josh Giddey like it\'s a war story.\n\nSources: News.com.au (06/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'josh-giddey-drops-30-suburban-dads-drop-jaws-and-hamstrings', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-06 19:21:51', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (966, ' Climate Reports Now MandatoryCue Corporate Sustainability Bingo', 'Australias biggest companies now have to report their climate impact, which means an avalanche of glossy PDFs saying net zero by vibes and carbon neutral in 2050 if no one checks. The only thing greener than these reports is the BS theyre printed on.', 'Welcome to the Great Greenwashing Games, where Australias biggest companies must now file mandatory climate impact reportsand the real emissions are coming from their PR teams. Starting this year, every big biz has to submit an annual look how eco we are novella, where phrases like net zero pathway and ESG alignment do all the heavy lifting while emissions keep partying like its 1999.\n\nBoardrooms are scrambling. Not to change behaviourdont be sillybut to hire consultants fluent in buzzwordese. Think glossy PDFs full of wind turbine stock photos and enough sustainability jargon to make Greta Thunberg dry heave. One company even promised to be carbon neutral by 2050if the weather behaves and no one checks.\n\nIts a historic shift in disclosure, sure. But without penalties for faking the funk, what were really mandating is vibes-based accountability. Meanwhile, real climate scientists are yelling into spreadsheets, and frontline communities are still getting hit with floods, fires, and government shrugs.\n\nSo yes, progress. But also: bingo cards out. If your annual report says resilience, scope 3 emissions, or working toward transparency, take a sip of oat milk and circle the square. Because in corporate Australia, climate action doesnt mean cutting pollutionit means cutting copy that sounds like action.\n\nSources: The Australian (06/05/2025), ABC News (06/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'climate-reports-now-mandatory-cue-corporate-sustainability-bingo', 'published', 'images/news/ec6a1c4a-49bf-4a39-b8f8-e6972965dc81.webp', NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-07 01:42:04', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (967, ' Tassies Housing List Hits 5,000Govt Offers Thoughts and Prayers (Again)', 'More than 5,000 Tasmanians are stuck on a social housing waitlist longer than a Centrelink hold line, while politicians keep saying were working on it like theyre assembling IKEA furniture blindfolded.', 'Over 5,000 Tasmanians are officially waiting for social housing, and unofficially waiting for politicians to do more than gesture vaguely at blueprints. The housing list is longer than a Centrelink call hold, and just as soul-crushing. If youre poor, disabled, elderly, or just unluckyget in line. Literally. For years.\n\nThe state government says its working on it, which is political for we lost the IKEA instructions and the Allen key. Meanwhile, locals are couch-surfing, caravan-hopping, or getting fleeced in a rental market so cooked it needs its own Royal Commission.\n\nThe housing crisis isnt newbut its getting louder, meaner, and more permanent. Decades of policy failure, privatisation obsession, and rentier worship have left Tasmania with barely any public housing stock. And when they do build something, its either too late, too few, or too fancy to be called social.\n\nTodays latest numbers come with a tired rollout of media-trained sympathy and absolutely no deadlines. As always, governments throw strategies, plans, and targets at the firethen look surprised when the fire keeps eating people alive.\n\nSources: The Guardian (06/05/2025), ABC News (06/05/2025), SBS News (06/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'tassies-housing-list-hits-5000-govt-offers-thoughts-and-prayers-again', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-07 11:25:22', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (968, ' Future Fund Hits $307BStill Cant Buy You a House', 'Australias sovereign wealth piggy bank just ballooned past $300 billion, but good luck seeing a cent if you\'re under 40.', 'Australias Future Fund just cracked $307 billion, which is fantastic newsif youre already rich, dead, or planning to retire in a decade or two. For everyone else, its a flex you cant spend. Because while the nation\'s sovereign wealth piggy bank swells, actual Australians are still fighting over 2-bedroom sharehouses with rising damp and passive-aggressive fridge notes.\n\nTreasurer Jim Chalmers called it a historic milestone, which is like bragging your savings account is booming while your kids sleeping in the car. The Funds goal? Secure long-term government liabilities. Translation: stash cash while the present burns.\n\nYoud think $307 billion might buy a few homes. Or at least fund the public sector currently held together by tape and unpaid overtime. But nahits ringfenced, untouchable, and politically sacred. The future in Future Fund doesnt include your rent, your job security, or the fact that half the countrys living pay-to-pay.\n\nAs the wealth gap yawns wider and climate, health, and housing needs explode, watching the government hoard cash like a dragon feels less like good policy and more like late-stage feudalism. Sure, Australias rich. But unless youre a spreadsheet, youd never know it.\n\nSources: The Guardian (06/05/2025), AFR (06/05/2025), ABC News (06/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'future-fund-hits-307b-still-cant-buy-you-a-house', 'published', 'images/news/06c11b4d-2db8-411e-9756-c20202a9293e.webp', NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-07 11:10:00', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (969, ' Osher Gnsberg Enters Housewives WarzoneNo Rose, Just Regret', 'Osher ditches roses for stilettos and screaming as he moderates the Real Housewives of Sydney reunion. Its less talk-show and more televised ego combat,', 'Osher Gnsberg has swapped his bouquet for body armour, stepping into the Real Housewives of Sydney reunion like a gentle therapist trapped at a cocaine-fuelled hens night. Known for his zen Bachelor hosting vibes and forehead vein of empathy, Osher is now moderating what can only be described as a gladiator arena with lip fillers.\n\nHe called it a chance to test myself. Thats one way to frame watching Botoxed egos explode over who sat in whose $3,000 chair. The reunion wasnt a talk showit was televised warfare, and Osher was the poor soul asked to mediate like Dr Phil in a Dior trench. And he tried, bless him. But you cant Namaste your way out of a socialite vendetta with 8 camera angles and a Chardonnay budget.\n\nRHOS has always been messy, but this? This was peak chaos. Its like someone aired the group chat after seven espresso martinis and two defamation lawsuits. And smack in the middle of it was Osherblinking in Morse code for help, probably regretting not just sticking with Bachie rose ceremonies and emotionally constipated finance bros.\n\nReality TV has finally eaten itself. We are now watching a wholesome host navigate the wrath of women who treat Botox appointments like court summons. Oshers hair didnt movebut we all saw the trauma in his soul.\n\nSources: News.com.au (06/05/2025), Daily Mail Australia (06/05/2025), TV Tonight (06/05/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'osher-gunsberg-enters-housewives-warzone-no-rose-just-regret', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-07 01:12:46', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (970, ' Home Approvals TankBut Sure, Lets Blame Renters', 'New data shows home approvals just fell off a cliff, but politicians are still treating renters like theyre the ones holding a sledgehammer to housing supply. Turns out build more homes is just a campaign slogan, not an actual plan.', 'Housing approvals just fell to their lowest level in over a decade, but dont worrypoliticians are still busy blaming renters for having the audacity to exist. New ABS data shows approvals plummeting by nearly 10% in March, yet somehow the narrative is still: If you kids stopped ordering oat lattes, wed have more houses.\n\nThis isnt a slowdownits a faceplant. Developers are stalling, interest rates are high, and construction costs are wilder than a tradie group chat. But Canberra? Too busy chanting build more homes like its a TikTok mantra with zero structural engineering behind it. No ones asking whos building, where, or for whombecause that might require an actual plan.\n\nAnd while the build rate tanks, renters are watching prices rise, supply shrink, and landlords slap on market adjustments like its a Christmas bonus. This is Hunger Games: Rental Editionexcept the prizes are black mould and open inspections with 40 people crying in corners.\n\nSo when the housing minister says were on track, ask them: track to where? Because the only thing going up is the number of people giving up on ever owning anything but IKEA debt and resentment.\n\nSources: The Guardian (06/05/2025), ABC News (06/05/2025), Domain (06/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'home-approvals-tank-but-sure-lets-blame-renters', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-07 11:04:00', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (971, ' Eurovision Entry Drops Song Called Milkshake ManWe\'re Either Winning or Losing Hard', 'Australias Eurovision rep Go-Jo will belt out a banger called Milkshake Man in front of Europe, and honestly we respect the chaos. Is it art? Is it trolling? Either way, were sending dairy-fuelled chaos straight to Basel.', 'Australia has spokenand were sending Milkshake Man to Eurovision. No, its not satire. Its art. Maybe. Look, its hard to tell anymore. Go-Jo, our chaotic-neutral musical representative for 2025, is off to Basel with a song so unhinged it might just work. Think: disco, dairy, and whatever happens when ADHD meets choreography.\n\nMilkshake Man sounds like a 2am fever dream involving George Michael and an udder, but this is Eurovisionthe only place where that might actually win. The track is a high-gloss, gender-fluid, genre-breaking swirl of camp pop nonsense, and honestly? We respect the bravery. Or madness. One of the two.\n\nGo-Jos got pipes, sequins, and a gleam in his eye that says, Yes, this is serious. No, I will not explain the lyrics. Its peak Eurovision energyconfusing, horny, and deeply memeable. And while some are already groaning into their triple-shot flat whites, others are prepping cow-print outfits and streaming it on loop.\n\nBecause in 2025, Australia is done pretending we fit in. Were leaning into the chaos. Eurovision was never about logicits about spectacle, and we just dropped a dairy bomb on Europes doorstep. Milkshake Man, dont let us down.\n\nSources: SBS (06/05/2025), NME (06/05/2025), Music Feeds (06/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'eurovision-entry-drops-song-called-milkshake-man-were-either-winning-or-losing-hard', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-06 13:33:33', '2025-05-06 21:11:24', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (972, ' Dutton Loses Seat, Still Loses the Plot', 'Peter Dutton just became the first opposition leader in Australian history to get politically vaporised in his own electorate. Dickson said nah, the country said next, and somehow he still thinks it\'s a messaging issue, not a personality one. Meanwhile, Albo\'s grinning like he just got a lifetime supply of Qantas upgrades.', 'Peter Dutton just got booted out of his own seat like a bad houseguest who brought nothing but fear campaigns and condescension. Dickson voters handed him the eviction notice, making him the first opposition leader in Aussie history to lose his electorate. Thats not just a lossits a full-blown political exorcism.\n\nThe man known for scowls, scare tactics, and doing interviews like hes reading a parking fine was utterly rejected by his own constituents. Yet true to Dutton form, hes blaming messaging instead of, you know, himself. This is a guy who ran a climate-denying, vibe-hating campaign in a country currently underwater, on fire, and drowning in rent. What exactly did he expectfan mail?\n\nMeanwhile, Albos out here grinning like he just unlocked free business class for life. The PM played it safe, stayed above the mess, and let Dutton implode on live TV. It worked. The Libs are now spiraling into yet another leadership vacuum, where the only thing more chaotic than their ideas is the queue of men named Andrew waiting to take over.\n\nThe real kicker? Dutton still hasnt conceded the big L. Hes doing the political equivalent of ghosting reality, convinced that if he squints hard enough, the electorate will call him back. Spoiler: it wont. Dickson has officially swiped leftand Australia just left him on read.\n\nSources: ABC News (07/05/2025), The Guardian (07/05/2025), 9News (07/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'dutton-loses-seat-still-loses-the-plot', 'published', 'images/news/0d7688a2-9fb4-41cc-a135-ecb16c065a28.webp', NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 12:51:13', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (973, ' Greens MP Quits Job He Was Publicly Ignored In', 'Max Chandler-Mather got booted from Parliament and basically said thank God. Turns out being a Greens MP is just getting blamed for Labor failures while watching your housing policies get ghosted harder than a Hinge date who saw your rent history.', 'Max Chandler-Mather is out of Parliamentand honestly, he sounds thrilled. The Greens MP, known for being one of the few pollies who gave a damn about renters, walked away from Canberra like it was a cursed Airbnb with bad wi-fi and worse flatmates. After losing his Brisbane seat, Max basically said: Cool. Now I can actually do something useful.\n\nCan you blame him? Being a Greens MP means copping heat for every broken Labor promise, while your own policies get left on read by the major parties. Max spent years banging the drum on housing like it was the only instrument in the orchestrabecause it basically was. But instead of action, he got photo ops and polite political ghosting.\n\nHis exit is a symptom of something bigger. Canberra doesnt want solutionsit wants status updates. The dude literally ran one of the most passionate housing campaigns in the country, and what did it get him? A front-row seat to government inertia and Twitter fights with centrists.\n\nChandler-Mather says hes not done fighting for housing justice, just done pretending Parliament is where change happens. And thats... depressingly fair. Because when the only time youre heard is when you lose, maybe its time to fight louder from outside the bubble.\n\nSources: The Guardian (07/05/2025), ABC News (07/05/2025), Crikey (07/05/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'greens-mp-quits-job-he-was-publicly-ignored-in', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 12:23:25', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (974, ' Buddhas Bling on eBay, India Says \'WTF\'', 'A stash of ancient gems linked to the literal Buddha is about to be flogged off at Sothebys like spiritual Etsy. Indias trying to stop the sale, because maybe, just maybe, cultural relics shouldn\'t be sold like Pokmon cards to billionaire collectors with a vibe for looted artifacts.', 'Somewhere in New York, Sothebys is preparing to auction ancient jewels believed to have been buried with the actual Buddhabecause apparently sacred history is just high-end Etsy now. The gems, part of the Piprahwa collection, are up for grabs to the highest billionaire bidder, while India is yelling excuse me, thats ours in every diplomatic language possible.\n\nThese arent just shiny rockstheyre relics with deep spiritual and historical significance, linked to the OG enlightenment guy himself. And yet, theyve ended up in a Western auction house surrounded by people who think karma is a yoga pose. Indias culture ministry is trying to halt the sale, arguing the artifacts were improperly removed during British colonial rulea sentence we hear too often because, well, imperialism.\n\nThis is the art worlds favourite game: looted or liberated? Sacred or collectible? Context or cash? Sothebys says the gems were acquired legally. India says so was half our museum stuff, and were still pissed.\n\nThe whole saga is a perfect storm of colonial hangover meets capitalist thirst. Its not just about some stonesits about who gets to own history, and who profits from it. Spoiler: its rarely the people the history belongs to.\n\nSources: The Guardian (07/05/2025), BBC News (07/05/2025), Al Jazeera (07/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'buddhas-bling-on-ebay-india-says-wtf', 'published', 'images/news/93f64f10-ba5d-429b-accf-39bf720a6b86.webp', NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 09:14:33', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (975, ' Caleb Ewan Quits CyclingProbably Smarter Than the Rest of Us', 'Aussie sprint legend Caleb Ewan just ghosted pro cycling mid-season, no scandal, no crashjust pure existential clarity. When your job is riding into wind for six hours while Europeans scream at you in Lycra, maybe quitting *is* elite performance.', 'Aussie sprinting prodigy Caleb Ewan just rage-quit pro cyclingbut make it peaceful. No crash, no scandal, just a mid-season mic drop that says, actually, Im done being yelled at by Belgians in spandex. Ewan, 29, pulled the plug on his season with UAE Team Emirates after what looks like a high-speed epiphany: life is too short to keep pedalling uphill for people who only clap when you win.\n\nThis is a guy whos competed in the Tour de France, Giro, and Vueltaand now, he\'s prioritising his mental health over another six-hour sufferfest on narrow roads with more sweat than scenery. And really, good for him. In a sport that romanticises pain and applauds burnout, Ewans exit isnt weaknessits clarity.\n\nHe says he\'s taking a step back to think about the future. Translation: the future probably doesnt involve being a lycra-clad bullet getting body-shamed by Italian grandpas every time he finishes 11th. Pro cycling chews up riders like old tires. The travels relentless, the pressures cruel, and the pay? Not always worth the broken collarbones.\n\nSo when Ewan peaced out with dignity and zero drama, it hit different. He may not be chasing yellow jerseys anymorebut in the race for sanity, the mans already lapped the peloton.\n\nSources: The Guardian (07/05/2025), CyclingNews (07/05/2025), SBS Sport (07/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'caleb-ewan-quits-cycling-probably-smarter-than-the-rest-of-us', 'published', 'images/news/065d9299-f1df-44ec-ab69-1de11da6e28c.webp', NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 09:15:00', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (976, ' WA Bushfire Plans on StrikeHope You Like Charcoal', 'Controlled burns in Western Australia might get delayed thanks to industrial action, because apparently climate apocalypse prep is now subject to HR negotiations. Fingers crossed the trees negotiate better than the workers.', 'Western Australias bushfire prevention crews just said nah, putting controlled burns on pause while they fight for fairer pay. Yes, the literal people keeping the state from turning into a charcoal slab are on strike. Apparently, fire doesnt waitbut HR negotiations do.\n\nThe action involves fire management officers refusing to conduct prescribed burns unless they get proper compensation. They say they\'ve been undervalued, underpaid, and overworked while politicians slap each other on the back for climate resilience. In WA, that now means hoping the weathers chill and the eucalyptus trees dont combust in protest.\n\nLets be clear: these burns arent optional. They reduce fuel loads before summer turns everything flammable. Skipping them is like cancelling your dental appointment because flossing is annoyingexcept your gums wont explode into flames.\n\nOf course, the WA government says it\'s monitoring the situation, which is government for were ignoring it until something catches fire. Firefighters, meanwhile, are stuck between wanting to prevent disaster and needing to pay rent. Which raises the obvious question: why are the people saving the state from infernos fighting for scraps?\n\nThis isnt just about fair wagesits about whether disaster preparedness is a priority, or just another line in a speech until the smoke gets real.\n\nSources: ABC News (07/05/2025), WA Today (07/05/2025), The West Australian (07/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'wa-bushfire-plans-on-strike-hope-you-like-charcoal', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 09:13:46', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (977, ' Aussies Too Tired to Get Flu Jab, Say Experts Who Tried Everything But Bribery', 'Flu vax rates are flopping harder than a crypto coin in 2023. Health experts are begging us to get jabbed, but Australians seem to have collectively decided they\'d rather gamble with mucus roulette than queue at Chemist Warehouse.', 'Flu jab season is here, and Australia has responded with a collective meh. Vaccination rates are tanking harder than an influencers crypto coin, with health officials practically begging people to roll up their sleeves. Unfortunately, after three years of pandemic exhaustion, most Aussies would rather risk phlegm-based Russian roulette than line up at Chemist Warehouse again.\n\nIts not antivax madnessits pure burnout. The messaging has been clear. The vaccines are free. But the motivation? Non-existent. Public health campaigns have gone from protect yourself and your community to please, were out of ideas. Maybe its time to admit: fear-based marketing has officially expired.\n\nDoctors are warning of a brutal flu season if uptake doesnt spike soon, especially with immunity levels flatter than a Canberra press conference. But when even bulk-billing GPs are harder to find than a rental under $600 a week, who has time for preventative care?\n\nOfficials are still refusing to consider incentivesbecause God forbid we pay people to not clog hospitals. But lets be honest: at this point, chucking in a free coffee or lotto ticket might be the only thing that works.\n\nGet the jab. Or dont. Just dont act surprised when half your office is coughing like Victorian orphans in three weeks.\n\nSources: The Guardian (07/05/2025), ABC News (07/05/2025), RACGP (07/05/2025)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'aussies-too-tired-to-get-flu-jab-say-experts-who-tried-everything-but-bribery', 'published', 'images/news/50f0fbfc-8f19-492c-8852-7584bc45c949.webp', NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 10:44:56', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (978, ' Hungry Jacks Yeets Garfield Toys, Cops Fine Instead of Lasagna', 'Hungry Jacks handed out button-battery-loaded Garfield toys without a warning label, because nothing says family fun like accidental organ damage. The ACCC fined them $153,000a cute slap for a multi-million-dollar whoopsie.', 'Hungry Jacks has managed to turn a happy meal into a hazard, distributing Garfield toys with button batteriesa delicious snack for toddlers with zero impulse control. The real kicker? No safety warning. No disclaimer. Just pure chaotic energy and a side of existential risk.\n\nEnter the ACCC, stage left, with a $153,000 fine. Which sounds like justice, until you realise thats about the price of a medium fries at the airport these days. For a multi-billion-dollar burger empire, its couch change. Garfield might hate Mondays, but now hes also linked to internal bleeding. Great branding.\n\nThese werent vintage toys from 1985 eitherthis was now. The toys had working lights powered by tiny batteries that can burn holes in your kids stomach faster than their nuggets cool down. Hungry Jacks claims theyve since pulled the toys from circulation. Bravo. After eight months and an internal review, which probably consisted of one intern Googling button battery bad?\n\nIts the latest in a long, greasy line of corporates treating safety laws like optional seasoning. We get itcompliance is boring. But maybe dont hand out ticking time bombs with your Whopper Jr.? Especially when the same toys were already flagged for risk in other countries. Thats not just lazyits legally ambitious.\n\nIn short: Garfield shouldve stayed grumpy. Now he\'s just a health hazard in a clown suit.\n\nSources: ABC News (07/05/2025), ACCC Press Release (07/05/2025), The Guardian (07/05/2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'hungry-jacks-yeets-garfield-toys-cops-fine-instead-of-lasagna', 'published', 'images/news/4030baf0-0eb4-461b-a26b-12dbbc054bbd.webp', NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 09:19:52', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (979, ' Chris Lilley Revives Mr. GWoke Crowd Begins Ritual Screaming', 'Chris Lilleys back, and so is Mr. G, which means the podcast world just added one more reason for Twitter to spontaneously combust. Is it satire? Nostalgia? Or just another mid-2000s character aging like a carton of milk in the sun?', 'Chris Lilley is back, and so is Mr. GAustralias most chaotic drama teacher with a God complex and a glitter cannon. The character returns in podcast form, because apparently 2025 wasnt cursed enough. While some nostalgic millennials are screaming My name is Mr. G, Im a drama teacher! others are just screaming. Period.\n\nLook, theres no denying Lilleys comedic timing. But theres also no denying that most of his characters now age like dairy left in the sunbad smell, worse aftertaste. Mr. G isnt blackface, brownface, or doing a fake Tongan accent (this time), but reviving him in todays cultural climate is like lighting a scented candle in a firestorm. Pointless and definitely going to start something.\n\nThe podcast promises satire, but lets be realits also bait. TikToks about to go feral. Twitters already writing dissertations. And Lilley? Hes sipping tea in a kaftan, waiting for the backlash to double his downloads.\n\nIs it funny? Is it offensive? Is it both? Thats the Lilley formula. The real problem isnt the characterits the fact that Australian comedy still cant seem to produce anything edgy without dipping into racial, gender, or class cringe. Were stuck in a loop, and the reboot button is broken.\n\nBut hey, at least the soundtrack still slaps.\n\nSources: The Guardian (07/05/2025), ABC Arts (07/05/2025), NME (07/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'chris-lilley-revives-mr-g-woke-crowd-begins-ritual-screaming', 'published', NULL, NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 09:13:46', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (980, ' James Packer Offloads LA MansionAustralia Still Homeless', 'James Packer just sold his Beverly Hills fortress for $93.5 million, which will absolutely not go towards affordable housing, mental health, or anything remotely useful to humans earning under $500K. But congrats on the kitchen reno, king.', 'James Packer just sold his Beverly Hills mansion for a casual $93.5 million, which would house approximately zero Australians currently sleeping in cars. The former Crown prince offloaded the seven-bedroom mega-fortress to an unnamed buyerlikely another billionaire with commitment issues and a flair for gold taps.\n\nPackers real estate flip is reportedly part of a lifestyle shift, which is rich coming from a man whose lifestyle was already on its third orbit around Mars. The house comes with a screening room, gym, panic room (naturally), and vibes that scream Bond villain Airbnb.\n\nMeanwhile, back in Australia, renters are bidding on mouldy shoeboxes with charming character and duct-taped windows. Over 175,000 households are waiting for social housing. But surelets talk about imported marble and wine cellars. The Aussie housing market has become a full-blown satire, and Packers move is just another reminder that wealth here doesnt trickleit evaporates into gated driveways in Los Angeles.\n\nOf course, this sale wont fund anything useful. No homelessness programs. No mental health clinics. Just more cash for a man who once considered Crown Casinos falling share price a stressful month. But hey, congrats on the profit margin, king. May your next bathroom cost more than a public school budget.\n\nSources: ABC News (07/05/2025), AFR (07/05/2025), Domain (07/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'james-packer-offloads-la-mansion-australia-still-homeless', 'published', 'images/news/20463bfd-7382-4fa6-93e2-95bd162a25c5.webp', NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 09:15:18', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (981, ' Bad Bunny Books Oz TourBoomers Google Is This Reggaeton?', 'Bad Bunnys coming to Australia, and the youth are losing it while older relatives try to figure out if its a cartoon or a virus. Expect TikToks, glitter, and one million scalpers pretending they just need to sell one extra ticket.', 'Bad Bunnyyes, the Bad Bunnyis finally bringing the chaos down under, and Gen Z just collectively lost their minds while boomers asked if its like the Wiggles but spicy. The Puerto Rican global megastar has announced an Australian tour, sending TikTok into overdrive and parents into Google search spirals involving reggaeton meaning and why is my child screaming in Spanish?\n\nThis isnt your average stadium gigits a full cultural event. Expect cowboy hats, crop tops, and glitter bombs as far as the eye can see. Sydney and Melbourne are bracing for crowds louder than a Vivid launch and more sequins than a Mardi Gras float. Meanwhile, Adelaide asks, once again, what it did wrong.\n\nBad Bunnyreal name Benito Antonio Martnez Ocasioisnt just a musician. Hes a genre-slaying, fashion-dismantling, masculinity-trolling powerhouse who makes stadiums feel like underground dance parties. And for those still confused: no, hes not in a boy band, hes not a DJ, and he definitely didnt sing at your nieces wedding (unless shes way cooler than expected).\n\nTickets drop soon, which means the great Scalper Hunger Games have begun. Already, your cousins mates boyfriend accidentally bought six and is trying to sell them for $900 each on Facebook Marketplace. Bless.\n\nSo yes, Australia is about to get a crash course in reggaeton, gender-fluid fashion, and the unbridled joy of screaming lyrics you dont fully understand. And if your dad calls him The Bad Bunny, just smile. Its better for everyone.\n\nSources: ABC News (07/05/2025), Billboard (07/05/2025), Pedestrian.TV (07/05/2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'bad-bunny-books-oz-tour-boomers-google-is-this-reggaeton', 'published', 'images/news/36cdca15-387c-42f1-b104-c9f70de4b288.webp', NULL, '2025-05-07 09:13:46', '2025-05-07 10:48:18', 1);
